CHAPTER I.\
\
YOU don\'92t know about me without you have read a book by the name of The\
Adventures of Tom Sawyer; but that ain\'92t no matter. \'a0That book was made\
by Mr. Mark Twain, and he told the truth, mainly. \'a0There was things\
which he stretched, but mainly he told the truth. \'a0That is nothing. \'a0I\
never seen anybody but lied one time or another, without it was Aunt\
Polly, or the widow, or maybe Mary. \'a0Aunt Polly--Tom\'92s Aunt Polly, she\
is--and Mary, and the Widow Douglas is all told about in that book, which\
is mostly a true book, with some stretchers, as I said before.\
\
Now the way that the book winds up is this: \'a0Tom and me found the money\
that the robbers hid in the cave, and it made us rich. \'a0We got six\
thousand dollars apiece--all gold. \'a0It was an awful sight of money when\
it was piled up. \'a0Well, Judge Thatcher he took it and put it out\
at interest, and it fetched us a dollar a day apiece all the year\
round--more than a body could tell what to do with. \'a0The Widow Douglas\
she took me for her son, and allowed she would sivilize me; but it was\
rough living in the house all the time, considering how dismal regular\
and decent the widow was in all her ways; and so when I couldn\'92t stand\
it no longer I lit out. \'a0I got into my old rags and my sugar-hogshead\
again, and was free and satisfied. \'a0But Tom Sawyer he hunted me up and\
said he was going to start a band of robbers, and I might join if I\
would go back to the widow and be respectable. \'a0So I went back.\
\
The widow she cried over me, and called me a poor lost lamb, and she\
called me a lot of other names, too, but she never meant no harm by\
it. She put me in them new clothes again, and I couldn\'92t do nothing but\
sweat and sweat, and feel all cramped up. \'a0Well, then, the old thing\
commenced again. \'a0The widow rung a bell for supper, and you had to come\
to time. When you got to the table you couldn\'92t go right to eating, but\
you had to wait for the widow to tuck down her head and grumble a little\
over the victuals, though there warn\'92t really anything the matter with\
them,--that is, nothing only everything was cooked by itself. \'a0In a\
barrel of odds and ends it is different; things get mixed up, and the\
juice kind of swaps around, and the things go better.\
\
After supper she got out her book and learned me about Moses and the\
Bulrushers, and I was in a sweat to find out all about him; but by and\
by she let it out that Moses had been dead a considerable long time; so\
then I didn\'92t care no more about him, because I don\'92t take no stock in\
dead people.\
\
Pretty soon I wanted to smoke, and asked the widow to let me. \'a0But she\
wouldn\'92t. \'a0She said it was a mean practice and wasn\'92t clean, and I must\
try to not do it any more. \'a0That is just the way with some people. \'a0They\
get down on a thing when they don\'92t know nothing about it. \'a0Here she was\
a-bothering about Moses, which was no kin to her, and no use to anybody,\
being gone, you see, yet finding a power of fault with me for doing a\
thing that had some good in it. \'a0And she took snuff, too; of course that\
was all right, because she done it herself.\
\
Her sister, Miss Watson, a tolerable slim old maid, with goggles on,\
had just come to live with her, and took a set at me now with a\
spelling-book. She worked me middling hard for about an hour, and then\
the widow made her ease up. \'a0I couldn\'92t stood it much longer. \'a0Then for\
an hour it was deadly dull, and I was fidgety. \'a0Miss Watson would say,\
\'93Don\'92t put your feet up there, Huckleberry;\'94 and \'93Don\'92t scrunch up\
like that, Huckleberry--set up straight;\'94 and pretty soon she would\
say, \'93Don\'92t gap and stretch like that, Huckleberry--why don\'92t you try to\
behave?\'94 \'a0Then she told me all about the bad place, and I said I wished\
I was there. She got mad then, but I didn\'92t mean no harm. \'a0All I wanted\
was to go somewheres; all I wanted was a change, I warn\'92t particular.\
\'a0She said it was wicked to say what I said; said she wouldn\'92t say it for\
the whole world; she was going to live so as to go to the good place.\
\'a0Well, I couldn\'92t see no advantage in going where she was going, so I\
made up my mind I wouldn\'92t try for it. \'a0But I never said so, because it\
would only make trouble, and wouldn\'92t do no good.\
\
Now she had got a start, and she went on and told me all about the good\
place. \'a0She said all a body would have to do there was to go around all\
day long with a harp and sing, forever and ever. \'a0So I didn\'92t think\
much of it. But I never said so. \'a0I asked her if she reckoned Tom Sawyer\
would go there, and she said not by a considerable sight. \'a0I was glad\
about that, because I wanted him and me to be together.\
\
Miss Watson she kept pecking at me, and it got tiresome and lonesome.\
\'a0By and by they fetched the niggers in and had prayers, and then\
everybody was off to bed. \'a0I went up to my room with a piece of candle,\
and put it on the table. \'a0Then I set down in a chair by the window and\
tried to think of something cheerful, but it warn\'92t no use. \'a0I felt\
so lonesome I most wished I was dead. \'a0The stars were shining, and the\
leaves rustled in the woods ever so mournful; and I heard an owl, away\
off, who-whooing about somebody that was dead, and a whippowill and a\
dog crying about somebody that was going to die; and the wind was trying\
to whisper something to me, and I couldn\'92t make out what it was, and so\
it made the cold shivers run over me. Then away out in the woods I heard\
that kind of a sound that a ghost makes when it wants to tell about\
something that\'92s on its mind and can\'92t make itself understood, and so\
can\'92t rest easy in its grave, and has to go about that way every night\
grieving. \'a0I got so down-hearted and scared I did wish I had some\
company. \'a0Pretty soon a spider went crawling up my shoulder, and I\
flipped it off and it lit in the candle; and before I could budge it\
was all shriveled up. \'a0I didn\'92t need anybody to tell me that that was\
an awful bad sign and would fetch me some bad luck, so I was scared\
and most shook the clothes off of me. I got up and turned around in my\
tracks three times and crossed my breast every time; and then I tied\
up a little lock of my hair with a thread to keep witches away. \'a0But\
I hadn\'92t no confidence. \'a0You do that when you\'92ve lost a horseshoe that\
you\'92ve found, instead of nailing it up over the door, but I hadn\'92t ever\
heard anybody say it was any way to keep off bad luck when you\'92d killed\
a spider.\
\
I set down again, a-shaking all over, and got out my pipe for a smoke;\
for the house was all as still as death now, and so the widow wouldn\'92t\
know. Well, after a long time I heard the clock away off in the town\
go boom--boom--boom--twelve licks; and all still again--stiller than\
ever. Pretty soon I heard a twig snap down in the dark amongst the\
trees--something was a stirring. \'a0I set still and listened. \'a0Directly I\
could just barely hear a \'93me-yow! me-yow!\'94 down there. \'a0That was good!\
\'a0Says I, \'93me-yow! me-yow!\'94 as soft as I could, and then I put out the\
light and scrambled out of the window on to the shed. \'a0Then I slipped\
down to the ground and crawled in among the trees, and, sure enough,\
there was Tom Sawyer waiting for me.\
