CHAPTER II.\
\
WE went tiptoeing along a path amongst the trees back towards the end of\
the widow\'92s garden, stooping down so as the branches wouldn\'92t scrape our\
heads. When we was passing by the kitchen I fell over a root and made\
a noise. \'a0We scrouched down and laid still. \'a0Miss Watson\'92s big nigger,\
named Jim, was setting in the kitchen door; we could see him pretty\
clear, because there was a light behind him. \'a0He got up and stretched\
his neck out about a minute, listening. \'a0Then he says:\
\
\'93Who dah?\'94\
\
He listened some more; then he come tiptoeing down and stood right\
between us; we could a touched him, nearly. \'a0Well, likely it was\
minutes and minutes that there warn\'92t a sound, and we all there so close\
together. \'a0There was a place on my ankle that got to itching, but I\
dasn\'92t scratch it; and then my ear begun to itch; and next my back,\
right between my shoulders. \'a0Seemed like I\'92d die if I couldn\'92t scratch.\
\'a0Well, I\'92ve noticed that thing plenty times since. \'a0If you are with\
the quality, or at a funeral, or trying to go to sleep when you ain\'92t\
sleepy--if you are anywheres where it won\'92t do for you to scratch, why\
you will itch all over in upwards of a thousand places. Pretty soon Jim\
says:\
\
\'93Say, who is you? \'a0Whar is you? \'a0Dog my cats ef I didn\'92 hear sumf\'92n.\
Well, I know what I\'92s gwyne to do: \'a0I\'92s gwyne to set down here and\
listen tell I hears it agin.\'94\
\
So he set down on the ground betwixt me and Tom. \'a0He leaned his back up\
against a tree, and stretched his legs out till one of them most touched\
one of mine. \'a0My nose begun to itch. \'a0It itched till the tears come into\
my eyes. \'a0But I dasn\'92t scratch. \'a0Then it begun to itch on the inside.\
Next I got to itching underneath. \'a0I didn\'92t know how I was going to set\
still. This miserableness went on as much as six or seven minutes; but\
it seemed a sight longer than that. \'a0I was itching in eleven different\
places now. \'a0I reckoned I couldn\'92t stand it more\'92n a minute longer,\
but I set my teeth hard and got ready to try. \'a0Just then Jim begun\
to breathe heavy; next he begun to snore--and then I was pretty soon\
comfortable again.\
\
Tom he made a sign to me--kind of a little noise with his mouth--and we\
went creeping away on our hands and knees. \'a0When we was ten foot off Tom\
whispered to me, and wanted to tie Jim to the tree for fun. \'a0But I said\
no; he might wake and make a disturbance, and then they\'92d find out I\
warn\'92t in. Then Tom said he hadn\'92t got candles enough, and he would slip\
in the kitchen and get some more. \'a0I didn\'92t want him to try. \'a0I said Jim\
might wake up and come. \'a0But Tom wanted to resk it; so we slid in there\
and got three candles, and Tom laid five cents on the table for pay.\
Then we got out, and I was in a sweat to get away; but nothing would do\
Tom but he must crawl to where Jim was, on his hands and knees, and play\
something on him. \'a0I waited, and it seemed a good while, everything was\
so still and lonesome.\
\
As soon as Tom was back we cut along the path, around the garden fence,\
and by and by fetched up on the steep top of the hill the other side of\
the house. \'a0Tom said he slipped Jim\'92s hat off of his head and hung it\
on a limb right over him, and Jim stirred a little, but he didn\'92t wake.\
Afterwards Jim said the witches be witched him and put him in a trance,\
and rode him all over the State, and then set him under the trees again,\
and hung his hat on a limb to show who done it. \'a0And next time Jim told\
it he said they rode him down to New Orleans; and, after that, every\
time he told it he spread it more and more, till by and by he said they\
rode him all over the world, and tired him most to death, and his back\
was all over saddle-boils. \'a0Jim was monstrous proud about it, and he\
got so he wouldn\'92t hardly notice the other niggers. \'a0Niggers would come\
miles to hear Jim tell about it, and he was more looked up to than any\
nigger in that country. \'a0Strange niggers would stand with their mouths\
open and look him all over, same as if he was a wonder. \'a0Niggers is\
always talking about witches in the dark by the kitchen fire; but\
whenever one was talking and letting on to know all about such things,\
Jim would happen in and say, \'93Hm! \'a0What you know \'91bout witches?\'94 and\
that nigger was corked up and had to take a back seat. \'a0Jim always kept\
that five-center piece round his neck with a string, and said it was a\
charm the devil give to him with his own hands, and told him he could\
cure anybody with it and fetch witches whenever he wanted to just by\
saying something to it; but he never told what it was he said to it.\
\'a0Niggers would come from all around there and give Jim anything they\
had, just for a sight of that five-center piece; but they wouldn\'92t touch\
it, because the devil had had his hands on it. \'a0Jim was most ruined for\
a servant, because he got stuck up on account of having seen the devil\
and been rode by witches.\
\
Well, when Tom and me got to the edge of the hilltop we looked away down\
into the village and could see three or four lights twinkling, where\
there was sick folks, maybe; and the stars over us was sparkling ever\
so fine; and down by the village was the river, a whole mile broad, and\
awful still and grand. \'a0We went down the hill and found Jo Harper and\
Ben Rogers, and two or three more of the boys, hid in the old tanyard.\
\'a0So we unhitched a skiff and pulled down the river two mile and a half,\
to the big scar on the hillside, and went ashore.\
\
We went to a clump of bushes, and Tom made everybody swear to keep the\
secret, and then showed them a hole in the hill, right in the thickest\
part of the bushes. \'a0Then we lit the candles, and crawled in on our\
hands and knees. \'a0We went about two hundred yards, and then the cave\
opened up. Tom poked about amongst the passages, and pretty soon ducked\
under a wall where you wouldn\'92t a noticed that there was a hole. \'a0We\
went along a narrow place and got into a kind of room, all damp and\
sweaty and cold, and there we stopped. \'a0Tom says:\
\
\'93Now, we\'92ll start this band of robbers and call it Tom Sawyer\'92s Gang.\
Everybody that wants to join has got to take an oath, and write his name\
in blood.\'94\
\
Everybody was willing. \'a0So Tom got out a sheet of paper that he had\
wrote the oath on, and read it. \'a0It swore every boy to stick to the\
band, and never tell any of the secrets; and if anybody done anything to\
any boy in the band, whichever boy was ordered to kill that person and\
his family must do it, and he mustn\'92t eat and he mustn\'92t sleep till he\
had killed them and hacked a cross in their breasts, which was the sign\
of the band. And nobody that didn\'92t belong to the band could use that\
mark, and if he did he must be sued; and if he done it again he must be\
killed. \'a0And if anybody that belonged to the band told the secrets, he\
must have his throat cut, and then have his carcass burnt up and the\
ashes scattered all around, and his name blotted off of the list with\
blood and never mentioned again by the gang, but have a curse put on it\
and be forgot forever.\
\
Everybody said it was a real beautiful oath, and asked Tom if he got\
it out of his own head. \'a0He said, some of it, but the rest was out of\
pirate-books and robber-books, and every gang that was high-toned had\
it.\
\
Some thought it would be good to kill the _families_ of boys that told\
the secrets. \'a0Tom said it was a good idea, so he took a pencil and wrote\
it in. Then Ben Rogers says:\
\
\'93Here\'92s Huck Finn, he hain\'92t got no family; what you going to do \'91bout\
him?\'94\
\
\'93Well, hain\'92t he got a father?\'94 says Tom Sawyer.\
\
\'93Yes, he\'92s got a father, but you can\'92t never find him these days. \'a0He\
used to lay drunk with the hogs in the tanyard, but he hain\'92t been seen\
in these parts for a year or more.\'94\
\
They talked it over, and they was going to rule me out, because they\
said every boy must have a family or somebody to kill, or else it\
wouldn\'92t be fair and square for the others. \'a0Well, nobody could think of\
anything to do--everybody was stumped, and set still. \'a0I was most ready\
to cry; but all at once I thought of a way, and so I offered them Miss\
Watson--they could kill her. \'a0Everybody said:\
\
\'93Oh, she\'92ll do. \'a0That\'92s all right. \'a0Huck can come in.\'94\
\
Then they all stuck a pin in their fingers to get blood to sign with,\
and I made my mark on the paper.\
\
\'93Now,\'94 says Ben Rogers, \'93what\'92s the line of business of this Gang?\'94\
\
\'93Nothing only robbery and murder,\'94 Tom said.\
\
\'93But who are we going to rob?--houses, or cattle, or--\'94\
\
\'93Stuff! stealing cattle and such things ain\'92t robbery; it\'92s burglary,\'94\
 says Tom Sawyer.  \'93We ain\'92t burglars. \'a0That ain\'92t no sort of style. \'a0We\
are highwaymen. \'a0We stop stages and carriages on the road, with masks\
on, and kill the people and take their watches and money.\'94\
\
\'93Must we always kill the people?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, certainly. \'a0It\'92s best. \'a0Some authorities think different, but\
mostly it\'92s considered best to kill them--except some that you bring to\
the cave here, and keep them till they\'92re ransomed.\'94\
\
\'93Ransomed? \'a0What\'92s that?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. \'a0But that\'92s what they do. \'a0I\'92ve seen it in books; and so\
of course that\'92s what we\'92ve got to do.\'94\
\
\'93But how can we do it if we don\'92t know what it is?\'94\
\
\'93Why, blame it all, we\'92ve _got_ to do it. \'a0Don\'92t I tell you it\'92s in the\
books? \'a0Do you want to go to doing different from what\'92s in the books,\
and get things all muddled up?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, that\'92s all very fine to _say_, Tom Sawyer, but how in the nation\
are these fellows going to be ransomed if we don\'92t know how to do it\
to them?--that\'92s the thing I want to get at. \'a0Now, what do you reckon it\
is?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I don\'92t know. \'a0But per\'92aps if we keep them till they\'92re ransomed,\
it means that we keep them till they\'92re dead.\'94\
\
\'93Now, that\'92s something _like_. \'a0That\'92ll answer. \'a0Why couldn\'92t you said\
that before? \'a0We\'92ll keep them till they\'92re ransomed to death; and a\
bothersome lot they\'92ll be, too--eating up everything, and always trying\
to get loose.\'94\
\
\'93How you talk, Ben Rogers. \'a0How can they get loose when there\'92s a guard\
over them, ready to shoot them down if they move a peg?\'94\
\
\'93A guard! \'a0Well, that _is_ good. \'a0So somebody\'92s got to set up all night\
and never get any sleep, just so as to watch them. \'a0I think that\'92s\
foolishness. Why can\'92t a body take a club and ransom them as soon as\
they get here?\'94\
\
\'93Because it ain\'92t in the books so--that\'92s why. \'a0Now, Ben Rogers, do you\
want to do things regular, or don\'92t you?--that\'92s the idea. \'a0Don\'92t you\
reckon that the people that made the books knows what\'92s the correct\
thing to do? \'a0Do you reckon _you_ can learn \'91em anything? \'a0Not by a good\
deal. No, sir, we\'92ll just go on and ransom them in the regular way.\'94\
\
\'93All right. \'a0I don\'92t mind; but I say it\'92s a fool way, anyhow. \'a0Say, do\
we kill the women, too?\'94\
\
\'93Well, Ben Rogers, if I was as ignorant as you I wouldn\'92t let on. \'a0Kill\
the women? \'a0No; nobody ever saw anything in the books like that. \'a0You\
fetch them to the cave, and you\'92re always as polite as pie to them;\
and by and by they fall in love with you, and never want to go home any\
more.\'94\
\
\'93Well, if that\'92s the way I\'92m agreed, but I don\'92t take no stock in it.\
Mighty soon we\'92ll have the cave so cluttered up with women, and fellows\
waiting to be ransomed, that there won\'92t be no place for the robbers.\
But go ahead, I ain\'92t got nothing to say.\'94\
\
Little Tommy Barnes was asleep now, and when they waked him up he was\
scared, and cried, and said he wanted to go home to his ma, and didn\'92t\
want to be a robber any more.\
\
So they all made fun of him, and called him cry-baby, and that made him\
mad, and he said he would go straight and tell all the secrets. \'a0But\
Tom give him five cents to keep quiet, and said we would all go home and\
meet next week, and rob somebody and kill some people.\
\
Ben Rogers said he couldn\'92t get out much, only Sundays, and so he wanted\
to begin next Sunday; but all the boys said it would be wicked to do it\
on Sunday, and that settled the thing. \'a0They agreed to get together and\
fix a day as soon as they could, and then we elected Tom Sawyer first\
captain and Jo Harper second captain of the Gang, and so started home.\
\
I clumb up the shed and crept into my window just before day was\
breaking. My new clothes was all greased up and clayey, and I was\
dog-tired.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER III.\
\
WELL, I got a good going-over in the morning from old Miss Watson on\
account of my clothes; but the widow she didn\'92t scold, but only cleaned\
off the grease and clay, and looked so sorry that I thought I would\
behave awhile if I could. \'a0Then Miss Watson she took me in the closet\
and prayed, but nothing come of it. \'a0She told me to pray every day, and\
whatever I asked for I would get it. \'a0But it warn\'92t so. \'a0I tried it.\
Once I got a fish-line, but no hooks. \'a0It warn\'92t any good to me without\
hooks. \'a0I tried for the hooks three or four times, but somehow I\
couldn\'92t make it work. \'a0By and by, one day, I asked Miss Watson to\
try for me, but she said I was a fool. \'a0She never told me why, and I\
couldn\'92t make it out no way.\
\
I set down one time back in the woods, and had a long think about it.\
\'a0I says to myself, if a body can get anything they pray for, why don\'92t\
Deacon Winn get back the money he lost on pork? \'a0Why can\'92t the widow get\
back her silver snuffbox that was stole? \'a0Why can\'92t Miss Watson fat up?\
No, says I to my self, there ain\'92t nothing in it. \'a0I went and told the\
widow about it, and she said the thing a body could get by praying for\
it was \'93spiritual gifts.\'94 \'a0This was too many for me, but she told me\
what she meant--I must help other people, and do everything I could for\
other people, and look out for them all the time, and never think about\
myself. This was including Miss Watson, as I took it. \'a0I went out in the\
woods and turned it over in my mind a long time, but I couldn\'92t see no\
advantage about it--except for the other people; so at last I reckoned\
I wouldn\'92t worry about it any more, but just let it go. \'a0Sometimes the\
widow would take me one side and talk about Providence in a way to make\
a body\'92s mouth water; but maybe next day Miss Watson would take hold\
and knock it all down again. \'a0I judged I could see that there was two\
Providences, and a poor chap would stand considerable show with the\
widow\'92s Providence, but if Miss Watson\'92s got him there warn\'92t no help\
for him any more. \'a0I thought it all out, and reckoned I would belong\
to the widow\'92s if he wanted me, though I couldn\'92t make out how he was\
a-going to be any better off then than what he was before, seeing I was\
so ignorant, and so kind of low-down and ornery.\
\
Pap he hadn\'92t been seen for more than a year, and that was comfortable\
for me; I didn\'92t want to see him no more. \'a0He used to always whale me\
when he was sober and could get his hands on me; though I used to take\
to the woods most of the time when he was around. \'a0Well, about this time\
he was found in the river drownded, about twelve mile above town, so\
people said. \'a0They judged it was him, anyway; said this drownded man was\
just his size, and was ragged, and had uncommon long hair, which was all\
like pap; but they couldn\'92t make nothing out of the face, because it had\
been in the water so long it warn\'92t much like a face at all. \'a0They said\
he was floating on his back in the water. \'a0They took him and buried him\
on the bank. \'a0But I warn\'92t comfortable long, because I happened to think\
of something. \'a0I knowed mighty well that a drownded man don\'92t float on\
his back, but on his face. \'a0So I knowed, then, that this warn\'92t pap, but\
a woman dressed up in a man\'92s clothes. \'a0So I was uncomfortable again.\
\'a0I judged the old man would turn up again by and by, though I wished he\
wouldn\'92t.\
\
We played robber now and then about a month, and then I resigned. \'a0All\
the boys did. \'a0We hadn\'92t robbed nobody, hadn\'92t killed any people, but\
only just pretended. \'a0We used to hop out of the woods and go charging\
down on hog-drivers and women in carts taking garden stuff to market,\
but we never hived any of them. \'a0Tom Sawyer called the hogs \'93ingots,\'94\
 and he called the turnips and stuff \'93julery,\'94 and we would go to the\
cave and powwow over what we had done, and how many people we had killed\
and marked. \'a0But I couldn\'92t see no profit in it. \'a0One time Tom sent a\
boy to run about town with a blazing stick, which he called a slogan\
(which was the sign for the Gang to get together), and then he said he\
had got secret news by his spies that next day a whole parcel of Spanish\
merchants and rich A-rabs was going to camp in Cave Hollow with two\
hundred elephants, and six hundred camels, and over a thousand \'93sumter\'94\
 mules, all loaded down with di\'92monds, and they didn\'92t have only a guard\
of four hundred soldiers, and so we would lay in ambuscade, as he called\
it, and kill the lot and scoop the things. \'a0He said we must slick up\
our swords and guns, and get ready. \'a0He never could go after even a\
turnip-cart but he must have the swords and guns all scoured up for it,\
though they was only lath and broomsticks, and you might scour at them\
till you rotted, and then they warn\'92t worth a mouthful of ashes more\
than what they was before. \'a0I didn\'92t believe we could lick such a crowd\
of Spaniards and A-rabs, but I wanted to see the camels and elephants,\
so I was on hand next day, Saturday, in the ambuscade; and when we got\
the word we rushed out of the woods and down the hill. \'a0But there warn\'92t\
no Spaniards and A-rabs, and there warn\'92t no camels nor no elephants.\
\'a0It warn\'92t anything but a Sunday-school picnic, and only a primer-class\
at that. \'a0We busted it up, and chased the children up the hollow; but we\
never got anything but some doughnuts and jam, though Ben Rogers got\
a rag doll, and Jo Harper got a hymn-book and a tract; and then the\
teacher charged in, and made us drop everything and cut.\
\
\'a0I didn\'92t see no di\'92monds, and I told Tom Sawyer so. \'a0He said there was\
loads of them there, anyway; and he said there was A-rabs there, too,\
and elephants and things. \'a0I said, why couldn\'92t we see them, then? \'a0He\
said if I warn\'92t so ignorant, but had read a book called Don Quixote, I\
would know without asking. \'a0He said it was all done by enchantment. \'a0He\
said there was hundreds of soldiers there, and elephants and treasure,\
and so on, but we had enemies which he called magicians; and they had\
turned the whole thing into an infant Sunday-school, just out of spite.\
\'a0I said, all right; then the thing for us to do was to go for the\
magicians. \'a0Tom Sawyer said I was a numskull.\
\
\'93Why,\'94 said he, \'93a magician could call up a lot of genies, and they\
would hash you up like nothing before you could say Jack Robinson. \'a0They\
are as tall as a tree and as big around as a church.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I says, \'93s\'92pose we got some genies to help _us_--can\'92t we lick\
the other crowd then?\'94\
\
\'93How you going to get them?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. \'a0How do _they_ get them?\'94\
\
\'93Why, they rub an old tin lamp or an iron ring, and then the genies\
come tearing in, with the thunder and lightning a-ripping around and the\
smoke a-rolling, and everything they\'92re told to do they up and do it.\
\'a0They don\'92t think nothing of pulling a shot-tower up by the roots, and\
belting a Sunday-school superintendent over the head with it--or any\
other man.\'94\
\
\'93Who makes them tear around so?\'94\
\
\'93Why, whoever rubs the lamp or the ring. \'a0They belong to whoever rubs\
the lamp or the ring, and they\'92ve got to do whatever he says. \'a0If he\
tells them to build a palace forty miles long out of di\'92monds, and fill\
it full of chewing-gum, or whatever you want, and fetch an emperor\'92s\
daughter from China for you to marry, they\'92ve got to do it--and they\'92ve\
got to do it before sun-up next morning, too. \'a0And more: \'a0they\'92ve got\
to waltz that palace around over the country wherever you want it, you\
understand.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says I, \'93I think they are a pack of flat-heads for not keeping\
the palace themselves \'91stead of fooling them away like that. \'a0And what\'92s\
more--if I was one of them I would see a man in Jericho before I would\
drop my business and come to him for the rubbing of an old tin lamp.\'94\
\
\'93How you talk, Huck Finn. \'a0Why, you\'92d _have_ to come when he rubbed it,\
whether you wanted to or not.\'94\
\
\'93What! and I as high as a tree and as big as a church? \'a0All right, then;\
I _would_ come; but I lay I\'92d make that man climb the highest tree there\
was in the country.\'94\
\
\'93Shucks, it ain\'92t no use to talk to you, Huck Finn. \'a0You don\'92t seem to\
know anything, somehow--perfect saphead.\'94\
\
I thought all this over for two or three days, and then I reckoned I\
would see if there was anything in it. \'a0I got an old tin lamp and an\
iron ring, and went out in the woods and rubbed and rubbed till I sweat\
like an Injun, calculating to build a palace and sell it; but it warn\'92t\
no use, none of the genies come. \'a0So then I judged that all that stuff\
was only just one of Tom Sawyer\'92s lies. \'a0I reckoned he believed in the\
A-rabs and the elephants, but as for me I think different. \'a0It had all\
the marks of a Sunday-school.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER IV.\
\
WELL, three or four months run along, and it was well into the winter\
now. I had been to school most all the time and could spell and read and\
write just a little, and could say the multiplication table up to six\
times seven is thirty-five, and I don\'92t reckon I could ever get any\
further than that if I was to live forever. \'a0I don\'92t take no stock in\
mathematics, anyway.\
\
At first I hated the school, but by and by I got so I could stand it.\
Whenever I got uncommon tired I played hookey, and the hiding I got next\
day done me good and cheered me up. \'a0So the longer I went to school the\
easier it got to be. \'a0I was getting sort of used to the widow\'92s ways,\
too, and they warn\'92t so raspy on me. \'a0Living in a house and sleeping in\
a bed pulled on me pretty tight mostly, but before the cold weather I\
used to slide out and sleep in the woods sometimes, and so that was a\
rest to me. \'a0I liked the old ways best, but I was getting so I liked the\
new ones, too, a little bit. The widow said I was coming along slow but\
sure, and doing very satisfactory. \'a0She said she warn\'92t ashamed of me.\
\
One morning I happened to turn over the salt-cellar at breakfast.\
\'a0I reached for some of it as quick as I could to throw over my left\
shoulder and keep off the bad luck, but Miss Watson was in ahead of me,\
and crossed me off. She says, \'93Take your hands away, Huckleberry; what\
a mess you are always making!\'94 \'a0The widow put in a good word for me, but\
that warn\'92t going to keep off the bad luck, I knowed that well enough.\
\'a0I started out, after breakfast, feeling worried and shaky, and\
wondering where it was going to fall on me, and what it was going to be.\
\'a0There is ways to keep off some kinds of bad luck, but this wasn\'92t one\
of them kind; so I never tried to do anything, but just poked along\
low-spirited and on the watch-out.\
\
I went down to the front garden and clumb over the stile where you go\
through the high board fence. \'a0There was an inch of new snow on the\
ground, and I seen somebody\'92s tracks. \'a0They had come up from the quarry\
and stood around the stile a while, and then went on around the garden\
fence. \'a0It was funny they hadn\'92t come in, after standing around so. \'a0I\
couldn\'92t make it out. \'a0It was very curious, somehow. \'a0I was going to\
follow around, but I stooped down to look at the tracks first. \'a0I didn\'92t\
notice anything at first, but next I did. \'a0There was a cross in the left\
boot-heel made with big nails, to keep off the devil.\
\
I was up in a second and shinning down the hill. \'a0I looked over my\
shoulder every now and then, but I didn\'92t see nobody. \'a0I was at Judge\
Thatcher\'92s as quick as I could get there. \'a0He said:\
\
\'93Why, my boy, you are all out of breath. \'a0Did you come for your\
interest?\'94\
\
\'93No, sir,\'94 I says; \'93is there some for me?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes, a half-yearly is in last night--over a hundred and fifty\
dollars. \'a0Quite a fortune for you. \'a0You had better let me invest it\
along with your six thousand, because if you take it you\'92ll spend it.\'94\
\
\'93No, sir,\'94 I says, \'93I don\'92t want to spend it. \'a0I don\'92t want it at\
all--nor the six thousand, nuther. \'a0I want you to take it; I want to give\
it to you--the six thousand and all.\'94\
\
He looked surprised. \'a0He couldn\'92t seem to make it out. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Why, what can you mean, my boy?\'94\
\
I says, \'93Don\'92t you ask me no questions about it, please. \'a0You\'92ll take\
it--won\'92t you?\'94\
\
He says:\
\
\'93Well, I\'92m puzzled. \'a0Is something the matter?\'94\
\
\'93Please take it,\'94 says I, \'93and don\'92t ask me nothing--then I won\'92t have to\
tell no lies.\'94\
\
He studied a while, and then he says:\
\
\'93Oho-o! \'a0I think I see. \'a0You want to _sell_ all your property to me--not\
give it. \'a0That\'92s the correct idea.\'94\
\
Then he wrote something on a paper and read it over, and says:\
\
\'93There; you see it says \'91for a consideration.\'92 \'a0That means I have bought\
it of you and paid you for it. \'a0Here\'92s a dollar for you. \'a0Now you sign\
it.\'94\
\
So I signed it, and left.\
\
Miss Watson\'92s nigger, Jim, had a hair-ball as big as your fist, which\
had been took out of the fourth stomach of an ox, and he used to do\
magic with it. \'a0He said there was a spirit inside of it, and it knowed\
everything. \'a0So I went to him that night and told him pap was here\
again, for I found his tracks in the snow. \'a0What I wanted to know was,\
what he was going to do, and was he going to stay? \'a0Jim got out his\
hair-ball and said something over it, and then he held it up and dropped\
it on the floor. \'a0It fell pretty solid, and only rolled about an inch.\
\'a0Jim tried it again, and then another time, and it acted just the same.\
\'a0Jim got down on his knees, and put his ear against it and listened.\
\'a0But it warn\'92t no use; he said it wouldn\'92t talk. He said sometimes it\
wouldn\'92t talk without money. \'a0I told him I had an old slick counterfeit\
quarter that warn\'92t no good because the brass showed through the silver\
a little, and it wouldn\'92t pass nohow, even if the brass didn\'92t show,\
because it was so slick it felt greasy, and so that would tell on it\
every time. \'a0(I reckoned I wouldn\'92t say nothing about the dollar I got\
from the judge.) I said it was pretty bad money, but maybe the hair-ball\
would take it, because maybe it wouldn\'92t know the difference. \'a0Jim smelt\
it and bit it and rubbed it, and said he would manage so the hair-ball\
would think it was good. \'a0He said he would split open a raw Irish potato\
and stick the quarter in between and keep it there all night, and next\
morning you couldn\'92t see no brass, and it wouldn\'92t feel greasy no more,\
and so anybody in town would take it in a minute, let alone a hair-ball.\
\'a0Well, I knowed a potato would do that before, but I had forgot it.\
\
Jim put the quarter under the hair-ball, and got down and listened\
again. This time he said the hair-ball was all right. \'a0He said it\
would tell my whole fortune if I wanted it to. \'a0I says, go on. \'a0So the\
hair-ball talked to Jim, and Jim told it to me. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Yo\'92 ole father doan\'92 know yit what he\'92s a-gwyne to do. \'a0Sometimes he\
spec he\'92ll go \'91way, en den agin he spec he\'92ll stay. \'a0De bes\'92 way is to\
res\'92 easy en let de ole man take his own way. \'a0Dey\'92s two angels hoverin\'92\
roun\'92 \'91bout him. \'a0One uv \'91em is white en shiny, en t\'92other one is black.\
De white one gits him to go right a little while, den de black one sail\
in en bust it all up. \'a0A body can\'92t tell yit which one gwyne to fetch\
him at de las\'92. \'a0But you is all right. \'a0You gwyne to have considable\
trouble in yo\'92 life, en considable joy. \'a0Sometimes you gwyne to git\
hurt, en sometimes you gwyne to git sick; but every time you\'92s gwyne\
to git well agin. \'a0Dey\'92s two gals flyin\'92 \'91bout you in yo\'92 life. \'a0One\
uv \'91em\'92s light en t\'92other one is dark. One is rich en t\'92other is po\'92.\
\'a0You\'92s gwyne to marry de po\'92 one fust en de rich one by en by. \'a0You\
wants to keep \'91way fum de water as much as you kin, en don\'92t run no\
resk, \'91kase it\'92s down in de bills dat you\'92s gwyne to git hung.\'94\
\
When I lit my candle and went up to my room that night there sat pap his\
own self!\
\
