\
CHAPTER V.\
\
I had shut the door to. \'a0Then I turned around and there he was. \'a0I used\
to be scared of him all the time, he tanned me so much. \'a0I reckoned I\
was scared now, too; but in a minute I see I was mistaken--that is, after\
the first jolt, as you may say, when my breath sort of hitched, he being\
so unexpected; but right away after I see I warn\'92t scared of him worth\
bothring about.\
\
He was most fifty, and he looked it. \'a0His hair was long and tangled and\
greasy, and hung down, and you could see his eyes shining through\
like he was behind vines. \'a0It was all black, no gray; so was his long,\
mixed-up whiskers. \'a0There warn\'92t no color in his face, where his face\
showed; it was white; not like another man\'92s white, but a white to make\
a body sick, a white to make a body\'92s flesh crawl--a tree-toad white, a\
fish-belly white. \'a0As for his clothes--just rags, that was all. \'a0He had\
one ankle resting on t\'92other knee; the boot on that foot was busted, and\
two of his toes stuck through, and he worked them now and then. \'a0His hat\
was laying on the floor--an old black slouch with the top caved in, like\
a lid.\
\
I stood a-looking at him; he set there a-looking at me, with his chair\
tilted back a little. \'a0I set the candle down. \'a0I noticed the window was\
up; so he had clumb in by the shed. \'a0He kept a-looking me all over. \'a0By\
and by he says:\
\
\'93Starchy clothes--very. \'a0You think you\'92re a good deal of a big-bug,\
_don\'92t_ you?\'94\
\
\'93Maybe I am, maybe I ain\'92t,\'94 I says.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you give me none o\'92 your lip,\'94 says he.  \'93You\'92ve put on\
considerable many frills since I been away. \'a0I\'92ll take you down a peg\
before I get done with you. \'a0You\'92re educated, too, they say--can read and\
write. \'a0You think you\'92re better\'92n your father, now, don\'92t you, because\
he can\'92t? \'a0_I\'92ll_ take it out of you. \'a0Who told you you might meddle\
with such hifalut\'92n foolishness, hey?--who told you you could?\'94\
\
\'93The widow. \'a0She told me.\'94\
\
\'93The widow, hey?--and who told the widow she could put in her shovel\
about a thing that ain\'92t none of her business?\'94\
\
\'93Nobody never told her.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I\'92ll learn her how to meddle. \'a0And looky here--you drop that\
school, you hear? \'a0I\'92ll learn people to bring up a boy to put on airs\
over his own father and let on to be better\'92n what _he_ is. \'a0You lemme\
catch you fooling around that school again, you hear? \'a0Your mother\
couldn\'92t read, and she couldn\'92t write, nuther, before she died. \'a0None\
of the family couldn\'92t before _they_ died. \'a0I can\'92t; and here you\'92re\
a-swelling yourself up like this. \'a0I ain\'92t the man to stand it--you hear?\
Say, lemme hear you read.\'94\
\
I took up a book and begun something about General Washington and the\
wars. When I\'92d read about a half a minute, he fetched the book a whack\
with his hand and knocked it across the house. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93It\'92s so. \'a0You can do it. \'a0I had my doubts when you told me. \'a0Now looky\
here; you stop that putting on frills. \'a0I won\'92t have it. \'a0I\'92ll lay for\
you, my smarty; and if I catch you about that school I\'92ll tan you good.\
First you know you\'92ll get religion, too. \'a0I never see such a son.\'94\
\
He took up a little blue and yaller picture of some cows and a boy, and\
says:\
\
\'93What\'92s this?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s something they give me for learning my lessons good.\'94\
\
He tore it up, and says:\
\
\'93I\'92ll give you something better--I\'92ll give you a cowhide.\'94\
\
He set there a-mumbling and a-growling a minute, and then he says:\
\
\'93_Ain\'92t_ you a sweet-scented dandy, though? \'a0A bed; and bedclothes; and\
a look\'92n\'92-glass; and a piece of carpet on the floor--and your own father\
got to sleep with the hogs in the tanyard. \'a0I never see such a son. \'a0I\
bet I\'92ll take some o\'92 these frills out o\'92 you before I\'92m done with you.\
Why, there ain\'92t no end to your airs--they say you\'92re rich. \'a0Hey?--how\'92s\
that?\'94\
\
\'93They lie--that\'92s how.\'94\
\
\'93Looky here--mind how you talk to me; I\'92m a-standing about all I can\
stand now--so don\'92t gimme no sass. \'a0I\'92ve been in town two days, and I\
hain\'92t heard nothing but about you bein\'92 rich. \'a0I heard about it\
away down the river, too. \'a0That\'92s why I come. \'a0You git me that money\
to-morrow--I want it.\'94\
\
\'93I hain\'92t got no money.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie. \'a0Judge Thatcher\'92s got it. \'a0You git it. \'a0I want it.\'94\
\
\'93I hain\'92t got no money, I tell you. \'a0You ask Judge Thatcher; he\'92ll tell\
you the same.\'94\
\
\'93All right. \'a0I\'92ll ask him; and I\'92ll make him pungle, too, or I\'92ll know\
the reason why. \'a0Say, how much you got in your pocket? \'a0I want it.\'94\
\
\'93I hain\'92t got only a dollar, and I want that to--\'94\
\
\'93It don\'92t make no difference what you want it for--you just shell it\
out.\'94\
\
He took it and bit it to see if it was good, and then he said he was\
going down town to get some whisky; said he hadn\'92t had a drink all day.\
When he had got out on the shed he put his head in again, and cussed\
me for putting on frills and trying to be better than him; and when I\
reckoned he was gone he come back and put his head in again, and told me\
to mind about that school, because he was going to lay for me and lick\
me if I didn\'92t drop that.\
\
Next day he was drunk, and he went to Judge Thatcher\'92s and bullyragged\
him, and tried to make him give up the money; but he couldn\'92t, and then\
he swore he\'92d make the law force him.\
\
The judge and the widow went to law to get the court to take me away\
from him and let one of them be my guardian; but it was a new judge that\
had just come, and he didn\'92t know the old man; so he said courts mustn\'92t\
interfere and separate families if they could help it; said he\'92d druther\
not take a child away from its father. \'a0So Judge Thatcher and the widow\
had to quit on the business.\
\
That pleased the old man till he couldn\'92t rest. \'a0He said he\'92d cowhide\
me till I was black and blue if I didn\'92t raise some money for him. \'a0I\
borrowed three dollars from Judge Thatcher, and pap took it and got\
drunk, and went a-blowing around and cussing and whooping and carrying\
on; and he kept it up all over town, with a tin pan, till most midnight;\
then they jailed him, and next day they had him before court, and jailed\
him again for a week. \'a0But he said _he_ was satisfied; said he was boss\
of his son, and he\'92d make it warm for _him_.\
\
When he got out the new judge said he was a-going to make a man of him.\
So he took him to his own house, and dressed him up clean and nice, and\
had him to breakfast and dinner and supper with the family, and was just\
old pie to him, so to speak. \'a0And after supper he talked to him about\
temperance and such things till the old man cried, and said he\'92d been\
a fool, and fooled away his life; but now he was a-going to turn over\
a new leaf and be a man nobody wouldn\'92t be ashamed of, and he hoped the\
judge would help him and not look down on him. \'a0The judge said he could\
hug him for them words; so he cried, and his wife she cried again; pap\
said he\'92d been a man that had always been misunderstood before, and the\
judge said he believed it. \'a0The old man said that what a man wanted\
that was down was sympathy, and the judge said it was so; so they cried\
again. \'a0And when it was bedtime the old man rose up and held out his\
hand, and says:\
\
\'93Look at it, gentlemen and ladies all; take a-hold of it; shake it.\
There\'92s a hand that was the hand of a hog; but it ain\'92t so no more; it\'92s\
the hand of a man that\'92s started in on a new life, and\'92ll die before\
he\'92ll go back. \'a0You mark them words--don\'92t forget I said them. \'a0It\'92s a\
clean hand now; shake it--don\'92t be afeard.\'94\
\
So they shook it, one after the other, all around, and cried. \'a0The\
judge\'92s wife she kissed it. \'a0Then the old man he signed a pledge--made\
his mark. The judge said it was the holiest time on record, or something\
like that. Then they tucked the old man into a beautiful room, which was\
the spare room, and in the night some time he got powerful thirsty and\
clumb out on to the porch-roof and slid down a stanchion and traded his\
new coat for a jug of forty-rod, and clumb back again and had a good old\
time; and towards daylight he crawled out again, drunk as a fiddler, and\
rolled off the porch and broke his left arm in two places, and was most\
froze to death when somebody found him after sun-up. \'a0And when they come\
to look at that spare room they had to take soundings before they could\
navigate it.\
\
The judge he felt kind of sore. \'a0He said he reckoned a body could reform\
the old man with a shotgun, maybe, but he didn\'92t know no other way.\
\
\
