\
CHAPTER VI.\
\
WELL, pretty soon the old man was up and around again, and then he went\
for Judge Thatcher in the courts to make him give up that money, and he\
went for me, too, for not stopping school. \'a0He catched me a couple of\
times and thrashed me, but I went to school just the same, and dodged\
him or outrun him most of the time. \'a0I didn\'92t want to go to school much\
before, but I reckoned I\'92d go now to spite pap. \'a0That law trial was a\
slow business--appeared like they warn\'92t ever going to get started on it;\
so every now and then I\'92d borrow two or three dollars off of the judge\
for him, to keep from getting a cowhiding. \'a0Every time he got money he\
got drunk; and every time he got drunk he raised Cain around town; and\
every time he raised Cain he got jailed. \'a0He was just suited--this kind\
of thing was right in his line.\
\
He got to hanging around the widow\'92s too much and so she told him at\
last that if he didn\'92t quit using around there she would make trouble\
for him. Well, _wasn\'92t_ he mad? \'a0He said he would show who was Huck\
Finn\'92s boss. \'a0So he watched out for me one day in the spring, and\
catched me, and took me up the river about three mile in a skiff, and\
crossed over to the Illinois shore where it was woody and there warn\'92t\
no houses but an old log hut in a place where the timber was so thick\
you couldn\'92t find it if you didn\'92t know where it was.\
\
He kept me with him all the time, and I never got a chance to run off.\
We lived in that old cabin, and he always locked the door and put the\
key under his head nights. \'a0He had a gun which he had stole, I reckon,\
and we fished and hunted, and that was what we lived on. \'a0Every little\
while he locked me in and went down to the store, three miles, to the\
ferry, and traded fish and game for whisky, and fetched it home and got\
drunk and had a good time, and licked me. \'a0The widow she found out where\
I was by and by, and she sent a man over to try to get hold of me; but\
pap drove him off with the gun, and it warn\'92t long after that till I was\
used to being where I was, and liked it--all but the cowhide part.\
\
It was kind of lazy and jolly, laying off comfortable all day, smoking\
and fishing, and no books nor study. \'a0Two months or more run along, and\
my clothes got to be all rags and dirt, and I didn\'92t see how I\'92d ever\
got to like it so well at the widow\'92s, where you had to wash, and eat on\
a plate, and comb up, and go to bed and get up regular, and be forever\
bothering over a book, and have old Miss Watson pecking at you all the\
time. \'a0I didn\'92t want to go back no more. \'a0I had stopped cussing, because\
the widow didn\'92t like it; but now I took to it again because pap hadn\'92t\
no objections. \'a0It was pretty good times up in the woods there, take it\
all around.\
\
But by and by pap got too handy with his hick\'92ry, and I couldn\'92t stand\
it. I was all over welts. \'a0He got to going away so much, too, and\
locking me in. \'a0Once he locked me in and was gone three days. \'a0It was\
dreadful lonesome. \'a0I judged he had got drownded, and I wasn\'92t ever\
going to get out any more. \'a0I was scared. \'a0I made up my mind I would fix\
up some way to leave there. \'a0I had tried to get out of that cabin many\
a time, but I couldn\'92t find no way. \'a0There warn\'92t a window to it big\
enough for a dog to get through. \'a0I couldn\'92t get up the chimbly; it\
was too narrow. \'a0The door was thick, solid oak slabs. \'a0Pap was pretty\
careful not to leave a knife or anything in the cabin when he was away;\
I reckon I had hunted the place over as much as a hundred times; well, I\
was most all the time at it, because it was about the only way to put in\
the time. \'a0But this time I found something at last; I found an old rusty\
wood-saw without any handle; it was laid in between a rafter and the\
clapboards of the roof. I greased it up and went to work. \'a0There was an\
old horse-blanket nailed against the logs at the far end of the cabin\
behind the table, to keep the wind from blowing through the chinks and\
putting the candle out. \'a0I got under the table and raised the blanket,\
and went to work to saw a section of the big bottom log out--big enough\
to let me through. \'a0Well, it was a good long job, but I was getting\
towards the end of it when I heard pap\'92s gun in the woods. \'a0I got rid of\
the signs of my work, and dropped the blanket and hid my saw, and pretty\
soon pap come in.\
\
Pap warn\'92t in a good humor--so he was his natural self. \'a0He said he was\
down town, and everything was going wrong. \'a0His lawyer said he reckoned\
he would win his lawsuit and get the money if they ever got started on\
the trial; but then there was ways to put it off a long time, and Judge\
Thatcher knowed how to do it. And he said people allowed there\'92d be\
another trial to get me away from him and give me to the widow for my\
guardian, and they guessed it would win this time. \'a0This shook me up\
considerable, because I didn\'92t want to go back to the widow\'92s any more\
and be so cramped up and sivilized, as they called it. \'a0Then the old man\
got to cussing, and cussed everything and everybody he could think of,\
and then cussed them all over again to make sure he hadn\'92t skipped any,\
and after that he polished off with a kind of a general cuss all round,\
including a considerable parcel of people which he didn\'92t know the names\
of, and so called them what\'92s-his-name when he got to them, and went\
right along with his cussing.\
\
He said he would like to see the widow get me. \'a0He said he would watch\
out, and if they tried to come any such game on him he knowed of a place\
six or seven mile off to stow me in, where they might hunt till they\
dropped and they couldn\'92t find me. \'a0That made me pretty uneasy again,\
but only for a minute; I reckoned I wouldn\'92t stay on hand till he got\
that chance.\
\
The old man made me go to the skiff and fetch the things he had\
got. There was a fifty-pound sack of corn meal, and a side of bacon,\
ammunition, and a four-gallon jug of whisky, and an old book and two\
newspapers for wadding, besides some tow. \'a0I toted up a load, and went\
back and set down on the bow of the skiff to rest. \'a0I thought it all\
over, and I reckoned I would walk off with the gun and some lines, and\
take to the woods when I run away. \'a0I guessed I wouldn\'92t stay in one\
place, but just tramp right across the country, mostly night times, and\
hunt and fish to keep alive, and so get so far away that the old man nor\
the widow couldn\'92t ever find me any more. \'a0I judged I would saw out and\
leave that night if pap got drunk enough, and I reckoned he would. \'a0I\
got so full of it I didn\'92t notice how long I was staying till the old\
man hollered and asked me whether I was asleep or drownded.\
\
I got the things all up to the cabin, and then it was about dark. \'a0While\
I was cooking supper the old man took a swig or two and got sort of\
warmed up, and went to ripping again. \'a0He had been drunk over in town,\
and laid in the gutter all night, and he was a sight to look at. \'a0A body\
would a thought he was Adam--he was just all mud. \'a0Whenever his liquor\
begun to work he most always went for the govment, this time he says:\
\
\'93Call this a govment! why, just look at it and see what it\'92s like.\
Here\'92s the law a-standing ready to take a man\'92s son away from him--a\
man\'92s own son, which he has had all the trouble and all the anxiety\
and all the expense of raising. \'a0Yes, just as that man has got that\
son raised at last, and ready to go to work and begin to do suthin\'92 for\
_him_ and give him a rest, the law up and goes for him. \'a0And they call\
_that_ govment! \'a0That ain\'92t all, nuther. \'a0The law backs that old Judge\
Thatcher up and helps him to keep me out o\'92 my property. \'a0Here\'92s what\
the law does: \'a0The law takes a man worth six thousand dollars and\
up\'92ards, and jams him into an old trap of a cabin like this, and lets\
him go round in clothes that ain\'92t fitten for a hog. They call that\
govment! \'a0A man can\'92t get his rights in a govment like this. Sometimes\
I\'92ve a mighty notion to just leave the country for good and all. Yes,\
and I _told_ \'91em so; I told old Thatcher so to his face. \'a0Lots of \'91em\
heard me, and can tell what I said. \'a0Says I, for two cents I\'92d leave the\
blamed country and never come a-near it agin. \'a0Them\'92s the very words. \'a0I\
says look at my hat--if you call it a hat--but the lid raises up and the\
rest of it goes down till it\'92s below my chin, and then it ain\'92t rightly\
a hat at all, but more like my head was shoved up through a jint o\'92\
stove-pipe. \'a0Look at it, says I--such a hat for me to wear--one of the\
wealthiest men in this town if I could git my rights.\
\
\'93Oh, yes, this is a wonderful govment, wonderful. \'a0Why, looky here.\
There was a free nigger there from Ohio--a mulatter, most as white as\
a white man. \'a0He had the whitest shirt on you ever see, too, and the\
shiniest hat; and there ain\'92t a man in that town that\'92s got as fine\
clothes as what he had; and he had a gold watch and chain, and a\
silver-headed cane--the awfulest old gray-headed nabob in the State. \'a0And\
what do you think? \'a0They said he was a p\'92fessor in a college, and could\
talk all kinds of languages, and knowed everything. \'a0And that ain\'92t the\
wust. They said he could _vote_ when he was at home. \'a0Well, that let me\
out. Thinks I, what is the country a-coming to? \'a0It was \'91lection day,\
and I was just about to go and vote myself if I warn\'92t too drunk to get\
there; but when they told me there was a State in this country where\
they\'92d let that nigger vote, I drawed out. \'a0I says I\'92ll never vote agin.\
\'a0Them\'92s the very words I said; they all heard me; and the country may\
rot for all me--I\'92ll never vote agin as long as I live. \'a0And to see the\
cool way of that nigger--why, he wouldn\'92t a give me the road if I hadn\'92t\
shoved him out o\'92 the way. \'a0I says to the people, why ain\'92t this nigger\
put up at auction and sold?--that\'92s what I want to know. \'a0And what do you\
reckon they said? Why, they said he couldn\'92t be sold till he\'92d been in\
the State six months, and he hadn\'92t been there that long yet. \'a0There,\
now--that\'92s a specimen. \'a0They call that a govment that can\'92t sell a free\
nigger till he\'92s been in the State six months. \'a0Here\'92s a govment that\
calls itself a govment, and lets on to be a govment, and thinks it is a\
govment, and yet\'92s got to set stock-still for six whole months before\
it can take a hold of a prowling, thieving, infernal, white-shirted free\
nigger, and--\'94\
\
Pap was agoing on so he never noticed where his old limber legs was\
taking him to, so he went head over heels over the tub of salt pork and\
barked both shins, and the rest of his speech was all the hottest kind\
of language--mostly hove at the nigger and the govment, though he give\
the tub some, too, all along, here and there. \'a0He hopped around the\
cabin considerable, first on one leg and then on the other, holding\
first one shin and then the other one, and at last he let out with his\
left foot all of a sudden and fetched the tub a rattling kick. \'a0But it\
warn\'92t good judgment, because that was the boot that had a couple of his\
toes leaking out of the front end of it; so now he raised a howl that\
fairly made a body\'92s hair raise, and down he went in the dirt, and\
rolled there, and held his toes; and the cussing he done then laid over\
anything he had ever done previous. \'a0He said so his own self afterwards.\
\'a0He had heard old Sowberry Hagan in his best days, and he said it laid\
over him, too; but I reckon that was sort of piling it on, maybe.\
\
After supper pap took the jug, and said he had enough whisky there\
for two drunks and one delirium tremens. \'a0That was always his word. \'a0I\
judged he would be blind drunk in about an hour, and then I would steal\
the key, or saw myself out, one or t\'92other. \'a0He drank and drank, and\
tumbled down on his blankets by and by; but luck didn\'92t run my way.\
\'a0He didn\'92t go sound asleep, but was uneasy. \'a0He groaned and moaned and\
thrashed around this way and that for a long time. \'a0At last I got so\
sleepy I couldn\'92t keep my eyes open all I could do, and so before I\
knowed what I was about I was sound asleep, and the candle burning.\
\
I don\'92t know how long I was asleep, but all of a sudden there was an\
awful scream and I was up. \'a0There was pap looking wild, and skipping\
around every which way and yelling about snakes. \'a0He said they was\
crawling up his legs; and then he would give a jump and scream, and say\
one had bit him on the cheek--but I couldn\'92t see no snakes. \'a0He started\
and run round and round the cabin, hollering \'93Take him off! take him\
off! he\'92s biting me on the neck!\'94 \'a0I never see a man look so wild in the\
eyes. Pretty soon he was all fagged out, and fell down panting; then he\
rolled over and over wonderful fast, kicking things every which way,\
and striking and grabbing at the air with his hands, and screaming and\
saying there was devils a-hold of him. \'a0He wore out by and by, and laid\
still a while, moaning. \'a0Then he laid stiller, and didn\'92t make a sound.\
\'a0I could hear the owls and the wolves away off in the woods, and it\
seemed terrible still. \'a0He was laying over by the corner. By and by he\
raised up part way and listened, with his head to one side. \'a0He says,\
very low:\
\
\'93Tramp--tramp--tramp; that\'92s the dead; tramp--tramp--tramp; they\'92re coming\
after me; but I won\'92t go. \'a0Oh, they\'92re here! don\'92t touch me--don\'92t! hands\
off--they\'92re cold; let go. \'a0Oh, let a poor devil alone!\'94\
\
Then he went down on all fours and crawled off, begging them to let him\
alone, and he rolled himself up in his blanket and wallowed in under the\
old pine table, still a-begging; and then he went to crying. \'a0I could\
hear him through the blanket.\
\
By and by he rolled out and jumped up on his feet looking wild, and he\
see me and went for me. \'a0He chased me round and round the place with a\
clasp-knife, calling me the Angel of Death, and saying he would kill me,\
and then I couldn\'92t come for him no more. \'a0I begged, and told him I\
was only Huck; but he laughed _such_ a screechy laugh, and roared and\
cussed, and kept on chasing me up. \'a0Once when I turned short and\
dodged under his arm he made a grab and got me by the jacket between my\
shoulders, and I thought I was gone; but I slid out of the jacket quick\
as lightning, and saved myself. Pretty soon he was all tired out, and\
dropped down with his back against the door, and said he would rest a\
minute and then kill me. He put his knife under him, and said he would\
sleep and get strong, and then he would see who was who.\
\
So he dozed off pretty soon. \'a0By and by I got the old split-bottom chair\
and clumb up as easy as I could, not to make any noise, and got down the\
gun. \'a0I slipped the ramrod down it to make sure it was loaded, then I\
laid it across the turnip barrel, pointing towards pap, and set down\
behind it to wait for him to stir. \'a0And how slow and still the time did\
drag along.\
\
