\
CHAPTER VII.\
\
\'93GIT up! \'a0What you \'91bout?\'94\
\
I opened my eyes and looked around, trying to make out where I was. \'a0It\
was after sun-up, and I had been sound asleep. \'a0Pap was standing over me\
looking sour and sick, too. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93What you doin\'92 with this gun?\'94\
\
I judged he didn\'92t know nothing about what he had been doing, so I says:\
\
\'93Somebody tried to get in, so I was laying for him.\'94\
\
\'93Why didn\'92t you roust me out?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I tried to, but I couldn\'92t; I couldn\'92t budge you.\'94\
\
\'93Well, all right. \'a0Don\'92t stand there palavering all day, but out with\
you and see if there\'92s a fish on the lines for breakfast. \'a0I\'92ll be along\
in a minute.\'94\
\
He unlocked the door, and I cleared out up the river-bank. \'a0I noticed\
some pieces of limbs and such things floating down, and a sprinkling of\
bark; so I knowed the river had begun to rise. \'a0I reckoned I would have\
great times now if I was over at the town. \'a0The June rise used to be\
always luck for me; because as soon as that rise begins here comes\
cordwood floating down, and pieces of log rafts--sometimes a dozen logs\
together; so all you have to do is to catch them and sell them to the\
wood-yards and the sawmill.\
\
I went along up the bank with one eye out for pap and t\'92other one out\
for what the rise might fetch along. \'a0Well, all at once here comes a\
canoe; just a beauty, too, about thirteen or fourteen foot long, riding\
high like a duck. \'a0I shot head-first off of the bank like a frog,\
clothes and all on, and struck out for the canoe. \'a0I just expected\
there\'92d be somebody laying down in it, because people often done that\
to fool folks, and when a chap had pulled a skiff out most to it they\'92d\
raise up and laugh at him. \'a0But it warn\'92t so this time. \'a0It was a\
drift-canoe sure enough, and I clumb in and paddled her ashore. \'a0Thinks\
I, the old man will be glad when he sees this--she\'92s worth ten dollars.\
\'a0But when I got to shore pap wasn\'92t in sight yet, and as I was running\
her into a little creek like a gully, all hung over with vines and\
willows, I struck another idea: \'a0I judged I\'92d hide her good, and then,\
\'91stead of taking to the woods when I run off, I\'92d go down the river\
about fifty mile and camp in one place for good, and not have such a\
rough time tramping on foot.\
\
It was pretty close to the shanty, and I thought I heard the old man\
coming all the time; but I got her hid; and then I out and looked around\
a bunch of willows, and there was the old man down the path a piece just\
drawing a bead on a bird with his gun. \'a0So he hadn\'92t seen anything.\
\
When he got along I was hard at it taking up a \'93trot\'94 line. \'a0He abused\
me a little for being so slow; but I told him I fell in the river, and\
that was what made me so long. \'a0I knowed he would see I was wet, and\
then he would be asking questions. \'a0We got five catfish off the lines\
and went home.\
\
While we laid off after breakfast to sleep up, both of us being about\
wore out, I got to thinking that if I could fix up some way to keep pap\
and the widow from trying to follow me, it would be a certainer thing\
than trusting to luck to get far enough off before they missed me; you\
see, all kinds of things might happen. \'a0Well, I didn\'92t see no way for a\
while, but by and by pap raised up a minute to drink another barrel of\
water, and he says:\
\
\'93Another time a man comes a-prowling round here you roust me out, you\
hear? That man warn\'92t here for no good. \'a0I\'92d a shot him. \'a0Next time you\
roust me out, you hear?\'94\
\
Then he dropped down and went to sleep again; but what he had been\
saying give me the very idea I wanted. \'a0I says to myself, I can fix it\
now so nobody won\'92t think of following me.\
\
About twelve o\'92clock we turned out and went along up the bank. \'a0The\
river was coming up pretty fast, and lots of driftwood going by on the\
rise. By and by along comes part of a log raft--nine logs fast together.\
\'a0We went out with the skiff and towed it ashore. \'a0Then we had dinner.\
Anybody but pap would a waited and seen the day through, so as to catch\
more stuff; but that warn\'92t pap\'92s style. \'a0Nine logs was enough for one\
time; he must shove right over to town and sell. \'a0So he locked me in and\
took the skiff, and started off towing the raft about half-past three.\
\'a0I judged he wouldn\'92t come back that night. \'a0I waited till I reckoned he\
had got a good start; then I out with my saw, and went to work on that\
log again. \'a0Before he was t\'92other side of the river I was out of the\
hole; him and his raft was just a speck on the water away off yonder.\
\
I took the sack of corn meal and took it to where the canoe was hid, and\
shoved the vines and branches apart and put it in; then I done the same\
with the side of bacon; then the whisky-jug. \'a0I took all the coffee and\
sugar there was, and all the ammunition; I took the wadding; I took the\
bucket and gourd; I took a dipper and a tin cup, and my old saw and two\
blankets, and the skillet and the coffee-pot. \'a0I took fish-lines and\
matches and other things--everything that was worth a cent. \'a0I cleaned\
out the place. \'a0I wanted an axe, but there wasn\'92t any, only the one out\
at the woodpile, and I knowed why I was going to leave that. \'a0I fetched\
out the gun, and now I was done.\
\
I had wore the ground a good deal crawling out of the hole and dragging\
out so many things. \'a0So I fixed that as good as I could from the outside\
by scattering dust on the place, which covered up the smoothness and the\
sawdust. \'a0Then I fixed the piece of log back into its place, and put two\
rocks under it and one against it to hold it there, for it was bent up\
at that place and didn\'92t quite touch ground. \'a0If you stood four or five\
foot away and didn\'92t know it was sawed, you wouldn\'92t never notice\
it; and besides, this was the back of the cabin, and it warn\'92t likely\
anybody would go fooling around there.\
\
It was all grass clear to the canoe, so I hadn\'92t left a track. \'a0I\
followed around to see. \'a0I stood on the bank and looked out over the\
river. \'a0All safe. \'a0So I took the gun and went up a piece into the woods,\
and was hunting around for some birds when I see a wild pig; hogs soon\
went wild in them bottoms after they had got away from the prairie\
farms. I shot this fellow and took him into camp.\
\
I took the axe and smashed in the door. \'a0I beat it and hacked it\
considerable a-doing it. \'a0I fetched the pig in, and took him back nearly\
to the table and hacked into his throat with the axe, and laid him down\
on the ground to bleed; I say ground because it was ground--hard packed,\
and no boards. \'a0Well, next I took an old sack and put a lot of big rocks\
in it--all I could drag--and I started it from the pig, and dragged it to\
the door and through the woods down to the river and dumped it in, and\
down it sunk, out of sight. \'a0You could easy see that something had been\
dragged over the ground. \'a0I did wish Tom Sawyer was there; I knowed he\
would take an interest in this kind of business, and throw in the fancy\
touches. \'a0Nobody could spread himself like Tom Sawyer in such a thing as\
that.\
\
Well, last I pulled out some of my hair, and blooded the axe good, and\
stuck it on the back side, and slung the axe in the corner. \'a0Then I\
took up the pig and held him to my breast with my jacket (so he couldn\'92t\
drip) till I got a good piece below the house and then dumped him into\
the river. \'a0Now I thought of something else. \'a0So I went and got the bag\
of meal and my old saw out of the canoe, and fetched them to the house.\
\'a0I took the bag to where it used to stand, and ripped a hole in the\
bottom of it with the saw, for there warn\'92t no knives and forks on the\
place--pap done everything with his clasp-knife about the cooking. \'a0Then\
I carried the sack about a hundred yards across the grass and through\
the willows east of the house, to a shallow lake that was five mile wide\
and full of rushes--and ducks too, you might say, in the season. \'a0There\
was a slough or a creek leading out of it on the other side that went\
miles away, I don\'92t know where, but it didn\'92t go to the river. \'a0The meal\
sifted out and made a little track all the way to the lake. \'a0I dropped\
pap\'92s whetstone there too, so as to look like it had been done by\
accident. Then I tied up the rip in the meal sack with a string, so it\
wouldn\'92t leak no more, and took it and my saw to the canoe again.\
\
It was about dark now; so I dropped the canoe down the river under some\
willows that hung over the bank, and waited for the moon to rise. \'a0I\
made fast to a willow; then I took a bite to eat, and by and by laid\
down in the canoe to smoke a pipe and lay out a plan. \'a0I says to myself,\
they\'92ll follow the track of that sackful of rocks to the shore and then\
drag the river for me. \'a0And they\'92ll follow that meal track to the lake\
and go browsing down the creek that leads out of it to find the robbers\
that killed me and took the things. \'a0They won\'92t ever hunt the river for\
anything but my dead carcass. They\'92ll soon get tired of that, and won\'92t\
bother no more about me. \'a0All right; I can stop anywhere I want to.\
Jackson\'92s Island is good enough for me; I know that island pretty well,\
and nobody ever comes there. \'a0And then I can paddle over to town nights,\
and slink around and pick up things I want. Jackson\'92s Island\'92s the\
place.\
\
I was pretty tired, and the first thing I knowed I was asleep. \'a0When\
I woke up I didn\'92t know where I was for a minute. \'a0I set up and looked\
around, a little scared. \'a0Then I remembered. \'a0The river looked miles and\
miles across. \'a0The moon was so bright I could a counted the drift logs\
that went a-slipping along, black and still, hundreds of yards out from\
shore. Everything was dead quiet, and it looked late, and _smelt_ late.\
You know what I mean--I don\'92t know the words to put it in.\
\
I took a good gap and a stretch, and was just going to unhitch and start\
when I heard a sound away over the water. \'a0I listened. \'a0Pretty soon I\
made it out. \'a0It was that dull kind of a regular sound that comes from\
oars working in rowlocks when it\'92s a still night. \'a0I peeped out through\
the willow branches, and there it was--a skiff, away across the water.\
\'a0I couldn\'92t tell how many was in it. \'a0It kept a-coming, and when it was\
abreast of me I see there warn\'92t but one man in it. \'a0Think\'92s I, maybe\
it\'92s pap, though I warn\'92t expecting him. \'a0He dropped below me with the\
current, and by and by he came a-swinging up shore in the easy water,\
and he went by so close I could a reached out the gun and touched him.\
\'a0Well, it _was_ pap, sure enough--and sober, too, by the way he laid his\
oars.\
\
I didn\'92t lose no time. \'a0The next minute I was a-spinning down stream\
soft but quick in the shade of the bank. \'a0I made two mile and a half,\
and then struck out a quarter of a mile or more towards the middle of\
the river, because pretty soon I would be passing the ferry landing, and\
people might see me and hail me. \'a0I got out amongst the driftwood, and\
then laid down in the bottom of the canoe and let her float.\
\
\'a0I laid there, and had a good rest and a smoke out of my pipe, looking\
away into the sky; not a cloud in it. \'a0The sky looks ever so deep when\
you lay down on your back in the moonshine; I never knowed it before.\
\'a0And how far a body can hear on the water such nights! \'a0I heard people\
talking at the ferry landing. I heard what they said, too--every word\
of it. \'a0One man said it was getting towards the long days and the short\
nights now. \'a0T\'92other one said _this_ warn\'92t one of the short ones, he\
reckoned--and then they laughed, and he said it over again, and they\
laughed again; then they waked up another fellow and told him, and\
laughed, but he didn\'92t laugh; he ripped out something brisk, and said\
let him alone. \'a0The first fellow said he \'91lowed to tell it to his\
old woman--she would think it was pretty good; but he said that warn\'92t\
nothing to some things he had said in his time. I heard one man say it\
was nearly three o\'92clock, and he hoped daylight wouldn\'92t wait more than\
about a week longer. \'a0After that the talk got further and further away,\
and I couldn\'92t make out the words any more; but I could hear the mumble,\
and now and then a laugh, too, but it seemed a long ways off.\
\
I was away below the ferry now. \'a0I rose up, and there was Jackson\'92s\
Island, about two mile and a half down stream, heavy timbered and\
standing up out of the middle of the river, big and dark and solid, like\
a steamboat without any lights. \'a0There warn\'92t any signs of the bar at\
the head--it was all under water now.\
\
It didn\'92t take me long to get there. \'a0I shot past the head at a ripping\
rate, the current was so swift, and then I got into the dead water and\
landed on the side towards the Illinois shore. \'a0I run the canoe into\
a deep dent in the bank that I knowed about; I had to part the willow\
branches to get in; and when I made fast nobody could a seen the canoe\
from the outside.\
\
I went up and set down on a log at the head of the island, and looked\
out on the big river and the black driftwood and away over to the town,\
three mile away, where there was three or four lights twinkling. \'a0A\
monstrous big lumber-raft was about a mile up stream, coming along down,\
with a lantern in the middle of it. \'a0I watched it come creeping down,\
and when it was most abreast of where I stood I heard a man say, \'93Stern\
oars, there! heave her head to stabboard!\'94 \'a0I heard that just as plain\
as if the man was by my side.\
\
There was a little gray in the sky now; so I stepped into the woods, and\
laid down for a nap before breakfast.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER VIII.\
\
THE sun was up so high when I waked that I judged it was after eight\
o\'92clock. \'a0I laid there in the grass and the cool shade thinking about\
things, and feeling rested and ruther comfortable and satisfied. \'a0I\
could see the sun out at one or two holes, but mostly it was big trees\
all about, and gloomy in there amongst them. \'a0There was freckled places\
on the ground where the light sifted down through the leaves, and the\
freckled places swapped about a little, showing there was a little\
breeze up there. \'a0A couple of squirrels set on a limb and jabbered at me\
very friendly.\
\
I was powerful lazy and comfortable--didn\'92t want to get up and cook\
breakfast. \'a0Well, I was dozing off again when I thinks I hears a deep\
sound of \'93boom!\'94 away up the river. \'a0I rouses up, and rests on my elbow\
and listens; pretty soon I hears it again. \'a0I hopped up, and went and\
looked out at a hole in the leaves, and I see a bunch of smoke laying\
on the water a long ways up--about abreast the ferry. \'a0And there was the\
ferryboat full of people floating along down. \'a0I knowed what was the\
matter now.  \'93Boom!\'94 I see the white smoke squirt out of the ferryboat\'92s\
side. \'a0You see, they was firing cannon over the water, trying to make my\
carcass come to the top.\
\
I was pretty hungry, but it warn\'92t going to do for me to start a fire,\
because they might see the smoke. \'a0So I set there and watched the\
cannon-smoke and listened to the boom. \'a0The river was a mile wide there,\
and it always looks pretty on a summer morning--so I was having a good\
enough time seeing them hunt for my remainders if I only had a bite to\
eat. Well, then I happened to think how they always put quicksilver in\
loaves of bread and float them off, because they always go right to the\
drownded carcass and stop there. \'a0So, says I, I\'92ll keep a lookout, and\
if any of them\'92s floating around after me I\'92ll give them a show. \'a0I\
changed to the Illinois edge of the island to see what luck I could\
have, and I warn\'92t disappointed. \'a0A big double loaf come along, and I\
most got it with a long stick, but my foot slipped and she floated out\
further. \'a0Of course I was where the current set in the closest to the\
shore--I knowed enough for that. \'a0But by and by along comes another one,\
and this time I won. \'a0I took out the plug and shook out the little dab\
of quicksilver, and set my teeth in. \'a0It was \'93baker\'92s bread\'94--what the\
quality eat; none of your low-down corn-pone.\
\
I got a good place amongst the leaves, and set there on a log, munching\
the bread and watching the ferry-boat, and very well satisfied. \'a0And\
then something struck me. \'a0I says, now I reckon the widow or the parson\
or somebody prayed that this bread would find me, and here it has gone\
and done it. \'a0So there ain\'92t no doubt but there is something in that\
thing--that is, there\'92s something in it when a body like the widow or the\
parson prays, but it don\'92t work for me, and I reckon it don\'92t work for\
only just the right kind.\
\
I lit a pipe and had a good long smoke, and went on watching. \'a0The\
ferryboat was floating with the current, and I allowed I\'92d have a chance\
to see who was aboard when she come along, because she would come in\
close, where the bread did. \'a0When she\'92d got pretty well along down\
towards me, I put out my pipe and went to where I fished out the bread,\
and laid down behind a log on the bank in a little open place. \'a0Where\
the log forked I could peep through.\
\
By and by she come along, and she drifted in so close that they could\
a run out a plank and walked ashore. \'a0Most everybody was on the boat.\
\'a0Pap, and Judge Thatcher, and Bessie Thatcher, and Jo Harper, and Tom\
Sawyer, and his old Aunt Polly, and Sid and Mary, and plenty more.\
\'a0Everybody was talking about the murder, but the captain broke in and\
says:\
\
\'93Look sharp, now; the current sets in the closest here, and maybe he\'92s\
washed ashore and got tangled amongst the brush at the water\'92s edge. \'a0I\
hope so, anyway.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t hope so. \'a0They all crowded up and leaned over the rails, nearly\
in my face, and kept still, watching with all their might. \'a0I could see\
them first-rate, but they couldn\'92t see me. \'a0Then the captain sung out:\
\
\'93Stand away!\'94 and the cannon let off such a blast right before me that\
it made me deef with the noise and pretty near blind with the smoke, and\
I judged I was gone. \'a0If they\'92d a had some bullets in, I reckon they\'92d\
a got the corpse they was after. \'a0Well, I see I warn\'92t hurt, thanks to\
goodness. The boat floated on and went out of sight around the shoulder\
of the island. \'a0I could hear the booming now and then, further and\
further off, and by and by, after an hour, I didn\'92t hear it no more.\
\'a0The island was three mile long. \'a0I judged they had got to the foot, and\
was giving it up. \'a0But they didn\'92t yet a while. \'a0They turned around\
the foot of the island and started up the channel on the Missouri side,\
under steam, and booming once in a while as they went. \'a0I crossed over\
to that side and watched them. When they got abreast the head of the\
island they quit shooting and dropped over to the Missouri shore and\
went home to the town.\
\
I knowed I was all right now. \'a0Nobody else would come a-hunting after\
me. I got my traps out of the canoe and made me a nice camp in the thick\
woods. \'a0I made a kind of a tent out of my blankets to put my things\
under so the rain couldn\'92t get at them. \'a0I catched a catfish and haggled\
him open with my saw, and towards sundown I started my camp fire and had\
supper. \'a0Then I set out a line to catch some fish for breakfast.\
\
When it was dark I set by my camp fire smoking, and feeling pretty well\
satisfied; but by and by it got sort of lonesome, and so I went and set\
on the bank and listened to the current swashing along, and counted the\
stars and drift logs and rafts that come down, and then went to bed;\
there ain\'92t no better way to put in time when you are lonesome; you\
can\'92t stay so, you soon get over it.\
\
And so for three days and nights. \'a0No difference--just the same thing.\
But the next day I went exploring around down through the island. \'a0I was\
boss of it; it all belonged to me, so to say, and I wanted to know\
all about it; but mainly I wanted to put in the time. \'a0I found plenty\
strawberries, ripe and prime; and green summer grapes, and green\
razberries; and the green blackberries was just beginning to show. \'a0They\
would all come handy by and by, I judged.\
\
Well, I went fooling along in the deep woods till I judged I warn\'92t\
far from the foot of the island. \'a0I had my gun along, but I hadn\'92t shot\
nothing; it was for protection; thought I would kill some game nigh\
home. About this time I mighty near stepped on a good-sized snake,\
and it went sliding off through the grass and flowers, and I after\
it, trying to get a shot at it. I clipped along, and all of a sudden I\
bounded right on to the ashes of a camp fire that was still smoking.\
\
My heart jumped up amongst my lungs. \'a0I never waited for to look\
further, but uncocked my gun and went sneaking back on my tiptoes as\
fast as ever I could. \'a0Every now and then I stopped a second amongst the\
thick leaves and listened, but my breath come so hard I couldn\'92t hear\
nothing else. \'a0I slunk along another piece further, then listened again;\
and so on, and so on. \'a0If I see a stump, I took it for a man; if I trod\
on a stick and broke it, it made me feel like a person had cut one of my\
breaths in two and I only got half, and the short half, too.\
\
When I got to camp I warn\'92t feeling very brash, there warn\'92t much sand\
in my craw; but I says, this ain\'92t no time to be fooling around. \'a0So I\
got all my traps into my canoe again so as to have them out of sight,\
and I put out the fire and scattered the ashes around to look like an\
old last year\'92s camp, and then clumb a tree.\
\
I reckon I was up in the tree two hours; but I didn\'92t see nothing,\
I didn\'92t hear nothing--I only _thought_ I heard and seen as much as a\
thousand things. \'a0Well, I couldn\'92t stay up there forever; so at last I\
got down, but I kept in the thick woods and on the lookout all the\
time. All I could get to eat was berries and what was left over from\
breakfast.\
\
By the time it was night I was pretty hungry. \'a0So when it was good\
and dark I slid out from shore before moonrise and paddled over to the\
Illinois bank--about a quarter of a mile. \'a0I went out in the woods and\
cooked a supper, and I had about made up my mind I would stay there\
all night when I hear a _plunkety-plunk, plunkety-plunk_, and says\
to myself, horses coming; and next I hear people\'92s voices. \'a0I got\
everything into the canoe as quick as I could, and then went creeping\
through the woods to see what I could find out. \'a0I hadn\'92t got far when I\
hear a man say:\
\
\'93We better camp here if we can find a good place; the horses is about\
beat out. \'a0Let\'92s look around.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t wait, but shoved out and paddled away easy. \'a0I tied up in the\
old place, and reckoned I would sleep in the canoe.\
\
I didn\'92t sleep much. \'a0I couldn\'92t, somehow, for thinking. \'a0And every time\
I waked up I thought somebody had me by the neck. \'a0So the sleep didn\'92t\
do me no good. \'a0By and by I says to myself, I can\'92t live this way; I\'92m\
a-going to find out who it is that\'92s here on the island with me; I\'92ll\
find it out or bust. \'a0Well, I felt better right off.\
\
So I took my paddle and slid out from shore just a step or two, and\
then let the canoe drop along down amongst the shadows. \'a0The moon was\
shining, and outside of the shadows it made it most as light as day.\
\'a0I poked along well on to an hour, everything still as rocks and sound\
asleep. Well, by this time I was most down to the foot of the island. \'a0A\
little ripply, cool breeze begun to blow, and that was as good as saying\
the night was about done. \'a0I give her a turn with the paddle and brung\
her nose to shore; then I got my gun and slipped out and into the edge\
of the woods. \'a0I sat down there on a log, and looked out through the\
leaves. \'a0I see the moon go off watch, and the darkness begin to blanket\
the river. But in a little while I see a pale streak over the treetops,\
and knowed the day was coming. \'a0So I took my gun and slipped off towards\
where I had run across that camp fire, stopping every minute or two\
to listen. \'a0But I hadn\'92t no luck somehow; I couldn\'92t seem to find the\
place. \'a0But by and by, sure enough, I catched a glimpse of fire away\
through the trees. \'a0I went for it, cautious and slow. \'a0By and by I was\
close enough to have a look, and there laid a man on the ground. \'a0It\
most give me the fan-tods. He had a blanket around his head, and his\
head was nearly in the fire. \'a0I set there behind a clump of bushes, in\
about six foot of him, and kept my eyes on him steady. \'a0It was getting\
gray daylight now. \'a0Pretty soon he gapped and stretched himself and hove\
off the blanket, and it was Miss Watson\'92s Jim! \'a0I bet I was glad to see\
him. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Hello, Jim!\'94 and skipped out.\
\
He bounced up and stared at me wild. \'a0Then he drops down on his knees,\
and puts his hands together and says:\
\
\'93Doan\'92 hurt me--don\'92t! \'a0I hain\'92t ever done no harm to a ghos\'92. \'a0I alwuz\
liked dead people, en done all I could for \'91em. \'a0You go en git in de\
river agin, whah you b\'92longs, en doan\'92 do nuffn to Ole Jim, \'91at \'91uz\
awluz yo\'92 fren\'92.\'94\
\
Well, I warn\'92t long making him understand I warn\'92t dead. \'a0I was ever so\
glad to see Jim. \'a0I warn\'92t lonesome now. \'a0I told him I warn\'92t afraid of\
_him_ telling the people where I was. \'a0I talked along, but he only set\
there and looked at me; never said nothing. \'a0Then I says:\
\
\'93It\'92s good daylight. \'a0Le\'92s get breakfast. \'a0Make up your camp fire good.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s de use er makin\'92 up de camp fire to cook strawbries en sich\
truck? But you got a gun, hain\'92t you? \'a0Den we kin git sumfn better den\
strawbries.\'94\
\
\'93Strawberries and such truck,\'94 I says.  \'93Is that what you live on?\'94\
\
\'93I couldn\'92 git nuffn else,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93Why, how long you been on the island, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93I come heah de night arter you\'92s killed.\'94\
\
\'93What, all that time?\'94\
\
\'93Yes--indeedy.\'94\
\
\'93And ain\'92t you had nothing but that kind of rubbage to eat?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah--nuffn else.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you must be most starved, ain\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93I reck\'92n I could eat a hoss. \'a0I think I could. How long you ben on de\
islan\'92?\'94\
\
\'93Since the night I got killed.\'94\
\
\'93No! \'a0W\'92y, what has you lived on? \'a0But you got a gun. \'a0Oh, yes, you got\
a gun. \'a0Dat\'92s good. \'a0Now you kill sumfn en I\'92ll make up de fire.\'94\
\
So we went over to where the canoe was, and while he built a fire in\
a grassy open place amongst the trees, I fetched meal and bacon and\
coffee, and coffee-pot and frying-pan, and sugar and tin cups, and the\
nigger was set back considerable, because he reckoned it was all done\
with witchcraft. I catched a good big catfish, too, and Jim cleaned him\
with his knife, and fried him.\
\
When breakfast was ready we lolled on the grass and eat it smoking hot.\
Jim laid it in with all his might, for he was most about starved. \'a0Then\
when we had got pretty well stuffed, we laid off and lazied. \'a0By and by\
Jim says:\
\
\'93But looky here, Huck, who wuz it dat \'91uz killed in dat shanty ef it\
warn\'92t you?\'94\
\
Then I told him the whole thing, and he said it was smart. \'a0He said Tom\
Sawyer couldn\'92t get up no better plan than what I had. \'a0Then I says:\
\
\'93How do you come to be here, Jim, and how\'92d you get here?\'94\
\
He looked pretty uneasy, and didn\'92t say nothing for a minute. \'a0Then he\
says:\
\
\'93Maybe I better not tell.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Well, dey\'92s reasons. \'a0But you wouldn\'92 tell on me ef I uz to tell you,\
would you, Huck?\'94\
\
\'93Blamed if I would, Jim.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I b\'92lieve you, Huck. \'a0I--_I run off_.\'94\
\
\'93Jim!\'94\
\
\'93But mind, you said you wouldn\'92 tell--you know you said you wouldn\'92 tell,\
Huck.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I did. \'a0I said I wouldn\'92t, and I\'92ll stick to it. \'a0Honest _injun_,\
I will. \'a0People would call me a low-down Abolitionist and despise me for\
keeping mum--but that don\'92t make no difference. \'a0I ain\'92t a-going to tell,\
and I ain\'92t a-going back there, anyways. \'a0So, now, le\'92s know all about\
it.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you see, it \'91uz dis way. \'a0Ole missus--dat\'92s Miss Watson--she pecks\
on me all de time, en treats me pooty rough, but she awluz said she\
wouldn\'92 sell me down to Orleans. \'a0But I noticed dey wuz a nigger trader\
roun\'92 de place considable lately, en I begin to git oneasy. \'a0Well, one\
night I creeps to de do\'92 pooty late, en de do\'92 warn\'92t quite shet, en I\
hear old missus tell de widder she gwyne to sell me down to Orleans, but\
she didn\'92 want to, but she could git eight hund\'92d dollars for me, en it\
\'91uz sich a big stack o\'92 money she couldn\'92 resis\'92. \'a0De widder she try to\
git her to say she wouldn\'92 do it, but I never waited to hear de res\'92. \'a0I\
lit out mighty quick, I tell you.\
\
\'93I tuck out en shin down de hill, en \'91spec to steal a skift \'91long de\
sho\'92 som\'92ers \'91bove de town, but dey wuz people a-stirring yit, so I hid\
in de ole tumble-down cooper-shop on de bank to wait for everybody to\
go \'91way. Well, I wuz dah all night. \'a0Dey wuz somebody roun\'92 all de time.\
 \'91Long \'91bout six in de mawnin\'92 skifts begin to go by, en \'91bout eight er\
nine every skift dat went \'91long wuz talkin\'92 \'91bout how yo\'92 pap come over\
to de town en say you\'92s killed. \'a0Dese las\'92 skifts wuz full o\'92 ladies en\
genlmen a-goin\'92 over for to see de place. \'a0Sometimes dey\'92d pull up at\
de sho\'92 en take a res\'92 b\'92fo\'92 dey started acrost, so by de talk I got to\
know all \'91bout de killin\'92. \'a0I \'91uz powerful sorry you\'92s killed, Huck, but\
I ain\'92t no mo\'92 now.\
\
\'93I laid dah under de shavin\'92s all day. \'a0I \'91uz hungry, but I warn\'92t\
afeard; bekase I knowed ole missus en de widder wuz goin\'92 to start to\
de camp-meet\'92n\'92 right arter breakfas\'92 en be gone all day, en dey knows\
I goes off wid de cattle \'91bout daylight, so dey wouldn\'92 \'91spec to see me\
roun\'92 de place, en so dey wouldn\'92 miss me tell arter dark in de evenin\'92.\
De yuther servants wouldn\'92 miss me, kase dey\'92d shin out en take holiday\
soon as de ole folks \'91uz out\'92n de way.\
\
\'93Well, when it come dark I tuck out up de river road, en went \'91bout two\
mile er more to whah dey warn\'92t no houses. \'a0I\'92d made up my mine \'91bout\
what I\'92s agwyne to do. \'a0You see, ef I kep\'92 on tryin\'92 to git away afoot,\
de dogs \'91ud track me; ef I stole a skift to cross over, dey\'92d miss dat\
skift, you see, en dey\'92d know \'91bout whah I\'92d lan\'92 on de yuther side, en\
whah to pick up my track. \'a0So I says, a raff is what I\'92s arter; it doan\'92\
_make_ no track.\
\
\'93I see a light a-comin\'92 roun\'92 de p\'92int bymeby, so I wade\'92 in en shove\'92\
a log ahead o\'92 me en swum more\'92n half way acrost de river, en got in\
\'91mongst de drift-wood, en kep\'92 my head down low, en kinder swum agin de\
current tell de raff come along. \'a0Den I swum to de stern uv it en tuck\
a-holt. \'a0It clouded up en \'91uz pooty dark for a little while. \'a0So I clumb\
up en laid down on de planks. \'a0De men \'91uz all \'91way yonder in de middle,\
whah de lantern wuz. \'a0De river wuz a-risin\'92, en dey wuz a good current;\
so I reck\'92n\'92d \'91at by fo\'92 in de mawnin\'92 I\'92d be twenty-five mile down de\
river, en den I\'92d slip in jis b\'92fo\'92 daylight en swim asho\'92, en take to\
de woods on de Illinois side.\
\
\'93But I didn\'92 have no luck. \'a0When we \'91uz mos\'92 down to de head er de\
islan\'92 a man begin to come aft wid de lantern, I see it warn\'92t no use\
fer to wait, so I slid overboard en struck out fer de islan\'92. \'a0Well, I\
had a notion I could lan\'92 mos\'92 anywhers, but I couldn\'92t--bank too bluff.\
\'a0I \'91uz mos\'92 to de foot er de islan\'92 b\'92fo\'92 I found\'92 a good place. \'a0I went\
into de woods en jedged I wouldn\'92 fool wid raffs no mo\'92, long as dey\
move de lantern roun\'92 so. \'a0I had my pipe en a plug er dog-leg, en some\
matches in my cap, en dey warn\'92t wet, so I \'91uz all right.\'94\
\
\'93And so you ain\'92t had no meat nor bread to eat all this time? \'a0Why\
didn\'92t you get mud-turkles?\'94\
\
\'93How you gwyne to git \'91m? \'a0You can\'92t slip up on um en grab um; en how\'92s\
a body gwyne to hit um wid a rock? \'a0How could a body do it in de night?\
\'a0En I warn\'92t gwyne to show mysef on de bank in de daytime.\'94\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s so. \'a0You\'92ve had to keep in the woods all the time, of\
course. Did you hear \'91em shooting the cannon?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. \'a0I knowed dey was arter you. \'a0I see um go by heah--watched um\
thoo de bushes.\'94\
\
Some young birds come along, flying a yard or two at a time and\
lighting. Jim said it was a sign it was going to rain. \'a0He said it was\
a sign when young chickens flew that way, and so he reckoned it was the\
same way when young birds done it. \'a0I was going to catch some of them,\
but Jim wouldn\'92t let me. \'a0He said it was death. \'a0He said his father laid\
mighty sick once, and some of them catched a bird, and his old granny\
said his father would die, and he did.\
\
And Jim said you mustn\'92t count the things you are going to cook for\
dinner, because that would bring bad luck. \'a0The same if you shook the\
table-cloth after sundown. \'a0And he said if a man owned a beehive\
and that man died, the bees must be told about it before sun-up next\
morning, or else the bees would all weaken down and quit work and die.\
\'a0Jim said bees wouldn\'92t sting idiots; but I didn\'92t believe that, because\
I had tried them lots of times myself, and they wouldn\'92t sting me.\
\
I had heard about some of these things before, but not all of them. \'a0Jim\
knowed all kinds of signs. \'a0He said he knowed most everything. \'a0I said\
it looked to me like all the signs was about bad luck, and so I asked\
him if there warn\'92t any good-luck signs. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Mighty few--an\'92 _dey_ ain\'92t no use to a body. \'a0What you want to know\
when good luck\'92s a-comin\'92 for? \'a0Want to keep it off?\'94 \'a0And he said:  \'93Ef\
you\'92s got hairy arms en a hairy breas\'92, it\'92s a sign dat you\'92s agwyne\
to be rich. Well, dey\'92s some use in a sign like dat, \'91kase it\'92s so fur\
ahead. You see, maybe you\'92s got to be po\'92 a long time fust, en so you\
might git discourage\'92 en kill yo\'92sef \'91f you didn\'92 know by de sign dat\
you gwyne to be rich bymeby.\'94\
\
\'93Have you got hairy arms and a hairy breast, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s de use to ax dat question? \'a0Don\'92t you see I has?\'94\
\
\'93Well, are you rich?\'94\
\
\'93No, but I ben rich wunst, and gwyne to be rich agin. \'a0Wunst I had\
foteen dollars, but I tuck to specalat\'92n\'92, en got busted out.\'94\
\
\'93What did you speculate in, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Well, fust I tackled stock.\'94\
\
\'93What kind of stock?\'94\
\
\'93Why, live stock--cattle, you know. \'a0I put ten dollars in a cow. \'a0But\
I ain\'92 gwyne to resk no mo\'92 money in stock. \'a0De cow up \'91n\'92 died on my\
han\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93So you lost the ten dollars.\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t lose it all. \'a0I on\'92y los\'92 \'91bout nine of it. \'a0I sole de\
hide en taller for a dollar en ten cents.\'94\
\
\'93You had five dollars and ten cents left. \'a0Did you speculate any more?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. \'a0You know that one-laigged nigger dat b\'92longs to old Misto\
Bradish? Well, he sot up a bank, en say anybody dat put in a dollar\
would git fo\'92 dollars mo\'92 at de en\'92 er de year. \'a0Well, all de niggers\
went in, but dey didn\'92t have much. \'a0I wuz de on\'92y one dat had much. \'a0So\
I stuck out for mo\'92 dan fo\'92 dollars, en I said \'91f I didn\'92 git it I\'92d\
start a bank mysef. Well, o\'92 course dat nigger want\'92 to keep me out er\
de business, bekase he says dey warn\'92t business \'91nough for two banks, so\
he say I could put in my five dollars en he pay me thirty-five at de en\'92\
er de year.\
\
\'93So I done it. \'a0Den I reck\'92n\'92d I\'92d inves\'92 de thirty-five dollars right\
off en keep things a-movin\'92. \'a0Dey wuz a nigger name\'92 Bob, dat had\
ketched a wood-flat, en his marster didn\'92 know it; en I bought it off\'92n\
him en told him to take de thirty-five dollars when de en\'92 er de\
year come; but somebody stole de wood-flat dat night, en nex day de\
one-laigged nigger say de bank\'92s busted. \'a0So dey didn\'92 none uv us git no\
money.\'94\
\
\'93What did you do with the ten cents, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I \'91uz gwyne to spen\'92 it, but I had a dream, en de dream tole me\
to give it to a nigger name\'92 Balum--Balum\'92s Ass dey call him for short;\
he\'92s one er dem chuckleheads, you know. \'a0But he\'92s lucky, dey say, en I\
see I warn\'92t lucky. \'a0De dream say let Balum inves\'92 de ten cents en he\'92d\
make a raise for me. \'a0Well, Balum he tuck de money, en when he wuz in\
church he hear de preacher say dat whoever give to de po\'92 len\'92 to de\
Lord, en boun\'92 to git his money back a hund\'92d times. \'a0So Balum he tuck\
en give de ten cents to de po\'92, en laid low to see what wuz gwyne to\
come of it.\'94\
\
\'93Well, what did come of it, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Nuffn never come of it. \'a0I couldn\'92 manage to k\'92leck dat money no way;\
en Balum he couldn\'92. \'a0I ain\'92 gwyne to len\'92 no mo\'92 money \'91dout I see de\
security. \'a0Boun\'92 to git yo\'92 money back a hund\'92d times, de preacher says!\
Ef I could git de ten _cents_ back, I\'92d call it squah, en be glad er de\
chanst.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it\'92s all right anyway, Jim, long as you\'92re going to be rich again\
some time or other.\'94\
\
\'93Yes; en I\'92s rich now, come to look at it. \'a0I owns mysef, en I\'92s wuth\
eight hund\'92d dollars. \'a0I wisht I had de money, I wouldn\'92 want no mo\'92.\'94\
\
\
