\
CHAPTER IX.\
\
I wanted to go and look at a place right about the middle of the island\
that I\'92d found when I was exploring; so we started and soon got to it,\
because the island was only three miles long and a quarter of a mile\
wide.\
\
This place was a tolerable long, steep hill or ridge about forty foot\
high. We had a rough time getting to the top, the sides was so steep and\
the bushes so thick. \'a0We tramped and clumb around all over it, and by\
and by found a good big cavern in the rock, most up to the top on the\
side towards Illinois. \'a0The cavern was as big as two or three rooms\
bunched together, and Jim could stand up straight in it. \'a0It was cool in\
there. Jim was for putting our traps in there right away, but I said we\
didn\'92t want to be climbing up and down there all the time.\
\
Jim said if we had the canoe hid in a good place, and had all the traps\
in the cavern, we could rush there if anybody was to come to the island,\
and they would never find us without dogs. \'a0And, besides, he said them\
little birds had said it was going to rain, and did I want the things to\
get wet?\
\
So we went back and got the canoe, and paddled up abreast the cavern,\
and lugged all the traps up there. \'a0Then we hunted up a place close by\
to hide the canoe in, amongst the thick willows. \'a0We took some fish off\
of the lines and set them again, and begun to get ready for dinner.\
\
The door of the cavern was big enough to roll a hogshead in, and on one\
side of the door the floor stuck out a little bit, and was flat and a\
good place to build a fire on. \'a0So we built it there and cooked dinner.\
\
We spread the blankets inside for a carpet, and eat our dinner in there.\
We put all the other things handy at the back of the cavern. \'a0Pretty\
soon it darkened up, and begun to thunder and lighten; so the birds was\
right about it. \'a0Directly it begun to rain, and it rained like all fury,\
too, and I never see the wind blow so. \'a0It was one of these regular\
summer storms. \'a0It would get so dark that it looked all blue-black\
outside, and lovely; and the rain would thrash along by so thick that\
the trees off a little ways looked dim and spider-webby; and here would\
come a blast of wind that would bend the trees down and turn up the\
pale underside of the leaves; and then a perfect ripper of a gust would\
follow along and set the branches to tossing their arms as if they\
was just wild; and next, when it was just about the bluest and\
blackest--_FST_! it was as bright as glory, and you\'92d have a little\
glimpse of tree-tops a-plunging about away off yonder in the storm,\
hundreds of yards further than you could see before; dark as sin again\
in a second, and now you\'92d hear the thunder let go with an awful crash,\
and then go rumbling, grumbling, tumbling, down the sky towards the\
under side of the world, like rolling empty barrels down stairs--where\
it\'92s long stairs and they bounce a good deal, you know.\
\
\'93Jim, this is nice,\'94 I says.  \'93I wouldn\'92t want to be nowhere else but\
here. Pass me along another hunk of fish and some hot corn-bread.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you wouldn\'92t a ben here \'91f it hadn\'92t a ben for Jim. \'a0You\'92d a ben\
down dah in de woods widout any dinner, en gittn\'92 mos\'92 drownded, too;\
dat you would, honey. \'a0Chickens knows when it\'92s gwyne to rain, en so do\
de birds, chile.\'94\
\
The river went on raising and raising for ten or twelve days, till at\
last it was over the banks. \'a0The water was three or four foot deep on\
the island in the low places and on the Illinois bottom. \'a0On that side\
it was a good many miles wide, but on the Missouri side it was the same\
old distance across--a half a mile--because the Missouri shore was just a\
wall of high bluffs.\
\
Daytimes we paddled all over the island in the canoe, It was mighty cool\
and shady in the deep woods, even if the sun was blazing outside. \'a0We\
went winding in and out amongst the trees, and sometimes the vines hung\
so thick we had to back away and go some other way. \'a0Well, on every old\
broken-down tree you could see rabbits and snakes and such things; and\
when the island had been overflowed a day or two they got so tame, on\
account of being hungry, that you could paddle right up and put your\
hand on them if you wanted to; but not the snakes and turtles--they would\
slide off in the water. \'a0The ridge our cavern was in was full of them.\
We could a had pets enough if we\'92d wanted them.\
\
One night we catched a little section of a lumber raft--nice pine planks.\
It was twelve foot wide and about fifteen or sixteen foot long, and\
the top stood above water six or seven inches--a solid, level floor. \'a0We\
could see saw-logs go by in the daylight sometimes, but we let them go;\
we didn\'92t show ourselves in daylight.\
\
Another night when we was up at the head of the island, just before\
daylight, here comes a frame-house down, on the west side. \'a0She was\
a two-story, and tilted over considerable. \'a0We paddled out and got\
aboard--clumb in at an upstairs window. \'a0But it was too dark to see yet,\
so we made the canoe fast and set in her to wait for daylight.\
\
The light begun to come before we got to the foot of the island. \'a0Then\
we looked in at the window. \'a0We could make out a bed, and a table, and\
two old chairs, and lots of things around about on the floor, and there\
was clothes hanging against the wall. \'a0There was something laying on the\
floor in the far corner that looked like a man. \'a0So Jim says:\
\
\'93Hello, you!\'94\
\
But it didn\'92t budge. \'a0So I hollered again, and then Jim says:\
\
\'93De man ain\'92t asleep--he\'92s dead. \'a0You hold still--I\'92ll go en see.\'94\
\
He went, and bent down and looked, and says:\
\
\'93It\'92s a dead man. \'a0Yes, indeedy; naked, too. \'a0He\'92s ben shot in de back.\
I reck\'92n he\'92s ben dead two er three days. \'a0Come in, Huck, but doan\'92 look\
at his face--it\'92s too gashly.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t look at him at all. \'a0Jim throwed some old rags over him, but\
he needn\'92t done it; I didn\'92t want to see him. \'a0There was heaps of old\
greasy cards scattered around over the floor, and old whisky bottles,\
and a couple of masks made out of black cloth; and all over the walls\
was the ignorantest kind of words and pictures made with charcoal.\
\'a0There was two old dirty calico dresses, and a sun-bonnet, and some\
women\'92s underclothes hanging against the wall, and some men\'92s clothing,\
too. \'a0We put the lot into the canoe--it might come good. \'a0There was a\
boy\'92s old speckled straw hat on the floor; I took that, too. \'a0And there\
was a bottle that had had milk in it, and it had a rag stopper for a\
baby to suck. \'a0We would a took the bottle, but it was broke. \'a0There was\
a seedy old chest, and an old hair trunk with the hinges broke. \'a0They\
stood open, but there warn\'92t nothing left in them that was any account.\
\'a0The way things was scattered about we reckoned the people left in a\
hurry, and warn\'92t fixed so as to carry off most of their stuff.\
\
We got an old tin lantern, and a butcher-knife without any handle, and\
a bran-new Barlow knife worth two bits in any store, and a lot of tallow\
candles, and a tin candlestick, and a gourd, and a tin cup, and a ratty\
old bedquilt off the bed, and a reticule with needles and pins and\
beeswax and buttons and thread and all such truck in it, and a hatchet\
and some nails, and a fishline as thick as my little finger with some\
monstrous hooks on it, and a roll of buckskin, and a leather dog-collar,\
and a horseshoe, and some vials of medicine that didn\'92t have no label\
on them; and just as we was leaving I found a tolerable good curry-comb,\
and Jim he found a ratty old fiddle-bow, and a wooden leg. \'a0The straps\
was broke off of it, but, barring that, it was a good enough leg, though\
it was too long for me and not long enough for Jim, and we couldn\'92t find\
the other one, though we hunted all around.\
\
And so, take it all around, we made a good haul. \'a0When we was ready to\
shove off we was a quarter of a mile below the island, and it was pretty\
broad day; so I made Jim lay down in the canoe and cover up with the\
quilt, because if he set up people could tell he was a nigger a good\
ways off. \'a0I paddled over to the Illinois shore, and drifted down most\
a half a mile doing it. \'a0I crept up the dead water under the bank, and\
hadn\'92t no accidents and didn\'92t see nobody. \'a0We got home all safe.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER X.\
\
AFTER breakfast I wanted to talk about the dead man and guess out how he\
come to be killed, but Jim didn\'92t want to. \'a0He said it would fetch bad\
luck; and besides, he said, he might come and ha\'92nt us; he said a man\
that warn\'92t buried was more likely to go a-ha\'92nting around than one\
that was planted and comfortable. \'a0That sounded pretty reasonable, so\
I didn\'92t say no more; but I couldn\'92t keep from studying over it and\
wishing I knowed who shot the man, and what they done it for.\
\
We rummaged the clothes we\'92d got, and found eight dollars in silver\
sewed up in the lining of an old blanket overcoat. \'a0Jim said he reckoned\
the people in that house stole the coat, because if they\'92d a knowed the\
money was there they wouldn\'92t a left it. \'a0I said I reckoned they killed\
him, too; but Jim didn\'92t want to talk about that. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Now you think it\'92s bad luck; but what did you say when I fetched in the\
snake-skin that I found on the top of the ridge day before yesterday?\
You said it was the worst bad luck in the world to touch a snake-skin\
with my hands. \'a0Well, here\'92s your bad luck! \'a0We\'92ve raked in all this\
truck and eight dollars besides. \'a0I wish we could have some bad luck\
like this every day, Jim.\'94\
\
\'93Never you mind, honey, never you mind. \'a0Don\'92t you git too peart. \'a0It\'92s\
a-comin\'92. \'a0Mind I tell you, it\'92s a-comin\'92.\'94\
\
It did come, too. \'a0It was a Tuesday that we had that talk. \'a0Well, after\
dinner Friday we was laying around in the grass at the upper end of the\
ridge, and got out of tobacco. \'a0I went to the cavern to get some, and\
found a rattlesnake in there. \'a0I killed him, and curled him up on the\
foot of Jim\'92s blanket, ever so natural, thinking there\'92d be some fun\
when Jim found him there. \'a0Well, by night I forgot all about the snake,\
and when Jim flung himself down on the blanket while I struck a light\
the snake\'92s mate was there, and bit him.\
\
He jumped up yelling, and the first thing the light showed was the\
varmint curled up and ready for another spring. \'a0I laid him out in a\
second with a stick, and Jim grabbed pap\'92s whisky-jug and begun to pour\
it down.\
\
He was barefooted, and the snake bit him right on the heel. \'a0That all\
comes of my being such a fool as to not remember that wherever you leave\
a dead snake its mate always comes there and curls around it. \'a0Jim told\
me to chop off the snake\'92s head and throw it away, and then skin the\
body and roast a piece of it. \'a0I done it, and he eat it and said it\
would help cure him. He made me take off the rattles and tie them around\
his wrist, too. \'a0He said that that would help. \'a0Then I slid out quiet\
and throwed the snakes clear away amongst the bushes; for I warn\'92t going\
to let Jim find out it was all my fault, not if I could help it.\
\
Jim sucked and sucked at the jug, and now and then he got out of his\
head and pitched around and yelled; but every time he come to himself he\
went to sucking at the jug again. \'a0His foot swelled up pretty big, and\
so did his leg; but by and by the drunk begun to come, and so I judged\
he was all right; but I\'92d druther been bit with a snake than pap\'92s\
whisky.\
\
Jim was laid up for four days and nights. \'a0Then the swelling was all\
gone and he was around again. \'a0I made up my mind I wouldn\'92t ever take\
a-holt of a snake-skin again with my hands, now that I see what had come\
of it. Jim said he reckoned I would believe him next time. \'a0And he said\
that handling a snake-skin was such awful bad luck that maybe we hadn\'92t\
got to the end of it yet. \'a0He said he druther see the new moon over his\
left shoulder as much as a thousand times than take up a snake-skin\
in his hand. \'a0Well, I was getting to feel that way myself, though I\'92ve\
always reckoned that looking at the new moon over your left shoulder is\
one of the carelessest and foolishest things a body can do. \'a0Old Hank\
Bunker done it once, and bragged about it; and in less than two years he\
got drunk and fell off of the shot-tower, and spread himself out so\
that he was just a kind of a layer, as you may say; and they slid him\
edgeways between two barn doors for a coffin, and buried him so, so\
they say, but I didn\'92t see it. \'a0Pap told me. \'a0But anyway it all come of\
looking at the moon that way, like a fool.\
\
Well, the days went along, and the river went down between its banks\
again; and about the first thing we done was to bait one of the big\
hooks with a skinned rabbit and set it and catch a catfish that was\
as big as a man, being six foot two inches long, and weighed over two\
hundred pounds. We couldn\'92t handle him, of course; he would a flung us\
into Illinois. \'a0We just set there and watched him rip and tear around\
till he drownded. \'a0We found a brass button in his stomach and a round\
ball, and lots of rubbage. \'a0We split the ball open with the hatchet,\
and there was a spool in it. \'a0Jim said he\'92d had it there a long time, to\
coat it over so and make a ball of it. \'a0It was as big a fish as was ever\
catched in the Mississippi, I reckon. \'a0Jim said he hadn\'92t ever seen\
a bigger one. \'a0He would a been worth a good deal over at the village.\
\'a0They peddle out such a fish as that by the pound in the market-house\
there; everybody buys some of him; his meat\'92s as white as snow and makes\
a good fry.\
\
Next morning I said it was getting slow and dull, and I wanted to get a\
stirring up some way. \'a0I said I reckoned I would slip over the river and\
find out what was going on. \'a0Jim liked that notion; but he said I\
must go in the dark and look sharp. \'a0Then he studied it over and said,\
couldn\'92t I put on some of them old things and dress up like a girl?\
\'a0That was a good notion, too. \'a0So we shortened up one of the calico\
gowns, and I turned up my trouser-legs to my knees and got into it. \'a0Jim\
hitched it behind with the hooks, and it was a fair fit. \'a0I put on the\
sun-bonnet and tied it under my chin, and then for a body to look in\
and see my face was like looking down a joint of stove-pipe. \'a0Jim said\
nobody would know me, even in the daytime, hardly. \'a0I practiced around\
all day to get the hang of the things, and by and by I could do pretty\
well in them, only Jim said I didn\'92t walk like a girl; and he said\
I must quit pulling up my gown to get at my britches-pocket. \'a0I took\
notice, and done better.\
\
I started up the Illinois shore in the canoe just after dark.\
\
I started across to the town from a little below the ferry-landing, and\
the drift of the current fetched me in at the bottom of the town. \'a0I\
tied up and started along the bank. \'a0There was a light burning in a\
little shanty that hadn\'92t been lived in for a long time, and I wondered\
who had took up quarters there. \'a0I slipped up and peeped in at the\
window. \'a0There was a woman about forty year old in there knitting by\
a candle that was on a pine table. \'a0I didn\'92t know her face; she was a\
stranger, for you couldn\'92t start a face in that town that I didn\'92t know.\
\'a0Now this was lucky, because I was weakening; I was getting afraid I had\
come; people might know my voice and find me out. \'a0But if this woman had\
been in such a little town two days she could tell me all I wanted to\
know; so I knocked at the door, and made up my mind I wouldn\'92t forget I\
was a girl.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XI.\
\
\'93COME in,\'94 says the woman, and I did. \'a0She says:  \'93Take a cheer.\'94\
\
I done it. \'a0She looked me all over with her little shiny eyes, and says:\
\
\'93What might your name be?\'94\
\
\'93Sarah Williams.\'94\
\
\'93Where \'91bouts do you live? \'a0In this neighborhood?\'92\
\
\'93No\'92m. \'a0In Hookerville, seven mile below. \'a0I\'92ve walked all the way and\
I\'92m all tired out.\'94\
\
\'93Hungry, too, I reckon. \'a0I\'92ll find you something.\'94\
\
\'93No\'92m, I ain\'92t hungry. \'a0I was so hungry I had to stop two miles below\
here at a farm; so I ain\'92t hungry no more. \'a0It\'92s what makes me so late.\
My mother\'92s down sick, and out of money and everything, and I come to\
tell my uncle Abner Moore. \'a0He lives at the upper end of the town, she\
says. \'a0I hain\'92t ever been here before. \'a0Do you know him?\'94\
\
\'93No; but I don\'92t know everybody yet. \'a0I haven\'92t lived here quite two\
weeks. It\'92s a considerable ways to the upper end of the town. \'a0You\
better stay here all night. \'a0Take off your bonnet.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I says; \'93I\'92ll rest a while, I reckon, and go on. \'a0I ain\'92t afeared\
of the dark.\'94\
\
She said she wouldn\'92t let me go by myself, but her husband would be in\
by and by, maybe in a hour and a half, and she\'92d send him along with me.\
Then she got to talking about her husband, and about her relations up\
the river, and her relations down the river, and about how much better\
off they used to was, and how they didn\'92t know but they\'92d made a mistake\
coming to our town, instead of letting well alone--and so on and so on,\
till I was afeard I had made a mistake coming to her to find out what\
was going on in the town; but by and by she dropped on to pap and the\
murder, and then I was pretty willing to let her clatter right along.\
\'a0She told about me and Tom Sawyer finding the six thousand dollars (only\
she got it ten) and all about pap and what a hard lot he was, and what\
a hard lot I was, and at last she got down to where I was murdered. \'a0I\
says:\
\
\'93Who done it? \'a0We\'92ve heard considerable about these goings on down in\
Hookerville, but we don\'92t know who \'91twas that killed Huck Finn.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I reckon there\'92s a right smart chance of people _here_ that\'92d\
like to know who killed him. \'a0Some think old Finn done it himself.\'94\
\
\'93No--is that so?\'94\
\
\'93Most everybody thought it at first. \'a0He\'92ll never know how nigh he come\
to getting lynched. \'a0But before night they changed around and judged it\
was done by a runaway nigger named Jim.\'94\
\
\'93Why _he_--\'94\
\
I stopped. \'a0I reckoned I better keep still. \'a0She run on, and never\
noticed I had put in at all:\
\
\'93The nigger run off the very night Huck Finn was killed. \'a0So there\'92s a\
reward out for him--three hundred dollars. \'a0And there\'92s a reward out for\
old Finn, too--two hundred dollars. \'a0You see, he come to town the\
morning after the murder, and told about it, and was out with \'91em on the\
ferryboat hunt, and right away after he up and left. \'a0Before night they\
wanted to lynch him, but he was gone, you see. \'a0Well, next day they\
found out the nigger was gone; they found out he hadn\'92t ben seen sence\
ten o\'92clock the night the murder was done. \'a0So then they put it on him,\
you see; and while they was full of it, next day, back comes old Finn,\
and went boo-hooing to Judge Thatcher to get money to hunt for the\
nigger all over Illinois with. The judge gave him some, and that evening\
he got drunk, and was around till after midnight with a couple of mighty\
hard-looking strangers, and then went off with them. \'a0Well, he hain\'92t\
come back sence, and they ain\'92t looking for him back till this thing\
blows over a little, for people thinks now that he killed his boy and\
fixed things so folks would think robbers done it, and then he\'92d get\
Huck\'92s money without having to bother a long time with a lawsuit.\
\'a0People do say he warn\'92t any too good to do it. \'a0Oh, he\'92s sly, I reckon.\
\'a0If he don\'92t come back for a year he\'92ll be all right. \'a0You can\'92t prove\
anything on him, you know; everything will be quieted down then, and\
he\'92ll walk in Huck\'92s money as easy as nothing.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I reckon so, \'91m. \'a0I don\'92t see nothing in the way of it. \'a0Has\
everybody quit thinking the nigger done it?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, no, not everybody. \'a0A good many thinks he done it. \'a0But they\'92ll get\
the nigger pretty soon now, and maybe they can scare it out of him.\'94\
\
\'93Why, are they after him yet?\'94\
\
\'93Well, you\'92re innocent, ain\'92t you! \'a0Does three hundred dollars lay\
around every day for people to pick up? \'a0Some folks think the nigger\
ain\'92t far from here. \'a0I\'92m one of them--but I hain\'92t talked it around. \'a0A\
few days ago I was talking with an old couple that lives next door in\
the log shanty, and they happened to say hardly anybody ever goes to\
that island over yonder that they call Jackson\'92s Island. \'a0Don\'92t anybody\
live there? says I. No, nobody, says they. \'a0I didn\'92t say any more, but\
I done some thinking. \'a0I was pretty near certain I\'92d seen smoke over\
there, about the head of the island, a day or two before that, so I says\
to myself, like as not that nigger\'92s hiding over there; anyway, says\
I, it\'92s worth the trouble to give the place a hunt. \'a0I hain\'92t seen any\
smoke sence, so I reckon maybe he\'92s gone, if it was him; but husband\'92s\
going over to see--him and another man. \'a0He was gone up the river; but he\
got back to-day, and I told him as soon as he got here two hours ago.\'94\
\
I had got so uneasy I couldn\'92t set still. \'a0I had to do something with my\
hands; so I took up a needle off of the table and went to threading\
it. My hands shook, and I was making a bad job of it. \'a0When the woman\
stopped talking I looked up, and she was looking at me pretty curious\
and smiling a little. \'a0I put down the needle and thread, and let on to\
be interested--and I was, too--and says:\
\
\'93Three hundred dollars is a power of money. \'a0I wish my mother could get\
it. Is your husband going over there to-night?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes. \'a0He went up-town with the man I was telling you of, to get a\
boat and see if they could borrow another gun. \'a0They\'92ll go over after\
midnight.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t they see better if they was to wait till daytime?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. \'a0And couldn\'92t the nigger see better, too? \'a0After midnight he\'92ll\
likely be asleep, and they can slip around through the woods and hunt up\
his camp fire all the better for the dark, if he\'92s got one.\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t think of that.\'94\
\
The woman kept looking at me pretty curious, and I didn\'92t feel a bit\
comfortable. \'a0Pretty soon she says,\
\
\'93What did you say your name was, honey?\'94\
\
\'93M--Mary Williams.\'94\
\
Somehow it didn\'92t seem to me that I said it was Mary before, so I didn\'92t\
look up--seemed to me I said it was Sarah; so I felt sort of cornered,\
and was afeared maybe I was looking it, too. \'a0I wished the woman would\
say something more; the longer she set still the uneasier I was. \'a0But\
now she says:\
\
\'93Honey, I thought you said it was Sarah when you first come in?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes\'92m, I did. \'a0Sarah Mary Williams. \'a0Sarah\'92s my first name. \'a0Some\
calls me Sarah, some calls me Mary.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, that\'92s the way of it?\'94\
\
\'93Yes\'92m.\'94\
\
I was feeling better then, but I wished I was out of there, anyway. \'a0I\
couldn\'92t look up yet.\
\
Well, the woman fell to talking about how hard times was, and how poor\
they had to live, and how the rats was as free as if they owned the\
place, and so forth and so on, and then I got easy again. \'a0She was right\
about the rats. You\'92d see one stick his nose out of a hole in the corner\
every little while. \'a0She said she had to have things handy to throw at\
them when she was alone, or they wouldn\'92t give her no peace. \'a0She showed\
me a bar of lead twisted up into a knot, and said she was a good shot\
with it generly, but she\'92d wrenched her arm a day or two ago, and didn\'92t\
know whether she could throw true now. \'a0But she watched for a chance,\
and directly banged away at a rat; but she missed him wide, and said\
\'93Ouch!\'94 it hurt her arm so. \'a0Then she told me to try for the next one.\
\'a0I wanted to be getting away before the old man got back, but of course\
I didn\'92t let on. \'a0I got the thing, and the first rat that showed his\
nose I let drive, and if he\'92d a stayed where he was he\'92d a been a\
tolerable sick rat. \'a0She said that was first-rate, and she reckoned I\
would hive the next one. \'a0She went and got the lump of lead and fetched\
it back, and brought along a hank of yarn which she wanted me to help\
her with. \'a0I held up my two hands and she put the hank over them, and\
went on talking about her and her husband\'92s matters. \'a0But she broke off\
to say:\
\
\'93Keep your eye on the rats. \'a0You better have the lead in your lap,\
handy.\'94\
\
So she dropped the lump into my lap just at that moment, and I clapped\
my legs together on it and she went on talking. \'a0But only about a\
minute. Then she took off the hank and looked me straight in the face,\
and very pleasant, and says:\
\
\'93Come, now, what\'92s your real name?\'94\
\
\'93Wh--what, mum?\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s your real name? \'a0Is it Bill, or Tom, or Bob?--or what is it?\'94\
\
I reckon I shook like a leaf, and I didn\'92t know hardly what to do. \'a0But\
I says:\
\
\'93Please to don\'92t poke fun at a poor girl like me, mum. \'a0If I\'92m in the\
way here, I\'92ll--\'94\
\
\'93No, you won\'92t. \'a0Set down and stay where you are. \'a0I ain\'92t going to hurt\
you, and I ain\'92t going to tell on you, nuther. \'a0You just tell me your\
secret, and trust me. \'a0I\'92ll keep it; and, what\'92s more, I\'92ll help\
you. So\'92ll my old man if you want him to. \'a0You see, you\'92re a runaway\
\'91prentice, that\'92s all. \'a0It ain\'92t anything. \'a0There ain\'92t no harm in it.\
You\'92ve been treated bad, and you made up your mind to cut. \'a0Bless you,\
child, I wouldn\'92t tell on you. \'a0Tell me all about it now, that\'92s a good\
boy.\'94\
\
So I said it wouldn\'92t be no use to try to play it any longer, and I\
would just make a clean breast and tell her everything, but she musn\'92t\
go back on her promise. \'a0Then I told her my father and mother was dead,\
and the law had bound me out to a mean old farmer in the country thirty\
mile back from the river, and he treated me so bad I couldn\'92t stand it\
no longer; he went away to be gone a couple of days, and so I took my\
chance and stole some of his daughter\'92s old clothes and cleared out, and\
I had been three nights coming the thirty miles. \'a0I traveled nights,\
and hid daytimes and slept, and the bag of bread and meat I carried from\
home lasted me all the way, and I had a-plenty. \'a0I said I believed my\
uncle Abner Moore would take care of me, and so that was why I struck\
out for this town of Goshen.\
\
\'93Goshen, child? \'a0This ain\'92t Goshen. \'a0This is St. Petersburg. \'a0Goshen\'92s\
ten mile further up the river. \'a0Who told you this was Goshen?\'94\
\
\'93Why, a man I met at daybreak this morning, just as I was going to turn\
into the woods for my regular sleep. \'a0He told me when the roads forked I\
must take the right hand, and five mile would fetch me to Goshen.\'94\
\
\'93He was drunk, I reckon. \'a0He told you just exactly wrong.\'94\
\
\'93Well, he did act like he was drunk, but it ain\'92t no matter now. \'a0I got\
to be moving along. \'a0I\'92ll fetch Goshen before daylight.\'94\
\
\'93Hold on a minute. \'a0I\'92ll put you up a snack to eat. \'a0You might want it.\'94\
\
So she put me up a snack, and says:\
\
\'93Say, when a cow\'92s laying down, which end of her gets up first? \'a0Answer\
up prompt now--don\'92t stop to study over it. \'a0Which end gets up first?\'94\
\
\'93The hind end, mum.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, a horse?\'94\
\
\'93The for\'92rard end, mum.\'94\
\
\'93Which side of a tree does the moss grow on?\'94\
\
\'93North side.\'94\
\
\'93If fifteen cows is browsing on a hillside, how many of them eats with\
their heads pointed the same direction?\'94\
\
\'93The whole fifteen, mum.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I reckon you _have_ lived in the country. \'a0I thought maybe you\
was trying to hocus me again. \'a0What\'92s your real name, now?\'94\
\
\'93George Peters, mum.\'94\
\
\'93Well, try to remember it, George. \'a0Don\'92t forget and tell me it\'92s\
Elexander before you go, and then get out by saying it\'92s George\
Elexander when I catch you. \'a0And don\'92t go about women in that old\
calico. \'a0You do a girl tolerable poor, but you might fool men, maybe.\
\'a0Bless you, child, when you set out to thread a needle don\'92t hold the\
thread still and fetch the needle up to it; hold the needle still and\
poke the thread at it; that\'92s the way a woman most always does, but a\
man always does t\'92other way. \'a0And when you throw at a rat or anything,\
hitch yourself up a tiptoe and fetch your hand up over your head as\
awkward as you can, and miss your rat about six or seven foot. Throw\
stiff-armed from the shoulder, like there was a pivot there for it to\
turn on, like a girl; not from the wrist and elbow, with your arm out\
to one side, like a boy. \'a0And, mind you, when a girl tries to catch\
anything in her lap she throws her knees apart; she don\'92t clap them\
together, the way you did when you catched the lump of lead. \'a0Why, I\
spotted you for a boy when you was threading the needle; and I contrived\
the other things just to make certain. \'a0Now trot along to your uncle,\
Sarah Mary Williams George Elexander Peters, and if you get into trouble\
you send word to Mrs. Judith Loftus, which is me, and I\'92ll do what I can\
to get you out of it. \'a0Keep the river road all the way, and next time\
you tramp take shoes and socks with you. The river road\'92s a rocky one,\
and your feet\'92ll be in a condition when you get to Goshen, I reckon.\'94\
\
I went up the bank about fifty yards, and then I doubled on my tracks\
and slipped back to where my canoe was, a good piece below the house. \'a0I\
jumped in, and was off in a hurry. \'a0I went up-stream far enough to\
make the head of the island, and then started across. \'a0I took off the\
sun-bonnet, for I didn\'92t want no blinders on then. \'a0When I was about the\
middle I heard the clock begin to strike, so I stops and listens; the\
sound come faint over the water but clear--eleven. \'a0When I struck the\
head of the island I never waited to blow, though I was most winded, but\
I shoved right into the timber where my old camp used to be, and started\
a good fire there on a high and dry spot.\
\
Then I jumped in the canoe and dug out for our place, a mile and a half\
below, as hard as I could go. \'a0I landed, and slopped through the timber\
and up the ridge and into the cavern. \'a0There Jim laid, sound asleep on\
the ground. \'a0I roused him out and says:\
\
\'93Git up and hump yourself, Jim! \'a0There ain\'92t a minute to lose. \'a0They\'92re\
after us!\'94\
\
Jim never asked no questions, he never said a word; but the way he\
worked for the next half an hour showed about how he was scared. \'a0By\
that time everything we had in the world was on our raft, and she was\
ready to be shoved out from the willow cove where she was hid. \'a0We\
put out the camp fire at the cavern the first thing, and didn\'92t show a\
candle outside after that.\
\
I took the canoe out from the shore a little piece, and took a look;\
but if there was a boat around I couldn\'92t see it, for stars and shadows\
ain\'92t good to see by. \'a0Then we got out the raft and slipped along down\
in the shade, past the foot of the island dead still--never saying a\
word.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XII.\
\
IT must a been close on to one o\'92clock when we got below the island at\
last, and the raft did seem to go mighty slow. \'a0If a boat was to come\
along we was going to take to the canoe and break for the Illinois\
shore; and it was well a boat didn\'92t come, for we hadn\'92t ever thought to\
put the gun in the canoe, or a fishing-line, or anything to eat. \'a0We\
was in ruther too much of a sweat to think of so many things. \'a0It warn\'92t\
good judgment to put _everything_ on the raft.\
\
If the men went to the island I just expect they found the camp fire I\
built, and watched it all night for Jim to come. \'a0Anyways, they stayed\
away from us, and if my building the fire never fooled them it warn\'92t no\
fault of mine. \'a0I played it as low down on them as I could.\
\
When the first streak of day began to show we tied up to a towhead in a\
big bend on the Illinois side, and hacked off cottonwood branches with\
the hatchet, and covered up the raft with them so she looked like there\
had been a cave-in in the bank there. \'a0A tow-head is a sandbar that has\
cottonwoods on it as thick as harrow-teeth.\
\
We had mountains on the Missouri shore and heavy timber on the Illinois\
side, and the channel was down the Missouri shore at that place, so we\
warn\'92t afraid of anybody running across us. \'a0We laid there all day,\
and watched the rafts and steamboats spin down the Missouri shore, and\
up-bound steamboats fight the big river in the middle. \'a0I told Jim all\
about the time I had jabbering with that woman; and Jim said she was\
a smart one, and if she was to start after us herself she wouldn\'92t set\
down and watch a camp fire--no, sir, she\'92d fetch a dog. \'a0Well, then, I\
said, why couldn\'92t she tell her husband to fetch a dog? \'a0Jim said he\
bet she did think of it by the time the men was ready to start, and he\
believed they must a gone up-town to get a dog and so they lost all that\
time, or else we wouldn\'92t be here on a towhead sixteen or seventeen mile\
below the village--no, indeedy, we would be in that same old town again.\
\'a0So I said I didn\'92t care what was the reason they didn\'92t get us as long\
as they didn\'92t.\
\
When it was beginning to come on dark we poked our heads out of the\
cottonwood thicket, and looked up and down and across; nothing in sight;\
so Jim took up some of the top planks of the raft and built a snug\
wigwam to get under in blazing weather and rainy, and to keep the things\
dry. Jim made a floor for the wigwam, and raised it a foot or more above\
the level of the raft, so now the blankets and all the traps was out of\
reach of steamboat waves. \'a0Right in the middle of the wigwam we made a\
layer of dirt about five or six inches deep with a frame around it for\
to hold it to its place; this was to build a fire on in sloppy weather\
or chilly; the wigwam would keep it from being seen. \'a0We made an extra\
steering-oar, too, because one of the others might get broke on a snag\
or something. We fixed up a short forked stick to hang the old lantern\
on, because we must always light the lantern whenever we see a steamboat\
coming down-stream, to keep from getting run over; but we wouldn\'92t have\
to light it for up-stream boats unless we see we was in what they call\
a \'93crossing\'94; for the river was pretty high yet, very low banks being\
still a little under water; so up-bound boats didn\'92t always run the\
channel, but hunted easy water.\
\
This second night we run between seven and eight hours, with a current\
that was making over four mile an hour. \'a0We catched fish and talked,\
and we took a swim now and then to keep off sleepiness. \'a0It was kind of\
solemn, drifting down the big, still river, laying on our backs looking\
up at the stars, and we didn\'92t ever feel like talking loud, and it\
warn\'92t often that we laughed--only a little kind of a low chuckle. \'a0We\
had mighty good weather as a general thing, and nothing ever happened to\
us at all--that night, nor the next, nor the next.\
\
Every night we passed towns, some of them away up on black hillsides,\
nothing but just a shiny bed of lights; not a house could you see. \'a0The\
fifth night we passed St. Louis, and it was like the whole world lit up.\
In St. Petersburg they used to say there was twenty or thirty thousand\
people in St. Louis, but I never believed it till I see that wonderful\
spread of lights at two o\'92clock that still night. \'a0There warn\'92t a sound\
there; everybody was asleep.\
\
Every night now I used to slip ashore towards ten o\'92clock at some little\
village, and buy ten or fifteen cents\'92 worth of meal or bacon or other\
stuff to eat; and sometimes I lifted a chicken that warn\'92t roosting\
comfortable, and took him along. \'a0Pap always said, take a chicken when\
you get a chance, because if you don\'92t want him yourself you can easy\
find somebody that does, and a good deed ain\'92t ever forgot. \'a0I never see\
pap when he didn\'92t want the chicken himself, but that is what he used to\
say, anyway.\
\
Mornings before daylight I slipped into cornfields and borrowed a\
watermelon, or a mushmelon, or a punkin, or some new corn, or things of\
that kind. \'a0Pap always said it warn\'92t no harm to borrow things if you\
was meaning to pay them back some time; but the widow said it warn\'92t\
anything but a soft name for stealing, and no decent body would do it.\
\'a0Jim said he reckoned the widow was partly right and pap was partly\
right; so the best way would be for us to pick out two or three things\
from the list and say we wouldn\'92t borrow them any more--then he reckoned\
it wouldn\'92t be no harm to borrow the others. \'a0So we talked it over all\
one night, drifting along down the river, trying to make up our minds\
whether to drop the watermelons, or the cantelopes, or the mushmelons,\
or what. \'a0But towards daylight we got it all settled satisfactory, and\
concluded to drop crabapples and p\'92simmons. \'a0We warn\'92t feeling just\
right before that, but it was all comfortable now. \'a0I was glad the way\
it come out, too, because crabapples ain\'92t ever good, and the p\'92simmons\
wouldn\'92t be ripe for two or three months yet.\
\
We shot a water-fowl now and then that got up too early in the morning\
or didn\'92t go to bed early enough in the evening. \'a0Take it all round, we\
lived pretty high.\
\
The fifth night below St. Louis we had a big storm after midnight, with\
a power of thunder and lightning, and the rain poured down in a solid\
sheet. We stayed in the wigwam and let the raft take care of itself.\
When the lightning glared out we could see a big straight river ahead,\
and high, rocky bluffs on both sides. \'a0By and by says I, \'93Hel-_lo_, Jim,\
looky yonder!\'94 It was a steamboat that had killed herself on a rock.\
\'a0We was drifting straight down for her. \'a0The lightning showed her very\
distinct. \'a0She was leaning over, with part of her upper deck above\
water, and you could see every little chimbly-guy clean and clear, and a\
chair by the big bell, with an old slouch hat hanging on the back of it,\
when the flashes come.\
\
Well, it being away in the night and stormy, and all so mysterious-like,\
I felt just the way any other boy would a felt when I see that wreck\
laying there so mournful and lonesome in the middle of the river. \'a0I\
wanted to get aboard of her and slink around a little, and see what\
there was there. \'a0So I says:\
\
\'93Le\'92s land on her, Jim.\'94\
\
But Jim was dead against it at first. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93I doan\'92 want to go fool\'92n \'91long er no wrack. \'a0We\'92s doin\'92 blame\'92 well,\
en we better let blame\'92 well alone, as de good book says. \'a0Like as not\
dey\'92s a watchman on dat wrack.\'94\
\
\'93Watchman your grandmother,\'94 I says; \'93there ain\'92t nothing to watch but\
the texas and the pilot-house; and do you reckon anybody\'92s going to resk\
his life for a texas and a pilot-house such a night as this, when\
it\'92s likely to break up and wash off down the river any minute?\'94 \'a0Jim\
couldn\'92t say nothing to that, so he didn\'92t try.  \'93And besides,\'94 I says,\
\'93we might borrow something worth having out of the captain\'92s stateroom.\
\'a0Seegars, I bet you--and cost five cents apiece, solid cash. \'a0Steamboat\
captains is always rich, and get sixty dollars a month, and _they_ don\'92t\
care a cent what a thing costs, you know, long as they want it. \'a0Stick a\
candle in your pocket; I can\'92t rest, Jim, till we give her a rummaging.\
\'a0Do you reckon Tom Sawyer would ever go by this thing? \'a0Not for pie, he\
wouldn\'92t. He\'92d call it an adventure--that\'92s what he\'92d call it; and he\'92d\
land on that wreck if it was his last act. \'a0And wouldn\'92t he throw style\
into it?--wouldn\'92t he spread himself, nor nothing? \'a0Why, you\'92d think it\
was Christopher C\'92lumbus discovering Kingdom-Come. \'a0I wish Tom Sawyer\
_was_ here.\'94\
\
Jim he grumbled a little, but give in. \'a0He said we mustn\'92t talk any more\
than we could help, and then talk mighty low. \'a0The lightning showed us\
the wreck again just in time, and we fetched the stabboard derrick, and\
made fast there.\
\
The deck was high out here. \'a0We went sneaking down the slope of it to\
labboard, in the dark, towards the texas, feeling our way slow with our\
feet, and spreading our hands out to fend off the guys, for it was so\
dark we couldn\'92t see no sign of them. \'a0Pretty soon we struck the forward\
end of the skylight, and clumb on to it; and the next step fetched us in\
front of the captain\'92s door, which was open, and by Jimminy, away down\
through the texas-hall we see a light! and all in the same second we\
seem to hear low voices in yonder!\
\
Jim whispered and said he was feeling powerful sick, and told me to come\
along. \'a0I says, all right, and was going to start for the raft; but just\
then I heard a voice wail out and say:\
\
\'93Oh, please don\'92t, boys; I swear I won\'92t ever tell!\'94\
\
Another voice said, pretty loud:\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie, Jim Turner. \'a0You\'92ve acted this way before. \'a0You always want\
more\'92n your share of the truck, and you\'92ve always got it, too, because\
you\'92ve swore \'91t if you didn\'92t you\'92d tell. \'a0But this time you\'92ve said\
it jest one time too many. \'a0You\'92re the meanest, treacherousest hound in\
this country.\'94\
\
By this time Jim was gone for the raft. \'a0I was just a-biling with\
curiosity; and I says to myself, Tom Sawyer wouldn\'92t back out now,\
and so I won\'92t either; I\'92m a-going to see what\'92s going on here. \'a0So I\
dropped on my hands and knees in the little passage, and crept aft\
in the dark till there warn\'92t but one stateroom betwixt me and the\
cross-hall of the texas. \'a0Then in there I see a man stretched on the\
floor and tied hand and foot, and two men standing over him, and one\
of them had a dim lantern in his hand, and the other one had a pistol.\
\'a0This one kept pointing the pistol at the man\'92s head on the floor, and\
saying:\
\
\'93I\'92d _like_ to! \'a0And I orter, too--a mean skunk!\'94\
\
The man on the floor would shrivel up and say, \'93Oh, please don\'92t, Bill;\
I hain\'92t ever goin\'92 to tell.\'94\
\
And every time he said that the man with the lantern would laugh and\
say:\
\
\'93\'91Deed you _ain\'92t!_ \'a0You never said no truer thing \'91n that, you bet\
you.\'94 And once he said:  \'93Hear him beg! and yit if we hadn\'92t got the\
best of him and tied him he\'92d a killed us both. \'a0And what _for_? \'a0Jist\
for noth\'92n. Jist because we stood on our _rights_--that\'92s what for. \'a0But\
I lay you ain\'92t a-goin\'92 to threaten nobody any more, Jim Turner. \'a0Put\
_up_ that pistol, Bill.\'94\
\
Bill says:\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to, Jake Packard. \'a0I\'92m for killin\'92 him--and didn\'92t he kill\
old Hatfield jist the same way--and don\'92t he deserve it?\'94\
\
\'93But I don\'92t _want_ him killed, and I\'92ve got my reasons for it.\'94\
\
\'93Bless yo\'92 heart for them words, Jake Packard! \'a0I\'92ll never forgit you\
long\'92s I live!\'94 says the man on the floor, sort of blubbering.\
\
Packard didn\'92t take no notice of that, but hung up his lantern on a nail\
and started towards where I was there in the dark, and motioned Bill\
to come. \'a0I crawfished as fast as I could about two yards, but the boat\
slanted so that I couldn\'92t make very good time; so to keep from getting\
run over and catched I crawled into a stateroom on the upper side.\
\'a0The man came a-pawing along in the dark, and when Packard got to my\
stateroom, he says:\
\
\'93Here--come in here.\'94\
\
And in he come, and Bill after him. \'a0But before they got in I was up\
in the upper berth, cornered, and sorry I come. \'a0Then they stood there,\
with their hands on the ledge of the berth, and talked. \'a0I couldn\'92t see\
them, but I could tell where they was by the whisky they\'92d been having.\
\'a0I was glad I didn\'92t drink whisky; but it wouldn\'92t made much difference\
anyway, because most of the time they couldn\'92t a treed me because I\
didn\'92t breathe. \'a0I was too scared. \'a0And, besides, a body _couldn\'92t_\
breathe and hear such talk. \'a0They talked low and earnest. \'a0Bill wanted\
to kill Turner. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93He\'92s said he\'92ll tell, and he will. \'a0If we was to give both our shares\
to him _now_ it wouldn\'92t make no difference after the row and the way\
we\'92ve served him. \'a0Shore\'92s you\'92re born, he\'92ll turn State\'92s evidence; now\
you hear _me_. \'a0I\'92m for putting him out of his troubles.\'94\
\
\'93So\'92m I,\'94 says Packard, very quiet.\
\
\'93Blame it, I\'92d sorter begun to think you wasn\'92t. \'a0Well, then, that\'92s all\
right. \'a0Le\'92s go and do it.\'94\
\
\'93Hold on a minute; I hain\'92t had my say yit. \'a0You listen to me.\
Shooting\'92s good, but there\'92s quieter ways if the thing\'92s _got_ to be\
done. But what I say is this: \'a0it ain\'92t good sense to go court\'92n around\
after a halter if you can git at what you\'92re up to in some way that\'92s\
jist as good and at the same time don\'92t bring you into no resks. \'a0Ain\'92t\
that so?\'94\
\
\'93You bet it is. \'a0But how you goin\'92 to manage it this time?\'94\
\
\'93Well, my idea is this: \'a0we\'92ll rustle around and gather up whatever\
pickins we\'92ve overlooked in the staterooms, and shove for shore and hide\
the truck. Then we\'92ll wait. \'a0Now I say it ain\'92t a-goin\'92 to be more\'92n two\
hours befo\'92 this wrack breaks up and washes off down the river. \'a0See?\
He\'92ll be drownded, and won\'92t have nobody to blame for it but his own\
self. \'a0I reckon that\'92s a considerble sight better \'91n killin\'92 of him.\
\'a0I\'92m unfavorable to killin\'92 a man as long as you can git aroun\'92 it; it\
ain\'92t good sense, it ain\'92t good morals. \'a0Ain\'92t I right?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I reck\'92n you are. \'a0But s\'92pose she _don\'92t_ break up and wash off?\'94\
\
\'93Well, we can wait the two hours anyway and see, can\'92t we?\'94\
\
\'93All right, then; come along.\'94\
\
So they started, and I lit out, all in a cold sweat, and scrambled\
forward. It was dark as pitch there; but I said, in a kind of a coarse\
whisper, \'93Jim!\'94 and he answered up, right at my elbow, with a sort of a\
moan, and I says:\
\
\'93Quick, Jim, it ain\'92t no time for fooling around and moaning; there\'92s a\
gang of murderers in yonder, and if we don\'92t hunt up their boat and set\
her drifting down the river so these fellows can\'92t get away from the\
wreck there\'92s one of \'91em going to be in a bad fix. \'a0But if we find their\
boat we can put _all_ of \'91em in a bad fix--for the sheriff \'91ll get \'91em.\
Quick--hurry! \'a0I\'92ll hunt the labboard side, you hunt the stabboard. You\
start at the raft, and--\'94\
\
\'93Oh, my lordy, lordy! \'a0_raf\'92_? \'a0Dey ain\'92 no raf\'92 no mo\'92; she done broke\
loose en gone I--en here we is!\'94\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XIII.\
\
WELL, I catched my breath and most fainted. \'a0Shut up on a wreck with\
such a gang as that! \'a0But it warn\'92t no time to be sentimentering. \'a0We\'92d\
_got_ to find that boat now--had to have it for ourselves. \'a0So we went\
a-quaking and shaking down the stabboard side, and slow work it was,\
too--seemed a week before we got to the stern. \'a0No sign of a boat. \'a0Jim\
said he didn\'92t believe he could go any further--so scared he hadn\'92t\
hardly any strength left, he said. \'a0But I said, come on, if we get left\
on this wreck we are in a fix, sure. \'a0So on we prowled again. \'a0We struck\
for the stern of the texas, and found it, and then scrabbled along\
forwards on the skylight, hanging on from shutter to shutter, for the\
edge of the skylight was in the water. \'a0When we got pretty close to the\
cross-hall door there was the skiff, sure enough! \'a0I could just barely\
see her. \'a0I felt ever so thankful. \'a0In another second I would a been\
aboard of her, but just then the door opened. \'a0One of the men stuck his\
head out only about a couple of foot from me, and I thought I was gone;\
but he jerked it in again, and says:\
\
\'93Heave that blame lantern out o\'92 sight, Bill!\'94\
\
He flung a bag of something into the boat, and then got in himself and\
set down. \'a0It was Packard. \'a0Then Bill _he_ come out and got in. \'a0Packard\
says, in a low voice:\
\
\'93All ready--shove off!\'94\
\
I couldn\'92t hardly hang on to the shutters, I was so weak. \'a0But Bill\
says:\
\
\'93Hold on--\'91d you go through him?\'94\
\
\'93No. \'a0Didn\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93No. \'a0So he\'92s got his share o\'92 the cash yet.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, come along; no use to take truck and leave money.\'94\
\
\'93Say, won\'92t he suspicion what we\'92re up to?\'94\
\
\'93Maybe he won\'92t. \'a0But we got to have it anyway. Come along.\'94\
\
So they got out and went in.\
\
The door slammed to because it was on the careened side; and in a half\
second I was in the boat, and Jim come tumbling after me. \'a0I out with my\
knife and cut the rope, and away we went!\
\
We didn\'92t touch an oar, and we didn\'92t speak nor whisper, nor hardly even\
breathe. \'a0We went gliding swift along, dead silent, past the tip of the\
paddle-box, and past the stern; then in a second or two more we was a\
hundred yards below the wreck, and the darkness soaked her up, every\
last sign of her, and we was safe, and knowed it.\
\
When we was three or four hundred yards down-stream we see the lantern\
show like a little spark at the texas door for a second, and we knowed\
by that that the rascals had missed their boat, and was beginning to\
understand that they was in just as much trouble now as Jim Turner was.\
\
Then Jim manned the oars, and we took out after our raft. \'a0Now was the\
first time that I begun to worry about the men--I reckon I hadn\'92t\
had time to before. \'a0I begun to think how dreadful it was, even for\
murderers, to be in such a fix. \'a0I says to myself, there ain\'92t no\
telling but I might come to be a murderer myself yet, and then how would\
I like it? \'a0So says I to Jim:\
\
\'93The first light we see we\'92ll land a hundred yards below it or above\
it, in a place where it\'92s a good hiding-place for you and the skiff, and\
then I\'92ll go and fix up some kind of a yarn, and get somebody to go for\
that gang and get them out of their scrape, so they can be hung when\
their time comes.\'94\
\
But that idea was a failure; for pretty soon it begun to storm again,\
and this time worse than ever. \'a0The rain poured down, and never a light\
showed; everybody in bed, I reckon. \'a0We boomed along down the river,\
watching for lights and watching for our raft. \'a0After a long time the\
rain let up, but the clouds stayed, and the lightning kept whimpering,\
and by and by a flash showed us a black thing ahead, floating, and we\
made for it.\
\
It was the raft, and mighty glad was we to get aboard of it again. \'a0We\
seen a light now away down to the right, on shore. \'a0So I said I would\
go for it. The skiff was half full of plunder which that gang had stole\
there on the wreck. \'a0We hustled it on to the raft in a pile, and I told\
Jim to float along down, and show a light when he judged he had gone\
about two mile, and keep it burning till I come; then I manned my oars\
and shoved for the light. \'a0As I got down towards it three or four more\
showed--up on a hillside. \'a0It was a village. \'a0I closed in above the shore\
light, and laid on my oars and floated. \'a0As I went by I see it was a\
lantern hanging on the jackstaff of a double-hull ferryboat. \'a0I skimmed\
around for the watchman, a-wondering whereabouts he slept; and by and\
by I found him roosting on the bitts forward, with his head down between\
his knees. \'a0I gave his shoulder two or three little shoves, and begun to\
cry.\
\
He stirred up in a kind of a startlish way; but when he see it was only\
me he took a good gap and stretch, and then he says:\
\
\'93Hello, what\'92s up? \'a0Don\'92t cry, bub. \'a0What\'92s the trouble?\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93Pap, and mam, and sis, and--\'94\
\
Then I broke down. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Oh, dang it now, _don\'92t_ take on so; we all has to have our troubles,\
and this \'91n \'91ll come out all right. \'a0What\'92s the matter with \'91em?\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re--they\'92re--are you the watchman of the boat?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 he says, kind of pretty-well-satisfied like.  \'93I\'92m the captain\
and the owner and the mate and the pilot and watchman and head\
deck-hand; and sometimes I\'92m the freight and passengers. \'a0I ain\'92t as\
rich as old Jim Hornback, and I can\'92t be so blame\'92 generous and good\
to Tom, Dick, and Harry as what he is, and slam around money the way he\
does; but I\'92ve told him a many a time \'91t I wouldn\'92t trade places with\
him; for, says I, a sailor\'92s life\'92s the life for me, and I\'92m derned if\
_I\'92d_ live two mile out o\'92 town, where there ain\'92t nothing ever goin\'92\
on, not for all his spondulicks and as much more on top of it. \'a0Says I--\'94\
\
I broke in and says:\
\
\'93They\'92re in an awful peck of trouble, and--\'94\
\
\'93_Who_ is?\'94\
\
\'93Why, pap and mam and sis and Miss Hooker; and if you\'92d take your\
ferryboat and go up there--\'94\
\
\'93Up where? \'a0Where are they?\'94\
\
\'93On the wreck.\'94\
\
\'93What wreck?\'94\
\
\'93Why, there ain\'92t but one.\'94\
\
\'93What, you don\'92t mean the Walter Scott?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Good land! what are they doin\'92 _there_, for gracious sakes?\'94\
\
\'93Well, they didn\'92t go there a-purpose.\'94\
\
\'93I bet they didn\'92t! \'a0Why, great goodness, there ain\'92t no chance for \'91em\
if they don\'92t git off mighty quick! \'a0Why, how in the nation did they\
ever git into such a scrape?\'94\
\
\'93Easy enough. \'a0Miss Hooker was a-visiting up there to the town--\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Booth\'92s Landing--go on.\'94\
\
\'93She was a-visiting there at Booth\'92s Landing, and just in the edge of\
the evening she started over with her nigger woman in the horse-ferry\
to stay all night at her friend\'92s house, Miss What-you-may-call-her I\
disremember her name--and they lost their steering-oar, and swung\
around and went a-floating down, stern first, about two mile, and\
saddle-baggsed on the wreck, and the ferryman and the nigger woman and\
the horses was all lost, but Miss Hooker she made a grab and got aboard\
the wreck. \'a0Well, about an hour after dark we come along down in our\
trading-scow, and it was so dark we didn\'92t notice the wreck till we was\
right on it; and so _we_ saddle-baggsed; but all of us was saved but\
Bill Whipple--and oh, he _was_ the best cretur!--I most wish \'91t it had\
been me, I do.\'94\
\
\'93My George! \'a0It\'92s the beatenest thing I ever struck. \'a0And _then_ what\
did you all do?\'94\
\
\'93Well, we hollered and took on, but it\'92s so wide there we couldn\'92t\
make nobody hear. \'a0So pap said somebody got to get ashore and get help\
somehow. I was the only one that could swim, so I made a dash for it,\
and Miss Hooker she said if I didn\'92t strike help sooner, come here and\
hunt up her uncle, and he\'92d fix the thing. \'a0I made the land about a mile\
below, and been fooling along ever since, trying to get people to do\
something, but they said, \'91What, in such a night and such a current?\
There ain\'92t no sense in it; go for the steam ferry.\'92 \'a0Now if you\'92ll go\
and--\'94\
\
\'93By Jackson, I\'92d _like_ to, and, blame it, I don\'92t know but I will; but\
who in the dingnation\'92s a-going\'92 to _pay_ for it? \'a0Do you reckon your\
pap--\'94\
\
\'93Why _that\'92s_ all right. \'a0Miss Hooker she tole me, _particular_, that\
her uncle Hornback--\'94\
\
\'93Great guns! is _he_ her uncle? \'a0Looky here, you break for that light\
over yonder-way, and turn out west when you git there, and about a\
quarter of a mile out you\'92ll come to the tavern; tell \'91em to dart you\
out to Jim Hornback\'92s, and he\'92ll foot the bill. \'a0And don\'92t you fool\
around any, because he\'92ll want to know the news. \'a0Tell him I\'92ll have\
his niece all safe before he can get to town. \'a0Hump yourself, now; I\'92m\
a-going up around the corner here to roust out my engineer.\'94\
\
I struck for the light, but as soon as he turned the corner I went back\
and got into my skiff and bailed her out, and then pulled up shore in\
the easy water about six hundred yards, and tucked myself in among\
some woodboats; for I couldn\'92t rest easy till I could see the ferryboat\
start. But take it all around, I was feeling ruther comfortable on\
accounts of taking all this trouble for that gang, for not many would\
a done it. \'a0I wished the widow knowed about it. \'a0I judged she would be\
proud of me for helping these rapscallions, because rapscallions and\
dead beats is the kind the widow and good people takes the most interest\
in.\
\
Well, before long here comes the wreck, dim and dusky, sliding along\
down! A kind of cold shiver went through me, and then I struck out for\
her. \'a0She was very deep, and I see in a minute there warn\'92t much chance\
for anybody being alive in her. \'a0I pulled all around her and hollered\
a little, but there wasn\'92t any answer; all dead still. \'a0I felt a little\
bit heavy-hearted about the gang, but not much, for I reckoned if they\
could stand it I could.\
\
Then here comes the ferryboat; so I shoved for the middle of the river\
on a long down-stream slant; and when I judged I was out of eye-reach\
I laid on my oars, and looked back and see her go and smell around the\
wreck for Miss Hooker\'92s remainders, because the captain would know her\
uncle Hornback would want them; and then pretty soon the ferryboat give\
it up and went for the shore, and I laid into my work and went a-booming\
down the river.\
\
It did seem a powerful long time before Jim\'92s light showed up; and when\
it did show it looked like it was a thousand mile off. \'a0By the time I\
got there the sky was beginning to get a little gray in the east; so we\
struck for an island, and hid the raft, and sunk the skiff, and turned\
in and slept like dead people.\
