\
CHAPTER XIV.\
\
BY and by, when we got up, we turned over the truck the gang had stole\
off of the wreck, and found boots, and blankets, and clothes, and all\
sorts of other things, and a lot of books, and a spyglass, and three\
boxes of seegars. \'a0We hadn\'92t ever been this rich before in neither of\
our lives. \'a0The seegars was prime. \'a0We laid off all the afternoon in the\
woods talking, and me reading the books, and having a general good\
time. I told Jim all about what happened inside the wreck and at the\
ferryboat, and I said these kinds of things was adventures; but he said\
he didn\'92t want no more adventures. \'a0He said that when I went in the\
texas and he crawled back to get on the raft and found her gone he\
nearly died, because he judged it was all up with _him_ anyway it could\
be fixed; for if he didn\'92t get saved he would get drownded; and if he\
did get saved, whoever saved him would send him back home so as to get\
the reward, and then Miss Watson would sell him South, sure. \'a0Well, he\
was right; he was most always right; he had an uncommon level head for a\
nigger.\
\
I read considerable to Jim about kings and dukes and earls and such, and\
how gaudy they dressed, and how much style they put on, and called each\
other your majesty, and your grace, and your lordship, and so on, \'91stead\
of mister; and Jim\'92s eyes bugged out, and he was interested. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93I didn\'92 know dey was so many un um. \'a0I hain\'92t hearn \'91bout none un um,\
skasely, but ole King Sollermun, onless you counts dem kings dat\'92s in a\
pack er k\'92yards. \'a0How much do a king git?\'94\
\
\'93Get?\'94 \'a0I says; \'93why, they get a thousand dollars a month if they want\
it; they can have just as much as they want; everything belongs to\
them.\'94\
\
\'93_Ain\'92_ dat gay? \'a0En what dey got to do, Huck?\'94\
\
\'93_They_ don\'92t do nothing! \'a0Why, how you talk! They just set around.\'94\
\
\'93No; is dat so?\'94\
\
\'93Of course it is. \'a0They just set around--except, maybe, when there\'92s a\
war; then they go to the war. \'a0But other times they just lazy around; or\
go hawking--just hawking and sp--Sh!--d\'92 you hear a noise?\'94\
\
We skipped out and looked; but it warn\'92t nothing but the flutter of a\
steamboat\'92s wheel away down, coming around the point; so we come back.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 says I, \'93and other times, when things is dull, they fuss with the\
parlyment; and if everybody don\'92t go just so he whacks their heads off.\
But mostly they hang round the harem.\'94\
\
\'93Roun\'92 de which?\'94\
\
\'93Harem.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s de harem?\'94\
\
\'93The place where he keeps his wives. \'a0Don\'92t you know about the harem?\
Solomon had one; he had about a million wives.\'94\
\
\'93Why, yes, dat\'92s so; I--I\'92d done forgot it. \'a0A harem\'92s a bo\'92d\'92n-house, I\
reck\'92n. \'a0Mos\'92 likely dey has rackety times in de nussery. \'a0En I reck\'92n\
de wives quarrels considable; en dat \'91crease de racket. \'a0Yit dey say\
Sollermun de wises\'92 man dat ever live\'92. \'a0I doan\'92 take no stock in\
dat. Bekase why: would a wise man want to live in de mids\'92 er sich a\
blim-blammin\'92 all de time? \'a0No--\'91deed he wouldn\'92t. \'a0A wise man \'91ud take\
en buil\'92 a biler-factry; en den he could shet _down_ de biler-factry\
when he want to res\'92.\'94\
\
\'93Well, but he _was_ the wisest man, anyway; because the widow she told\
me so, her own self.\'94\
\
\'93I doan k\'92yer what de widder say, he _warn\'92t_ no wise man nuther. \'a0He\
had some er de dad-fetchedes\'92 ways I ever see. \'a0Does you know \'91bout dat\
chile dat he \'91uz gwyne to chop in two?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, the widow told me all about it.\'94\
\
\'93_Well_, den! \'a0Warn\'92 dat de beatenes\'92 notion in de worl\'92? \'a0You jes\'92\
take en look at it a minute. \'a0Dah\'92s de stump, dah--dat\'92s one er de women;\
heah\'92s you--dat\'92s de yuther one; I\'92s Sollermun; en dish yer dollar bill\'92s\
de chile. \'a0Bofe un you claims it. \'a0What does I do? \'a0Does I shin aroun\'92\
mongs\'92 de neighbors en fine out which un you de bill _do_ b\'92long to, en\
han\'92 it over to de right one, all safe en soun\'92, de way dat anybody dat\
had any gumption would? \'a0No; I take en whack de bill in _two_, en give\
half un it to you, en de yuther half to de yuther woman. \'a0Dat\'92s de way\
Sollermun was gwyne to do wid de chile. \'a0Now I want to ast you: \'a0what\'92s\
de use er dat half a bill?--can\'92t buy noth\'92n wid it. \'a0En what use is a\
half a chile? \'a0I wouldn\'92 give a dern for a million un um.\'94\
\
\'93But hang it, Jim, you\'92ve clean missed the point--blame it, you\'92ve missed\
it a thousand mile.\'94\
\
\'93Who? \'a0Me? \'a0Go \'91long. \'a0Doan\'92 talk to me \'91bout yo\'92 pints. \'a0I reck\'92n I\
knows sense when I sees it; en dey ain\'92 no sense in sich doin\'92s as\
dat. De \'91spute warn\'92t \'91bout a half a chile, de \'91spute was \'91bout a whole\
chile; en de man dat think he kin settle a \'91spute \'91bout a whole chile\
wid a half a chile doan\'92 know enough to come in out\'92n de rain. \'a0Doan\'92\
talk to me \'91bout Sollermun, Huck, I knows him by de back.\'94\
\
\'93But I tell you you don\'92t get the point.\'94\
\
\'93Blame de point! \'a0I reck\'92n I knows what I knows. \'a0En mine you, de _real_\
pint is down furder--it\'92s down deeper. \'a0It lays in de way Sollermun was\
raised. \'a0You take a man dat\'92s got on\'92y one or two chillen; is dat man\
gwyne to be waseful o\'92 chillen? \'a0No, he ain\'92t; he can\'92t \'91ford it. \'a0_He_\
know how to value \'91em. \'a0But you take a man dat\'92s got \'91bout five million\
chillen runnin\'92 roun\'92 de house, en it\'92s diffunt. \'a0_He_ as soon chop a\
chile in two as a cat. Dey\'92s plenty mo\'92. \'a0A chile er two, mo\'92 er less,\
