\
CHAPTER XV.\
\
WE judged that three nights more would fetch us to Cairo, at the bottom\
of Illinois, where the Ohio River comes in, and that was what we was\
after. \'a0We would sell the raft and get on a steamboat and go way up the\
Ohio amongst the free States, and then be out of trouble.\
\
Well, the second night a fog begun to come on, and we made for a towhead\
to tie to, for it wouldn\'92t do to try to run in a fog; but when I paddled\
ahead in the canoe, with the line to make fast, there warn\'92t anything\
but little saplings to tie to. \'a0I passed the line around one of them\
right on the edge of the cut bank, but there was a stiff current, and\
the raft come booming down so lively she tore it out by the roots and\
away she went. \'a0I see the fog closing down, and it made me so sick and\
scared I couldn\'92t budge for most a half a minute it seemed to me--and\
then there warn\'92t no raft in sight; you couldn\'92t see twenty yards. \'a0I\
jumped into the canoe and run back to the stern, and grabbed the paddle\
and set her back a stroke. \'a0But she didn\'92t come. \'a0I was in such a hurry\
I hadn\'92t untied her. \'a0I got up and tried to untie her, but I was so\
excited my hands shook so I couldn\'92t hardly do anything with them.\
\
As soon as I got started I took out after the raft, hot and heavy, right\
down the towhead. \'a0That was all right as far as it went, but the towhead\
warn\'92t sixty yards long, and the minute I flew by the foot of it I shot\
out into the solid white fog, and hadn\'92t no more idea which way I was\
going than a dead man.\
\
Thinks I, it won\'92t do to paddle; first I know I\'92ll run into the bank\
or a towhead or something; I got to set still and float, and yet it\'92s\
mighty fidgety business to have to hold your hands still at such a time.\
\'a0I whooped and listened. \'a0Away down there somewheres I hears a small\
whoop, and up comes my spirits. \'a0I went tearing after it, listening\
sharp to hear it again. \'a0The next time it come I see I warn\'92t heading\
for it, but heading away to the right of it. \'a0And the next time I was\
heading away to the left of it--and not gaining on it much either, for\
I was flying around, this way and that and t\'92other, but it was going\
straight ahead all the time.\
\
I did wish the fool would think to beat a tin pan, and beat it all the\
time, but he never did, and it was the still places between the whoops\
that was making the trouble for me. \'a0Well, I fought along, and directly\
I hears the whoop _behind_ me. \'a0I was tangled good now. \'a0That was\
somebody else\'92s whoop, or else I was turned around.\
\
I throwed the paddle down. \'a0I heard the whoop again; it was behind me\
yet, but in a different place; it kept coming, and kept changing its\
place, and I kept answering, till by and by it was in front of me again,\
and I knowed the current had swung the canoe\'92s head down-stream, and I\
was all right if that was Jim and not some other raftsman hollering.\
\'a0I couldn\'92t tell nothing about voices in a fog, for nothing don\'92t look\
natural nor sound natural in a fog.\
\
The whooping went on, and in about a minute I come a-booming down on a\
cut bank with smoky ghosts of big trees on it, and the current throwed\
me off to the left and shot by, amongst a lot of snags that fairly\
roared, the currrent was tearing by them so swift.\
\
In another second or two it was solid white and still again. \'a0I set\
perfectly still then, listening to my heart thump, and I reckon I didn\'92t\
draw a breath while it thumped a hundred.\
\
I just give up then. \'a0I knowed what the matter was. \'a0That cut bank\
was an island, and Jim had gone down t\'92other side of it. \'a0It warn\'92t no\
towhead that you could float by in ten minutes. \'a0It had the big timber\
of a regular island; it might be five or six miles long and more than\
half a mile wide.\
\
I kept quiet, with my ears cocked, about fifteen minutes, I reckon. \'a0I\
was floating along, of course, four or five miles an hour; but you don\'92t\
ever think of that. \'a0No, you _feel_ like you are laying dead still on\
the water; and if a little glimpse of a snag slips by you don\'92t think to\
yourself how fast _you\'92re_ going, but you catch your breath and think,\
my! how that snag\'92s tearing along. \'a0If you think it ain\'92t dismal and\
lonesome out in a fog that way by yourself in the night, you try it\
once--you\'92ll see.\
\
Next, for about a half an hour, I whoops now and then; at last I hears\
the answer a long ways off, and tries to follow it, but I couldn\'92t do\
it, and directly I judged I\'92d got into a nest of towheads, for I had\
little dim glimpses of them on both sides of me--sometimes just a narrow\
channel between, and some that I couldn\'92t see I knowed was there because\
I\'92d hear the wash of the current against the old dead brush and trash\
that hung over the banks. \'a0Well, I warn\'92t long loosing the whoops down\
amongst the towheads; and I only tried to chase them a little while,\
anyway, because it was worse than chasing a Jack-o\'92-lantern. \'a0You never\
knowed a sound dodge around so, and swap places so quick and so much.\
\
I had to claw away from the bank pretty lively four or five times, to\
keep from knocking the islands out of the river; and so I judged the\
raft must be butting into the bank every now and then, or else it would\
get further ahead and clear out of hearing--it was floating a little\
faster than what I was.\
\
Well, I seemed to be in the open river again by and by, but I couldn\'92t\
hear no sign of a whoop nowheres. \'a0I reckoned Jim had fetched up on a\
snag, maybe, and it was all up with him. \'a0I was good and tired, so I\
laid down in the canoe and said I wouldn\'92t bother no more. \'a0I didn\'92t\
want to go to sleep, of course; but I was so sleepy I couldn\'92t help it;\
so I thought I would take jest one little cat-nap.\
\
But I reckon it was more than a cat-nap, for when I waked up the stars\
was shining bright, the fog was all gone, and I was spinning down a\
big bend stern first. \'a0First I didn\'92t know where I was; I thought I was\
dreaming; and when things began to come back to me they seemed to come\
up dim out of last week.\
\
It was a monstrous big river here, with the tallest and the thickest\
kind of timber on both banks; just a solid wall, as well as I could see\
by the stars. \'a0I looked away down-stream, and seen a black speck on the\
water. I took after it; but when I got to it it warn\'92t nothing but a\
couple of sawlogs made fast together. \'a0Then I see another speck, and\
chased that; then another, and this time I was right. \'a0It was the raft.\
\
When I got to it Jim was setting there with his head down between his\
knees, asleep, with his right arm hanging over the steering-oar. \'a0The\
other oar was smashed off, and the raft was littered up with leaves and\
branches and dirt. \'a0So she\'92d had a rough time.\
\
I made fast and laid down under Jim\'92s nose on the raft, and began to\
gap, and stretch my fists out against Jim, and says:\
\
\'93Hello, Jim, have I been asleep? \'a0Why didn\'92t you stir me up?\'94\
\
\'93Goodness gracious, is dat you, Huck? \'a0En you ain\'92 dead--you ain\'92\
drownded--you\'92s back agin? \'a0It\'92s too good for true, honey, it\'92s too good\
for true. Lemme look at you chile, lemme feel o\'92 you. \'a0No, you ain\'92\
dead! you\'92s back agin, \'91live en soun\'92, jis de same ole Huck--de same ole\
Huck, thanks to goodness!\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter with you, Jim? \'a0You been a-drinking?\'94\
\
\'93Drinkin\'92? \'a0Has I ben a-drinkin\'92? \'a0Has I had a chance to be a-drinkin\'92?\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what makes you talk so wild?\'94\
\
\'93How does I talk wild?\'94\
\
\'93_How_? \'a0Why, hain\'92t you been talking about my coming back, and all that\
stuff, as if I\'92d been gone away?\'94\
\
\'93Huck--Huck Finn, you look me in de eye; look me in de eye. \'a0_Hain\'92t_ you\
ben gone away?\'94\
\
\'93Gone away? \'a0Why, what in the nation do you mean? \'a0I hain\'92t been gone\
anywheres. \'a0Where would I go to?\'94\
\
\'93Well, looky here, boss, dey\'92s sumf\'92n wrong, dey is. \'a0Is I _me_, or who\
_is_ I? Is I heah, or whah _is_ I? \'a0Now dat\'92s what I wants to know.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I think you\'92re here, plain enough, but I think you\'92re a\
tangle-headed old fool, Jim.\'94\
\
\'93I is, is I? \'a0Well, you answer me dis: \'a0Didn\'92t you tote out de line in\
de canoe fer to make fas\'92 to de tow-head?\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t. \'a0What tow-head? \'a0I hain\'92t see no tow-head.\'94\
\
\'93You hain\'92t seen no towhead? \'a0Looky here, didn\'92t de line pull loose en\
de raf\'92 go a-hummin\'92 down de river, en leave you en de canoe behine in\
de fog?\'94\
\
\'93What fog?\'94\
\
\'93Why, de fog!--de fog dat\'92s been aroun\'92 all night. \'a0En didn\'92t you whoop,\
en didn\'92t I whoop, tell we got mix\'92 up in de islands en one un us got\
los\'92 en t\'92other one was jis\'92 as good as los\'92, \'91kase he didn\'92 know whah\
he wuz? En didn\'92t I bust up agin a lot er dem islands en have a turrible\
time en mos\'92 git drownded? \'a0Now ain\'92 dat so, boss--ain\'92t it so? \'a0You\
answer me dat.\'94\
\
\'93Well, this is too many for me, Jim. \'a0I hain\'92t seen no fog, nor no\
islands, nor no troubles, nor nothing. \'a0I been setting here talking with\
you all night till you went to sleep about ten minutes ago, and I reckon\
I done the same. \'a0You couldn\'92t a got drunk in that time, so of course\
you\'92ve been dreaming.\'94\
\
\'93Dad fetch it, how is I gwyne to dream all dat in ten minutes?\'94\
\
\'93Well, hang it all, you did dream it, because there didn\'92t any of it\
happen.\'94\
\
\'93But, Huck, it\'92s all jis\'92 as plain to me as--\'94\
\
\'93It don\'92t make no difference how plain it is; there ain\'92t nothing in it.\
I know, because I\'92ve been here all the time.\'94\
\
Jim didn\'92t say nothing for about five minutes, but set there studying\
over it. \'a0Then he says:\
\
\'93Well, den, I reck\'92n I did dream it, Huck; but dog my cats ef it ain\'92t\
de powerfullest dream I ever see. \'a0En I hain\'92t ever had no dream b\'92fo\'92\
dat\'92s tired me like dis one.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, well, that\'92s all right, because a dream does tire a body like\
everything sometimes. \'a0But this one was a staving dream; tell me all\
about it, Jim.\'94\
\
So Jim went to work and told me the whole thing right through, just as\
it happened, only he painted it up considerable. \'a0Then he said he must\
start in and \'93\'91terpret\'94 it, because it was sent for a warning. \'a0He said\
the first towhead stood for a man that would try to do us some good, but\
the current was another man that would get us away from him. \'a0The whoops\
was warnings that would come to us every now and then, and if we didn\'92t\
try hard to make out to understand them they\'92d just take us into bad\
luck, \'91stead of keeping us out of it. \'a0The lot of towheads was troubles\
we was going to get into with quarrelsome people and all kinds of mean\
folks, but if we minded our business and didn\'92t talk back and aggravate\
them, we would pull through and get out of the fog and into the big\
clear river, which was the free States, and wouldn\'92t have no more\
trouble.\
\
It had clouded up pretty dark just after I got on to the raft, but it\
was clearing up again now.\
\
\'93Oh, well, that\'92s all interpreted well enough as far as it goes, Jim,\'94 I\
says; \'93but what does _these_ things stand for?\'94\
\
It was the leaves and rubbish on the raft and the smashed oar. \'a0You\
could see them first-rate now.\
\
Jim looked at the trash, and then looked at me, and back at the trash\
again. \'a0He had got the dream fixed so strong in his head that he\
couldn\'92t seem to shake it loose and get the facts back into its place\
again right away. \'a0But when he did get the thing straightened around he\
looked at me steady without ever smiling, and says:\
\
\'93What do dey stan\'92 for? \'a0I\'92se gwyne to tell you. \'a0When I got all wore\
out wid work, en wid de callin\'92 for you, en went to sleep, my heart wuz\
mos\'92 broke bekase you wuz los\'92, en I didn\'92 k\'92yer no\'92 mo\'92 what become\
er me en de raf\'92. \'a0En when I wake up en fine you back agin, all safe\
en soun\'92, de tears come, en I could a got down on my knees en kiss yo\'92\
foot, I\'92s so thankful. En all you wuz thinkin\'92 \'91bout wuz how you could\
make a fool uv ole Jim wid a lie. \'a0Dat truck dah is _trash_; en trash\
is what people is dat puts dirt on de head er dey fren\'92s en makes \'91em\
ashamed.\'94\
\
Then he got up slow and walked to the wigwam, and went in there without\
saying anything but that. \'a0But that was enough. \'a0It made me feel so mean\
I could almost kissed _his_ foot to get him to take it back.\
\
It was fifteen minutes before I could work myself up to go and humble\
myself to a nigger; but I done it, and I warn\'92t ever sorry for it\
afterwards, neither. \'a0I didn\'92t do him no more mean tricks, and I\
wouldn\'92t done that one if I\'92d a knowed it would make him feel that way.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XVI.\
\
WE slept most all day, and started out at night, a little ways behind a\
monstrous long raft that was as long going by as a procession. \'a0She had\
four long sweeps at each end, so we judged she carried as many as thirty\
men, likely. \'a0She had five big wigwams aboard, wide apart, and an open\
camp fire in the middle, and a tall flag-pole at each end. \'a0There was a\
power of style about her. \'a0It _amounted_ to something being a raftsman\
on such a craft as that.\
\
We went drifting down into a big bend, and the night clouded up and got\
hot. \'a0The river was very wide, and was walled with solid timber on\
both sides; you couldn\'92t see a break in it hardly ever, or a light. \'a0We\
talked about Cairo, and wondered whether we would know it when we got to\
it. \'a0I said likely we wouldn\'92t, because I had heard say there warn\'92t but\
about a dozen houses there, and if they didn\'92t happen to have them lit\
up, how was we going to know we was passing a town? \'a0Jim said if the two\
big rivers joined together there, that would show. \'a0But I said maybe\
we might think we was passing the foot of an island and coming into the\
same old river again. That disturbed Jim--and me too. \'a0So the question\
was, what to do? \'a0I said, paddle ashore the first time a light showed,\
and tell them pap was behind, coming along with a trading-scow, and\
was a green hand at the business, and wanted to know how far it was to\
Cairo. \'a0Jim thought it was a good idea, so we took a smoke on it and\
waited.\
\
There warn\'92t nothing to do now but to look out sharp for the town, and\
not pass it without seeing it. \'a0He said he\'92d be mighty sure to see it,\
because he\'92d be a free man the minute he seen it, but if he missed it\
he\'92d be in a slave country again and no more show for freedom. \'a0Every\
little while he jumps up and says:\
\
\'93Dah she is?\'94\
\
But it warn\'92t. \'a0It was Jack-o\'92-lanterns, or lightning bugs; so he set\
down again, and went to watching, same as before. \'a0Jim said it made him\
all over trembly and feverish to be so close to freedom. \'a0Well, I can\
tell you it made me all over trembly and feverish, too, to hear him,\
because I begun to get it through my head that he _was_ most free--and\
who was to blame for it? \'a0Why, _me_. \'a0I couldn\'92t get that out of my\
conscience, no how nor no way. It got to troubling me so I couldn\'92t\
rest; I couldn\'92t stay still in one place. \'a0It hadn\'92t ever come home to\
me before, what this thing was that I was doing. \'a0But now it did; and it\
stayed with me, and scorched me more and more. \'a0I tried to make out to\
myself that I warn\'92t to blame, because I didn\'92t run Jim off from his\
rightful owner; but it warn\'92t no use, conscience up and says, every\
time, \'93But you knowed he was running for his freedom, and you could a\
paddled ashore and told somebody.\'94 \'a0That was so--I couldn\'92t get around\
that noway. \'a0That was where it pinched. \'a0Conscience says to me, \'93What\
had poor Miss Watson done to you that you could see her nigger go off\
right under your eyes and never say one single word? \'a0What did that poor\
old woman do to you that you could treat her so mean? \'a0Why, she tried to\
learn you your book, she tried to learn you your manners, she tried to\
be good to you every way she knowed how. \'a0_That\'92s_ what she done.\'94\
\
I got to feeling so mean and so miserable I most wished I was dead. \'a0I\
fidgeted up and down the raft, abusing myself to myself, and Jim was\
fidgeting up and down past me. \'a0We neither of us could keep still.\
\'a0Every time he danced around and says, \'93Dah\'92s Cairo!\'94 it went through me\
like a shot, and I thought if it _was_ Cairo I reckoned I would die of\
miserableness.\
\
Jim talked out loud all the time while I was talking to myself. \'a0He was\
saying how the first thing he would do when he got to a free State he\
would go to saving up money and never spend a single cent, and when he\
got enough he would buy his wife, which was owned on a farm close to\
where Miss Watson lived; and then they would both work to buy the\
two children, and if their master wouldn\'92t sell them, they\'92d get an\
Ab\'92litionist to go and steal them.\
\
It most froze me to hear such talk. \'a0He wouldn\'92t ever dared to talk such\
talk in his life before. \'a0Just see what a difference it made in him the\
minute he judged he was about free. \'a0It was according to the old saying,\
\'93Give a nigger an inch and he\'92ll take an ell.\'94 \'a0Thinks I, this is what\
comes of my not thinking. \'a0Here was this nigger, which I had as good\
as helped to run away, coming right out flat-footed and saying he would\
steal his children--children that belonged to a man I didn\'92t even know; a\
man that hadn\'92t ever done me no harm.\
\
I was sorry to hear Jim say that, it was such a lowering of him. \'a0My\
conscience got to stirring me up hotter than ever, until at last I says\
to it, \'93Let up on me--it ain\'92t too late yet--I\'92ll paddle ashore at the\
first light and tell.\'94 \'a0I felt easy and happy and light as a feather\
right off. \'a0All my troubles was gone. \'a0I went to looking out sharp for a\
light, and sort of singing to myself. \'a0By and by one showed. \'a0Jim sings\
out:\
\
\'93We\'92s safe, Huck, we\'92s safe! \'a0Jump up and crack yo\'92 heels! \'a0Dat\'92s de\
good ole Cairo at las\'92, I jis knows it!\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93I\'92ll take the canoe and go and see, Jim. \'a0It mightn\'92t be, you know.\'94\
\
He jumped and got the canoe ready, and put his old coat in the bottom\
for me to set on, and give me the paddle; and as I shoved off, he says:\
\
\'93Pooty soon I\'92ll be a-shout\'92n\'92 for joy, en I\'92ll say, it\'92s all on\
accounts o\'92 Huck; I\'92s a free man, en I couldn\'92t ever ben free ef it\
hadn\'92 ben for Huck; Huck done it. \'a0Jim won\'92t ever forgit you, Huck;\
you\'92s de bes\'92 fren\'92 Jim\'92s ever had; en you\'92s de _only_ fren\'92 ole Jim\'92s\
got now.\'94\
\
I was paddling off, all in a sweat to tell on him; but when he says\
this, it seemed to kind of take the tuck all out of me. \'a0I went along\
slow then, and I warn\'92t right down certain whether I was glad I started\
or whether I warn\'92t. \'a0When I was fifty yards off, Jim says:\
\
\'93Dah you goes, de ole true Huck; de on\'92y white genlman dat ever kep\'92 his\
promise to ole Jim.\'94\
\
Well, I just felt sick. \'a0But I says, I _got_ to do it--I can\'92t get _out_\
of it. \'a0Right then along comes a skiff with two men in it with guns, and\
they stopped and I stopped. \'a0One of them says:\
\
\'93What\'92s that yonder?\'94\
\
\'93A piece of a raft,\'94 I says.\
\
\'93Do you belong on it?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, sir.\'94\
\
\'93Any men on it?\'94\
\
\'93Only one, sir.\'94\
\
\'93Well, there\'92s five niggers run off to-night up yonder, above the head\
of the bend. \'a0Is your man white or black?\'94\
\
I didn\'92t answer up prompt. \'a0I tried to, but the words wouldn\'92t come. I\
tried for a second or two to brace up and out with it, but I warn\'92t man\
enough--hadn\'92t the spunk of a rabbit. \'a0I see I was weakening; so I just\
give up trying, and up and says:\
\
\'93He\'92s white.\'94\
\
\'93I reckon we\'92ll go and see for ourselves.\'94\
\
\'93I wish you would,\'94 says I, \'93because it\'92s pap that\'92s there, and maybe\
you\'92d help me tow the raft ashore where the light is. \'a0He\'92s sick--and so\
is mam and Mary Ann.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, the devil! we\'92re in a hurry, boy. \'a0But I s\'92pose we\'92ve got to.\
\'a0Come, buckle to your paddle, and let\'92s get along.\'94\
\
I buckled to my paddle and they laid to their oars. \'a0When we had made a\
stroke or two, I says:\
\
\'93Pap\'92ll be mighty much obleeged to you, I can tell you. \'a0Everybody goes\
away when I want them to help me tow the raft ashore, and I can\'92t do it\
by myself.\'94\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s infernal mean. \'a0Odd, too. \'a0Say, boy, what\'92s the matter\
with your father?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s the--a--the--well, it ain\'92t anything much.\'94\
\
They stopped pulling. \'a0It warn\'92t but a mighty little ways to the raft\
now. One says:\
\
\'93Boy, that\'92s a lie. \'a0What _is_ the matter with your pap? \'a0Answer up\
square now, and it\'92ll be the better for you.\'94\
\
\'93I will, sir, I will, honest--but don\'92t leave us, please. \'a0It\'92s\
the--the--Gentlemen, if you\'92ll only pull ahead, and let me heave you the\
headline, you won\'92t have to come a-near the raft--please do.\'94\
\
\'93Set her back, John, set her back!\'94 says one. \'a0They backed water.  \'93Keep\
away, boy--keep to looard. \'a0Confound it, I just expect the wind has\
blowed it to us. \'a0Your pap\'92s got the small-pox, and you know it precious\
well. \'a0Why didn\'92t you come out and say so? \'a0Do you want to spread it all\
over?\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says I, a-blubbering, \'93I\'92ve told everybody before, and they just\
went away and left us.\'94\
\
\'93Poor devil, there\'92s something in that. \'a0We are right down sorry for\
you, but we--well, hang it, we don\'92t want the small-pox, you see. \'a0Look\
here, I\'92ll tell you what to do. \'a0Don\'92t you try to land by yourself, or\
you\'92ll smash everything to pieces. \'a0You float along down about twenty\
miles, and you\'92ll come to a town on the left-hand side of the river. \'a0It\
will be long after sun-up then, and when you ask for help you tell them\
your folks are all down with chills and fever. \'a0Don\'92t be a fool again,\
and let people guess what is the matter. \'a0Now we\'92re trying to do you a\
kindness; so you just put twenty miles between us, that\'92s a good boy.\
\'a0It wouldn\'92t do any good to land yonder where the light is--it\'92s only a\
wood-yard. Say, I reckon your father\'92s poor, and I\'92m bound to say he\'92s\
in pretty hard luck. \'a0Here, I\'92ll put a twenty-dollar gold piece on this\
board, and you get it when it floats by. \'a0I feel mighty mean to leave\
you; but my kingdom! it won\'92t do to fool with small-pox, don\'92t you see?\'94\
\
\'93Hold on, Parker,\'94 says the other man, \'93here\'92s a twenty to put on the\
board for me. \'a0Good-bye, boy; you do as Mr. Parker told you, and you\'92ll\
be all right.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s so, my boy--good-bye, good-bye. \'a0If you see any runaway niggers\
you get help and nab them, and you can make some money by it.\'94\
\
\'93Good-bye, sir,\'94 says I; \'93I won\'92t let no runaway niggers get by me if I\
can help it.\'94\
\
They went off and I got aboard the raft, feeling bad and low, because I\
knowed very well I had done wrong, and I see it warn\'92t no use for me\
to try to learn to do right; a body that don\'92t get _started_ right when\
he\'92s little ain\'92t got no show--when the pinch comes there ain\'92t nothing\
to back him up and keep him to his work, and so he gets beat. \'a0Then I\
thought a minute, and says to myself, hold on; s\'92pose you\'92d a done right\
and give Jim up, would you felt better than what you do now? \'a0No, says\
I, I\'92d feel bad--I\'92d feel just the same way I do now. \'a0Well, then, says\
I, what\'92s the use you learning to do right when it\'92s troublesome to do\
right and ain\'92t no trouble to do wrong, and the wages is just the same?\
\'a0I was stuck. \'a0I couldn\'92t answer that. \'a0So I reckoned I wouldn\'92t bother\
no more about it, but after this always do whichever come handiest at\
the time.\
\
I went into the wigwam; Jim warn\'92t there. \'a0I looked all around; he\
warn\'92t anywhere. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Jim!\'94\
\
\'93Here I is, Huck. \'a0Is dey out o\'92 sight yit? \'a0Don\'92t talk loud.\'94\
\
He was in the river under the stern oar, with just his nose out. \'a0I told\
him they were out of sight, so he come aboard. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93I was a-listenin\'92 to all de talk, en I slips into de river en was gwyne\
to shove for sho\'92 if dey come aboard. \'a0Den I was gwyne to swim to de\
raf\'92 agin when dey was gone. \'a0But lawsy, how you did fool \'91em, Huck!\
\'a0Dat _wuz_ de smartes\'92 dodge! \'a0I tell you, chile, I\'92spec it save\'92 ole\
Jim--ole Jim ain\'92t going to forgit you for dat, honey.\'94\
\
Then we talked about the money. \'a0It was a pretty good raise--twenty\
dollars apiece. \'a0Jim said we could take deck passage on a steamboat\
now, and the money would last us as far as we wanted to go in the free\
States. He said twenty mile more warn\'92t far for the raft to go, but he\
wished we was already there.\
\
Towards daybreak we tied up, and Jim was mighty particular about hiding\
the raft good. \'a0Then he worked all day fixing things in bundles, and\
getting all ready to quit rafting.\
\
That night about ten we hove in sight of the lights of a town away down\
in a left-hand bend.\
\
I went off in the canoe to ask about it. \'a0Pretty soon I found a man out\
in the river with a skiff, setting a trot-line. \'a0I ranged up and says:\
\
\'93Mister, is that town Cairo?\'94\
\
\'93Cairo? no. \'a0You must be a blame\'92 fool.\'94\
\
\'93What town is it, mister?\'94\
\
\'93If you want to know, go and find out. \'a0If you stay here botherin\'92\
around me for about a half a minute longer you\'92ll get something you\
won\'92t want.\'94\
\
I paddled to the raft. \'a0Jim was awful disappointed, but I said never\
mind, Cairo would be the next place, I reckoned.\
\
We passed another town before daylight, and I was going out again; but\
it was high ground, so I didn\'92t go. \'a0No high ground about Cairo, Jim\
said. I had forgot it. \'a0We laid up for the day on a towhead tolerable\
close to the left-hand bank. \'a0I begun to suspicion something. \'a0So did\
Jim. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Maybe we went by Cairo in the fog that night.\'94\
\
He says:\
\
\'93Doan\'92 le\'92s talk about it, Huck. \'a0Po\'92 niggers can\'92t have no luck. \'a0I\
awluz \'91spected dat rattlesnake-skin warn\'92t done wid its work.\'94\
\
\'93I wish I\'92d never seen that snake-skin, Jim--I do wish I\'92d never laid\
eyes on it.\'94\
\
\'93It ain\'92t yo\'92 fault, Huck; you didn\'92 know. \'a0Don\'92t you blame yo\'92self\
\'91bout it.\'94\
\
When it was daylight, here was the clear Ohio water inshore, sure\
enough, and outside was the old regular Muddy! \'a0So it was all up with\
Cairo.\
\
We talked it all over. \'a0It wouldn\'92t do to take to the shore; we couldn\'92t\
take the raft up the stream, of course. \'a0There warn\'92t no way but to wait\
for dark, and start back in the canoe and take the chances. \'a0So we slept\
all day amongst the cottonwood thicket, so as to be fresh for the work,\
and when we went back to the raft about dark the canoe was gone!\
\
We didn\'92t say a word for a good while. \'a0There warn\'92t anything to\
say. \'a0We both knowed well enough it was some more work of the\
rattlesnake-skin; so what was the use to talk about it? \'a0It would only\
look like we was finding fault, and that would be bound to fetch more\
bad luck--and keep on fetching it, too, till we knowed enough to keep\
still.\
\
By and by we talked about what we better do, and found there warn\'92t no\
way but just to go along down with the raft till we got a chance to buy\
a canoe to go back in. \'a0We warn\'92t going to borrow it when there warn\'92t\
anybody around, the way pap would do, for that might set people after\
us.\
\
So we shoved out after dark on the raft.\
\
Anybody that don\'92t believe yet that it\'92s foolishness to handle a\
snake-skin, after all that that snake-skin done for us, will believe it\
now if they read on and see what more it done for us.\
\
The place to buy canoes is off of rafts laying up at shore. \'a0But we\
didn\'92t see no rafts laying up; so we went along during three hours and\
more. \'a0Well, the night got gray and ruther thick, which is the next\
meanest thing to fog. \'a0You can\'92t tell the shape of the river, and you\
can\'92t see no distance. It got to be very late and still, and then along\
comes a steamboat up the river. \'a0We lit the lantern, and judged she\
would see it. \'a0Up-stream boats didn\'92t generly come close to us; they\
go out and follow the bars and hunt for easy water under the reefs; but\
nights like this they bull right up the channel against the whole river.\
\
We could hear her pounding along, but we didn\'92t see her good till she\
was close. \'a0She aimed right for us. \'a0Often they do that and try to see\
how close they can come without touching; sometimes the wheel bites off\
a sweep, and then the pilot sticks his head out and laughs, and thinks\
he\'92s mighty smart. \'a0Well, here she comes, and we said she was going to\
try and shave us; but she didn\'92t seem to be sheering off a bit. \'a0She\
was a big one, and she was coming in a hurry, too, looking like a black\
cloud with rows of glow-worms around it; but all of a sudden she bulged\
out, big and scary, with a long row of wide-open furnace doors shining\
like red-hot teeth, and her monstrous bows and guards hanging right\
over us. \'a0There was a yell at us, and a jingling of bells to stop the\
engines, a powwow of cussing, and whistling of steam--and as Jim went\
overboard on one side and I on the other, she come smashing straight\
through the raft.\
\
I dived--and I aimed to find the bottom, too, for a thirty-foot wheel\
had got to go over me, and I wanted it to have plenty of room. \'a0I could\
always stay under water a minute; this time I reckon I stayed under a\
minute and a half. \'a0Then I bounced for the top in a hurry, for I was\
nearly busting. \'a0I popped out to my armpits and blowed the water out of\
my nose, and puffed a bit. \'a0Of course there was a booming current; and\
of course that boat started her engines again ten seconds after she\
stopped them, for they never cared much for raftsmen; so now she was\
churning along up the river, out of sight in the thick weather, though I\
could hear her.\
\
I sung out for Jim about a dozen times, but I didn\'92t get any answer;\
so I grabbed a plank that touched me while I was \'93treading water,\'94 and\
struck out for shore, shoving it ahead of me. \'a0But I made out to see\
that the drift of the current was towards the left-hand shore, which\
meant that I was in a crossing; so I changed off and went that way.\
\
It was one of these long, slanting, two-mile crossings; so I was a good\
long time in getting over. \'a0I made a safe landing, and clumb up the\
bank. I couldn\'92t see but a little ways, but I went poking along over\
rough ground for a quarter of a mile or more, and then I run across a\
big old-fashioned double log-house before I noticed it. \'a0I was going to\
rush by and get away, but a lot of dogs jumped out and went to howling\
and barking at me, and I knowed better than to move another peg.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XVII.\
\
IN about a minute somebody spoke out of a window without putting his\
head out, and says:\
\
\'93Be done, boys! \'a0Who\'92s there?\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93It\'92s me.\'94\
\
\'93Who\'92s me?\'94\
\
\'93George Jackson, sir.\'94\
\
\'93What do you want?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t want nothing, sir. \'a0I only want to go along by, but the dogs\
won\'92t let me.\'94\
\
\'93What are you prowling around here this time of night for--hey?\'94\
\
\'93I warn\'92t prowling around, sir, I fell overboard off of the steamboat.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, you did, did you? \'a0Strike a light there, somebody. \'a0What did you\
say your name was?\'94\
\
\'93George Jackson, sir. \'a0I\'92m only a boy.\'94\
\
\'93Look here, if you\'92re telling the truth you needn\'92t be afraid--nobody\'92ll\
hurt you. \'a0But don\'92t try to budge; stand right where you are. \'a0Rouse out\
Bob and Tom, some of you, and fetch the guns. \'a0George Jackson, is there\
anybody with you?\'94\
\
\'93No, sir, nobody.\'94\
\
I heard the people stirring around in the house now, and see a light.\
The man sung out:\
\
\'93Snatch that light away, Betsy, you old fool--ain\'92t you got any sense?\
Put it on the floor behind the front door. \'a0Bob, if you and Tom are\
ready, take your places.\'94\
\
\'93All ready.\'94\
\
\'93Now, George Jackson, do you know the Shepherdsons?\'94\
\
\'93No, sir; I never heard of them.\'94\
\
\'93Well, that may be so, and it mayn\'92t. \'a0Now, all ready. \'a0Step forward,\
George Jackson. \'a0And mind, don\'92t you hurry--come mighty slow. \'a0If there\'92s\
anybody with you, let him keep back--if he shows himself he\'92ll be shot.\
Come along now. \'a0Come slow; push the door open yourself--just enough to\
squeeze in, d\'92 you hear?\'94\
\
I didn\'92t hurry; I couldn\'92t if I\'92d a wanted to. \'a0I took one slow step at\
a time and there warn\'92t a sound, only I thought I could hear my heart.\
\'a0The dogs were as still as the humans, but they followed a little behind\
me. When I got to the three log doorsteps I heard them unlocking and\
unbarring and unbolting. \'a0I put my hand on the door and pushed it a\
little and a little more till somebody said, \'93There, that\'92s enough--put\
your head in.\'94 I done it, but I judged they would take it off.\
\
The candle was on the floor, and there they all was, looking at me, and\
me at them, for about a quarter of a minute: \'a0Three big men with guns\
pointed at me, which made me wince, I tell you; the oldest, gray\
and about sixty, the other two thirty or more--all of them fine and\
handsome--and the sweetest old gray-headed lady, and back of her two\
young women which I couldn\'92t see right well. \'a0The old gentleman says:\
\
\'93There; I reckon it\'92s all right. \'a0Come in.\'94\
\
As soon as I was in the old gentleman he locked the door and barred it\
and bolted it, and told the young men to come in with their guns, and\
they all went in a big parlor that had a new rag carpet on the floor,\
and got together in a corner that was out of the range of the front\
windows--there warn\'92t none on the side. \'a0They held the candle, and took a\
good look at me, and all said, \'93Why, _he_ ain\'92t a Shepherdson--no, there\
ain\'92t any Shepherdson about him.\'94 \'a0Then the old man said he hoped I\
wouldn\'92t mind being searched for arms, because he didn\'92t mean no harm by\
it--it was only to make sure. \'a0So he didn\'92t pry into my pockets, but only\
felt outside with his hands, and said it was all right. \'a0He told me to\
make myself easy and at home, and tell all about myself; but the old\
lady says:\
\
\'93Why, bless you, Saul, the poor thing\'92s as wet as he can be; and don\'92t\
you reckon it may be he\'92s hungry?\'94\
\
\'93True for you, Rachel--I forgot.\'94\
\
So the old lady says:\
\
\'93Betsy\'94 (this was a nigger woman), \'93you fly around and get him something\
to eat as quick as you can, poor thing; and one of you girls go and wake\
up Buck and tell him--oh, here he is himself. \'a0Buck, take this little\
stranger and get the wet clothes off from him and dress him up in some\
of yours that\'92s dry.\'94\
\
Buck looked about as old as me--thirteen or fourteen or along there,\
though he was a little bigger than me. \'a0He hadn\'92t on anything but a\
shirt, and he was very frowzy-headed. \'a0He came in gaping and digging one\
fist into his eyes, and he was dragging a gun along with the other one.\
He says:\
\
\'93Ain\'92t they no Shepherdsons around?\'94\
\
They said, no, \'91twas a false alarm.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93if they\'92d a ben some, I reckon I\'92d a got one.\'94\
\
They all laughed, and Bob says:\
\
\'93Why, Buck, they might have scalped us all, you\'92ve been so slow in\
coming.\'94\
\
\'93Well, nobody come after me, and it ain\'92t right I\'92m always kept down; I\
don\'92t get no show.\'94\
\
\'93Never mind, Buck, my boy,\'94 says the old man, \'93you\'92ll have show enough,\
all in good time, don\'92t you fret about that. \'a0Go \'91long with you now, and\
do as your mother told you.\'94\
\
When we got up-stairs to his room he got me a coarse shirt and a\
roundabout and pants of his, and I put them on. \'a0While I was at it he\
asked me what my name was, but before I could tell him he started to\
tell me about a bluejay and a young rabbit he had catched in the woods\
day before yesterday, and he asked me where Moses was when the candle\
went out. \'a0I said I didn\'92t know; I hadn\'92t heard about it before, no way.\
\
\'93Well, guess,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93How\'92m I going to guess,\'94 says I, \'93when I never heard tell of it\
before?\'94\
\
\'93But you can guess, can\'92t you? \'a0It\'92s just as easy.\'94\
\
\'93_Which_ candle?\'94 \'a0I says.\
\
\'93Why, any candle,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93I don\'92t know where he was,\'94 says I; \'93where was he?\'94\
\
\'93Why, he was in the _dark_! \'a0That\'92s where he was!\'94\
\
\'93Well, if you knowed where he was, what did you ask me for?\'94\
\
\'93Why, blame it, it\'92s a riddle, don\'92t you see? \'a0Say, how long are you\
going to stay here? \'a0You got to stay always. \'a0We can just have booming\
times--they don\'92t have no school now. \'a0Do you own a dog? \'a0I\'92ve got a\
dog--and he\'92ll go in the river and bring out chips that you throw in. \'a0Do\
you like to comb up Sundays, and all that kind of foolishness? \'a0You bet\
I don\'92t, but ma she makes me. \'a0Confound these ole britches! \'a0I reckon\
I\'92d better put \'91em on, but I\'92d ruther not, it\'92s so warm. \'a0Are you all\
ready? All right. \'a0Come along, old hoss.\'94\
\
Cold corn-pone, cold corn-beef, butter and buttermilk--that is what they\
had for me down there, and there ain\'92t nothing better that ever I\'92ve\
come across yet. \'a0Buck and his ma and all of them smoked cob pipes,\
except the nigger woman, which was gone, and the two young women. \'a0They\
all smoked and talked, and I eat and talked. \'a0The young women had\
quilts around them, and their hair down their backs. \'a0They all asked me\
questions, and I told them how pap and me and all the family was living\
on a little farm down at the bottom of Arkansaw, and my sister Mary Ann\
run off and got married and never was heard of no more, and Bill went\
to hunt them and he warn\'92t heard of no more, and Tom and Mort died,\
and then there warn\'92t nobody but just me and pap left, and he was just\
trimmed down to nothing, on account of his troubles; so when he died\
I took what there was left, because the farm didn\'92t belong to us, and\
started up the river, deck passage, and fell overboard; and that was how\
I come to be here. \'a0So they said I could have a home there as long as I\
wanted it. \'a0Then it was most daylight and everybody went to bed, and I\
went to bed with Buck, and when I waked up in the morning, drat it all,\
I had forgot what my name was. So I laid there about an hour trying to\
think, and when Buck waked up I says:\
\
\'93Can you spell, Buck?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93I bet you can\'92t spell my name,\'94 says I.\
\
\'93I bet you what you dare I can,\'94 says he.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 says I, \'93go ahead.\'94\
\
\'93G-e-o-r-g-e J-a-x-o-n--there now,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says I, \'93you done it, but I didn\'92t think you could. \'a0It ain\'92t no\
slouch of a name to spell--right off without studying.\'94\
\
I set it down, private, because somebody might want _me_ to spell it\
next, and so I wanted to be handy with it and rattle it off like I was\
used to it.\
\
It was a mighty nice family, and a mighty nice house, too. \'a0I hadn\'92t\
seen no house out in the country before that was so nice and had so much\
style. \'a0It didn\'92t have an iron latch on the front door, nor a wooden one\
with a buckskin string, but a brass knob to turn, the same as houses in\
town. There warn\'92t no bed in the parlor, nor a sign of a bed; but heaps\
of parlors in towns has beds in them. \'a0There was a big fireplace that\
was bricked on the bottom, and the bricks was kept clean and red by\
pouring water on them and scrubbing them with another brick; sometimes\
they wash them over with red water-paint that they call Spanish-brown,\
same as they do in town. \'a0They had big brass dog-irons that could hold\
up a saw-log. There was a clock on the middle of the mantelpiece, with\
a picture of a town painted on the bottom half of the glass front, and\
a round place in the middle of it for the sun, and you could see the\
pendulum swinging behind it. \'a0It was beautiful to hear that clock tick;\
and sometimes when one of these peddlers had been along and scoured her\
up and got her in good shape, she would start in and strike a hundred\
and fifty before she got tuckered out. \'a0They wouldn\'92t took any money for\
her.\
\
Well, there was a big outlandish parrot on each side of the clock,\
made out of something like chalk, and painted up gaudy. \'a0By one of the\
parrots was a cat made of crockery, and a crockery dog by the other;\
and when you pressed down on them they squeaked, but didn\'92t open\
their mouths nor look different nor interested. \'a0They squeaked through\
underneath. \'a0There was a couple of big wild-turkey-wing fans spread out\
behind those things. \'a0On the table in the middle of the room was a kind\
of a lovely crockery basket that had apples and oranges and peaches and\
grapes piled up in it, which was much redder and yellower and prettier\
than real ones is, but they warn\'92t real because you could see where\
pieces had got chipped off and showed the white chalk, or whatever it\
was, underneath.\
\
This table had a cover made out of beautiful oilcloth, with a red and\
blue spread-eagle painted on it, and a painted border all around. \'a0It\
come all the way from Philadelphia, they said. \'a0There was some books,\
too, piled up perfectly exact, on each corner of the table. \'a0One was a\
big family Bible full of pictures. \'a0One was Pilgrim\'92s Progress, about a\
man that left his family, it didn\'92t say why. \'a0I read considerable in it\
now and then. \'a0The statements was interesting, but tough. \'a0Another was\
Friendship\'92s Offering, full of beautiful stuff and poetry; but I didn\'92t\
read the poetry. \'a0Another was Henry Clay\'92s Speeches, and another was Dr.\
Gunn\'92s Family Medicine, which told you all about what to do if a body\
was sick or dead. \'a0There was a hymn book, and a lot of other books. \'a0And\
there was nice split-bottom chairs, and perfectly sound, too--not bagged\
down in the middle and busted, like an old basket.\
\
They had pictures hung on the walls--mainly Washingtons and Lafayettes,\
and battles, and Highland Marys, and one called \'93Signing the\
Declaration.\'94 There was some that they called crayons, which one of the\
daughters which was dead made her own self when she was only\
fifteen years old. \'a0They was different from any pictures I ever see\
before--blacker, mostly, than is common. \'a0One was a woman in a slim black\
dress, belted small under the armpits, with bulges like a cabbage in\
the middle of the sleeves, and a large black scoop-shovel bonnet with\
a black veil, and white slim ankles crossed about with black tape, and\
very wee black slippers, like a chisel, and she was leaning pensive on a\
tombstone on her right elbow, under a weeping willow, and her other hand\
hanging down her side holding a white handkerchief and a reticule,\
and underneath the picture it said \'93Shall I Never See Thee More Alas.\'94\
 \'a0Another one was a young lady with her hair all combed up straight\
to the top of her head, and knotted there in front of a comb like a\
chair-back, and she was crying into a handkerchief and had a dead bird\
laying on its back in her other hand with its heels up, and underneath\
the picture it said \'93I Shall Never Hear Thy Sweet Chirrup More Alas.\'94\
 \'a0There was one where a young lady was at a window looking up at the\
moon, and tears running down her cheeks; and she had an open letter in\
one hand with black sealing wax showing on one edge of it, and she was\
mashing a locket with a chain to it against her mouth, and underneath\
the picture it said \'93And Art Thou Gone Yes Thou Art Gone Alas.\'94 \'a0These\
was all nice pictures, I reckon, but I didn\'92t somehow seem to take\
to them, because if ever I was down a little they always give me the\
fan-tods. \'a0Everybody was sorry she died, because she had laid out a lot\
more of these pictures to do, and a body could see by what she had done\
what they had lost. \'a0But I reckoned that with her disposition she was\
having a better time in the graveyard. \'a0She was at work on what they\
said was her greatest picture when she took sick, and every day and\
every night it was her prayer to be allowed to live till she got it\
done, but she never got the chance. \'a0It was a picture of a young woman\
in a long white gown, standing on the rail of a bridge all ready to jump\
off, with her hair all down her back, and looking up to the moon, with\
the tears running down her face, and she had two arms folded across her\
breast, and two arms stretched out in front, and two more reaching up\
towards the moon--and the idea was to see which pair would look best,\
and then scratch out all the other arms; but, as I was saying, she died\
before she got her mind made up, and now they kept this picture over the\
head of the bed in her room, and every time her birthday come they hung\
flowers on it. \'a0Other times it was hid with a little curtain. \'a0The young\
woman in the picture had a kind of a nice sweet face, but there was so\
many arms it made her look too spidery, seemed to me.\
\
This young girl kept a scrap-book when she was alive, and used to paste\
obituaries and accidents and cases of patient suffering in it out of the\
Presbyterian Observer, and write poetry after them out of her own head.\
It was very good poetry. This is what she wrote about a boy by the name\
of Stephen Dowling Bots that fell down a well and was drownded:\
\
ODE TO STEPHEN DOWLING BOTS, DEC\'92D\
\
And did young Stephen sicken, \'a0 \'a0And did young Stephen die? And did the\
sad hearts thicken, \'a0 \'a0And did the mourners cry?\
\
No; such was not the fate of \'a0 \'a0Young Stephen Dowling Bots; Though sad\
hearts round him thickened, \'a0  \'91Twas not from sickness\'92 shots.\
\
No whooping-cough did rack his frame, \'a0 \'a0Nor measles drear with spots;\
Not these impaired the sacred name \'a0 \'a0Of Stephen Dowling Bots.\
\
Despised love struck not with woe \'a0 \'a0That head of curly knots, Nor\
stomach troubles laid him low, \'a0 \'a0Young Stephen Dowling Bots.\
\
O no. Then list with tearful eye, \'a0 \'a0Whilst I his fate do tell. His soul\
did from this cold world fly \'a0 \'a0By falling down a well.\
\
They got him out and emptied him; \'a0 \'a0Alas it was too late; His spirit\
was gone for to sport aloft \'a0 \'a0In the realms of the good and great.\
\
If Emmeline Grangerford could make poetry like that before she was\
fourteen, there ain\'92t no telling what she could a done by and by. \'a0Buck\
said she could rattle off poetry like nothing. \'a0She didn\'92t ever have to\
stop to think. \'a0He said she would slap down a line, and if she couldn\'92t\
find anything to rhyme with it would just scratch it out and slap down\
another one, and go ahead. She warn\'92t particular; she could write about\
anything you choose to give her to write about just so it was sadful.\
Every time a man died, or a woman died, or a child died, she would be on\
hand with her \'93tribute\'94 before he was cold. \'a0She called them tributes.\
The neighbors said it was the doctor first, then Emmeline, then the\
undertaker--the undertaker never got in ahead of Emmeline but once, and\
then she hung fire on a rhyme for the dead person\'92s name, which was\
Whistler. \'a0She warn\'92t ever the same after that; she never complained,\
but she kinder pined away and did not live long. \'a0Poor thing, many\'92s the\
time I made myself go up to the little room that used to be hers and get\
out her poor old scrap-book and read in it when her pictures had been\
aggravating me and I had soured on her a little. \'a0I liked all that\
family, dead ones and all, and warn\'92t going to let anything come between\
us. \'a0Poor Emmeline made poetry about all the dead people when she was\
alive, and it didn\'92t seem right that there warn\'92t nobody to make some\
about her now she was gone; so I tried to sweat out a verse or two\
myself, but I couldn\'92t seem to make it go somehow. \'a0They kept Emmeline\'92s\
room trim and nice, and all the things fixed in it just the way she\
liked to have them when she was alive, and nobody ever slept there.\
\'a0The old lady took care of the room herself, though there was plenty\
of niggers, and she sewed there a good deal and read her Bible there\
mostly.\
\
Well, as I was saying about the parlor, there was beautiful curtains on\
the windows: \'a0white, with pictures painted on them of castles with vines\
all down the walls, and cattle coming down to drink. \'a0There was a little\
old piano, too, that had tin pans in it, I reckon, and nothing was ever\
so lovely as to hear the young ladies sing \'93The Last Link is Broken\'94\
 and play \'93The Battle of Prague\'94 on it. \'a0The walls of all the rooms was\
plastered, and most had carpets on the floors, and the whole house was\
whitewashed on the outside.\
\
It was a double house, and the big open place betwixt them was roofed\
and floored, and sometimes the table was set there in the middle of the\
day, and it was a cool, comfortable place. \'a0Nothing couldn\'92t be better.\
\'a0And warn\'92t the cooking good, and just bushels of it too!\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XVIII.\
\
COL. \'a0Grangerford was a gentleman, you see. \'a0He was a gentleman all\
over; and so was his family. \'a0He was well born, as the saying is, and\
that\'92s worth as much in a man as it is in a horse, so the Widow Douglas\
said, and nobody ever denied that she was of the first aristocracy\
in our town; and pap he always said it, too, though he warn\'92t no more\
quality than a mudcat himself. \'a0Col. \'a0Grangerford was very tall and\
very slim, and had a darkish-paly complexion, not a sign of red in it\
anywheres; he was clean shaved every morning all over his thin face, and\
he had the thinnest kind of lips, and the thinnest kind of nostrils, and\
a high nose, and heavy eyebrows, and the blackest kind of eyes, sunk so\
deep back that they seemed like they was looking out of caverns at\
you, as you may say. \'a0His forehead was high, and his hair was black and\
straight and hung to his shoulders. His hands was long and thin, and\
every day of his life he put on a clean shirt and a full suit from head\
to foot made out of linen so white it hurt your eyes to look at it;\
and on Sundays he wore a blue tail-coat with brass buttons on it. \'a0He\
carried a mahogany cane with a silver head to it. \'a0There warn\'92t no\
frivolishness about him, not a bit, and he warn\'92t ever loud. \'a0He was\
as kind as he could be--you could feel that, you know, and so you had\
confidence. \'a0Sometimes he smiled, and it was good to see; but when he\
straightened himself up like a liberty-pole, and the lightning begun to\
flicker out from under his eyebrows, you wanted to climb a tree first,\
and find out what the matter was afterwards. \'a0He didn\'92t ever have to\
tell anybody to mind their manners--everybody was always good-mannered\
where he was. \'a0Everybody loved to have him around, too; he was sunshine\
most always--I mean he made it seem like good weather. \'a0When he turned\
into a cloudbank it was awful dark for half a minute, and that was\
enough; there wouldn\'92t nothing go wrong again for a week.\
\
When him and the old lady come down in the morning all the family got\
up out of their chairs and give them good-day, and didn\'92t set down again\
till they had set down. \'a0Then Tom and Bob went to the sideboard where\
the decanter was, and mixed a glass of bitters and handed it to him, and\
he held it in his hand and waited till Tom\'92s and Bob\'92s was mixed, and\
then they bowed and said, \'93Our duty to you, sir, and madam;\'94 and _they_\
bowed the least bit in the world and said thank you, and so they drank,\
all three, and Bob and Tom poured a spoonful of water on the sugar and\
the mite of whisky or apple brandy in the bottom of their tumblers, and\
give it to me and Buck, and we drank to the old people too.\
\
Bob was the oldest and Tom next--tall, beautiful men with very broad\
shoulders and brown faces, and long black hair and black eyes. \'a0They\
dressed in white linen from head to foot, like the old gentleman, and\
wore broad Panama hats.\
\
Then there was Miss Charlotte; she was twenty-five, and tall and proud\
and grand, but as good as she could be when she warn\'92t stirred up; but\
when she was she had a look that would make you wilt in your tracks,\
like her father. \'a0She was beautiful.\
\
So was her sister, Miss Sophia, but it was a different kind. \'a0She was\
gentle and sweet like a dove, and she was only twenty.\
\
Each person had their own nigger to wait on them--Buck too. \'a0My nigger\
had a monstrous easy time, because I warn\'92t used to having anybody do\
anything for me, but Buck\'92s was on the jump most of the time.\
\
This was all there was of the family now, but there used to be\
more--three sons; they got killed; and Emmeline that died.\
\
The old gentleman owned a lot of farms and over a hundred niggers.\
Sometimes a stack of people would come there, horseback, from ten or\
fifteen mile around, and stay five or six days, and have such junketings\
round about and on the river, and dances and picnics in the woods\
daytimes, and balls at the house nights. \'a0These people was mostly\
kinfolks of the family. \'a0The men brought their guns with them. \'a0It was a\
handsome lot of quality, I tell you.\
\
There was another clan of aristocracy around there--five or six\
families--mostly of the name of Shepherdson. \'a0They was as high-toned\
and well born and rich and grand as the tribe of Grangerfords. \'a0The\
Shepherdsons and Grangerfords used the same steamboat landing, which was\
about two mile above our house; so sometimes when I went up there with a\
lot of our folks I used to see a lot of the Shepherdsons there on their\
fine horses.\
\
One day Buck and me was away out in the woods hunting, and heard a horse\
coming. \'a0We was crossing the road. \'a0Buck says:\
\
\'93Quick! \'a0Jump for the woods!\'94\
\
We done it, and then peeped down the woods through the leaves. \'a0Pretty\
soon a splendid young man come galloping down the road, setting his\
horse easy and looking like a soldier. \'a0He had his gun across his\
pommel. \'a0I had seen him before. \'a0It was young Harney Shepherdson. \'a0I\
heard Buck\'92s gun go off at my ear, and Harney\'92s hat tumbled off from his\
head. \'a0He grabbed his gun and rode straight to the place where we was\
hid. \'a0But we didn\'92t wait. \'a0We started through the woods on a run. \'a0The\
woods warn\'92t thick, so I looked over my shoulder to dodge the bullet,\
and twice I seen Harney cover Buck with his gun; and then he rode away\
the way he come--to get his hat, I reckon, but I couldn\'92t see. \'a0We never\
stopped running till we got home. \'a0The old gentleman\'92s eyes blazed a\
minute--\'91twas pleasure, mainly, I judged--then his face sort of smoothed\
down, and he says, kind of gentle:\
\
\'93I don\'92t like that shooting from behind a bush. \'a0Why didn\'92t you step\
into the road, my boy?\'94\
\
\'93The Shepherdsons don\'92t, father. \'a0They always take advantage.\'94\
\
Miss Charlotte she held her head up like a queen while Buck was telling\
his tale, and her nostrils spread and her eyes snapped. \'a0The two young\
men looked dark, but never said nothing. \'a0Miss Sophia she turned pale,\
but the color come back when she found the man warn\'92t hurt.\
\
Soon as I could get Buck down by the corn-cribs under the trees by\
ourselves, I says:\
\
\'93Did you want to kill him, Buck?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I bet I did.\'94\
\
\'93What did he do to you?\'94\
\
\'93Him? \'a0He never done nothing to me.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what did you want to kill him for?\'94\
\
\'93Why, nothing--only it\'92s on account of the feud.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s a feud?\'94\
\
\'93Why, where was you raised? \'a0Don\'92t you know what a feud is?\'94\
\
\'93Never heard of it before--tell me about it.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says Buck, \'93a feud is this way: \'a0A man has a quarrel with\
another man, and kills him; then that other man\'92s brother kills _him_;\
then the other brothers, on both sides, goes for one another; then the\
_cousins_ chip in--and by and by everybody\'92s killed off, and there ain\'92t\
no more feud. \'a0But it\'92s kind of slow, and takes a long time.\'94\
\
\'93Has this one been going on long, Buck?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I should _reckon_! \'a0It started thirty year ago, or som\'92ers along\
there. \'a0There was trouble \'91bout something, and then a lawsuit to settle\
it; and the suit went agin one of the men, and so he up and shot the\
man that won the suit--which he would naturally do, of course. \'a0Anybody\
would.\'94\
\
\'93What was the trouble about, Buck?--land?\'94\
\
\'93I reckon maybe--I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93Well, who done the shooting? \'a0Was it a Grangerford or a Shepherdson?\'94\
\
\'93Laws, how do I know? \'a0It was so long ago.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t anybody know?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes, pa knows, I reckon, and some of the other old people; but they\
don\'92t know now what the row was about in the first place.\'94\
\
\'93Has there been many killed, Buck?\'94\
\
\'93Yes; right smart chance of funerals. \'a0But they don\'92t always kill. \'a0Pa\'92s\
got a few buckshot in him; but he don\'92t mind it \'91cuz he don\'92t weigh\
much, anyway. \'a0Bob\'92s been carved up some with a bowie, and Tom\'92s been\
hurt once or twice.\'94\
\
\'93Has anybody been killed this year, Buck?\'94\
\
\'93Yes; we got one and they got one.  \'91Bout three months ago my cousin\
Bud, fourteen year old, was riding through the woods on t\'92other side\
of the river, and didn\'92t have no weapon with him, which was blame\'92\
foolishness, and in a lonesome place he hears a horse a-coming behind\
him, and sees old Baldy Shepherdson a-linkin\'92 after him with his gun in\
his hand and his white hair a-flying in the wind; and \'91stead of jumping\
off and taking to the brush, Bud \'91lowed he could out-run him; so they\
had it, nip and tuck, for five mile or more, the old man a-gaining all\
the time; so at last Bud seen it warn\'92t any use, so he stopped and faced\
around so as to have the bullet holes in front, you know, and the old\
man he rode up and shot him down. \'a0But he didn\'92t git much chance to\
enjoy his luck, for inside of a week our folks laid _him_ out.\'94\
\
\'93I reckon that old man was a coward, Buck.\'94\
\
\'93I reckon he _warn\'92t_ a coward. \'a0Not by a blame\'92 sight. \'a0There ain\'92t a\
coward amongst them Shepherdsons--not a one. \'a0And there ain\'92t no cowards\
amongst the Grangerfords either. \'a0Why, that old man kep\'92 up his end in a\
fight one day for half an hour against three Grangerfords, and come\
out winner. \'a0They was all a-horseback; he lit off of his horse and got\
behind a little woodpile, and kep\'92 his horse before him to stop the\
bullets; but the Grangerfords stayed on their horses and capered around\
the old man, and peppered away at him, and he peppered away at them.\
\'a0Him and his horse both went home pretty leaky and crippled, but the\
Grangerfords had to be _fetched_ home--and one of \'91em was dead, and\
another died the next day. \'a0No, sir; if a body\'92s out hunting for cowards\
he don\'92t want to fool away any time amongst them Shepherdsons, becuz\
they don\'92t breed any of that _kind_.\'94\
\
Next Sunday we all went to church, about three mile, everybody\
a-horseback. The men took their guns along, so did Buck, and kept\
them between their knees or stood them handy against the wall. \'a0The\
Shepherdsons done the same. \'a0It was pretty ornery preaching--all about\
brotherly love, and such-like tiresomeness; but everybody said it was\
a good sermon, and they all talked it over going home, and had such\
a powerful lot to say about faith and good works and free grace and\
preforeordestination, and I don\'92t know what all, that it did seem to me\
to be one of the roughest Sundays I had run across yet.\
\
About an hour after dinner everybody was dozing around, some in their\
chairs and some in their rooms, and it got to be pretty dull. \'a0Buck and\
a dog was stretched out on the grass in the sun sound asleep. \'a0I went up\
to our room, and judged I would take a nap myself. \'a0I found that sweet\
Miss Sophia standing in her door, which was next to ours, and she took\
me in her room and shut the door very soft, and asked me if I liked her,\
and I said I did; and she asked me if I would do something for her and\
not tell anybody, and I said I would. \'a0Then she said she\'92d forgot her\
Testament, and left it in the seat at church between two other books,\
and would I slip out quiet and go there and fetch it to her, and not say\
nothing to nobody. \'a0I said I would. So I slid out and slipped off up the\
road, and there warn\'92t anybody at the church, except maybe a hog or two,\
for there warn\'92t any lock on the door, and hogs likes a puncheon floor\
in summer-time because it\'92s cool. \'a0If you notice, most folks don\'92t go to\
church only when they\'92ve got to; but a hog is different.\
\
Says I to myself, something\'92s up; it ain\'92t natural for a girl to be in\
such a sweat about a Testament. \'a0So I give it a shake, and out drops a\
little piece of paper with \'93HALF-PAST TWO\'94 wrote on it with a pencil. \'a0I\
ransacked it, but couldn\'92t find anything else. \'a0I couldn\'92t make anything\
out of that, so I put the paper in the book again, and when I got home\
and upstairs there was Miss Sophia in her door waiting for me. \'a0She\
pulled me in and shut the door; then she looked in the Testament till\
she found the paper, and as soon as she read it she looked glad; and\
before a body could think she grabbed me and give me a squeeze, and\
said I was the best boy in the world, and not to tell anybody. \'a0She was\
mighty red in the face for a minute, and her eyes lighted up, and it\
made her powerful pretty. \'a0I was a good deal astonished, but when I got\
my breath I asked her what the paper was about, and she asked me if I\
had read it, and I said no, and she asked me if I could read writing,\
and I told her \'93no, only coarse-hand,\'94 and then she said the paper\
warn\'92t anything but a book-mark to keep her place, and I might go and\
play now.\
\
I went off down to the river, studying over this thing, and pretty soon\
I noticed that my nigger was following along behind. \'a0When we was out\
of sight of the house he looked back and around a second, and then comes\
a-running, and says:\
\
\'93Mars Jawge, if you\'92ll come down into de swamp I\'92ll show you a whole\
stack o\'92 water-moccasins.\'94\
\
Thinks I, that\'92s mighty curious; he said that yesterday. \'a0He oughter\
know a body don\'92t love water-moccasins enough to go around hunting for\
them. What is he up to, anyway? \'a0So I says:\
\
\'93All right; trot ahead.\'94\
\
I followed a half a mile; then he struck out over the swamp, and waded\
ankle deep as much as another half-mile. \'a0We come to a little flat piece\
of land which was dry and very thick with trees and bushes and vines,\
and he says:\
\
\'93You shove right in dah jist a few steps, Mars Jawge; dah\'92s whah dey is.\
I\'92s seed \'91m befo\'92; I don\'92t k\'92yer to see \'91em no mo\'92.\'94\
\
Then he slopped right along and went away, and pretty soon the trees hid\
him. \'a0I poked into the place a-ways and come to a little open patch\
as big as a bedroom all hung around with vines, and found a man laying\
there asleep--and, by jings, it was my old Jim!\
\
I waked him up, and I reckoned it was going to be a grand surprise to\
him to see me again, but it warn\'92t. \'a0He nearly cried he was so glad, but\
he warn\'92t surprised. \'a0Said he swum along behind me that night, and heard\
me yell every time, but dasn\'92t answer, because he didn\'92t want nobody to\
pick _him_ up and take him into slavery again. \'a0Says he:\
\
\'93I got hurt a little, en couldn\'92t swim fas\'92, so I wuz a considable ways\
behine you towards de las\'92; when you landed I reck\'92ned I could ketch\
up wid you on de lan\'92 \'91dout havin\'92 to shout at you, but when I see dat\
house I begin to go slow. \'a0I \'91uz off too fur to hear what dey say to\
you--I wuz \'91fraid o\'92 de dogs; but when it \'91uz all quiet agin I knowed\
you\'92s in de house, so I struck out for de woods to wait for day. \'a0Early\
in de mawnin\'92 some er de niggers come along, gwyne to de fields, en dey\
tuk me en showed me dis place, whah de dogs can\'92t track me on accounts\
o\'92 de water, en dey brings me truck to eat every night, en tells me how\
you\'92s a-gitt\'92n along.\'94\
\
\'93Why didn\'92t you tell my Jack to fetch me here sooner, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Well, \'91twarn\'92t no use to \'91sturb you, Huck, tell we could do sumfn--but\
we\'92s all right now. \'a0I ben a-buyin\'92 pots en pans en vittles, as I got a\
chanst, en a-patchin\'92 up de raf\'92 nights when--\'94\
\
\'93_What_ raft, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93Our ole raf\'92.\'94\
\
\'93You mean to say our old raft warn\'92t smashed all to flinders?\'94\
\
\'93No, she warn\'92t. \'a0She was tore up a good deal--one en\'92 of her was; but\
dey warn\'92t no great harm done, on\'92y our traps was mos\'92 all los\'92. \'a0Ef we\
hadn\'92 dive\'92 so deep en swum so fur under water, en de night hadn\'92 ben\
so dark, en we warn\'92t so sk\'92yerd, en ben sich punkin-heads, as de sayin\'92\
is, we\'92d a seed de raf\'92. \'a0But it\'92s jis\'92 as well we didn\'92t, \'91kase now\
she\'92s all fixed up agin mos\'92 as good as new, en we\'92s got a new lot o\'92\
stuff, in de place o\'92 what \'91uz los\'92.\'94\
\
\'93Why, how did you get hold of the raft again, Jim--did you catch her?\'94\
\
\'93How I gwyne to ketch her en I out in de woods? \'a0No; some er de niggers\
foun\'92 her ketched on a snag along heah in de ben\'92, en dey hid her in a\
crick \'91mongst de willows, en dey wuz so much jawin\'92 \'91bout which un \'91um\
she b\'92long to de mos\'92 dat I come to heah \'91bout it pooty soon, so I ups\
en settles de trouble by tellin\'92 \'91um she don\'92t b\'92long to none uv um, but\
to you en me; en I ast \'91m if dey gwyne to grab a young white genlman\'92s\
propaty, en git a hid\'92n for it? \'a0Den I gin \'91m ten cents apiece, en dey\
\'91uz mighty well satisfied, en wisht some mo\'92 raf\'92s \'91ud come along en\
make \'91m rich agin. Dey\'92s mighty good to me, dese niggers is, en whatever\
I wants \'91m to do fur me I doan\'92 have to ast \'91m twice, honey. \'a0Dat Jack\'92s\
a good nigger, en pooty smart.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he is. \'a0He ain\'92t ever told me you was here; told me to come, and\
he\'92d show me a lot of water-moccasins. \'a0If anything happens _he_ ain\'92t\
mixed up in it. \'a0He can say he never seen us together, and it \'91ll be the\
truth.\'94\
\
I don\'92t want to talk much about the next day. \'a0I reckon I\'92ll cut it\
pretty short. \'a0I waked up about dawn, and was a-going to turn over and\
go to sleep again when I noticed how still it was--didn\'92t seem to be\
anybody stirring. \'a0That warn\'92t usual. \'a0Next I noticed that Buck was\
up and gone. Well, I gets up, a-wondering, and goes down stairs--nobody\
around; everything as still as a mouse. \'a0Just the same outside. \'a0Thinks\
I, what does it mean? \'a0Down by the wood-pile I comes across my Jack, and\
says:\
\
\'93What\'92s it all about?\'94\
\
Says he:\
\
\'93Don\'92t you know, Mars Jawge?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says I, \'93I don\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Well, den, Miss Sophia\'92s run off! \'91deed she has. \'a0She run off in de\
night some time--nobody don\'92t know jis\'92 when; run off to get married\
to dat young Harney Shepherdson, you know--leastways, so dey \'91spec. \'a0De\
fambly foun\'92 it out \'91bout half an hour ago--maybe a little mo\'92--en\'92 I\
_tell_ you dey warn\'92t no time los\'92. \'a0Sich another hurryin\'92 up guns\
en hosses _you_ never see! \'a0De women folks has gone for to stir up de\
relations, en ole Mars Saul en de boys tuck dey guns en rode up de\
river road for to try to ketch dat young man en kill him \'91fo\'92 he kin\
git acrost de river wid Miss Sophia. \'a0I reck\'92n dey\'92s gwyne to be mighty\
rough times.\'94\
\
\'93Buck went off \'91thout waking me up.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I reck\'92n he _did_! \'a0Dey warn\'92t gwyne to mix you up in it.\
\'a0Mars Buck he loaded up his gun en \'91lowed he\'92s gwyne to fetch home a\
Shepherdson or bust. Well, dey\'92ll be plenty un \'91m dah, I reck\'92n, en you\
bet you he\'92ll fetch one ef he gits a chanst.\'94\
\
I took up the river road as hard as I could put. \'a0By and by I begin to\
hear guns a good ways off. \'a0When I come in sight of the log store and\
the woodpile where the steamboats lands I worked along under the trees\
and brush till I got to a good place, and then I clumb up into the\
forks of a cottonwood that was out of reach, and watched. \'a0There was a\
wood-rank four foot high a little ways in front of the tree, and first I\
was going to hide behind that; but maybe it was luckier I didn\'92t.\
\
There was four or five men cavorting around on their horses in the open\
place before the log store, cussing and yelling, and trying to get at\
a couple of young chaps that was behind the wood-rank alongside of the\
steamboat landing; but they couldn\'92t come it. \'a0Every time one of them\
showed himself on the river side of the woodpile he got shot at. \'a0The\
two boys was squatting back to back behind the pile, so they could watch\
both ways.\
\
By and by the men stopped cavorting around and yelling. \'a0They started\
riding towards the store; then up gets one of the boys, draws a steady\
bead over the wood-rank, and drops one of them out of his saddle. \'a0All\
the men jumped off of their horses and grabbed the hurt one and started\
to carry him to the store; and that minute the two boys started on the\
run. \'a0They got half way to the tree I was in before the men noticed.\
Then the men see them, and jumped on their horses and took out after\
them. \'a0They gained on the boys, but it didn\'92t do no good, the boys had\
too good a start; they got to the woodpile that was in front of my tree,\
and slipped in behind it, and so they had the bulge on the men again.\
One of the boys was Buck, and the other was a slim young chap about\
nineteen years old.\
\
The men ripped around awhile, and then rode away. \'a0As soon as they was\
out of sight I sung out to Buck and told him. \'a0He didn\'92t know what\
to make of my voice coming out of the tree at first. \'a0He was awful\
surprised. \'a0He told me to watch out sharp and let him know when the\
men come in sight again; said they was up to some devilment or\
other--wouldn\'92t be gone long. \'a0I wished I was out of that tree, but I\
dasn\'92t come down. \'a0Buck begun to cry and rip, and \'91lowed that him and\
his cousin Joe (that was the other young chap) would make up for this\
day yet. \'a0He said his father and his two brothers was killed, and two\
or three of the enemy. \'a0Said the Shepherdsons laid for them in\
ambush. \'a0Buck said his father and brothers ought to waited for their\
relations--the Shepherdsons was too strong for them. \'a0I asked him what\
was become of young Harney and Miss Sophia. \'a0He said they\'92d got across\
the river and was safe. \'a0I was glad of that; but the way Buck did take\
on because he didn\'92t manage to kill Harney that day he shot at him--I\
hain\'92t ever heard anything like it.\
\
All of a sudden, bang! bang! bang! goes three or four guns--the men had\
slipped around through the woods and come in from behind without their\
horses! \'a0The boys jumped for the river--both of them hurt--and as they\
swum down the current the men run along the bank shooting at them and\
singing out, \'93Kill them, kill them!\'94 \'a0It made me so sick I most fell out\
of the tree. \'a0I ain\'92t a-going to tell _all_ that happened--it would make\
me sick again if I was to do that. \'a0I wished I hadn\'92t ever come ashore\
that night to see such things. \'a0I ain\'92t ever going to get shut of\
them--lots of times I dream about them.\
\
I stayed in the tree till it begun to get dark, afraid to come down.\
Sometimes I heard guns away off in the woods; and twice I seen little\
gangs of men gallop past the log store with guns; so I reckoned the\
trouble was still a-going on. \'a0I was mighty downhearted; so I made up my\
mind I wouldn\'92t ever go anear that house again, because I reckoned I\
was to blame, somehow. I judged that that piece of paper meant that Miss\
Sophia was to meet Harney somewheres at half-past two and run off; and\
I judged I ought to told her father about that paper and the curious way\
she acted, and then maybe he would a locked her up, and this awful mess\
wouldn\'92t ever happened.\
\
When I got down out of the tree I crept along down the river bank a\
piece, and found the two bodies laying in the edge of the water, and\
tugged at them till I got them ashore; then I covered up their faces,\
and got away as quick as I could. \'a0I cried a little when I was covering\
up Buck\'92s face, for he was mighty good to me.\
\
It was just dark now. \'a0I never went near the house, but struck through\
the woods and made for the swamp. \'a0Jim warn\'92t on his island, so I\
tramped off in a hurry for the crick, and crowded through the willows,\
red-hot to jump aboard and get out of that awful country. \'a0The raft was\
gone! \'a0My souls, but I was scared! \'a0I couldn\'92t get my breath for most\
a minute. Then I raised a yell. \'a0A voice not twenty-five foot from me\
says:\
\
\'93Good lan\'92! is dat you, honey? \'a0Doan\'92 make no noise.\'94\
\
It was Jim\'92s voice--nothing ever sounded so good before. \'a0I run along the\
bank a piece and got aboard, and Jim he grabbed me and hugged me, he was\
so glad to see me. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Laws bless you, chile, I \'91uz right down sho\'92 you\'92s dead agin. \'a0Jack\'92s\
been heah; he say he reck\'92n you\'92s ben shot, kase you didn\'92 come home no\
mo\'92; so I\'92s jes\'92 dis minute a startin\'92 de raf\'92 down towards de mouf er\
de crick, so\'92s to be all ready for to shove out en leave soon as Jack\
comes agin en tells me for certain you _is_ dead. \'a0Lawsy, I\'92s mighty\
glad to git you back again, honey.\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93All right--that\'92s mighty good; they won\'92t find me, and they\'92ll think\
I\'92ve been killed, and floated down the river--there\'92s something up there\
that \'91ll help them think so--so don\'92t you lose no time, Jim, but just\
shove off for the big water as fast as ever you can.\'94\
\
I never felt easy till the raft was two mile below there and out in\
the middle of the Mississippi. \'a0Then we hung up our signal lantern, and\
judged that we was free and safe once more. \'a0I hadn\'92t had a bite to eat\
since yesterday, so Jim he got out some corn-dodgers and buttermilk,\
and pork and cabbage and greens--there ain\'92t nothing in the world so good\
when it\'92s cooked right--and whilst I eat my supper we talked and had a\
good time. \'a0I was powerful glad to get away from the feuds, and so was\
Jim to get away from the swamp. \'a0We said there warn\'92t no home like a\
raft, after all. \'a0Other places do seem so cramped up and smothery, but a\
raft don\'92t. \'a0You feel mighty free and easy and comfortable on a raft.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XIX.\
\
TWO or three days and nights went by; I reckon I might say they swum by,\
they slid along so quiet and smooth and lovely. \'a0Here is the way we put\
in the time. \'a0It was a monstrous big river down there--sometimes a mile\
and a half wide; we run nights, and laid up and hid daytimes; soon as\
night was most gone we stopped navigating and tied up--nearly always\
in the dead water under a towhead; and then cut young cottonwoods and\
willows, and hid the raft with them. \'a0Then we set out the lines. \'a0Next\
we slid into the river and had a swim, so as to freshen up and cool\
off; then we set down on the sandy bottom where the water was about knee\
deep, and watched the daylight come. \'a0Not a sound anywheres--perfectly\
still--just like the whole world was asleep, only sometimes the bullfrogs\
a-cluttering, maybe. \'a0The first thing to see, looking away over the\
water, was a kind of dull line--that was the woods on t\'92other side; you\
couldn\'92t make nothing else out; then a pale place in the sky; then more\
paleness spreading around; then the river softened up away off, and\
warn\'92t black any more, but gray; you could see little dark spots\
drifting along ever so far away--trading scows, and such things; and\
long black streaks--rafts; sometimes you could hear a sweep screaking; or\
jumbled up voices, it was so still, and sounds come so far; and by and\
by you could see a streak on the water which you know by the look of the\
streak that there\'92s a snag there in a swift current which breaks on it\
and makes that streak look that way; and you see the mist curl up off\
of the water, and the east reddens up, and the river, and you make out a\
log-cabin in the edge of the woods, away on the bank on t\'92other side of\
the river, being a woodyard, likely, and piled by them cheats so you can\
throw a dog through it anywheres; then the nice breeze springs up, and\
comes fanning you from over there, so cool and fresh and sweet to smell\
on account of the woods and the flowers; but sometimes not that way,\
because they\'92ve left dead fish laying around, gars and such, and they\
do get pretty rank; and next you\'92ve got the full day, and everything\
smiling in the sun, and the song-birds just going it!\
\
A little smoke couldn\'92t be noticed now, so we would take some fish off\
of the lines and cook up a hot breakfast. \'a0And afterwards we would watch\
the lonesomeness of the river, and kind of lazy along, and by and by\
lazy off to sleep. \'a0Wake up by and by, and look to see what done it, and\
maybe see a steamboat coughing along up-stream, so far off towards the\
other side you couldn\'92t tell nothing about her only whether she was\
a stern-wheel or side-wheel; then for about an hour there wouldn\'92t be\
nothing to hear nor nothing to see--just solid lonesomeness. \'a0Next\
you\'92d see a raft sliding by, away off yonder, and maybe a galoot on it\
chopping, because they\'92re most always doing it on a raft; you\'92d see the\
axe flash and come down--you don\'92t hear nothing; you see that axe go\
up again, and by the time it\'92s above the man\'92s head then you hear the\
_k\'92chunk_!--it had took all that time to come over the water. \'a0So we\
would put in the day, lazying around, listening to the stillness. \'a0Once\
there was a thick fog, and the rafts and things that went by was beating\
tin pans so the steamboats wouldn\'92t run over them. \'a0A scow or a\
raft went by so close we could hear them talking and cussing and\
laughing--heard them plain; but we couldn\'92t see no sign of them; it made\
you feel crawly; it was like spirits carrying on that way in the air.\
\'a0Jim said he believed it was spirits; but I says:\
\
\'93No; spirits wouldn\'92t say, \'91Dern the dern fog.\'92\'94\
\
Soon as it was night out we shoved; when we got her out to about the\
middle we let her alone, and let her float wherever the current wanted\
her to; then we lit the pipes, and dangled our legs in the water, and\
talked about all kinds of things--we was always naked, day and night,\
whenever the mosquitoes would let us--the new clothes Buck\'92s folks made\
for me was too good to be comfortable, and besides I didn\'92t go much on\
clothes, nohow.\
\
Sometimes we\'92d have that whole river all to ourselves for the longest\
time. Yonder was the banks and the islands, across the water; and maybe\
a spark--which was a candle in a cabin window; and sometimes on the water\
you could see a spark or two--on a raft or a scow, you know; and maybe\
you could hear a fiddle or a song coming over from one of them crafts.\
It\'92s lovely to live on a raft. \'a0We had the sky up there, all speckled\
with stars, and we used to lay on our backs and look up at them, and\
discuss about whether they was made or only just happened. \'a0Jim he\
allowed they was made, but I allowed they happened; I judged it would\
have took too long to _make_ so many. \'a0Jim said the moon could a _laid_\
them; well, that looked kind of reasonable, so I didn\'92t say nothing\
against it, because I\'92ve seen a frog lay most as many, so of course it\
could be done. We used to watch the stars that fell, too, and see them\
streak down. \'a0Jim allowed they\'92d got spoiled and was hove out of the\
nest.\
\
Once or twice of a night we would see a steamboat slipping along in the\
dark, and now and then she would belch a whole world of sparks up out\
of her chimbleys, and they would rain down in the river and look awful\
pretty; then she would turn a corner and her lights would wink out and\
her powwow shut off and leave the river still again; and by and by her\
waves would get to us, a long time after she was gone, and joggle the\
raft a bit, and after that you wouldn\'92t hear nothing for you couldn\'92t\
tell how long, except maybe frogs or something.\
\
After midnight the people on shore went to bed, and then for two or\
three hours the shores was black--no more sparks in the cabin windows.\
\'a0These sparks was our clock--the first one that showed again meant\
morning was coming, so we hunted a place to hide and tie up right away.\
\
One morning about daybreak I found a canoe and crossed over a chute to\
the main shore--it was only two hundred yards--and paddled about a mile\
up a crick amongst the cypress woods, to see if I couldn\'92t get some\
berries. Just as I was passing a place where a kind of a cowpath crossed\
the crick, here comes a couple of men tearing up the path as tight as\
they could foot it. \'a0I thought I was a goner, for whenever anybody was\
after anybody I judged it was _me_--or maybe Jim. \'a0I was about to dig out\
from there in a hurry, but they was pretty close to me then, and sung\
out and begged me to save their lives--said they hadn\'92t been doing\
nothing, and was being chased for it--said there was men and dogs\
a-coming. \'a0They wanted to jump right in, but I says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t you do it. \'a0I don\'92t hear the dogs and horses yet; you\'92ve got time\
to crowd through the brush and get up the crick a little ways; then you\
take to the water and wade down to me and get in--that\'92ll throw the dogs\
off the scent.\'94\
\
They done it, and soon as they was aboard I lit out for our towhead,\
and in about five or ten minutes we heard the dogs and the men away off,\
shouting. We heard them come along towards the crick, but couldn\'92t\
see them; they seemed to stop and fool around a while; then, as we got\
further and further away all the time, we couldn\'92t hardly hear them at\
all; by the time we had left a mile of woods behind us and struck the\
river, everything was quiet, and we paddled over to the towhead and hid\
in the cottonwoods and was safe.\
\
One of these fellows was about seventy or upwards, and had a bald head\
and very gray whiskers. \'a0He had an old battered-up slouch hat on, and\
a greasy blue woollen shirt, and ragged old blue jeans britches stuffed\
into his boot-tops, and home-knit galluses--no, he only had one. \'a0He had\
an old long-tailed blue jeans coat with slick brass buttons flung over\
his arm, and both of them had big, fat, ratty-looking carpet-bags.\
\
The other fellow was about thirty, and dressed about as ornery. \'a0After\
breakfast we all laid off and talked, and the first thing that come out\
was that these chaps didn\'92t know one another.\
\
\'93What got you into trouble?\'94 says the baldhead to t\'92other chap.\
\
\'93Well, I\'92d been selling an article to take the tartar off the teeth--and\
it does take it off, too, and generly the enamel along with it--but I\
stayed about one night longer than I ought to, and was just in the act\
of sliding out when I ran across you on the trail this side of town, and\
you told me they were coming, and begged me to help you to get off. \'a0So\
I told you I was expecting trouble myself, and would scatter out _with_\
you. That\'92s the whole yarn--what\'92s yourn?\
\
\'93Well, I\'92d ben a-running\'92 a little temperance revival thar \'91bout a week,\
and was the pet of the women folks, big and little, for I was makin\'92 it\
mighty warm for the rummies, I _tell_ you, and takin\'92 as much as five\
or six dollars a night--ten cents a head, children and niggers free--and\
business a-growin\'92 all the time, when somehow or another a little report\
got around last night that I had a way of puttin\'92 in my time with a\
private jug on the sly. \'a0A nigger rousted me out this mornin\'92, and told\
me the people was getherin\'92 on the quiet with their dogs and horses, and\
they\'92d be along pretty soon and give me \'91bout half an hour\'92s start,\
and then run me down if they could; and if they got me they\'92d tar\
and feather me and ride me on a rail, sure. \'a0I didn\'92t wait for no\
breakfast--I warn\'92t hungry.\'94\
\
\'93Old man,\'94 said the young one, \'93I reckon we might double-team it\
together; what do you think?\'94\
\
\'93I ain\'92t undisposed. \'a0What\'92s your line--mainly?\'94\
\
\'93Jour printer by trade; do a little in patent medicines;\
theater-actor--tragedy, you know; take a turn to mesmerism and phrenology\
when there\'92s a chance; teach singing-geography school for a change;\
sling a lecture sometimes--oh, I do lots of things--most anything that\
comes handy, so it ain\'92t work. \'a0What\'92s your lay?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve done considerble in the doctoring way in my time. \'a0Layin\'92 on o\'92\
hands is my best holt--for cancer and paralysis, and sich things; and I\
k\'92n tell a fortune pretty good when I\'92ve got somebody along to find out\
the facts for me. \'a0Preachin\'92s my line, too, and workin\'92 camp-meetin\'92s,\
and missionaryin\'92 around.\'94\
\
Nobody never said anything for a while; then the young man hove a sigh\
and says:\
\
\'93Alas!\'94\
\
\'93What \'91re you alassin\'92 about?\'94 says the bald-head.\
\
\'93To think I should have lived to be leading such a life, and be degraded\
down into such company.\'94 \'a0And he begun to wipe the corner of his eye\
with a rag.\
\
\'93Dern your skin, ain\'92t the company good enough for you?\'94 says the\
baldhead, pretty pert and uppish.\
\
\'93Yes, it _is_ good enough for me; it\'92s as good as I deserve; for who\
fetched me so low when I was so high? \'a0I did myself. \'a0I don\'92t blame\
_you_, gentlemen--far from it; I don\'92t blame anybody. \'a0I deserve it\
all. \'a0Let the cold world do its worst; one thing I know--there\'92s a grave\
somewhere for me. The world may go on just as it\'92s always done, and take\
everything from me--loved ones, property, everything; but it can\'92t take\
that. Some day I\'92ll lie down in it and forget it all, and my poor broken\
heart will be at rest.\'94 \'a0He went on a-wiping.\
\
\'93Drot your pore broken heart,\'94 says the baldhead; \'93what are you heaving\
your pore broken heart at _us_ f\'92r? \'a0_we_ hain\'92t done nothing.\'94\
\
\'93No, I know you haven\'92t. \'a0I ain\'92t blaming you, gentlemen. \'a0I brought\
myself down--yes, I did it myself. \'a0It\'92s right I should suffer--perfectly\
right--I don\'92t make any moan.\'94\
\
\'93Brought you down from whar? \'a0Whar was you brought down from?\'94\
\
\'93Ah, you would not believe me; the world never believes--let it pass--\'91tis\
no matter. \'a0The secret of my birth--\'94\
\
\'93The secret of your birth! \'a0Do you mean to say--\'94\
\
\'93Gentlemen,\'94 says the young man, very solemn, \'93I will reveal it to you,\
for I feel I may have confidence in you. \'a0By rights I am a duke!\'94\
\
Jim\'92s eyes bugged out when he heard that; and I reckon mine did, too.\
Then the baldhead says:  \'93No! you can\'92t mean it?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. \'a0My great-grandfather, eldest son of the Duke of Bridgewater, fled\
to this country about the end of the last century, to breathe the pure\
air of freedom; married here, and died, leaving a son, his own father\
dying about the same time. \'a0The second son of the late duke seized the\
titles and estates--the infant real duke was ignored. \'a0I am the lineal\
descendant of that infant--I am the rightful Duke of Bridgewater; and\
here am I, forlorn, torn from my high estate, hunted of men, despised\
by the cold world, ragged, worn, heart-broken, and degraded to the\
companionship of felons on a raft!\'94\
\
Jim pitied him ever so much, and so did I. We tried to comfort him, but\
he said it warn\'92t much use, he couldn\'92t be much comforted; said if we\
was a mind to acknowledge him, that would do him more good than most\
anything else; so we said we would, if he would tell us how. \'a0He said we\
ought to bow when we spoke to him, and say \'93Your Grace,\'94 or \'93My Lord,\'94\
 or \'93Your Lordship\'94--and he wouldn\'92t mind it if we called him plain\
\'93Bridgewater,\'94 which, he said, was a title anyway, and not a name; and\
one of us ought to wait on him at dinner, and do any little thing for\
him he wanted done.\
\
Well, that was all easy, so we done it. \'a0All through dinner Jim stood\
around and waited on him, and says, \'93Will yo\'92 Grace have some o\'92 dis or\
some o\'92 dat?\'94 and so on, and a body could see it was mighty pleasing to\
him.\
\
But the old man got pretty silent by and by--didn\'92t have much to say, and\
didn\'92t look pretty comfortable over all that petting that was going on\
around that duke. \'a0He seemed to have something on his mind. \'a0So, along\
in the afternoon, he says:\
\
\'93Looky here, Bilgewater,\'94 he says, \'93I\'92m nation sorry for you, but you\
ain\'92t the only person that\'92s had troubles like that.\'94\
\
\'93No?\'94\
\
\'93No you ain\'92t. \'a0You ain\'92t the only person that\'92s ben snaked down\
wrongfully out\'92n a high place.\'94\
\
\'93Alas!\'94\
\
\'93No, you ain\'92t the only person that\'92s had a secret of his birth.\'94 \'a0And,\
by jings, _he_ begins to cry.\
\
\'93Hold! \'a0What do you mean?\'94\
\
\'93Bilgewater, kin I trust you?\'94 says the old man, still sort of sobbing.\
\
\'93To the bitter death!\'94 \'a0He took the old man by the hand and squeezed it,\
and says, \'93That secret of your being: \'a0speak!\'94\
\
\'93Bilgewater, I am the late Dauphin!\'94\
\
You bet you, Jim and me stared this time. \'a0Then the duke says:\
\
\'93You are what?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, my friend, it is too true--your eyes is lookin\'92 at this very moment\
on the pore disappeared Dauphin, Looy the Seventeen, son of Looy the\
Sixteen and Marry Antonette.\'94\
\
\'93You! \'a0At your age! \'a0No! \'a0You mean you\'92re the late Charlemagne; you must\
be six or seven hundred years old, at the very least.\'94\
\
\'93Trouble has done it, Bilgewater, trouble has done it; trouble has brung\
these gray hairs and this premature balditude. \'a0Yes, gentlemen, you\
see before you, in blue jeans and misery, the wanderin\'92, exiled,\
trampled-on, and sufferin\'92 rightful King of France.\'94\
\
Well, he cried and took on so that me and Jim didn\'92t know hardly what to\
do, we was so sorry--and so glad and proud we\'92d got him with us, too.\
\'a0So we set in, like we done before with the duke, and tried to comfort\
_him_. But he said it warn\'92t no use, nothing but to be dead and done\
with it all could do him any good; though he said it often made him feel\
easier and better for a while if people treated him according to his\
rights, and got down on one knee to speak to him, and always called him\
\'93Your Majesty,\'94 and waited on him first at meals, and didn\'92t set down\
in his presence till he asked them. So Jim and me set to majestying him,\
and doing this and that and t\'92other for him, and standing up till he\
told us we might set down. \'a0This done him heaps of good, and so he\
got cheerful and comfortable. \'a0But the duke kind of soured on him, and\
didn\'92t look a bit satisfied with the way things was going; still,\
the king acted real friendly towards him, and said the duke\'92s\
great-grandfather and all the other Dukes of Bilgewater was a good\
deal thought of by _his_ father, and was allowed to come to the palace\
considerable; but the duke stayed huffy a good while, till by and by the\
king says:\
\
\'93Like as not we got to be together a blamed long time on this h-yer\
raft, Bilgewater, and so what\'92s the use o\'92 your bein\'92 sour? \'a0It \'91ll only\
make things oncomfortable. \'a0It ain\'92t my fault I warn\'92t born a duke,\
it ain\'92t your fault you warn\'92t born a king--so what\'92s the use to worry?\
\'a0Make the best o\'92 things the way you find \'91em, says I--that\'92s my motto.\
\'a0This ain\'92t no bad thing that we\'92ve struck here--plenty grub and an easy\
life--come, give us your hand, duke, and le\'92s all be friends.\'94\
\
The duke done it, and Jim and me was pretty glad to see it. \'a0It took\
away all the uncomfortableness and we felt mighty good over it, because\
it would a been a miserable business to have any unfriendliness on the\
raft; for what you want, above all things, on a raft, is for everybody\
to be satisfied, and feel right and kind towards the others.\
\
It didn\'92t take me long to make up my mind that these liars warn\'92t no\
kings nor dukes at all, but just low-down humbugs and frauds. \'a0But I\
never said nothing, never let on; kept it to myself; it\'92s the best way;\
then you don\'92t have no quarrels, and don\'92t get into no trouble. \'a0If they\
wanted us to call them kings and dukes, I hadn\'92t no objections, \'91long as\
it would keep peace in the family; and it warn\'92t no use to tell Jim, so\
I didn\'92t tell him. \'a0If I never learnt nothing else out of pap, I learnt\
that the best way to get along with his kind of people is to let them\
have their own way.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XX.\
\
THEY asked us considerable many questions; wanted to know what we\
covered up the raft that way for, and laid by in the daytime instead of\
running--was Jim a runaway nigger? \'a0Says I:\
\
\'93Goodness sakes! would a runaway nigger run _south_?\'94\
\
No, they allowed he wouldn\'92t. \'a0I had to account for things some way, so\
I says:\
\
\'93My folks was living in Pike County, in Missouri, where I was born, and\
they all died off but me and pa and my brother Ike. \'a0Pa, he \'91lowed\
he\'92d break up and go down and live with Uncle Ben, who\'92s got a little\
one-horse place on the river, forty-four mile below Orleans. \'a0Pa was\
pretty poor, and had some debts; so when he\'92d squared up there warn\'92t\
nothing left but sixteen dollars and our nigger, Jim. \'a0That warn\'92t\
enough to take us fourteen hundred mile, deck passage nor no other way.\
\'a0Well, when the river rose pa had a streak of luck one day; he ketched\
this piece of a raft; so we reckoned we\'92d go down to Orleans on it.\
\'a0Pa\'92s luck didn\'92t hold out; a steamboat run over the forrard corner of\
the raft one night, and we all went overboard and dove under the wheel;\
Jim and me come up all right, but pa was drunk, and Ike was only four\
years old, so they never come up no more. \'a0Well, for the next day or\
two we had considerable trouble, because people was always coming out in\
skiffs and trying to take Jim away from me, saying they believed he was\
a runaway nigger. \'a0We don\'92t run daytimes no more now; nights they don\'92t\
bother us.\'94\
\
The duke says:\
\
\'93Leave me alone to cipher out a way so we can run in the daytime if we\
want to. \'a0I\'92ll think the thing over--I\'92ll invent a plan that\'92ll fix it.\
We\'92ll let it alone for to-day, because of course we don\'92t want to go by\
that town yonder in daylight--it mightn\'92t be healthy.\'94\
\
Towards night it begun to darken up and look like rain; the heat\
lightning was squirting around low down in the sky, and the leaves was\
beginning to shiver--it was going to be pretty ugly, it was easy to see\
that. \'a0So the duke and the king went to overhauling our wigwam, to see\
what the beds was like. \'a0My bed was a straw tick better than Jim\'92s,\
which was a corn-shuck tick; there\'92s always cobs around about in a shuck\
tick, and they poke into you and hurt; and when you roll over the dry\
shucks sound like you was rolling over in a pile of dead leaves; it\
makes such a rustling that you wake up. \'a0Well, the duke allowed he would\
take my bed; but the king allowed he wouldn\'92t. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93I should a reckoned the difference in rank would a sejested to you that\
a corn-shuck bed warn\'92t just fitten for me to sleep on. \'a0Your Grace \'91ll\
take the shuck bed yourself.\'94\
\
Jim and me was in a sweat again for a minute, being afraid there was\
going to be some more trouble amongst them; so we was pretty glad when\
the duke says:\
\
\'93\'91Tis my fate to be always ground into the mire under the iron heel of\
oppression. \'a0Misfortune has broken my once haughty spirit; I yield, I\
submit; \'91tis my fate. \'a0I am alone in the world--let me suffer; can bear\
it.\'94\
\
We got away as soon as it was good and dark. \'a0The king told us to stand\
well out towards the middle of the river, and not show a light till we\
got a long ways below the town. \'a0We come in sight of the little bunch of\
lights by and by--that was the town, you know--and slid by, about a half\
a mile out, all right. \'a0When we was three-quarters of a mile below we\
hoisted up our signal lantern; and about ten o\'92clock it come on to rain\
and blow and thunder and lighten like everything; so the king told us\
to both stay on watch till the weather got better; then him and the duke\
crawled into the wigwam and turned in for the night. \'a0It was my watch\
below till twelve, but I wouldn\'92t a turned in anyway if I\'92d had a bed,\
because a body don\'92t see such a storm as that every day in the week, not\
by a long sight. \'a0My souls, how the wind did scream along! \'a0And every\
second or two there\'92d come a glare that lit up the white-caps for a half\
a mile around, and you\'92d see the islands looking dusty through the rain,\
and the trees thrashing around in the wind; then comes a H-WHACK!--bum!\
bum! bumble-umble-um-bum-bum-bum-bum--and the thunder would go rumbling\
and grumbling away, and quit--and then RIP comes another flash and\
another sockdolager. \'a0The waves most washed me off the raft sometimes,\
but I hadn\'92t any clothes on, and didn\'92t mind. \'a0We didn\'92t have no trouble\
about snags; the lightning was glaring and flittering around so constant\
that we could see them plenty soon enough to throw her head this way or\
that and miss them.\
\
I had the middle watch, you know, but I was pretty sleepy by that time,\
so Jim he said he would stand the first half of it for me; he was always\
mighty good that way, Jim was. \'a0I crawled into the wigwam, but the king\
and the duke had their legs sprawled around so there warn\'92t no show for\
me; so I laid outside--I didn\'92t mind the rain, because it was warm, and\
the waves warn\'92t running so high now. \'a0About two they come up again,\
though, and Jim was going to call me; but he changed his mind, because\
he reckoned they warn\'92t high enough yet to do any harm; but he was\
mistaken about that, for pretty soon all of a sudden along comes a\
regular ripper and washed me overboard. \'a0It most killed Jim a-laughing.\
\'a0He was the easiest nigger to laugh that ever was, anyway.\
\
I took the watch, and Jim he laid down and snored away; and by and by\
the storm let up for good and all; and the first cabin-light that showed\
I rousted him out, and we slid the raft into hiding quarters for the\
day.\
\
The king got out an old ratty deck of cards after breakfast, and him\
and the duke played seven-up a while, five cents a game. \'a0Then they got\
tired of it, and allowed they would \'93lay out a campaign,\'94 as they called\
it. The duke went down into his carpet-bag, and fetched up a lot of\
little printed bills and read them out loud. \'a0One bill said, \'93The\
celebrated Dr. Armand de Montalban, of Paris,\'94 would \'93lecture on the\
Science of Phrenology\'94 at such and such a place, on the blank day of\
blank, at ten cents admission, and \'93furnish charts of character at\
twenty-five cents apiece.\'94 \'a0The duke said that was _him_. \'a0In another\
bill he was the \'93world-renowned Shakespearian tragedian, Garrick the\
Younger, of Drury Lane, London.\'94 \'a0In other bills he had a lot of other\
names and done other wonderful things, like finding water and gold with\
a \'93divining-rod,\'94 \'93dissipating witch spells,\'94 and so on. \'a0By and by he\
says:\
\
\'93But the histrionic muse is the darling. \'a0Have you ever trod the boards,\
Royalty?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says the king.\
\
\'93You shall, then, before you\'92re three days older, Fallen Grandeur,\'94 says\
the duke.  \'93The first good town we come to we\'92ll hire a hall and do the\
sword fight in Richard III. and the balcony scene in Romeo and Juliet.\
How does that strike you?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m in, up to the hub, for anything that will pay, Bilgewater; but, you\
see, I don\'92t know nothing about play-actin\'92, and hain\'92t ever seen much\
of it. \'a0I was too small when pap used to have \'91em at the palace. \'a0Do you\
reckon you can learn me?\'94\
\
\'93Easy!\'94\
\
\'93All right. \'a0I\'92m jist a-freezn\'92 for something fresh, anyway. \'a0Le\'92s\
commence right away.\'94\
\
So the duke he told him all about who Romeo was and who Juliet was, and\
said he was used to being Romeo, so the king could be Juliet.\
\
\'93But if Juliet\'92s such a young gal, duke, my peeled head and my white\
whiskers is goin\'92 to look oncommon odd on her, maybe.\'94\
\
\'93No, don\'92t you worry; these country jakes won\'92t ever think of that.\
Besides, you know, you\'92ll be in costume, and that makes all the\
difference in the world; Juliet\'92s in a balcony, enjoying the moonlight\
before she goes to bed, and she\'92s got on her night-gown and her ruffled\
nightcap. \'a0Here are the costumes for the parts.\'94\
\
He got out two or three curtain-calico suits, which he said was\
meedyevil armor for Richard III. and t\'92other chap, and a long white\
cotton nightshirt and a ruffled nightcap to match. \'a0The king was\
satisfied; so the duke got out his book and read the parts over in the\
most splendid spread-eagle way, prancing around and acting at the same\
time, to show how it had got to be done; then he give the book to the\
king and told him to get his part by heart.\
\
There was a little one-horse town about three mile down the bend, and\
after dinner the duke said he had ciphered out his idea about how to run\
in daylight without it being dangersome for Jim; so he allowed he would\
go down to the town and fix that thing. \'a0The king allowed he would go,\
too, and see if he couldn\'92t strike something. \'a0We was out of coffee, so\
Jim said I better go along with them in the canoe and get some.\
\
When we got there there warn\'92t nobody stirring; streets empty, and\
perfectly dead and still, like Sunday. \'a0We found a sick nigger sunning\
himself in a back yard, and he said everybody that warn\'92t too young or\
too sick or too old was gone to camp-meeting, about two mile back in the\
woods. \'a0The king got the directions, and allowed he\'92d go and work that\
camp-meeting for all it was worth, and I might go, too.\
\
The duke said what he was after was a printing-office. \'a0We found it;\
a little bit of a concern, up over a carpenter shop--carpenters and\
printers all gone to the meeting, and no doors locked. \'a0It was a dirty,\
littered-up place, and had ink marks, and handbills with pictures of\
horses and runaway niggers on them, all over the walls. \'a0The duke shed\
his coat and said he was all right now. \'a0So me and the king lit out for\
the camp-meeting.\
\
We got there in about a half an hour fairly dripping, for it was a most\
awful hot day. \'a0There was as much as a thousand people there from\
twenty mile around. \'a0The woods was full of teams and wagons, hitched\
everywheres, feeding out of the wagon-troughs and stomping to keep\
off the flies. \'a0There was sheds made out of poles and roofed over with\
branches, where they had lemonade and gingerbread to sell, and piles of\
watermelons and green corn and such-like truck.\
\
The preaching was going on under the same kinds of sheds, only they was\
bigger and held crowds of people. \'a0The benches was made out of outside\
slabs of logs, with holes bored in the round side to drive sticks into\
for legs. They didn\'92t have no backs. \'a0The preachers had high platforms\
to stand on at one end of the sheds. \'a0The women had on sun-bonnets;\
and some had linsey-woolsey frocks, some gingham ones, and a few of the\
young ones had on calico. \'a0Some of the young men was barefooted, and\
some of the children didn\'92t have on any clothes but just a tow-linen\
shirt. \'a0Some of the old women was knitting, and some of the young folks\
was courting on the sly.\
\
The first shed we come to the preacher was lining out a hymn. \'a0He lined\
out two lines, everybody sung it, and it was kind of grand to hear it,\
there was so many of them and they done it in such a rousing way; then\
he lined out two more for them to sing--and so on. \'a0The people woke up\
more and more, and sung louder and louder; and towards the end some\
begun to groan, and some begun to shout. \'a0Then the preacher begun to\
preach, and begun in earnest, too; and went weaving first to one side of\
the platform and then the other, and then a-leaning down over the front\
of it, with his arms and his body going all the time, and shouting his\
words out with all his might; and every now and then he would hold up\
his Bible and spread it open, and kind of pass it around this way and\
that, shouting, \'93It\'92s the brazen serpent in the wilderness! \'a0Look upon\
it and live!\'94 \'a0And people would shout out, \'93Glory!--A-a-_men_!\'94 \'a0And so\
he went on, and the people groaning and crying and saying amen:\
\
\'93Oh, come to the mourners\'92 bench! come, black with sin! (_Amen_!) come,\
sick and sore! (_Amen_!) come, lame and halt and blind! (_Amen_!) come,\
pore and needy, sunk in shame! (_A-A-Men_!) come, all that\'92s worn and\
soiled and suffering!--come with a broken spirit! come with a contrite\
heart! come in your rags and sin and dirt! the waters that cleanse\
is free, the door of heaven stands open--oh, enter in and be at rest!\'94\
 (_A-A-Men_! \'a0_Glory, Glory Hallelujah!_)\
\
And so on. \'a0You couldn\'92t make out what the preacher said any more, on\
account of the shouting and crying. \'a0Folks got up everywheres in the\
crowd, and worked their way just by main strength to the mourners\'92\
bench, with the tears running down their faces; and when all the\
mourners had got up there to the front benches in a crowd, they sung and\
shouted and flung themselves down on the straw, just crazy and wild.\
\
Well, the first I knowed the king got a-going, and you could hear him\
over everybody; and next he went a-charging up on to the platform, and\
the preacher he begged him to speak to the people, and he done it. \'a0He\
told them he was a pirate--been a pirate for thirty years out in the\
Indian Ocean--and his crew was thinned out considerable last spring in\
a fight, and he was home now to take out some fresh men, and thanks to\
goodness he\'92d been robbed last night and put ashore off of a steamboat\
without a cent, and he was glad of it; it was the blessedest thing that\
ever happened to him, because he was a changed man now, and happy for\
the first time in his life; and, poor as he was, he was going to start\
right off and work his way back to the Indian Ocean, and put in the rest\
of his life trying to turn the pirates into the true path; for he could\
do it better than anybody else, being acquainted with all pirate crews\
in that ocean; and though it would take him a long time to get there\
without money, he would get there anyway, and every time he convinced\
a pirate he would say to him, \'93Don\'92t you thank me, don\'92t you give me no\
credit; it all belongs to them dear people in Pokeville camp-meeting,\
natural brothers and benefactors of the race, and that dear preacher\
there, the truest friend a pirate ever had!\'94\
\
And then he busted into tears, and so did everybody. \'a0Then somebody\
sings out, \'93Take up a collection for him, take up a collection!\'94 \'a0Well,\
a half a dozen made a jump to do it, but somebody sings out, \'93Let _him_\
pass the hat around!\'94 \'a0Then everybody said it, the preacher too.\
\
So the king went all through the crowd with his hat swabbing his eyes,\
and blessing the people and praising them and thanking them for being\
so good to the poor pirates away off there; and every little while the\
prettiest kind of girls, with the tears running down their cheeks, would\
up and ask him would he let them kiss him for to remember him by; and he\
always done it; and some of them he hugged and kissed as many as five or\
six times--and he was invited to stay a week; and everybody wanted him to\
live in their houses, and said they\'92d think it was an honor; but he said\
as this was the last day of the camp-meeting he couldn\'92t do no good, and\
besides he was in a sweat to get to the Indian Ocean right off and go to\
work on the pirates.\
\
When we got back to the raft and he come to count up he found he had\
collected eighty-seven dollars and seventy-five cents. \'a0And then he had\
fetched away a three-gallon jug of whisky, too, that he found under a\
wagon when he was starting home through the woods. \'a0The king said,\
take it all around, it laid over any day he\'92d ever put in in the\
missionarying line. \'a0He said it warn\'92t no use talking, heathens don\'92t\
amount to shucks alongside of pirates to work a camp-meeting with.\
\
The duke was thinking _he\'92d_ been doing pretty well till the king come\
to show up, but after that he didn\'92t think so so much. \'a0He had set\
up and printed off two little jobs for farmers in that\
printing-office--horse bills--and took the money, four dollars. \'a0And he\
had got in ten dollars\'92 worth of advertisements for the paper, which he\
said he would put in for four dollars if they would pay in advance--so\
they done it. The price of the paper was two dollars a year, but he took\
in three subscriptions for half a dollar apiece on condition of them\
paying him in advance; they were going to pay in cordwood and onions as\
usual, but he said he had just bought the concern and knocked down the\
price as low as he could afford it, and was going to run it for cash.\
\'a0He set up a little piece of poetry, which he made, himself, out of\
his own head--three verses--kind of sweet and saddish--the name of it was,\
\'93Yes, crush, cold world, this breaking heart\'94--and he left that all set\
up and ready to print in the paper, and didn\'92t charge nothing for it.\
\'a0Well, he took in nine dollars and a half, and said he\'92d done a pretty\
square day\'92s work for it.\
\
Then he showed us another little job he\'92d printed and hadn\'92t charged\
for, because it was for us. \'a0It had a picture of a runaway nigger with\
a bundle on a stick over his shoulder, and \'93$200 reward\'94 under it. \'a0The\
reading was all about Jim, and just described him to a dot. \'a0It said\
he run away from St. Jacques\'92 plantation, forty mile below New Orleans,\
last winter, and likely went north, and whoever would catch him and send\
him back he could have the reward and expenses.\
\
\'93Now,\'94 says the duke, \'93after to-night we can run in the daytime if we\
want to. \'a0Whenever we see anybody coming we can tie Jim hand and foot\
with a rope, and lay him in the wigwam and show this handbill and say we\
captured him up the river, and were too poor to travel on a steamboat,\
so we got this little raft on credit from our friends and are going down\
to get the reward. \'a0Handcuffs and chains would look still better on Jim,\
but it wouldn\'92t go well with the story of us being so poor. \'a0Too much\
like jewelry. \'a0Ropes are the correct thing--we must preserve the unities,\
as we say on the boards.\'94\
\
We all said the duke was pretty smart, and there couldn\'92t be no trouble\
about running daytimes. \'a0We judged we could make miles enough that night\
to get out of the reach of the powwow we reckoned the duke\'92s work in\
the printing office was going to make in that little town; then we could\
boom right along if we wanted to.\
\
We laid low and kept still, and never shoved out till nearly ten\
o\'92clock; then we slid by, pretty wide away from the town, and didn\'92t\
hoist our lantern till we was clear out of sight of it.\
\
When Jim called me to take the watch at four in the morning, he says:\
\
\'93Huck, does you reck\'92n we gwyne to run acrost any mo\'92 kings on dis\
trip?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I says, \'93I reckon not.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 says he, \'93dat\'92s all right, den. \'a0I doan\'92 mine one er two kings,\
but dat\'92s enough. \'a0Dis one\'92s powerful drunk, en de duke ain\'92 much\
better.\'94\
\
I found Jim had been trying to get him to talk French, so he could hear\
what it was like; but he said he had been in this country so long, and\
had so much trouble, he\'92d forgot it.\
\
\
