\
Then we went loafing around the town. The stores and houses was most all\
old shackly dried-up frame concerns that hadn\'92t ever been painted; they\
was set up three or four foot above ground on stilts, so as to be out of\
reach of the water when the river was overflowed. The houses had little\
gardens around them, but they didn\'92t seem to raise hardly anything in\
them but jimpson weeds, and sunflowers, and ash-piles, and old curled-up\
boots and shoes, and pieces of bottles, and rags, and played-out\
tin-ware. The fences was made of different kinds of boards, nailed on\
at different times; and they leaned every which-way, and had gates that\
didn\'92t generly have but one hinge--a leather one. Some of the fences\
had been whitewashed, some time or another, but the duke said it was in\
Clumbus\'92s time, like enough. There was generly hogs in the garden, and\
people driving them out.\
\
All the stores was along one street. \'a0They had white domestic awnings in\
front, and the country people hitched their horses to the awning-posts.\
There was empty drygoods boxes under the awnings, and loafers roosting\
on them all day long, whittling them with their Barlow knives; and\
chawing tobacco, and gaping and yawning and stretching--a mighty ornery\
lot. They generly had on yellow straw hats most as wide as an umbrella,\
but didn\'92t wear no coats nor waistcoats, they called one another Bill,\
and Buck, and Hank, and Joe, and Andy, and talked lazy and drawly, and\
used considerable many cuss words. \'a0There was as many as one loafer\
leaning up against every awning-post, and he most always had his hands\
in his britches-pockets, except when he fetched them out to lend a chaw\
of tobacco or scratch. \'a0What a body was hearing amongst them all the\
time was:\
\
\'93Gimme a chaw \'91v tobacker, Hank.\'94\
\
\'93Cain\'92t; I hain\'92t got but one chaw left. \'a0Ask Bill.\'94\
\
Maybe Bill he gives him a chaw; maybe he lies and says he ain\'92t got\
none. Some of them kinds of loafers never has a cent in the world, nor a\
chaw of tobacco of their own. \'a0They get all their chawing by borrowing;\
they say to a fellow, \'93I wisht you\'92d len\'92 me a chaw, Jack, I jist this\
minute give Ben Thompson the last chaw I had\'94--which is a lie pretty\
much everytime; it don\'92t fool nobody but a stranger; but Jack ain\'92t no\
stranger, so he says:\
\
\'93_You_ give him a chaw, did you? \'a0So did your sister\'92s cat\'92s\
grandmother. You pay me back the chaws you\'92ve awready borry\'92d off\'92n me,\
Lafe Buckner, then I\'92ll loan you one or two ton of it, and won\'92t charge\
you no back intrust, nuther.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I _did_ pay you back some of it wunst.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, you did--\'91bout six chaws. \'a0You borry\'92d store tobacker and paid back\
nigger-head.\'94\
\
Store tobacco is flat black plug, but these fellows mostly chaws the\
natural leaf twisted. \'a0When they borrow a chaw they don\'92t generly cut it\
off with a knife, but set the plug in between their teeth, and gnaw with\
their teeth and tug at the plug with their hands till they get it in\
two; then sometimes the one that owns the tobacco looks mournful at it\
when it\'92s handed back, and says, sarcastic:\
\
\'93Here, gimme the _chaw_, and you take the _plug_.\'94\
\
All the streets and lanes was just mud; they warn\'92t nothing else _but_\
mud--mud as black as tar and nigh about a foot deep in some places,\
and two or three inches deep in _all_ the places. \'a0The hogs loafed and\
grunted around everywheres. \'a0You\'92d see a muddy sow and a litter of pigs\
come lazying along the street and whollop herself right down in the way,\
where folks had to walk around her, and she\'92d stretch out and shut her\
eyes and wave her ears whilst the pigs was milking her, and look as\
happy as if she was on salary. And pretty soon you\'92d hear a loafer\
sing out, \'93Hi! \'a0_so_ boy! sick him, Tige!\'94 and away the sow would go,\
squealing most horrible, with a dog or two swinging to each ear, and\
three or four dozen more a-coming; and then you would see all the\
loafers get up and watch the thing out of sight, and laugh at the fun\
and look grateful for the noise. \'a0Then they\'92d settle back again till\
there was a dog fight. \'a0There couldn\'92t anything wake them up all over,\
and make them happy all over, like a dog fight--unless it might be\
putting turpentine on a stray dog and setting fire to him, or tying a\
tin pan to his tail and see him run himself to death.\
\
On the river front some of the houses was sticking out over the bank,\
and they was bowed and bent, and about ready to tumble in. The people\
had moved out of them. \'a0The bank was caved away under one corner of some\
others, and that corner was hanging over. \'a0People lived in them yet, but\
it was dangersome, because sometimes a strip of land as wide as a house\
caves in at a time. \'a0Sometimes a belt of land a quarter of a mile deep\
will start in and cave along and cave along till it all caves into the\
river in one summer. Such a town as that has to be always moving back,\
and back, and back, because the river\'92s always gnawing at it.\
\
The nearer it got to noon that day the thicker and thicker was the\
wagons and horses in the streets, and more coming all the time.\
\'a0Families fetched their dinners with them from the country, and eat them\
in the wagons. \'a0There was considerable whisky drinking going on, and I\
seen three fights. \'a0By and by somebody sings out:\
\
\'93Here comes old Boggs!--in from the country for his little old monthly\
drunk; here he comes, boys!\'94\
\
All the loafers looked glad; I reckoned they was used to having fun out\
of Boggs. \'a0One of them says:\
\
\'93Wonder who he\'92s a-gwyne to chaw up this time. \'a0If he\'92d a-chawed up all\
the men he\'92s ben a-gwyne to chaw up in the last twenty year he\'92d have\
considerable ruputation now.\'94\
\
Another one says, \'93I wisht old Boggs \'91d threaten me, \'91cuz then I\'92d know\
I warn\'92t gwyne to die for a thousan\'92 year.\'94\
\
Boggs comes a-tearing along on his horse, whooping and yelling like an\
Injun, and singing out:\
\
\'93Cler the track, thar. \'a0I\'92m on the waw-path, and the price uv coffins is\
a-gwyne to raise.\'94\
\
He was drunk, and weaving about in his saddle; he was over fifty year\
old, and had a very red face. \'a0Everybody yelled at him and laughed at\
him and sassed him, and he sassed back, and said he\'92d attend to them and\
lay them out in their regular turns, but he couldn\'92t wait now because\
he\'92d come to town to kill old Colonel Sherburn, and his motto was, \'93Meat\
first, and spoon vittles to top off on.\'94\
\
He see me, and rode up and says:\
\
\'93Whar\'92d you come f\'92m, boy? \'a0You prepared to die?\'94\
\
Then he rode on. \'a0I was scared, but a man says:\
\
\'93He don\'92t mean nothing; he\'92s always a-carryin\'92 on like that when he\'92s\
drunk. \'a0He\'92s the best naturedest old fool in Arkansaw--never hurt nobody,\
drunk nor sober.\'94\
\
Boggs rode up before the biggest store in town, and bent his head down\
so he could see under the curtain of the awning and yells:\
\
\'93Come out here, Sherburn! Come out and meet the man you\'92ve swindled.\
You\'92re the houn\'92 I\'92m after, and I\'92m a-gwyne to have you, too!\'94\
\
And so he went on, calling Sherburn everything he could lay his tongue\
to, and the whole street packed with people listening and laughing and\
going on. \'a0By and by a proud-looking man about fifty-five--and he was a\
heap the best dressed man in that town, too--steps out of the store, and\
the crowd drops back on each side to let him come. \'a0He says to Boggs,\
mighty ca\'92m and slow--he says:\
\
\'93I\'92m tired of this, but I\'92ll endure it till one o\'92clock. \'a0Till one\
o\'92clock, mind--no longer. \'a0If you open your mouth against me only once\
after that time you can\'92t travel so far but I will find you.\'94\
\
Then he turns and goes in. \'a0The crowd looked mighty sober; nobody\
stirred, and there warn\'92t no more laughing. \'a0Boggs rode off\
blackguarding Sherburn as loud as he could yell, all down the street;\
and pretty soon back he comes and stops before the store, still keeping\
it up. \'a0Some men crowded around him and tried to get him to shut up,\
but he wouldn\'92t; they told him it would be one o\'92clock in about fifteen\
minutes, and so he _must_ go home--he must go right away. \'a0But it didn\'92t\
do no good. \'a0He cussed away with all his might, and throwed his hat down\
in the mud and rode over it, and pretty soon away he went a-raging down\
the street again, with his gray hair a-flying. Everybody that could get\
a chance at him tried their best to coax him off of his horse so they\
could lock him up and get him sober; but it warn\'92t no use--up the street\
he would tear again, and give Sherburn another cussing. \'a0By and by\
somebody says:\
\
\'93Go for his daughter!--quick, go for his daughter; sometimes he\'92ll listen\
to her. \'a0If anybody can persuade him, she can.\'94\
\
So somebody started on a run. \'a0I walked down street a ways and stopped.\
In about five or ten minutes here comes Boggs again, but not on his\
horse. \'a0He was a-reeling across the street towards me, bare-headed, with\
a friend on both sides of him a-holt of his arms and hurrying him along.\
He was quiet, and looked uneasy; and he warn\'92t hanging back any, but was\
doing some of the hurrying himself. \'a0Somebody sings out:\
\
\'93Boggs!\'94\
\
I looked over there to see who said it, and it was that Colonel\
Sherburn. He was standing perfectly still in the street, and had a\
pistol raised in his right hand--not aiming it, but holding it out with\
the barrel tilted up towards the sky. \'a0The same second I see a young\
girl coming on the run, and two men with her. \'a0Boggs and the men turned\
round to see who called him, and when they see the pistol the men\
jumped to one side, and the pistol-barrel come down slow and steady to\
a level--both barrels cocked. Boggs throws up both of his hands and says,\
\'93O Lord, don\'92t shoot!\'94 \'a0Bang! goes the first shot, and he staggers back,\
clawing at the air--bang! goes the second one, and he tumbles backwards\
on to the ground, heavy and solid, with his arms spread out. \'a0That young\
girl screamed out and comes rushing, and down she throws herself on her\
father, crying, and saying, \'93Oh, he\'92s killed him, he\'92s killed him!\'94 \'a0The\
crowd closed up around them, and shouldered and jammed one another, with\
their necks stretched, trying to see, and people on the inside trying to\
shove them back and shouting, \'93Back, back! give him air, give him air!\'94\
\
Colonel Sherburn he tossed his pistol on to the ground, and turned\
around on his heels and walked off.\
\
They took Boggs to a little drug store, the crowd pressing around just\
the same, and the whole town following, and I rushed and got a good\
place at the window, where I was close to him and could see in. \'a0They\
laid him on the floor and put one large Bible under his head, and opened\
another one and spread it on his breast; but they tore open his shirt\
first, and I seen where one of the bullets went in. \'a0He made about a\
dozen long gasps, his breast lifting the Bible up when he drawed in his\
breath, and letting it down again when he breathed it out--and after that\
he laid still; he was dead. \'a0Then they pulled his daughter away from\
him, screaming and crying, and took her off. \'a0She was about sixteen, and\
very sweet and gentle looking, but awful pale and scared.\
\
Well, pretty soon the whole town was there, squirming and scrouging and\
pushing and shoving to get at the window and have a look, but people\
that had the places wouldn\'92t give them up, and folks behind them was\
saying all the time, \'93Say, now, you\'92ve looked enough, you fellows;\
\'91tain\'92t right and \'91tain\'92t fair for you to stay thar all the time, and\
never give nobody a chance; other folks has their rights as well as\
you.\'94\
\
There was considerable jawing back, so I slid out, thinking maybe\
there was going to be trouble. \'a0The streets was full, and everybody was\
excited. Everybody that seen the shooting was telling how it happened,\
and there was a big crowd packed around each one of these fellows,\
stretching their necks and listening. \'a0One long, lanky man, with long\
hair and a big white fur stovepipe hat on the back of his head, and a\
crooked-handled cane, marked out the places on the ground where Boggs\
stood and where Sherburn stood, and the people following him around from\
one place to t\'92other and watching everything he done, and bobbing their\
heads to show they understood, and stooping a little and resting their\
hands on their thighs to watch him mark the places on the ground with\
his cane; and then he stood up straight and stiff where Sherburn had\
stood, frowning and having his hat-brim down over his eyes, and sung\
out, \'93Boggs!\'94 and then fetched his cane down slow to a level, and says\
\'93Bang!\'94 staggered backwards, says \'93Bang!\'94 again, and fell down flat on\
his back. The people that had seen the thing said he done it perfect;\
said it was just exactly the way it all happened. \'a0Then as much as a\
dozen people got out their bottles and treated him.\
\
Well, by and by somebody said Sherburn ought to be lynched. \'a0In about a\
minute everybody was saying it; so away they went, mad and yelling, and\
snatching down every clothes-line they come to to do the hanging with.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXII.\
\
THEY swarmed up towards Sherburn\'92s house, a-whooping and raging like\
Injuns, and everything had to clear the way or get run over and tromped\
to mush, and it was awful to see. \'a0Children was heeling it ahead of the\
mob, screaming and trying to get out of the way; and every window along\
the road was full of women\'92s heads, and there was nigger boys in every\
tree, and bucks and wenches looking over every fence; and as soon as the\
mob would get nearly to them they would break and skaddle back out of\
reach. \'a0Lots of the women and girls was crying and taking on, scared\
most to death.\
\
They swarmed up in front of Sherburn\'92s palings as thick as they could\
jam together, and you couldn\'92t hear yourself think for the noise. \'a0It\
was a little twenty-foot yard. \'a0Some sung out \'93Tear down the fence! tear\
down the fence!\'94 \'a0Then there was a racket of ripping and tearing and\
smashing, and down she goes, and the front wall of the crowd begins to\
roll in like a wave.\
\
Just then Sherburn steps out on to the roof of his little front porch,\
with a double-barrel gun in his hand, and takes his stand, perfectly\
ca\'92m and deliberate, not saying a word. \'a0The racket stopped, and the\
wave sucked back.\
\
Sherburn never said a word--just stood there, looking down. \'a0The\
stillness was awful creepy and uncomfortable. \'a0Sherburn run his eye slow\
along the crowd; and wherever it struck the people tried a little to\
out-gaze him, but they couldn\'92t; they dropped their eyes and looked\
sneaky. Then pretty soon Sherburn sort of laughed; not the pleasant\
kind, but the kind that makes you feel like when you are eating bread\
that\'92s got sand in it.\
\
Then he says, slow and scornful:\
\
\'93The idea of _you_ lynching anybody! \'a0It\'92s amusing. \'a0The idea of you\
thinking you had pluck enough to lynch a _man_! \'a0Because you\'92re brave\
enough to tar and feather poor friendless cast-out women that come along\
here, did that make you think you had grit enough to lay your hands on a\
_man_? \'a0Why, a _man\'92s_ safe in the hands of ten thousand of your kind--as\
long as it\'92s daytime and you\'92re not behind him.\
\
\'93Do I know you? \'a0I know you clear through. I was born and raised in the\
South, and I\'92ve lived in the North; so I know the average all around.\
The average man\'92s a coward. \'a0In the North he lets anybody walk over him\
that wants to, and goes home and prays for a humble spirit to bear it.\
In the South one man all by himself, has stopped a stage full of men\
in the daytime, and robbed the lot. \'a0Your newspapers call you a\
brave people so much that you think you are braver than any other\
people--whereas you\'92re just _as_ brave, and no braver. \'a0Why don\'92t your\
juries hang murderers? \'a0Because they\'92re afraid the man\'92s friends will\
shoot them in the back, in the dark--and it\'92s just what they _would_ do.\
\
\'93So they always acquit; and then a _man_ goes in the night, with a\
hundred masked cowards at his back and lynches the rascal. \'a0Your mistake\
is, that you didn\'92t bring a man with you; that\'92s one mistake, and the\
other is that you didn\'92t come in the dark and fetch your masks. \'a0You\
brought _part_ of a man--Buck Harkness, there--and if you hadn\'92t had him\
to start you, you\'92d a taken it out in blowing.\
\
\'93You didn\'92t want to come. \'a0The average man don\'92t like trouble and\
danger. _You_ don\'92t like trouble and danger. \'a0But if only _half_ a\
man--like Buck Harkness, there--shouts \'91Lynch him! lynch him!\'92 you\'92re\
afraid to back down--afraid you\'92ll be found out to be what you\
are--_cowards_--and so you raise a yell, and hang yourselves on to that\
half-a-man\'92s coat-tail, and come raging up here, swearing what big\
things you\'92re going to do. The pitifulest thing out is a mob; that\'92s\
what an army is--a mob; they don\'92t fight with courage that\'92s born in\
them, but with courage that\'92s borrowed from their mass, and from their\
officers. \'a0But a mob without any _man_ at the head of it is _beneath_\
pitifulness. \'a0Now the thing for _you_ to do is to droop your tails and\
go home and crawl in a hole. \'a0If any real lynching\'92s going to be done it\
will be done in the dark, Southern fashion; and when they come they\'92ll\
bring their masks, and fetch a _man_ along. \'a0Now _leave_--and take your\
half-a-man with you\'94--tossing his gun up across his left arm and cocking\
it when he says this.\
\
The crowd washed back sudden, and then broke all apart, and went tearing\
off every which way, and Buck Harkness he heeled it after them, looking\
tolerable cheap. \'a0I could a stayed if I wanted to, but I didn\'92t want to.\
\
I went to the circus and loafed around the back side till the watchman\
went by, and then dived in under the tent. \'a0I had my twenty-dollar gold\
piece and some other money, but I reckoned I better save it, because\
there ain\'92t no telling how soon you are going to need it, away from\
home and amongst strangers that way. \'a0You can\'92t be too careful. \'a0I ain\'92t\
opposed to spending money on circuses when there ain\'92t no other way, but\
there ain\'92t no use in _wasting_ it on them.\
\
It was a real bully circus. \'a0It was the splendidest sight that ever was\
when they all come riding in, two and two, a gentleman and lady, side\
by side, the men just in their drawers and undershirts, and no shoes\
nor stirrups, and resting their hands on their thighs easy and\
comfortable--there must a been twenty of them--and every lady with a\
lovely complexion, and perfectly beautiful, and looking just like a gang\
of real sure-enough queens, and dressed in clothes that cost millions of\
dollars, and just littered with diamonds. \'a0It was a powerful fine sight;\
I never see anything so lovely. \'a0And then one by one they got up\
and stood, and went a-weaving around the ring so gentle and wavy and\
graceful, the men looking ever so tall and airy and straight, with their\
heads bobbing and skimming along, away up there under the tent-roof, and\
every lady\'92s rose-leafy dress flapping soft and silky around her hips,\
and she looking like the most loveliest parasol.\
\
And then faster and faster they went, all of them dancing, first one\
foot out in the air and then the other, the horses leaning more and\
more, and the ringmaster going round and round the center-pole, cracking\
his whip and shouting \'93Hi!--hi!\'94 and the clown cracking jokes behind\
him; and by and by all hands dropped the reins, and every lady put her\
knuckles on her hips and every gentleman folded his arms, and then how\
the horses did lean over and hump themselves! \'a0And so one after the\
other they all skipped off into the ring, and made the sweetest bow I\
ever see, and then scampered out, and everybody clapped their hands and\
went just about wild.\
\
Well, all through the circus they done the most astonishing things; and\
all the time that clown carried on so it most killed the people. \'a0The\
ringmaster couldn\'92t ever say a word to him but he was back at him quick\
as a wink with the funniest things a body ever said; and how he ever\
_could_ think of so many of them, and so sudden and so pat, was what I\
couldn\'92t noway understand. Why, I couldn\'92t a thought of them in a year.\
And by and by a drunk man tried to get into the ring--said he wanted to\
ride; said he could ride as well as anybody that ever was. \'a0They argued\
and tried to keep him out, but he wouldn\'92t listen, and the whole show\
come to a standstill. \'a0Then the people begun to holler at him and make\
fun of him, and that made him mad, and he begun to rip and tear; so that\
stirred up the people, and a lot of men begun to pile down off of the\
benches and swarm towards the ring, saying, \'93Knock him down! throw him\
out!\'94 and one or two women begun to scream. \'a0So, then, the ringmaster\
he made a little speech, and said he hoped there wouldn\'92t be no\
disturbance, and if the man would promise he wouldn\'92t make no more\
trouble he would let him ride if he thought he could stay on the horse.\
\'a0So everybody laughed and said all right, and the man got on. The minute\
he was on, the horse begun to rip and tear and jump and cavort around,\
with two circus men hanging on to his bridle trying to hold him, and the\
drunk man hanging on to his neck, and his heels flying in the air every\
jump, and the whole crowd of people standing up shouting and laughing\
till tears rolled down. \'a0And at last, sure enough, all the circus men\
could do, the horse broke loose, and away he went like the very nation,\
round and round the ring, with that sot laying down on him and hanging\
to his neck, with first one leg hanging most to the ground on one side,\
and then t\'92other one on t\'92other side, and the people just crazy. \'a0It\
warn\'92t funny to me, though; I was all of a tremble to see his danger.\
\'a0But pretty soon he struggled up astraddle and grabbed the bridle,\
a-reeling this way and that; and the next minute he sprung up and\
dropped the bridle and stood! and the horse a-going like a house afire\
too. \'a0He just stood up there, a-sailing around as easy and comfortable\
as if he warn\'92t ever drunk in his life--and then he begun to pull off his\
clothes and sling them. \'a0He shed them so thick they kind of clogged up\
the air, and altogether he shed seventeen suits. And, then, there he\
was, slim and handsome, and dressed the gaudiest and prettiest you\
ever saw, and he lit into that horse with his whip and made him fairly\
hum--and finally skipped off, and made his bow and danced off to\
the dressing-room, and everybody just a-howling with pleasure and\
astonishment.\
\
Then the ringmaster he see how he had been fooled, and he _was_ the\
sickest ringmaster you ever see, I reckon. \'a0Why, it was one of his own\
men! \'a0He had got up that joke all out of his own head, and never let on\
to nobody. Well, I felt sheepish enough to be took in so, but I wouldn\'92t\
a been in that ringmaster\'92s place, not for a thousand dollars. \'a0I don\'92t\
know; there may be bullier circuses than what that one was, but I\
never struck them yet. Anyways, it was plenty good enough for _me_; and\
wherever I run across it, it can have all of _my_ custom every time.\
\
Well, that night we had _our_ show; but there warn\'92t only about twelve\
people there--just enough to pay expenses. \'a0And they laughed all the\
time, and that made the duke mad; and everybody left, anyway, before\
the show was over, but one boy which was asleep. \'a0So the duke said these\
Arkansaw lunkheads couldn\'92t come up to Shakespeare; what they wanted\
was low comedy--and maybe something ruther worse than low comedy, he\
reckoned. \'a0He said he could size their style. \'a0So next morning he got\
some big sheets of wrapping paper and some black paint, and drawed off\
some handbills, and stuck them up all over the village. \'a0The bills said:\
\
