CHAPTER XXIII.\
\
WELL, all day him and the king was hard at it, rigging up a stage and\
a curtain and a row of candles for footlights; and that night the house\
was jam full of men in no time. \'a0When the place couldn\'92t hold no more,\
the duke he quit tending door and went around the back way and come on\
to the stage and stood up before the curtain and made a little speech,\
and praised up this tragedy, and said it was the most thrillingest one\
that ever was; and so he went on a-bragging about the tragedy, and about\
Edmund Kean the Elder, which was to play the main principal part in it;\
and at last when he\'92d got everybody\'92s expectations up high enough, he\
rolled up the curtain, and the next minute the king come a-prancing\
out on all fours, naked; and he was painted all over,\
ring-streaked-and-striped, all sorts of colors, as splendid as a\
rainbow. \'a0And--but never mind the rest of his outfit; it was just wild,\
but it was awful funny. The people most killed themselves laughing; and\
when the king got done capering and capered off behind the scenes, they\
roared and clapped and stormed and haw-hawed till he come back and done\
it over again, and after that they made him do it another time. Well, it\
would make a cow laugh to see the shines that old idiot cut.\
\
Then the duke he lets the curtain down, and bows to the people, and says\
the great tragedy will be performed only two nights more, on accounts of\
pressing London engagements, where the seats is all sold already for it\
in Drury Lane; and then he makes them another bow, and says if he has\
succeeded in pleasing them and instructing them, he will be deeply\
obleeged if they will mention it to their friends and get them to come\
and see it.\
\
Twenty people sings out:\
\
\'93What, is it over? \'a0Is that _all_?\'94\
\
The duke says yes. \'a0Then there was a fine time. \'a0Everybody sings\
out, \'93Sold!\'94 and rose up mad, and was a-going for that stage and them\
tragedians. \'a0But a big, fine looking man jumps up on a bench and shouts:\
\
\'93Hold on! \'a0Just a word, gentlemen.\'94 \'a0They stopped to listen.  \'93We are\
sold--mighty badly sold. \'a0But we don\'92t want to be the laughing stock of\
this whole town, I reckon, and never hear the last of this thing as long\
as we live. \'a0_No_. \'a0What we want is to go out of here quiet, and talk\
this show up, and sell the _rest_ of the town! \'a0Then we\'92ll all be in the\
same boat. \'a0Ain\'92t that sensible?\'94 (\'93You bet it is!--the jedge is right!\'94\
 everybody sings out.) \'93All right, then--not a word about any sell. \'a0Go\
along home, and advise everybody to come and see the tragedy.\'94\
\
Next day you couldn\'92t hear nothing around that town but how splendid\
that show was. \'a0House was jammed again that night, and we sold this\
crowd the same way. \'a0When me and the king and the duke got home to the\
raft we all had a supper; and by and by, about midnight, they made Jim\
and me back her out and float her down the middle of the river, and\
fetch her in and hide her about two mile below town.\
\
The third night the house was crammed again--and they warn\'92t new-comers\
this time, but people that was at the show the other two nights. \'a0I\
stood by the duke at the door, and I see that every man that went in had\
his pockets bulging, or something muffled up under his coat--and I see it\
warn\'92t no perfumery, neither, not by a long sight. \'a0I smelt sickly eggs\
by the barrel, and rotten cabbages, and such things; and if I know the\
signs of a dead cat being around, and I bet I do, there was sixty-four\
of them went in. \'a0I shoved in there for a minute, but it was too various\
for me; I couldn\'92t stand it. \'a0Well, when the place couldn\'92t hold no more\
people the duke he give a fellow a quarter and told him to tend door\
for him a minute, and then he started around for the stage door, I after\
him; but the minute we turned the corner and was in the dark he says:\
\
\'93Walk fast now till you get away from the houses, and then shin for the\
raft like the dickens was after you!\'94\
\
I done it, and he done the same. \'a0We struck the raft at the same time,\
and in less than two seconds we was gliding down stream, all dark and\
still, and edging towards the middle of the river, nobody saying a\
word. I reckoned the poor king was in for a gaudy time of it with the\
audience, but nothing of the sort; pretty soon he crawls out from under\
the wigwam, and says:\
\
\'93Well, how\'92d the old thing pan out this time, duke?\'94 \'a0He hadn\'92t been\
up-town at all.\
\
We never showed a light till we was about ten mile below the village.\
Then we lit up and had a supper, and the king and the duke fairly\
laughed their bones loose over the way they\'92d served them people. \'a0The\
duke says:\
\
\'93Greenhorns, flatheads! \'a0I knew the first house would keep mum and let\
the rest of the town get roped in; and I knew they\'92d lay for us the\
third night, and consider it was _their_ turn now. \'a0Well, it _is_ their\
turn, and I\'92d give something to know how much they\'92d take for it. \'a0I\
_would_ just like to know how they\'92re putting in their opportunity.\
\'a0They can turn it into a picnic if they want to--they brought plenty\
provisions.\'94\
\
Them rapscallions took in four hundred and sixty-five dollars in that\
three nights. \'a0I never see money hauled in by the wagon-load like that\
before. \'a0By and by, when they was asleep and snoring, Jim says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t it s\'92prise you de way dem kings carries on, Huck?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 I says, \'93it don\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Why don\'92t it, Huck?\'94\
\
\'93Well, it don\'92t, because it\'92s in the breed. \'a0I reckon they\'92re all\
alike.\'94\
\
\'93But, Huck, dese kings o\'92 ourn is reglar rapscallions; dat\'92s jist what\
dey is; dey\'92s reglar rapscallions.\'94\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s what I\'92m a-saying; all kings is mostly rapscallions, as\
fur as I can make out.\'94\
\
\'93Is dat so?\'94\
\
\'93You read about them once--you\'92ll see. \'a0Look at Henry the Eight; this \'91n\
\'91s a Sunday-school Superintendent to _him_. \'a0And look at Charles Second,\
and Louis Fourteen, and Louis Fifteen, and James Second, and Edward\
Second, and Richard Third, and forty more; besides all them Saxon\
heptarchies that used to rip around so in old times and raise Cain. \'a0My,\
you ought to seen old Henry the Eight when he was in bloom. \'a0He _was_ a\
blossom. \'a0He used to marry a new wife every day, and chop off her head\
next morning. \'a0And he would do it just as indifferent as if he was\
ordering up eggs.  \'91Fetch up Nell Gwynn,\'92 he says. \'a0They fetch her up.\
Next morning, \'91Chop off her head!\'92 \'a0And they chop it off.  \'91Fetch up\
Jane Shore,\'92 he says; and up she comes, Next morning, \'91Chop off her\
head\'92--and they chop it off.  \'91Ring up Fair Rosamun.\'92 \'a0Fair Rosamun\
answers the bell. \'a0Next morning, \'91Chop off her head.\'92 \'a0And he made every\
one of them tell him a tale every night; and he kept that up till he had\
hogged a thousand and one tales that way, and then he put them all in a\
book, and called it Domesday Book--which was a good name and stated the\
case. \'a0You don\'92t know kings, Jim, but I know them; and this old rip\
of ourn is one of the cleanest I\'92ve struck in history. \'a0Well, Henry he\
takes a notion he wants to get up some trouble with this country. How\
does he go at it--give notice?--give the country a show? \'a0No. \'a0All of a\
sudden he heaves all the tea in Boston Harbor overboard, and whacks\
out a declaration of independence, and dares them to come on. \'a0That was\
_his_ style--he never give anybody a chance. \'a0He had suspicions of his\
father, the Duke of Wellington. \'a0Well, what did he do? \'a0Ask him to show\
up? \'a0No--drownded him in a butt of mamsey, like a cat. \'a0S\'92pose people\
left money laying around where he was--what did he do? \'a0He collared it.\
\'a0S\'92pose he contracted to do a thing, and you paid him, and didn\'92t set\
down there and see that he done it--what did he do? \'a0He always done the\
other thing. S\'92pose he opened his mouth--what then? \'a0If he didn\'92t shut it\
up powerful quick he\'92d lose a lie every time. \'a0That\'92s the kind of a bug\
Henry was; and if we\'92d a had him along \'91stead of our kings he\'92d a fooled\
that town a heap worse than ourn done. \'a0I don\'92t say that ourn is lambs,\
because they ain\'92t, when you come right down to the cold facts; but they\
ain\'92t nothing to _that_ old ram, anyway. \'a0All I say is, kings is kings,\
and you got to make allowances. \'a0Take them all around, they\'92re a mighty\
ornery lot. It\'92s the way they\'92re raised.\'94\
\
\'93But dis one do _smell_ so like de nation, Huck.\'94\
\
\'93Well, they all do, Jim. \'a0We can\'92t help the way a king smells; history\
don\'92t tell no way.\'94\
\
\'93Now de duke, he\'92s a tolerble likely man in some ways.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, a duke\'92s different. \'a0But not very different. \'a0This one\'92s\
a middling hard lot for a duke. \'a0When he\'92s drunk there ain\'92t no\
near-sighted man could tell him from a king.\'94\
\
\'93Well, anyways, I doan\'92 hanker for no mo\'92 un um, Huck. \'a0Dese is all I\
kin stan\'92.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s the way I feel, too, Jim. \'a0But we\'92ve got them on our hands, and we\
got to remember what they are, and make allowances. \'a0Sometimes I wish we\
could hear of a country that\'92s out of kings.\'94\
\
What was the use to tell Jim these warn\'92t real kings and dukes? \'a0It\
wouldn\'92t a done no good; and, besides, it was just as I said: \'a0you\
couldn\'92t tell them from the real kind.\
\
I went to sleep, and Jim didn\'92t call me when it was my turn. \'a0He often\
done that. \'a0When I waked up just at daybreak he was sitting there with\
his head down betwixt his knees, moaning and mourning to himself. \'a0I\
didn\'92t take notice nor let on. \'a0I knowed what it was about. \'a0He was\
thinking about his wife and his children, away up yonder, and he was low\
and homesick; because he hadn\'92t ever been away from home before in his\
life; and I do believe he cared just as much for his people as white\
folks does for their\'92n. \'a0It don\'92t seem natural, but I reckon it\'92s so.\
\'a0He was often moaning and mourning that way nights, when he judged I\
was asleep, and saying, \'93Po\'92 little \'91Lizabeth! po\'92 little Johnny! it\'92s\
mighty hard; I spec\'92 I ain\'92t ever gwyne to see you no mo\'92, no mo\'92!\'94 \'a0He\
was a mighty good nigger, Jim was.\
\
But this time I somehow got to talking to him about his wife and young\
ones; and by and by he says:\
\
\'93What makes me feel so bad dis time \'91uz bekase I hear sumpn over yonder\
on de bank like a whack, er a slam, while ago, en it mine me er de time\
I treat my little \'91Lizabeth so ornery. \'a0She warn\'92t on\'92y \'91bout fo\'92 year\
ole, en she tuck de sk\'92yarlet fever, en had a powful rough spell; but\
she got well, en one day she was a-stannin\'92 aroun\'92, en I says to her, I\
says:\
\
\'93\'91Shet de do\'92.\'92\
\
\'93She never done it; jis\'92 stood dah, kiner smilin\'92 up at me. \'a0It make me\
mad; en I says agin, mighty loud, I says:\
\
\'93\'91Doan\'92 you hear me? \'a0Shet de do\'92!\'92\
\
\'93She jis stood de same way, kiner smilin\'92 up. \'a0I was a-bilin\'92! \'a0I says:\
\
\'93\'91I lay I _make_ you mine!\'92\
\
\'93En wid dat I fetch\'92 her a slap side de head dat sont her a-sprawlin\'92.\
Den I went into de yuther room, en \'91uz gone \'91bout ten minutes; en when\
I come back dah was dat do\'92 a-stannin\'92 open _yit_, en dat chile stannin\'92\
mos\'92 right in it, a-lookin\'92 down and mournin\'92, en de tears runnin\'92 down.\
\'a0My, but I _wuz_ mad! \'a0I was a-gwyne for de chile, but jis\'92 den--it was a\
do\'92 dat open innerds--jis\'92 den, \'91long come de wind en slam it to, behine\
de chile, ker-BLAM!--en my lan\'92, de chile never move\'92! \'a0My breff mos\'92\
hop outer me; en I feel so--so--I doan\'92 know HOW I feel. \'a0I crope out,\
all a-tremblin\'92, en crope aroun\'92 en open de do\'92 easy en slow, en poke my\
head in behine de chile, sof\'92 en still, en all uv a sudden I says POW!\
jis\'92 as loud as I could yell. \'a0_She never budge!_ \'a0Oh, Huck, I bust out\
a-cryin\'92 en grab her up in my arms, en say, \'91Oh, de po\'92 little thing!\
\'a0De Lord God Amighty fogive po\'92 ole Jim, kaze he never gwyne to fogive\
hisself as long\'92s he live!\'92 \'a0Oh, she was plumb deef en dumb, Huck, plumb\
deef en dumb--en I\'92d ben a-treat\'92n her so!\'94\
\
