CHAPTER XXIV.\
\
NEXT day, towards night, we laid up under a little willow towhead out in\
the middle, where there was a village on each side of the river, and the\
duke and the king begun to lay out a plan for working them towns. \'a0Jim\
he spoke to the duke, and said he hoped it wouldn\'92t take but a few\
hours, because it got mighty heavy and tiresome to him when he had to\
lay all day in the wigwam tied with the rope. \'a0You see, when we left him\
all alone we had to tie him, because if anybody happened on to him all\
by himself and not tied it wouldn\'92t look much like he was a runaway\
nigger, you know. So the duke said it _was_ kind of hard to have to lay\
roped all day, and he\'92d cipher out some way to get around it.\
\
He was uncommon bright, the duke was, and he soon struck it. \'a0He dressed\
Jim up in King Lear\'92s outfit--it was a long curtain-calico gown, and a\
white horse-hair wig and whiskers; and then he took his theater paint\
and painted Jim\'92s face and hands and ears and neck all over a dead,\
dull, solid blue, like a man that\'92s been drownded nine days. \'a0Blamed if\
he warn\'92t the horriblest looking outrage I ever see. \'a0Then the duke took\
and wrote out a sign on a shingle so:\
\
Sick Arab--but harmless when not out of his head.\
\
And he nailed that shingle to a lath, and stood the lath up four or five\
foot in front of the wigwam. \'a0Jim was satisfied. \'a0He said it was a sight\
better than lying tied a couple of years every day, and trembling all\
over every time there was a sound. \'a0The duke told him to make himself\
free and easy, and if anybody ever come meddling around, he must hop\
out of the wigwam, and carry on a little, and fetch a howl or two like\
a wild beast, and he reckoned they would light out and leave him alone.\
\'a0Which was sound enough judgment; but you take the average man, and he\
wouldn\'92t wait for him to howl. \'a0Why, he didn\'92t only look like he was\
dead, he looked considerable more than that.\
\
These rapscallions wanted to try the Nonesuch again, because there was\
so much money in it, but they judged it wouldn\'92t be safe, because maybe\
the news might a worked along down by this time. \'a0They couldn\'92t hit no\
project that suited exactly; so at last the duke said he reckoned he\'92d\
lay off and work his brains an hour or two and see if he couldn\'92t put up\
something on the Arkansaw village; and the king he allowed he would drop\
over to t\'92other village without any plan, but just trust in Providence\
to lead him the profitable way--meaning the devil, I reckon. \'a0We had all\
bought store clothes where we stopped last; and now the king put his\'92n\
on, and he told me to put mine on. \'a0I done it, of course. \'a0The king\'92s\
duds was all black, and he did look real swell and starchy. \'a0I never\
knowed how clothes could change a body before. \'a0Why, before, he looked\
like the orneriest old rip that ever was; but now, when he\'92d take off\
his new white beaver and make a bow and do a smile, he looked that grand\
and good and pious that you\'92d say he had walked right out of the ark,\
and maybe was old Leviticus himself. \'a0Jim cleaned up the canoe, and I\
got my paddle ready. \'a0There was a big steamboat laying at the shore away\
up under the point, about three mile above the town--been there a couple\
of hours, taking on freight. \'a0Says the king:\
\
\'93Seein\'92 how I\'92m dressed, I reckon maybe I better arrive down from St.\
Louis or Cincinnati, or some other big place. \'a0Go for the steamboat,\
Huckleberry; we\'92ll come down to the village on her.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t have to be ordered twice to go and take a steamboat ride.\
\'a0I fetched the shore a half a mile above the village, and then went\
scooting along the bluff bank in the easy water. \'a0Pretty soon we come to\
a nice innocent-looking young country jake setting on a log swabbing the\
sweat off of his face, for it was powerful warm weather; and he had a\
couple of big carpet-bags by him.\
\
\'93Run her nose in shore,\'94 says the king. \'a0I done it.  \'93Wher\'92 you bound\
for, young man?\'94\
\
\'93For the steamboat; going to Orleans.\'94\
\
\'93Git aboard,\'94 says the king.  \'93Hold on a minute, my servant \'91ll he\'92p you\
with them bags. \'a0Jump out and he\'92p the gentleman, Adolphus\'94--meaning me,\
I see.\
\
I done so, and then we all three started on again. \'a0The young chap was\
mighty thankful; said it was tough work toting his baggage such weather.\
He asked the king where he was going, and the king told him he\'92d come\
down the river and landed at the other village this morning, and now he\
was going up a few mile to see an old friend on a farm up there. \'a0The\
young fellow says:\
\
\'93When I first see you I says to myself, \'91It\'92s Mr. Wilks, sure, and he\
come mighty near getting here in time.\'92 \'a0But then I says again, \'91No, I\
reckon it ain\'92t him, or else he wouldn\'92t be paddling up the river.\'92 \'a0You\
_ain\'92t_ him, are you?\'94\
\
\'93No, my name\'92s Blodgett--Elexander Blodgett--_Reverend_ Elexander\
Blodgett, I s\'92pose I must say, as I\'92m one o\'92 the Lord\'92s poor servants.\
\'a0But still I\'92m jist as able to be sorry for Mr. Wilks for not arriving\
in time, all the same, if he\'92s missed anything by it--which I hope he\
hasn\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Well, he don\'92t miss any property by it, because he\'92ll get that all\
right; but he\'92s missed seeing his brother Peter die--which he mayn\'92t\
mind, nobody can tell as to that--but his brother would a give anything\
in this world to see _him_ before he died; never talked about nothing\
else all these three weeks; hadn\'92t seen him since they was boys\
together--and hadn\'92t ever seen his brother William at all--that\'92s the deef\
and dumb one--William ain\'92t more than thirty or thirty-five. \'a0Peter and\
George were the only ones that come out here; George was the married\
brother; him and his wife both died last year. \'a0Harvey and William\'92s the\
only ones that\'92s left now; and, as I was saying, they haven\'92t got here\
in time.\'94\
\
\'93Did anybody send \'91em word?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes; a month or two ago, when Peter was first took; because Peter\
said then that he sorter felt like he warn\'92t going to get well this\
time. You see, he was pretty old, and George\'92s g\'92yirls was too young to\
be much company for him, except Mary Jane, the red-headed one; and so he\
was kinder lonesome after George and his wife died, and didn\'92t seem\
to care much to live. \'a0He most desperately wanted to see Harvey--and\
William, too, for that matter--because he was one of them kind that can\'92t\
bear to make a will. \'a0He left a letter behind for Harvey, and said he\'92d\
told in it where his money was hid, and how he wanted the rest of the\
property divided up so George\'92s g\'92yirls would be all right--for George\
didn\'92t leave nothing. \'a0And that letter was all they could get him to put\
a pen to.\'94\
\
\'93Why do you reckon Harvey don\'92t come? \'a0Wher\'92 does he live?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, he lives in England--Sheffield--preaches there--hasn\'92t ever been in\
this country. \'a0He hasn\'92t had any too much time--and besides he mightn\'92t a\
got the letter at all, you know.\'94\
\
\'93Too bad, too bad he couldn\'92t a lived to see his brothers, poor soul.\
You going to Orleans, you say?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, but that ain\'92t only a part of it. \'a0I\'92m going in a ship, next\
Wednesday, for Ryo Janeero, where my uncle lives.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a pretty long journey. \'a0But it\'92ll be lovely; wisht I was a-going.\
Is Mary Jane the oldest? \'a0How old is the others?\'94\
\
\'93Mary Jane\'92s nineteen, Susan\'92s fifteen, and Joanna\'92s about\
fourteen--that\'92s the one that gives herself to good works and has a\
hare-lip.\'94\
\
\'93Poor things! to be left alone in the cold world so.\'94\
\
\'93Well, they could be worse off. \'a0Old Peter had friends, and they\
ain\'92t going to let them come to no harm. \'a0There\'92s Hobson, the Babtis\'92\
preacher; and Deacon Lot Hovey, and Ben Rucker, and Abner Shackleford,\
and Levi Bell, the lawyer; and Dr. Robinson, and their wives, and the\
widow Bartley, and--well, there\'92s a lot of them; but these are the ones\
that Peter was thickest with, and used to write about sometimes, when\
he wrote home; so Harvey \'91ll know where to look for friends when he gets\
here.\'94\
\
Well, the old man went on asking questions till he just fairly emptied\
that young fellow. \'a0Blamed if he didn\'92t inquire about everybody and\
everything in that blessed town, and all about the Wilkses; and about\
Peter\'92s business--which was a tanner; and about George\'92s--which was a\
carpenter; and about Harvey\'92s--which was a dissentering minister; and so\
on, and so on. \'a0Then he says:\
\
\'93What did you want to walk all the way up to the steamboat for?\'94\
\
\'93Because she\'92s a big Orleans boat, and I was afeard she mightn\'92t stop\
there. \'a0When they\'92re deep they won\'92t stop for a hail. \'a0A Cincinnati boat\
will, but this is a St. Louis one.\'94\
\
\'93Was Peter Wilks well off?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes, pretty well off. \'a0He had houses and land, and it\'92s reckoned he\
left three or four thousand in cash hid up som\'92ers.\'94\
\
\'93When did you say he died?\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t say, but it was last night.\'94\
\
\'93Funeral to-morrow, likely?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, \'91bout the middle of the day.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it\'92s all terrible sad; but we\'92ve all got to go, one time or\
another. So what we want to do is to be prepared; then we\'92re all right.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, sir, it\'92s the best way. \'a0Ma used to always say that.\'94\
\
When we struck the boat she was about done loading, and pretty soon she\
got off. \'a0The king never said nothing about going aboard, so I lost\
my ride, after all. \'a0When the boat was gone the king made me paddle up\
another mile to a lonesome place, and then he got ashore and says:\
\
\'93Now hustle back, right off, and fetch the duke up here, and the new\
carpet-bags. \'a0And if he\'92s gone over to t\'92other side, go over there and\
git him. \'a0And tell him to git himself up regardless. \'a0Shove along, now.\'94\
\
I see what _he_ was up to; but I never said nothing, of course. \'a0When\
I got back with the duke we hid the canoe, and then they set down on a\
log, and the king told him everything, just like the young fellow had\
said it--every last word of it. \'a0And all the time he was a-doing it he\
tried to talk like an Englishman; and he done it pretty well, too, for\
a slouch. I can\'92t imitate him, and so I ain\'92t a-going to try to; but he\
really done it pretty good. \'a0Then he says:\
\
\'93How are you on the deef and dumb, Bilgewater?\'94\
\
The duke said, leave him alone for that; said he had played a deef\
and dumb person on the histronic boards. \'a0So then they waited for a\
steamboat.\
\
About the middle of the afternoon a couple of little boats come along,\
but they didn\'92t come from high enough up the river; but at last there\
was a big one, and they hailed her. \'a0She sent out her yawl, and we went\
aboard, and she was from Cincinnati; and when they found we only wanted\
to go four or five mile they was booming mad, and gave us a cussing, and\
said they wouldn\'92t land us. \'a0But the king was ca\'92m. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93If gentlemen kin afford to pay a dollar a mile apiece to be took on and\
put off in a yawl, a steamboat kin afford to carry \'91em, can\'92t it?\'94\
\
So they softened down and said it was all right; and when we got to the\
village they yawled us ashore. \'a0About two dozen men flocked down when\
they see the yawl a-coming, and when the king says:\
\
\'93Kin any of you gentlemen tell me wher\'92 Mr. Peter Wilks lives?\'94 they\
give a glance at one another, and nodded their heads, as much as to say,\
\'93What d\'92 I tell you?\'94 \'a0Then one of them says, kind of soft and gentle:\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry sir, but the best we can do is to tell you where he _did_\
live yesterday evening.\'94\
\
Sudden as winking the ornery old cretur went an to smash, and fell up\
against the man, and put his chin on his shoulder, and cried down his\
back, and says:\
\
\'93Alas, alas, our poor brother--gone, and we never got to see him; oh,\
it\'92s too, too hard!\'94\
\
Then he turns around, blubbering, and makes a lot of idiotic signs to\
the duke on his hands, and blamed if he didn\'92t drop a carpet-bag and\
bust out a-crying. \'a0If they warn\'92t the beatenest lot, them two frauds,\
that ever I struck.\
\
Well, the men gathered around and sympathized with them, and said all\
sorts of kind things to them, and carried their carpet-bags up the hill\
for them, and let them lean on them and cry, and told the king all about\
his brother\'92s last moments, and the king he told it all over again on\
his hands to the duke, and both of them took on about that dead tanner\
like they\'92d lost the twelve disciples. \'a0Well, if ever I struck anything\
like it, I\'92m a nigger. It was enough to make a body ashamed of the human\
race.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXV.\
\
THE news was all over town in two minutes, and you could see the people\
tearing down on the run from every which way, some of them putting on\
their coats as they come. \'a0Pretty soon we was in the middle of a crowd,\
and the noise of the tramping was like a soldier march. \'a0The windows and\
dooryards was full; and every minute somebody would say, over a fence:\
\
\'93Is it _them_?\'94\
\
And somebody trotting along with the gang would answer back and say:\
\
\'93You bet it is.\'94\
\
When we got to the house the street in front of it was packed, and the\
three girls was standing in the door. \'a0Mary Jane _was_ red-headed, but\
that don\'92t make no difference, she was most awful beautiful, and her\
face and her eyes was all lit up like glory, she was so glad her uncles\
was come. The king he spread his arms, and Mary Jane she jumped for\
them, and the hare-lip jumped for the duke, and there they had it!\
\'a0Everybody most, leastways women, cried for joy to see them meet again\
at last and have such good times.\
\
Then the king he hunched the duke private--I see him do it--and then he\
looked around and see the coffin, over in the corner on two chairs; so\
then him and the duke, with a hand across each other\'92s shoulder, and\
t\'92other hand to their eyes, walked slow and solemn over there, everybody\
dropping back to give them room, and all the talk and noise stopping,\
people saying \'93Sh!\'94 and all the men taking their hats off and drooping\
their heads, so you could a heard a pin fall. \'a0And when they got there\
they bent over and looked in the coffin, and took one sight, and then\
they bust out a-crying so you could a heard them to Orleans, most; and\
then they put their arms around each other\'92s necks, and hung their chins\
over each other\'92s shoulders; and then for three minutes, or maybe four,\
I never see two men leak the way they done. \'a0And, mind you, everybody\
was doing the same; and the place was that damp I never see anything\
like it. Then one of them got on one side of the coffin, and t\'92other on\
t\'92other side, and they kneeled down and rested their foreheads on the\
coffin, and let on to pray all to themselves. \'a0Well, when it come\
to that it worked the crowd like you never see anything like it, and\
everybody broke down and went to sobbing right out loud--the poor girls,\
too; and every woman, nearly, went up to the girls, without saying a\
word, and kissed them, solemn, on the forehead, and then put their hand\
on their head, and looked up towards the sky, with the tears running\
down, and then busted out and went off sobbing and swabbing, and give\
the next woman a show. \'a0I never see anything so disgusting.\
\
Well, by and by the king he gets up and comes forward a little, and\
works himself up and slobbers out a speech, all full of tears and\
flapdoodle about its being a sore trial for him and his poor brother\
to lose the diseased, and to miss seeing diseased alive after the long\
journey of four thousand mile, but it\'92s a trial that\'92s sweetened and\
sanctified to us by this dear sympathy and these holy tears, and so he\
thanks them out of his heart and out of his brother\'92s heart, because out\
of their mouths they can\'92t, words being too weak and cold, and all that\
kind of rot and slush, till it was just sickening; and then he blubbers\
out a pious goody-goody Amen, and turns himself loose and goes to crying\
fit to bust.\
\
And the minute the words were out of his mouth somebody over in the\
crowd struck up the doxolojer, and everybody joined in with all their\
might, and it just warmed you up and made you feel as good as church\
letting out. Music is a good thing; and after all that soul-butter and\
hogwash I never see it freshen up things so, and sound so honest and\
bully.\
\
Then the king begins to work his jaw again, and says how him and his\
nieces would be glad if a few of the main principal friends of the\
family would take supper here with them this evening, and help set up\
with the ashes of the diseased; and says if his poor brother laying\
yonder could speak he knows who he would name, for they was names that\
was very dear to him, and mentioned often in his letters; and so he will\
name the same, to wit, as follows, vizz.:--Rev. Mr. Hobson, and Deacon\
Lot Hovey, and Mr. Ben Rucker, and Abner Shackleford, and Levi Bell, and\
Dr. Robinson, and their wives, and the widow Bartley.\
\
Rev. Hobson and Dr. Robinson was down to the end of the town a-hunting\
together--that is, I mean the doctor was shipping a sick man to t\'92other\
world, and the preacher was pinting him right. \'a0Lawyer Bell was away up\
to Louisville on business. \'a0But the rest was on hand, and so they all\
come and shook hands with the king and thanked him and talked to him;\
and then they shook hands with the duke and didn\'92t say nothing, but just\
kept a-smiling and bobbing their heads like a passel of sapheads whilst\
he made all sorts of signs with his hands and said \'93Goo-goo--goo-goo-goo\'94\
 all the time, like a baby that can\'92t talk.\
\
So the king he blattered along, and managed to inquire about pretty\
much everybody and dog in town, by his name, and mentioned all sorts\
of little things that happened one time or another in the town, or to\
George\'92s family, or to Peter. \'a0And he always let on that Peter wrote him\
the things; but that was a lie: \'a0he got every blessed one of them out of\
that young flathead that we canoed up to the steamboat.\
\
Then Mary Jane she fetched the letter her father left behind, and the\
king he read it out loud and cried over it. \'a0It give the dwelling-house\
and three thousand dollars, gold, to the girls; and it give the tanyard\
(which was doing a good business), along with some other houses and\
land (worth about seven thousand), and three thousand dollars in gold\
to Harvey and William, and told where the six thousand cash was hid down\
cellar. \'a0So these two frauds said they\'92d go and fetch it up, and have\
everything square and above-board; and told me to come with a candle.\
\'a0We shut the cellar door behind us, and when they found the bag\
they spilt it out on the floor, and it was a lovely sight, all them\
yaller-boys. \'a0My, the way the king\'92s eyes did shine! \'a0He slaps the duke\
on the shoulder and says:\
\
\'93Oh, _this_ ain\'92t bully nor noth\'92n! \'a0Oh, no, I reckon not! \'a0Why,\
_bully_, it beats the Nonesuch, _don\'92t_ it?\'94\
\
The duke allowed it did. \'a0They pawed the yaller-boys, and sifted them\
through their fingers and let them jingle down on the floor; and the\
king says:\
\
\'93It ain\'92t no use talkin\'92; bein\'92 brothers to a rich dead man and\
representatives of furrin heirs that\'92s got left is the line for you and\
me, Bilge. \'a0Thish yer comes of trust\'92n to Providence. \'a0It\'92s the best\
way, in the long run. \'a0I\'92ve tried \'91em all, and ther\'92 ain\'92t no better\
way.\'94\
\
Most everybody would a been satisfied with the pile, and took it on\
trust; but no, they must count it. \'a0So they counts it, and it comes out\
four hundred and fifteen dollars short. \'a0Says the king:\
\
\'93Dern him, I wonder what he done with that four hundred and fifteen\
dollars?\'94\
\
They worried over that awhile, and ransacked all around for it. \'a0Then\
the duke says:\
\
\'93Well, he was a pretty sick man, and likely he made a mistake--I reckon\
that\'92s the way of it. \'a0The best way\'92s to let it go, and keep still about\
it. \'a0We can spare it.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, shucks, yes, we can _spare_ it. \'a0I don\'92t k\'92yer noth\'92n \'91bout\
that--it\'92s the _count_ I\'92m thinkin\'92 about. \'a0We want to be awful square\
and open and above-board here, you know. \'a0We want to lug this h-yer\
money up stairs and count it before everybody--then ther\'92 ain\'92t noth\'92n\
suspicious. \'a0But when the dead man says ther\'92s six thous\'92n dollars, you\
know, we don\'92t want to--\'94\
\
\'93Hold on,\'94 says the duke.  \'93Le\'92s make up the deffisit,\'94 and he begun to\
haul out yaller-boys out of his pocket.\
\
\'93It\'92s a most amaz\'92n\'92 good idea, duke--you _have_ got a rattlin\'92 clever\
head on you,\'94 says the king.  \'93Blest if the old Nonesuch ain\'92t a heppin\'92\
us out agin,\'94 and _he_ begun to haul out yaller-jackets and stack them\
up.\
\
It most busted them, but they made up the six thousand clean and clear.\
\
\'93Say,\'94 says the duke, \'93I got another idea. \'a0Le\'92s go up stairs and count\
this money, and then take and _give it to the girls_.\'94\
\
\'93Good land, duke, lemme hug you! \'a0It\'92s the most dazzling idea \'91at ever a\
man struck. \'a0You have cert\'92nly got the most astonishin\'92 head I ever see.\
Oh, this is the boss dodge, ther\'92 ain\'92t no mistake \'91bout it. \'a0Let \'91em\
fetch along their suspicions now if they want to--this \'91ll lay \'91em out.\'94\
\
When we got up-stairs everybody gethered around the table, and the king\
he counted it and stacked it up, three hundred dollars in a pile--twenty\
elegant little piles. \'a0Everybody looked hungry at it, and licked their\
chops. \'a0Then they raked it into the bag again, and I see the king begin\
to swell himself up for another speech. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Friends all, my poor brother that lays yonder has done generous by\
them that\'92s left behind in the vale of sorrers. \'a0He has done generous by\
these yer poor little lambs that he loved and sheltered, and that\'92s left\
fatherless and motherless. \'a0Yes, and we that knowed him knows that he\
would a done _more_ generous by \'91em if he hadn\'92t ben afeard o\'92 woundin\'92\
his dear William and me. \'a0Now, _wouldn\'92t_ he? \'a0Ther\'92 ain\'92t no question\
\'91bout it in _my_ mind. \'a0Well, then, what kind o\'92 brothers would it be\
that \'91d stand in his way at sech a time? \'a0And what kind o\'92 uncles would\
it be that \'91d rob--yes, _rob_--sech poor sweet lambs as these \'91at he loved\
so at sech a time? \'a0If I know William--and I _think_ I do--he--well, I\'92ll\
jest ask him.\'94 He turns around and begins to make a lot of signs to\
the duke with his hands, and the duke he looks at him stupid and\
leather-headed a while; then all of a sudden he seems to catch his\
meaning, and jumps for the king, goo-gooing with all his might for joy,\
and hugs him about fifteen times before he lets up. \'a0Then the king says,\
\'93I knowed it; I reckon _that \'91ll_ convince anybody the way _he_ feels\
about it. \'a0Here, Mary Jane, Susan, Joanner, take the money--take it\
_all_. \'a0It\'92s the gift of him that lays yonder, cold but joyful.\'94\
\
Mary Jane she went for him, Susan and the hare-lip went for the\
duke, and then such another hugging and kissing I never see yet. \'a0And\
everybody crowded up with the tears in their eyes, and most shook the\
hands off of them frauds, saying all the time:\
\
\'93You _dear_ good souls!--how _lovely_!--how _could_ you!\'94\
\
Well, then, pretty soon all hands got to talking about the diseased\
again, and how good he was, and what a loss he was, and all that; and\
before long a big iron-jawed man worked himself in there from outside,\
and stood a-listening and looking, and not saying anything; and nobody\
saying anything to him either, because the king was talking and they was\
all busy listening. \'a0The king was saying--in the middle of something he\'92d\
started in on--\
\
\'93--they bein\'92 partickler friends o\'92 the diseased. \'a0That\'92s why they\'92re\
invited here this evenin\'92; but tomorrow we want _all_ to come--everybody;\
for he respected everybody, he liked everybody, and so it\'92s fitten that\
his funeral orgies sh\'92d be public.\'94\
\
And so he went a-mooning on and on, liking to hear himself talk, and\
every little while he fetched in his funeral orgies again, till the duke\
he couldn\'92t stand it no more; so he writes on a little scrap of paper,\
\'93_Obsequies_, you old fool,\'94 and folds it up, and goes to goo-gooing and\
reaching it over people\'92s heads to him. \'a0The king he reads it and puts\
it in his pocket, and says:\
\
\'93Poor William, afflicted as he is, his _heart\'92s_ aluz right. \'a0Asks me\
to invite everybody to come to the funeral--wants me to make \'91em all\
welcome. \'a0But he needn\'92t a worried--it was jest what I was at.\'94\
\
Then he weaves along again, perfectly ca\'92m, and goes to dropping in his\
funeral orgies again every now and then, just like he done before. \'a0And\
when he done it the third time he says:\
\
\'93I say orgies, not because it\'92s the common term, because it\
ain\'92t--obsequies bein\'92 the common term--but because orgies is the right\
term. Obsequies ain\'92t used in England no more now--it\'92s gone out. \'a0We\
say orgies now in England. \'a0Orgies is better, because it means the thing\
you\'92re after more exact. \'a0It\'92s a word that\'92s made up out\'92n the Greek\
_orgo_, outside, open, abroad; and the Hebrew _jeesum_, to plant, cover\
up; hence in_ter._ \'a0So, you see, funeral orgies is an open er public\
funeral.\'94\
\
He was the _worst_ I ever struck. \'a0Well, the iron-jawed man he laughed\
right in his face. \'a0Everybody was shocked. \'a0Everybody says, \'93Why,\
_doctor_!\'94 and Abner Shackleford says:\
\
\'93Why, Robinson, hain\'92t you heard the news? \'a0This is Harvey Wilks.\'94\
\
The king he smiled eager, and shoved out his flapper, and says:\
\
\'93Is it my poor brother\'92s dear good friend and physician? \'a0I--\'94\
\
\'93Keep your hands off of me!\'94 says the doctor.  \'93_You_ talk like an\
Englishman, _don\'92t_ you? \'a0It\'92s the worst imitation I ever heard. \'a0_You_\
Peter Wilks\'92s brother! \'a0You\'92re a fraud, that\'92s what you are!\'94\
\
Well, how they all took on! \'a0They crowded around the doctor and tried to\
quiet him down, and tried to explain to him and tell him how Harvey \'91d\
showed in forty ways that he _was_ Harvey, and knowed everybody by name,\
and the names of the very dogs, and begged and _begged_ him not to hurt\
Harvey\'92s feelings and the poor girl\'92s feelings, and all that. \'a0But it\
warn\'92t no use; he stormed right along, and said any man that pretended\
to be an Englishman and couldn\'92t imitate the lingo no better than what\
he did was a fraud and a liar. \'a0The poor girls was hanging to the king\
and crying; and all of a sudden the doctor ups and turns on _them_. \'a0He\
says:\
\
\'93I was your father\'92s friend, and I\'92m your friend; and I warn you as a\
friend, and an honest one that wants to protect you and keep you out of\
harm and trouble, to turn your backs on that scoundrel and have nothing\
to do with him, the ignorant tramp, with his idiotic Greek and Hebrew,\
as he calls it. \'a0He is the thinnest kind of an impostor--has come here\
with a lot of empty names and facts which he picked up somewheres, and\
you take them for _proofs_, and are helped to fool yourselves by these\
foolish friends here, who ought to know better. \'a0Mary Jane Wilks, you\
know me for your friend, and for your unselfish friend, too. \'a0Now listen\
to me; turn this pitiful rascal out--I _beg_ you to do it. \'a0Will you?\'94\
\
Mary Jane straightened herself up, and my, but she was handsome! \'a0She\
says:\
\
\'93_Here_ is my answer.\'94 \'a0She hove up the bag of money and put it in the\
king\'92s hands, and says, \'93Take this six thousand dollars, and invest for\
me and my sisters any way you want to, and don\'92t give us no receipt for\
it.\'94\
\
Then she put her arm around the king on one side, and Susan and the\
hare-lip done the same on the other. \'a0Everybody clapped their hands and\
stomped on the floor like a perfect storm, whilst the king held up his\
head and smiled proud. \'a0The doctor says:\
\
\'93All right; I wash _my_ hands of the matter. \'a0But I warn you all that a\
time \'91s coming when you\'92re going to feel sick whenever you think of this\
day.\'94 And away he went.\
\
\'93All right, doctor,\'94 says the king, kinder mocking him; \'93we\'92ll try and\
get \'91em to send for you;\'94 which made them all laugh, and they said it\
was a prime good hit.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXVI.\
\
WELL, when they was all gone the king he asks Mary Jane how they was off\
for spare rooms, and she said she had one spare room, which would do for\
Uncle William, and she\'92d give her own room to Uncle Harvey, which was\
a little bigger, and she would turn into the room with her sisters and\
sleep on a cot; and up garret was a little cubby, with a pallet in it.\
The king said the cubby would do for his valley--meaning me.\
\
So Mary Jane took us up, and she showed them their rooms, which was\
plain but nice. \'a0She said she\'92d have her frocks and a lot of other traps\
took out of her room if they was in Uncle Harvey\'92s way, but he said\
they warn\'92t. \'a0The frocks was hung along the wall, and before them was\
a curtain made out of calico that hung down to the floor. \'a0There was an\
old hair trunk in one corner, and a guitar-box in another, and all sorts\
of little knickknacks and jimcracks around, like girls brisken up a room\
with. \'a0The king said it was all the more homely and more pleasanter for\
these fixings, and so don\'92t disturb them. \'a0The duke\'92s room was pretty\
small, but plenty good enough, and so was my cubby.\
\
That night they had a big supper, and all them men and women was there,\
and I stood behind the king and the duke\'92s chairs and waited on them,\
and the niggers waited on the rest. \'a0Mary Jane she set at the head of\
the table, with Susan alongside of her, and said how bad the biscuits\
was, and how mean the preserves was, and how ornery and tough the fried\
chickens was--and all that kind of rot, the way women always do for to\
force out compliments; and the people all knowed everything was tiptop,\
and said so--said \'93How _do_ you get biscuits to brown so nice?\'94 and\
\'93Where, for the land\'92s sake, _did_ you get these amaz\'92n pickles?\'94 and\
all that kind of humbug talky-talk, just the way people always does at a\
supper, you know.\
\
And when it was all done me and the hare-lip had supper in the kitchen\
off of the leavings, whilst the others was helping the niggers clean up\
the things. \'a0The hare-lip she got to pumping me about England, and blest\
if I didn\'92t think the ice was getting mighty thin sometimes. \'a0She says:\
\
\'93Did you ever see the king?\'94\
\
\'93Who? \'a0William Fourth? \'a0Well, I bet I have--he goes to our church.\'94 \'a0I\
knowed he was dead years ago, but I never let on. \'a0So when I says he\
goes to our church, she says:\
\
\'93What--regular?\'94\
\
\'93Yes--regular. \'a0His pew\'92s right over opposite ourn--on t\'92other side the\
pulpit.\'94\
\
\'93I thought he lived in London?\'94\
\
\'93Well, he does. \'a0Where _would_ he live?\'94\
\
\'93But I thought _you_ lived in Sheffield?\'94\
\
I see I was up a stump. \'a0I had to let on to get choked with a chicken\
bone, so as to get time to think how to get down again. \'a0Then I says:\
\
\'93I mean he goes to our church regular when he\'92s in Sheffield. \'a0That\'92s\
only in the summer time, when he comes there to take the sea baths.\'94\
\
\'93Why, how you talk--Sheffield ain\'92t on the sea.\'94\
\
\'93Well, who said it was?\'94\
\
\'93Why, you did.\'94\
\
\'93I _didn\'92t_ nuther.\'94\
\
\'93You did!\'94\
\
\'93I didn\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93You did.\'94\
\
\'93I never said nothing of the kind.\'94\
\
\'93Well, what _did_ you say, then?\'94\
\
\'93Said he come to take the sea _baths_--that\'92s what I said.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, how\'92s he going to take the sea baths if it ain\'92t on the\
sea?\'94\
\
\'93Looky here,\'94 I says; \'93did you ever see any Congress-water?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Well, did you have to go to Congress to get it?\'94\
\
\'93Why, no.\'94\
\
\'93Well, neither does William Fourth have to go to the sea to get a sea\
bath.\'94\
\
\'93How does he get it, then?\'94\
\
\'93Gets it the way people down here gets Congress-water--in barrels. \'a0There\
in the palace at Sheffield they\'92ve got furnaces, and he wants his water\
hot. \'a0They can\'92t bile that amount of water away off there at the sea.\
They haven\'92t got no conveniences for it.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I see, now. \'a0You might a said that in the first place and saved\
time.\'94\
\
When she said that I see I was out of the woods again, and so I was\
comfortable and glad. \'a0Next, she says:\
\
\'93Do you go to church, too?\'94\
\
\'93Yes--regular.\'94\
\
\'93Where do you set?\'94\
\
\'93Why, in our pew.\'94\
\
\'93_Whose_ pew?\'94\
\
\'93Why, _ourn_--your Uncle Harvey\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93His\'92n? \'a0What does _he_ want with a pew?\'94\
\
\'93Wants it to set in. \'a0What did you _reckon_ he wanted with it?\'94\
\
\'93Why, I thought he\'92d be in the pulpit.\'94\
\
Rot him, I forgot he was a preacher. \'a0I see I was up a stump again, so I\
played another chicken bone and got another think. \'a0Then I says:\
\
\'93Blame it, do you suppose there ain\'92t but one preacher to a church?\'94\
\
\'93Why, what do they want with more?\'94\
\
\'93What!--to preach before a king? \'a0I never did see such a girl as you.\
They don\'92t have no less than seventeen.\'94\
\
\'93Seventeen! \'a0My land! \'a0Why, I wouldn\'92t set out such a string as that,\
not if I _never_ got to glory. \'a0It must take \'91em a week.\'94\
\
\'93Shucks, they don\'92t _all_ of \'91em preach the same day--only _one_ of \'91em.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what does the rest of \'91em do?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, nothing much. \'a0Loll around, pass the plate--and one thing or\
another. \'a0But mainly they don\'92t do nothing.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what are they _for_?\'94\
\
\'93Why, they\'92re for _style_. \'a0Don\'92t you know nothing?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I don\'92t _want_ to know no such foolishness as that. \'a0How is\
servants treated in England? \'a0Do they treat \'91em better \'91n we treat our\
niggers?\'94\
\
\'93_No_! \'a0A servant ain\'92t nobody there. \'a0They treat them worse than dogs.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t they give \'91em holidays, the way we do, Christmas and New Year\'92s\
week, and Fourth of July?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, just listen! \'a0A body could tell _you_ hain\'92t ever been to England\
by that. \'a0Why, Hare-l--why, Joanna, they never see a holiday from year\'92s\
end to year\'92s end; never go to the circus, nor theater, nor nigger\
shows, nor nowheres.\'94\
\
\'93Nor church?\'94\
\
\'93Nor church.\'94\
\
\'93But _you_ always went to church.\'94\
\
Well, I was gone up again. \'a0I forgot I was the old man\'92s servant. \'a0But\
next minute I whirled in on a kind of an explanation how a valley was\
different from a common servant and _had_ to go to church whether he\
wanted to or not, and set with the family, on account of its being the\
law. \'a0But I didn\'92t do it pretty good, and when I got done I see she\
warn\'92t satisfied. \'a0She says:\
\
\'93Honest injun, now, hain\'92t you been telling me a lot of lies?\'94\
\
\'93Honest injun,\'94 says I.\
\
\'93None of it at all?\'94\
\
\'93None of it at all. \'a0Not a lie in it,\'94 says I.\
\
\'93Lay your hand on this book and say it.\'94\
\
I see it warn\'92t nothing but a dictionary, so I laid my hand on it and\
said it. \'a0So then she looked a little better satisfied, and says:\
\
\'93Well, then, I\'92ll believe some of it; but I hope to gracious if I\'92ll\
believe the rest.\'94\
\
\'93What is it you won\'92t believe, Joe?\'94 says Mary Jane, stepping in with\
Susan behind her.  \'93It ain\'92t right nor kind for you to talk so to him,\
and him a stranger and so far from his people. \'a0How would you like to be\
treated so?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s always your way, Maim--always sailing in to help somebody before\
they\'92re hurt. \'a0I hain\'92t done nothing to him. \'a0He\'92s told some stretchers,\
I reckon, and I said I wouldn\'92t swallow it all; and that\'92s every bit\
and grain I _did_ say. \'a0I reckon he can stand a little thing like that,\
can\'92t he?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t care whether \'91twas little or whether \'91twas big; he\'92s here in\
our house and a stranger, and it wasn\'92t good of you to say it. \'a0If you\
was in his place it would make you feel ashamed; and so you oughtn\'92t to\
say a thing to another person that will make _them_ feel ashamed.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Mam, he said--\'94\
\
\'93It don\'92t make no difference what he _said_--that ain\'92t the thing. \'a0The\
thing is for you to treat him _kind_, and not be saying things to make\
him remember he ain\'92t in his own country and amongst his own folks.\'94\
\
I says to myself, _this_ is a girl that I\'92m letting that old reptile rob\
her of her money!\
\
Then Susan _she_ waltzed in; and if you\'92ll believe me, she did give\
Hare-lip hark from the tomb!\
\
Says I to myself, and this is _another_ one that I\'92m letting him rob her\
of her money!\
\
Then Mary Jane she took another inning, and went in sweet and lovely\
again--which was her way; but when she got done there warn\'92t hardly\
anything left o\'92 poor Hare-lip. \'a0So she hollered.\
\
\'93All right, then,\'94 says the other girls; \'93you just ask his pardon.\'94\
\
She done it, too; and she done it beautiful. \'a0She done it so beautiful\
it was good to hear; and I wished I could tell her a thousand lies, so\
she could do it again.\
\
I says to myself, this is _another_ one that I\'92m letting him rob her of\
her money. \'a0And when she got through they all jest laid theirselves\
out to make me feel at home and know I was amongst friends. \'a0I felt so\
ornery and low down and mean that I says to myself, my mind\'92s made up;\
I\'92ll hive that money for them or bust.\
\
So then I lit out--for bed, I said, meaning some time or another. \'a0When\
I got by myself I went to thinking the thing over. \'a0I says to myself,\
shall I go to that doctor, private, and blow on these frauds? \'a0No--that\
won\'92t do. He might tell who told him; then the king and the duke would\
make it warm for me. \'a0Shall I go, private, and tell Mary Jane? \'a0No--I\
dasn\'92t do it. Her face would give them a hint, sure; they\'92ve got the\
money, and they\'92d slide right out and get away with it. \'a0If she was to\
fetch in help I\'92d get mixed up in the business before it was done with,\
I judge. \'a0No; there ain\'92t no good way but one. \'a0I got to steal that\
money, somehow; and I got to steal it some way that they won\'92t suspicion\
that I done it. They\'92ve got a good thing here, and they ain\'92t a-going\
to leave till they\'92ve played this family and this town for all they\'92re\
worth, so I\'92ll find a chance time enough. I\'92ll steal it and hide it; and\
by and by, when I\'92m away down the river, I\'92ll write a letter and tell\
Mary Jane where it\'92s hid. \'a0But I better hive it tonight if I can,\
because the doctor maybe hasn\'92t let up as much as he lets on he has; he\
might scare them out of here yet.\
\
So, thinks I, I\'92ll go and search them rooms. \'a0Upstairs the hall was\
dark, but I found the duke\'92s room, and started to paw around it with\
my hands; but I recollected it wouldn\'92t be much like the king to let\
anybody else take care of that money but his own self; so then I went to\
his room and begun to paw around there. \'a0But I see I couldn\'92t do nothing\
without a candle, and I dasn\'92t light one, of course. \'a0So I judged I\'92d\
got to do the other thing--lay for them and eavesdrop. \'a0About that time\
I hears their footsteps coming, and was going to skip under the bed; I\
reached for it, but it wasn\'92t where I thought it would be; but I touched\
the curtain that hid Mary Jane\'92s frocks, so I jumped in behind that and\
snuggled in amongst the gowns, and stood there perfectly still.\
\
They come in and shut the door; and the first thing the duke done was to\
get down and look under the bed. \'a0Then I was glad I hadn\'92t found the bed\
when I wanted it. \'a0And yet, you know, it\'92s kind of natural to hide under\
the bed when you are up to anything private. \'a0They sets down then, and\
the king says:\
\
\'93Well, what is it? \'a0And cut it middlin\'92 short, because it\'92s better for\
us to be down there a-whoopin\'92 up the mournin\'92 than up here givin\'92 \'91em a\
chance to talk us over.\'94\
\
\'93Well, this is it, Capet. \'a0I ain\'92t easy; I ain\'92t comfortable. \'a0That\
doctor lays on my mind. \'a0I wanted to know your plans. \'a0I\'92ve got a\
notion, and I think it\'92s a sound one.\'94\
\
\'93What is it, duke?\'94\
\
\'93That we better glide out of this before three in the morning, and clip\
it down the river with what we\'92ve got. \'a0Specially, seeing we got it so\
easy--_given_ back to us, flung at our heads, as you may say, when of\
course we allowed to have to steal it back. \'a0I\'92m for knocking off and\
lighting out.\'94\
\
That made me feel pretty bad. \'a0About an hour or two ago it would a been\
a little different, but now it made me feel bad and disappointed, The\
king rips out and says:\
\
\'93What! \'a0And not sell out the rest o\'92 the property? \'a0March off like\
a passel of fools and leave eight or nine thous\'92n\'92 dollars\'92 worth o\'92\
property layin\'92 around jest sufferin\'92 to be scooped in?--and all good,\
salable stuff, too.\'94\
\
The duke he grumbled; said the bag of gold was enough, and he didn\'92t\
want to go no deeper--didn\'92t want to rob a lot of orphans of _everything_\
they had.\
\
\'93Why, how you talk!\'94 says the king.  \'93We sha\'92n\'92t rob \'91em of nothing at\
all but jest this money. \'a0The people that _buys_ the property is the\
suff\'92rers; because as soon \'91s it\'92s found out \'91at we didn\'92t own it--which\
won\'92t be long after we\'92ve slid--the sale won\'92t be valid, and it \'91ll all\
go back to the estate. \'a0These yer orphans \'91ll git their house back agin,\
and that\'92s enough for _them_; they\'92re young and spry, and k\'92n easy\
earn a livin\'92. \'a0_they_ ain\'92t a-goin to suffer. \'a0Why, jest think--there\'92s\
thous\'92n\'92s and thous\'92n\'92s that ain\'92t nigh so well off. \'a0Bless you, _they_\
ain\'92t got noth\'92n\'92 to complain of.\'94\
\
Well, the king he talked him blind; so at last he give in, and said all\
right, but said he believed it was blamed foolishness to stay, and that\
doctor hanging over them. \'a0But the king says:\
\
\'93Cuss the doctor! \'a0What do we k\'92yer for _him_? \'a0Hain\'92t we got all the\
fools in town on our side? \'a0And ain\'92t that a big enough majority in any\
town?\'94\
\
So they got ready to go down stairs again. \'a0The duke says:\
\
\'93I don\'92t think we put that money in a good place.\'94\
\
That cheered me up. \'a0I\'92d begun to think I warn\'92t going to get a hint of\
no kind to help me. \'a0The king says:\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93Because Mary Jane \'91ll be in mourning from this out; and first you know\
the nigger that does up the rooms will get an order to box these duds\
up and put \'91em away; and do you reckon a nigger can run across money and\
not borrow some of it?\'94\
\
\'93Your head\'92s level agin, duke,\'94 says the king; and he comes a-fumbling\
under the curtain two or three foot from where I was. \'a0I stuck tight to\
the wall and kept mighty still, though quivery; and I wondered what them\
fellows would say to me if they catched me; and I tried to think what\
I\'92d better do if they did catch me. \'a0But the king he got the bag before\
I could think more than about a half a thought, and he never suspicioned\
I was around. \'a0They took and shoved the bag through a rip in the straw\
tick that was under the feather-bed, and crammed it in a foot or two\
amongst the straw and said it was all right now, because a nigger only\
makes up the feather-bed, and don\'92t turn over the straw tick only about\
twice a year, and so it warn\'92t in no danger of getting stole now.\
\
But I knowed better. \'a0I had it out of there before they was half-way\
down stairs. \'a0I groped along up to my cubby, and hid it there till I\
could get a chance to do better. \'a0I judged I better hide it outside\
of the house somewheres, because if they missed it they would give the\
house a good ransacking: \'a0I knowed that very well. \'a0Then I turned in,\
with my clothes all on; but I couldn\'92t a gone to sleep if I\'92d a wanted\
to, I was in such a sweat to get through with the business. \'a0By and by I\
heard the king and the duke come up; so I rolled off my pallet and laid\
with my chin at the top of my ladder, and waited to see if anything was\
going to happen. \'a0But nothing did.\
\
So I held on till all the late sounds had quit and the early ones hadn\'92t\
begun yet; and then I slipped down the ladder.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXVII.\
\
I crept to their doors and listened; they was snoring. \'a0So I tiptoed\
along, and got down stairs all right. \'a0There warn\'92t a sound anywheres.\
\'a0I peeped through a crack of the dining-room door, and see the men that\
was watching the corpse all sound asleep on their chairs. \'a0The door\
was open into the parlor, where the corpse was laying, and there was a\
candle in both rooms. I passed along, and the parlor door was open; but\
I see there warn\'92t nobody in there but the remainders of Peter; so I\
shoved on by; but the front door was locked, and the key wasn\'92t there.\
\'a0Just then I heard somebody coming down the stairs, back behind me. \'a0I\
run in the parlor and took a swift look around, and the only place I\
see to hide the bag was in the coffin. \'a0The lid was shoved along about\
a foot, showing the dead man\'92s face down in there, with a wet cloth over\
it, and his shroud on. \'a0I tucked the money-bag in under the lid, just\
down beyond where his hands was crossed, which made me creep, they was\
so cold, and then I run back across the room and in behind the door.\
\
The person coming was Mary Jane. \'a0She went to the coffin, very soft, and\
kneeled down and looked in; then she put up her handkerchief, and I see\
she begun to cry, though I couldn\'92t hear her, and her back was to me. \'a0I\
slid out, and as I passed the dining-room I thought I\'92d make sure them\
watchers hadn\'92t seen me; so I looked through the crack, and everything\
was all right. \'a0They hadn\'92t stirred.\
\
I slipped up to bed, feeling ruther blue, on accounts of the thing\
playing out that way after I had took so much trouble and run so much\
resk about it. \'a0Says I, if it could stay where it is, all right; because\
when we get down the river a hundred mile or two I could write back to\
Mary Jane, and she could dig him up again and get it; but that ain\'92t the\
thing that\'92s going to happen; the thing that\'92s going to happen is, the\
money \'91ll be found when they come to screw on the lid. \'a0Then the king\
\'91ll get it again, and it \'91ll be a long day before he gives anybody\
another chance to smouch it from him. Of course I _wanted_ to slide\
down and get it out of there, but I dasn\'92t try it. \'a0Every minute it was\
getting earlier now, and pretty soon some of them watchers would begin\
to stir, and I might get catched--catched with six thousand dollars in my\
hands that nobody hadn\'92t hired me to take care of. \'a0I don\'92t wish to be\
mixed up in no such business as that, I says to myself.\
\
When I got down stairs in the morning the parlor was shut up, and the\
watchers was gone. \'a0There warn\'92t nobody around but the family and the\
widow Bartley and our tribe. \'a0I watched their faces to see if anything\
had been happening, but I couldn\'92t tell.\
\
Towards the middle of the day the undertaker come with his man, and they\
set the coffin in the middle of the room on a couple of chairs, and then\
set all our chairs in rows, and borrowed more from the neighbors till\
the hall and the parlor and the dining-room was full. \'a0I see the coffin\
lid was the way it was before, but I dasn\'92t go to look in under it, with\
folks around.\
\
Then the people begun to flock in, and the beats and the girls took\
seats in the front row at the head of the coffin, and for a half an hour\
the people filed around slow, in single rank, and looked down at the\
dead man\'92s face a minute, and some dropped in a tear, and it was\
all very still and solemn, only the girls and the beats holding\
handkerchiefs to their eyes and keeping their heads bent, and sobbing a\
little. \'a0There warn\'92t no other sound but the scraping of the feet on\
the floor and blowing noses--because people always blows them more at a\
funeral than they do at other places except church.\
\
When the place was packed full the undertaker he slid around in his\
black gloves with his softy soothering ways, putting on the last\
touches, and getting people and things all ship-shape and comfortable,\
and making no more sound than a cat. \'a0He never spoke; he moved people\
around, he squeezed in late ones, he opened up passageways, and done\
it with nods, and signs with his hands. \'a0Then he took his place over\
against the wall. He was the softest, glidingest, stealthiest man I ever\
see; and there warn\'92t no more smile to him than there is to a ham.\
\
They had borrowed a melodeum--a sick one; and when everything was ready\
a young woman set down and worked it, and it was pretty skreeky and\
colicky, and everybody joined in and sung, and Peter was the only one\
that had a good thing, according to my notion. \'a0Then the Reverend Hobson\
opened up, slow and solemn, and begun to talk; and straight off the most\
outrageous row busted out in the cellar a body ever heard; it was only\
one dog, but he made a most powerful racket, and he kept it up right\
along; the parson he had to stand there, over the coffin, and wait--you\
couldn\'92t hear yourself think. \'a0It was right down awkward, and nobody\
didn\'92t seem to know what to do. \'a0But pretty soon they see that\
long-legged undertaker make a sign to the preacher as much as to say,\
\'93Don\'92t you worry--just depend on me.\'94 \'a0Then he stooped down and begun\
to glide along the wall, just his shoulders showing over the people\'92s\
heads. \'a0So he glided along, and the powwow and racket getting more and\
more outrageous all the time; and at last, when he had gone around two\
sides of the room, he disappears down cellar. \'a0Then in about two seconds\
we heard a whack, and the dog he finished up with a most amazing howl or\
two, and then everything was dead still, and the parson begun his solemn\
talk where he left off. \'a0In a minute or two here comes this undertaker\'92s\
back and shoulders gliding along the wall again; and so he glided and\
glided around three sides of the room, and then rose up, and shaded his\
mouth with his hands, and stretched his neck out towards the preacher,\
over the people\'92s heads, and says, in a kind of a coarse whisper, \'93_He\
had a rat_!\'94 \'a0Then he drooped down and glided along the wall again to\
his place. \'a0You could see it was a great satisfaction to the people,\
because naturally they wanted to know. \'a0A little thing like that don\'92t\
cost nothing, and it\'92s just the little things that makes a man to be\
looked up to and liked. \'a0There warn\'92t no more popular man in town than\
what that undertaker was.\
\
Well, the funeral sermon was very good, but pison long and tiresome; and\
then the king he shoved in and got off some of his usual rubbage, and\
at last the job was through, and the undertaker begun to sneak up on the\
coffin with his screw-driver. \'a0I was in a sweat then, and watched him\
pretty keen. But he never meddled at all; just slid the lid along as\
soft as mush, and screwed it down tight and fast. \'a0So there I was! \'a0I\
didn\'92t know whether the money was in there or not. \'a0So, says I, s\'92pose\
somebody has hogged that bag on the sly?--now how do I know whether\
to write to Mary Jane or not? S\'92pose she dug him up and didn\'92t find\
nothing, what would she think of me? Blame it, I says, I might get\
hunted up and jailed; I\'92d better lay low and keep dark, and not write at\
all; the thing\'92s awful mixed now; trying to better it, I\'92ve worsened it\
a hundred times, and I wish to goodness I\'92d just let it alone, dad fetch\
the whole business!\
\
They buried him, and we come back home, and I went to watching faces\
again--I couldn\'92t help it, and I couldn\'92t rest easy. \'a0But nothing come of\
it; the faces didn\'92t tell me nothing.\
\
The king he visited around in the evening, and sweetened everybody up,\
and made himself ever so friendly; and he give out the idea that his\
congregation over in England would be in a sweat about him, so he must\
hurry and settle up the estate right away and leave for home. \'a0He was\
very sorry he was so pushed, and so was everybody; they wished he could\
stay longer, but they said they could see it couldn\'92t be done. \'a0And he\
said of course him and William would take the girls home with them; and\
that pleased everybody too, because then the girls would be well fixed\
and amongst their own relations; and it pleased the girls, too--tickled\
them so they clean forgot they ever had a trouble in the world; and told\
him to sell out as quick as he wanted to, they would be ready. \'a0Them\
poor things was that glad and happy it made my heart ache to see them\
getting fooled and lied to so, but I didn\'92t see no safe way for me to\
chip in and change the general tune.\
\
Well, blamed if the king didn\'92t bill the house and the niggers and all\
the property for auction straight off--sale two days after the funeral;\
but anybody could buy private beforehand if they wanted to.\
\
So the next day after the funeral, along about noon-time, the girls\'92 joy\
got the first jolt. \'a0A couple of nigger traders come along, and the king\
sold them the niggers reasonable, for three-day drafts as they called\
it, and away they went, the two sons up the river to Memphis, and their\
mother down the river to Orleans. \'a0I thought them poor girls and them\
niggers would break their hearts for grief; they cried around each\
other, and took on so it most made me down sick to see it. \'a0The girls\
said they hadn\'92t ever dreamed of seeing the family separated or sold\
away from the town. \'a0I can\'92t ever get it out of my memory, the sight of\
them poor miserable girls and niggers hanging around each other\'92s necks\
and crying; and I reckon I couldn\'92t a stood it all, but would a had\
to bust out and tell on our gang if I hadn\'92t knowed the sale warn\'92t no\
account and the niggers would be back home in a week or two.\
\
The thing made a big stir in the town, too, and a good many come out\
flatfooted and said it was scandalous to separate the mother and the\
children that way. \'a0It injured the frauds some; but the old fool he\
bulled right along, spite of all the duke could say or do, and I tell\
you the duke was powerful uneasy.\
\
Next day was auction day. \'a0About broad day in the morning the king and\
the duke come up in the garret and woke me up, and I see by their look\
that there was trouble. \'a0The king says:\
\
\'93Was you in my room night before last?\'94\
\
\'93No, your majesty\'94--which was the way I always called him when nobody but\
our gang warn\'92t around.\
\
\'93Was you in there yisterday er last night?\'94\
\
\'93No, your majesty.\'94\
\
\'93Honor bright, now--no lies.\'94\
\
\'93Honor bright, your majesty, I\'92m telling you the truth. \'a0I hain\'92t been\
a-near your room since Miss Mary Jane took you and the duke and showed\
it to you.\'94\
\
The duke says:\
\
\'93Have you seen anybody else go in there?\'94\
\
\'93No, your grace, not as I remember, I believe.\'94\
\
\'93Stop and think.\'94\
\
I studied awhile and see my chance; then I says:\
\
\'93Well, I see the niggers go in there several times.\'94\
\
Both of them gave a little jump, and looked like they hadn\'92t ever\
expected it, and then like they _had_. \'a0Then the duke says:\
\
\'93What, all of them?\'94\
\
\'93No--leastways, not all at once--that is, I don\'92t think I ever see them\
all come _out_ at once but just one time.\'94\
\
\'93Hello! \'a0When was that?\'94\
\
\'93It was the day we had the funeral. \'a0In the morning. \'a0It warn\'92t early,\
because I overslept. \'a0I was just starting down the ladder, and I see\
them.\'94\
\
\'93Well, go on, _go_ on! \'a0What did they do? \'a0How\'92d they act?\'94\
\
\'93They didn\'92t do nothing. \'a0And they didn\'92t act anyway much, as fur as I\
see. They tiptoed away; so I seen, easy enough, that they\'92d shoved in\
there to do up your majesty\'92s room, or something, s\'92posing you was up;\
and found you _warn\'92t_ up, and so they was hoping to slide out of the\
way of trouble without waking you up, if they hadn\'92t already waked you\
up.\'94\
\
\'93Great guns, _this_ is a go!\'94 says the king; and both of them looked\
pretty sick and tolerable silly. \'a0They stood there a-thinking and\
scratching their heads a minute, and the duke he bust into a kind of a\
little raspy chuckle, and says:\
\
\'93It does beat all how neat the niggers played their hand. \'a0They let on\
to be _sorry_ they was going out of this region! \'a0And I believed they\
_was_ sorry, and so did you, and so did everybody. \'a0Don\'92t ever tell _me_\
any more that a nigger ain\'92t got any histrionic talent. \'a0Why, the way\
they played that thing it would fool _anybody_. \'a0In my opinion, there\'92s\
a fortune in \'91em. \'a0If I had capital and a theater, I wouldn\'92t want a\
better lay-out than that--and here we\'92ve gone and sold \'91em for a song.\
\'a0Yes, and ain\'92t privileged to sing the song yet. \'a0Say, where _is_ that\
song--that draft?\'94\
\
\'93In the bank for to be collected. \'a0Where _would_ it be?\'94\
\
\'93Well, _that\'92s_ all right then, thank goodness.\'94\
\
Says I, kind of timid-like:\
\
\'93Is something gone wrong?\'94\
\
The king whirls on me and rips out:\
\
\'93None o\'92 your business! \'a0You keep your head shet, and mind y\'92r own\
affairs--if you got any. \'a0Long as you\'92re in this town don\'92t you forgit\
_that_--you hear?\'94 \'a0Then he says to the duke, \'93We got to jest swaller it\
and say noth\'92n\'92: \'a0mum\'92s the word for _us_.\'94\
\
As they was starting down the ladder the duke he chuckles again, and\
says:\
\
\'93Quick sales _and_ small profits! \'a0It\'92s a good business--yes.\'94\
\
The king snarls around on him and says:\
\
\'93I was trying to do for the best in sellin\'92 \'91em out so quick. \'a0If the\
profits has turned out to be none, lackin\'92 considable, and none to\
carry, is it my fault any more\'92n it\'92s yourn?\'94\
\
\'93Well, _they\'92d_ be in this house yet and we _wouldn\'92t_ if I could a got\
my advice listened to.\'94\
\
The king sassed back as much as was safe for him, and then swapped\
around and lit into _me_ again. \'a0He give me down the banks for not\
coming and _telling_ him I see the niggers come out of his room acting\
that way--said any fool would a _knowed_ something was up. \'a0And then\
waltzed in and cussed _himself_ awhile, and said it all come of him not\
laying late and taking his natural rest that morning, and he\'92d be\
blamed if he\'92d ever do it again. \'a0So they went off a-jawing; and I felt\
dreadful glad I\'92d worked it all off on to the niggers, and yet hadn\'92t\
done the niggers no harm by it.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXVIII.\
\
BY and by it was getting-up time. \'a0So I come down the ladder and started\
for down-stairs; but as I come to the girls\'92 room the door was open, and\
I see Mary Jane setting by her old hair trunk, which was open and she\'92d\
been packing things in it--getting ready to go to England. \'a0But she\
had stopped now with a folded gown in her lap, and had her face in her\
hands, crying. \'a0I felt awful bad to see it; of course anybody would. \'a0I\
went in there and says:\
\
\'93Miss Mary Jane, you can\'92t a-bear to see people in trouble, and I\
can\'92t--most always. \'a0Tell me about it.\'94\
\
So she done it. \'a0And it was the niggers--I just expected it. \'a0She said\
the beautiful trip to England was most about spoiled for her; she didn\'92t\
know _how_ she was ever going to be happy there, knowing the mother and\
the children warn\'92t ever going to see each other no more--and then busted\
out bitterer than ever, and flung up her hands, and says:\
\
\'93Oh, dear, dear, to think they ain\'92t _ever_ going to see each other any\
more!\'94\
\
\'93But they _will_--and inside of two weeks--and I _know_ it!\'94 says I.\
\
Laws, it was out before I could think! \'a0And before I could budge she\
throws her arms around my neck and told me to say it _again_, say it\
_again_, say it _again_!\
\
I see I had spoke too sudden and said too much, and was in a close\
place. I asked her to let me think a minute; and she set there, very\
impatient and excited and handsome, but looking kind of happy and\
eased-up, like a person that\'92s had a tooth pulled out. \'a0So I went to\
studying it out. \'a0I says to myself, I reckon a body that ups and tells\
the truth when he is in a tight place is taking considerable many resks,\
though I ain\'92t had no experience, and can\'92t say for certain; but it\
looks so to me, anyway; and yet here\'92s a case where I\'92m blest if it\
don\'92t look to me like the truth is better and actuly _safer_ than a lie.\
\'a0I must lay it by in my mind, and think it over some time or other, it\'92s\
so kind of strange and unregular. I never see nothing like it. \'a0Well, I\
says to myself at last, I\'92m a-going to chance it; I\'92ll up and tell the\
truth this time, though it does seem most like setting down on a kag of\
powder and touching it off just to see where you\'92ll go to. Then I says:\
\
\'93Miss Mary Jane, is there any place out of town a little ways where you\
could go and stay three or four days?\'94\
\
\'93Yes; Mr. Lothrop\'92s. \'a0Why?\'94\
\
\'93Never mind why yet. \'a0If I\'92ll tell you how I know the niggers will see\
each other again inside of two weeks--here in this house--and _prove_ how\
I know it--will you go to Mr. Lothrop\'92s and stay four days?\'94\
\
\'93Four days!\'94 she says; \'93I\'92ll stay a year!\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I says, \'93I don\'92t want nothing more out of _you_ than just\
your word--I druther have it than another man\'92s kiss-the-Bible.\'94 \'a0She\
smiled and reddened up very sweet, and I says, \'93If you don\'92t mind it,\
I\'92ll shut the door--and bolt it.\'94\
\
Then I come back and set down again, and says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t you holler. \'a0Just set still and take it like a man. \'a0I got to\
tell the truth, and you want to brace up, Miss Mary, because it\'92s a\
bad kind, and going to be hard to take, but there ain\'92t no help for\
it. \'a0These uncles of yourn ain\'92t no uncles at all; they\'92re a couple of\
frauds--regular dead-beats. \'a0There, now we\'92re over the worst of it, you\
can stand the rest middling easy.\'94\
\
It jolted her up like everything, of course; but I was over the shoal\
water now, so I went right along, her eyes a-blazing higher and higher\
all the time, and told her every blame thing, from where we first struck\
that young fool going up to the steamboat, clear through to where she\
flung herself on to the king\'92s breast at the front door and he kissed\
her sixteen or seventeen times--and then up she jumps, with her face\
afire like sunset, and says:\
\
\'93The brute! \'a0Come, don\'92t waste a minute--not a _second_--we\'92ll have them\
tarred and feathered, and flung in the river!\'94\
\
Says I:\
\
\'93Cert\'92nly. \'a0But do you mean _before_ you go to Mr. Lothrop\'92s, or--\'94\
\
\'93Oh,\'94 she says, \'93what am I _thinking_ about!\'94 she says, and set right\
down again.  \'93Don\'92t mind what I said--please don\'92t--you _won\'92t,_ now,\
_will_ you?\'94 Laying her silky hand on mine in that kind of a way that\
I said I would die first.  \'93I never thought, I was so stirred up,\'94 she\
says; \'93now go on, and I won\'92t do so any more. \'a0You tell me what to do,\
and whatever you say I\'92ll do it.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I says, \'93it\'92s a rough gang, them two frauds, and I\'92m fixed so\
I got to travel with them a while longer, whether I want to or not--I\
druther not tell you why; and if you was to blow on them this town would\
get me out of their claws, and I\'92d be all right; but there\'92d be another\
person that you don\'92t know about who\'92d be in big trouble. \'a0Well, we\
got to save _him_, hain\'92t we? \'a0Of course. \'a0Well, then, we won\'92t blow on\
them.\'94\
\
Saying them words put a good idea in my head. \'a0I see how maybe I could\
get me and Jim rid of the frauds; get them jailed here, and then leave.\
But I didn\'92t want to run the raft in the daytime without anybody aboard\
to answer questions but me; so I didn\'92t want the plan to begin working\
till pretty late to-night. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Miss Mary Jane, I\'92ll tell you what we\'92ll do, and you won\'92t have to stay\
at Mr. Lothrop\'92s so long, nuther. \'a0How fur is it?\'94\
\
\'93A little short of four miles--right out in the country, back here.\'94\
\
\'93Well, that \'91ll answer. \'a0Now you go along out there, and lay low\
till nine or half-past to-night, and then get them to fetch you home\
again--tell them you\'92ve thought of something. \'a0If you get here before\
eleven put a candle in this window, and if I don\'92t turn up wait _till_\
eleven, and _then_ if I don\'92t turn up it means I\'92m gone, and out of the\
way, and safe. Then you come out and spread the news around, and get\
these beats jailed.\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 she says, \'93I\'92ll do it.\'94\
\
\'93And if it just happens so that I don\'92t get away, but get took up along\
with them, you must up and say I told you the whole thing beforehand,\
and you must stand by me all you can.\'94\
\
\'93Stand by you! indeed I will. \'a0They sha\'92n\'92t touch a hair of your head!\'94\
 she says, and I see her nostrils spread and her eyes snap when she said\
it, too.\
\
\'93If I get away I sha\'92n\'92t be here,\'94 I says, \'93to prove these rapscallions\
ain\'92t your uncles, and I couldn\'92t do it if I _was_ here. \'a0I could swear\
they was beats and bummers, that\'92s all, though that\'92s worth something.\
Well, there\'92s others can do that better than what I can, and they\'92re\
people that ain\'92t going to be doubted as quick as I\'92d be. \'a0I\'92ll tell you\
how to find them. \'a0Gimme a pencil and a piece of paper. \'a0There--\'91Royal\
Nonesuch, Bricksville.\'92 \'a0Put it away, and don\'92t lose it. \'a0When the\
court wants to find out something about these two, let them send up to\
Bricksville and say they\'92ve got the men that played the Royal Nonesuch,\
and ask for some witnesses--why, you\'92ll have that entire town down here\
before you can hardly wink, Miss Mary. \'a0And they\'92ll come a-biling, too.\'94\
\
I judged we had got everything fixed about right now. \'a0So I says:\
\
\'93Just let the auction go right along, and don\'92t worry. \'a0Nobody don\'92t\
have to pay for the things they buy till a whole day after the auction\
on accounts of the short notice, and they ain\'92t going out of this till\
they get that money; and the way we\'92ve fixed it the sale ain\'92t going to\
count, and they ain\'92t going to get no money. \'a0It\'92s just like the way\
it was with the niggers--it warn\'92t no sale, and the niggers will be\
back before long. \'a0Why, they can\'92t collect the money for the _niggers_\
yet--they\'92re in the worst kind of a fix, Miss Mary.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 she says, \'93I\'92ll run down to breakfast now, and then I\'92ll start\
straight for Mr. Lothrop\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93\'91Deed, _that_ ain\'92t the ticket, Miss Mary Jane,\'94 I says, \'93by no manner\
of means; go _before_ breakfast.\'94\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93What did you reckon I wanted you to go at all for, Miss Mary?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I never thought--and come to think, I don\'92t know. \'a0What was it?\'94\
\
\'93Why, it\'92s because you ain\'92t one of these leather-face people. \'a0I don\'92t\
want no better book than what your face is. \'a0A body can set down and\
read it off like coarse print. \'a0Do you reckon you can go and face your\
uncles when they come to kiss you good-morning, and never--\'94\
\
\'93There, there, don\'92t! \'a0Yes, I\'92ll go before breakfast--I\'92ll be glad to.\
And leave my sisters with them?\'94\
\
\'93Yes; never mind about them. \'a0They\'92ve got to stand it yet a while. \'a0They\
might suspicion something if all of you was to go. \'a0I don\'92t want you to\
see them, nor your sisters, nor nobody in this town; if a neighbor was\
to ask how is your uncles this morning your face would tell something.\
\'a0No, you go right along, Miss Mary Jane, and I\'92ll fix it with all of\
them. I\'92ll tell Miss Susan to give your love to your uncles and say\
you\'92ve went away for a few hours for to get a little rest and change, or\
to see a friend, and you\'92ll be back to-night or early in the morning.\'94\
\
\'93Gone to see a friend is all right, but I won\'92t have my love given to\
them.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, it sha\'92n\'92t be.\'94 \'a0It was well enough to tell _her_ so--no\
harm in it. \'a0It was only a little thing to do, and no trouble; and it\'92s\
the little things that smooths people\'92s roads the most, down here below;\
it would make Mary Jane comfortable, and it wouldn\'92t cost nothing. \'a0Then\
I says:  \'93There\'92s one more thing--that bag of money.\'94\
\
\'93Well, they\'92ve got that; and it makes me feel pretty silly to think\
_how_ they got it.\'94\
\
\'93No, you\'92re out, there. \'a0They hain\'92t got it.\'94\
\
\'93Why, who\'92s got it?\'94\
\
\'93I wish I knowed, but I don\'92t. \'a0I _had_ it, because I stole it from\
them; and I stole it to give to you; and I know where I hid it, but I\'92m\
afraid it ain\'92t there no more. \'a0I\'92m awful sorry, Miss Mary Jane, I\'92m\
just as sorry as I can be; but I done the best I could; I did honest. \'a0I\
come nigh getting caught, and I had to shove it into the first place I\
come to, and run--and it warn\'92t a good place.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, stop blaming yourself--it\'92s too bad to do it, and I won\'92t allow\
it--you couldn\'92t help it; it wasn\'92t your fault. \'a0Where did you hide it?\'94\
\
I didn\'92t want to set her to thinking about her troubles again; and I\
couldn\'92t seem to get my mouth to tell her what would make her see that\
corpse laying in the coffin with that bag of money on his stomach. \'a0So\
for a minute I didn\'92t say nothing; then I says:\
\
\'93I\'92d ruther not _tell_ you where I put it, Miss Mary Jane, if you don\'92t\
mind letting me off; but I\'92ll write it for you on a piece of paper, and\
you can read it along the road to Mr. Lothrop\'92s, if you want to. \'a0Do you\
reckon that \'91ll do?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes.\'94\
\
So I wrote:  \'93I put it in the coffin. \'a0It was in there when you was\
crying there, away in the night. \'a0I was behind the door, and I was\
mighty sorry for you, Miss Mary Jane.\'94\
\
It made my eyes water a little to remember her crying there all by\
herself in the night, and them devils laying there right under her own\
roof, shaming her and robbing her; and when I folded it up and give it\
to her I see the water come into her eyes, too; and she shook me by the\
hand, hard, and says:\
\
\'93_Good_-bye. \'a0I\'92m going to do everything just as you\'92ve told me; and if\
I don\'92t ever see you again, I sha\'92n\'92t ever forget you and I\'92ll think of\
you a many and a many a time, and I\'92ll _pray_ for you, too!\'94--and she was\
gone.\
\
Pray for me! \'a0I reckoned if she knowed me she\'92d take a job that was more\
nearer her size. \'a0But I bet she done it, just the same--she was just that\
kind. \'a0She had the grit to pray for Judus if she took the notion--there\
warn\'92t no back-down to her, I judge. \'a0You may say what you want to, but\
in my opinion she had more sand in her than any girl I ever see; in\
my opinion she was just full of sand. \'a0It sounds like flattery, but it\
ain\'92t no flattery. \'a0And when it comes to beauty--and goodness, too--she\
lays over them all. \'a0I hain\'92t ever seen her since that time that I see\
her go out of that door; no, I hain\'92t ever seen her since, but I reckon\
I\'92ve thought of her a many and a many a million times, and of her saying\
she would pray for me; and if ever I\'92d a thought it would do any good\
for me to pray for _her_, blamed if I wouldn\'92t a done it or bust.\
\
Well, Mary Jane she lit out the back way, I reckon; because nobody see\
her go. \'a0When I struck Susan and the hare-lip, I says:\
\
\'93What\'92s the name of them people over on t\'92other side of the river that\
you all goes to see sometimes?\'94\
\
They says:\
\
\'93There\'92s several; but it\'92s the Proctors, mainly.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s the name,\'94 I says; \'93I most forgot it. \'a0Well, Miss Mary Jane she\
told me to tell you she\'92s gone over there in a dreadful hurry--one of\
them\'92s sick.\'94\
\
\'93Which one?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know; leastways, I kinder forget; but I thinks it\'92s--\'94\
\
\'93Sakes alive, I hope it ain\'92t _Hanner_?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry to say it,\'94 I says, \'93but Hanner\'92s the very one.\'94\
\
\'93My goodness, and she so well only last week! \'a0Is she took bad?\'94\
\
\'93It ain\'92t no name for it. \'a0They set up with her all night, Miss Mary\
Jane said, and they don\'92t think she\'92ll last many hours.\'94\
\
\'93Only think of that, now! \'a0What\'92s the matter with her?\'94\
\
I couldn\'92t think of anything reasonable, right off that way, so I says:\
\
\'93Mumps.\'94\
\
\'93Mumps your granny! \'a0They don\'92t set up with people that\'92s got the\
mumps.\'94\
\
\'93They don\'92t, don\'92t they? \'a0You better bet they do with _these_ mumps.\
\'a0These mumps is different. \'a0It\'92s a new kind, Miss Mary Jane said.\'94\
\
\'93How\'92s it a new kind?\'94\
\
\'93Because it\'92s mixed up with other things.\'94\
\
\'93What other things?\'94\
\
\'93Well, measles, and whooping-cough, and erysiplas, and consumption, and\
yaller janders, and brain-fever, and I don\'92t know what all.\'94\
\
\'93My land! \'a0And they call it the _mumps_?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s what Miss Mary Jane said.\'94\
\
\'93Well, what in the nation do they call it the _mumps_ for?\'94\
\
\'93Why, because it _is_ the mumps. \'a0That\'92s what it starts with.\'94\
\
\'93Well, ther\'92 ain\'92t no sense in it. \'a0A body might stump his toe, and take\
pison, and fall down the well, and break his neck, and bust his brains\
out, and somebody come along and ask what killed him, and some numskull\
up and say, \'91Why, he stumped his _toe_.\'92 \'a0Would ther\'92 be any sense\
in that? _No_. \'a0And ther\'92 ain\'92t no sense in _this_, nuther. \'a0Is it\
ketching?\'94\
\
\'93Is it _ketching_? \'a0Why, how you talk. \'a0Is a _harrow_ catching--in the\
dark? If you don\'92t hitch on to one tooth, you\'92re bound to on another,\
ain\'92t you? And you can\'92t get away with that tooth without fetching the\
whole harrow along, can you? \'a0Well, these kind of mumps is a kind of a\
harrow, as you may say--and it ain\'92t no slouch of a harrow, nuther, you\
come to get it hitched on good.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it\'92s awful, I think,\'94 says the hare-lip.  \'93I\'92ll go to Uncle\
Harvey and--\'94\
\
\'93Oh, yes,\'94 I says, \'93I _would_. \'a0Of _course_ I would. \'a0I wouldn\'92t lose no\
time.\'94\
\
\'93Well, why wouldn\'92t you?\'94\
\
\'93Just look at it a minute, and maybe you can see. \'a0Hain\'92t your uncles\
obleegd to get along home to England as fast as they can? \'a0And do you\
reckon they\'92d be mean enough to go off and leave you to go all that\
journey by yourselves? \'a0_you_ know they\'92ll wait for you. \'a0So fur, so\
good. Your uncle Harvey\'92s a preacher, ain\'92t he? \'a0Very well, then; is a\
_preacher_ going to deceive a steamboat clerk? is he going to deceive\
a _ship clerk?_--so as to get them to let Miss Mary Jane go aboard? \'a0Now\
_you_ know he ain\'92t. \'a0What _will_ he do, then? \'a0Why, he\'92ll say, \'91It\'92s a\
great pity, but my church matters has got to get along the best way they\
can; for my niece has been exposed to the dreadful pluribus-unum mumps,\
and so it\'92s my bounden duty to set down here and wait the three months\
it takes to show on her if she\'92s got it.\'92 \'a0But never mind, if you think\
it\'92s best to tell your uncle Harvey--\'94\
\
\'93Shucks, and stay fooling around here when we could all be having good\
times in England whilst we was waiting to find out whether Mary Jane\'92s\
got it or not? \'a0Why, you talk like a muggins.\'94\
\
\'93Well, anyway, maybe you\'92d better tell some of the neighbors.\'94\
\
\'93Listen at that, now. \'a0You do beat all for natural stupidness. \'a0Can\'92t\
you _see_ that _they\'92d_ go and tell? \'a0Ther\'92 ain\'92t no way but just to not\
tell anybody at _all_.\'94\
\
\'93Well, maybe you\'92re right--yes, I judge you _are_ right.\'94\
\
\'93But I reckon we ought to tell Uncle Harvey she\'92s gone out a while,\
anyway, so he won\'92t be uneasy about her?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, Miss Mary Jane she wanted you to do that. \'a0She says, \'91Tell them to\
give Uncle Harvey and William my love and a kiss, and say I\'92ve run over\
the river to see Mr.\'92--Mr.--what _is_ the name of that rich family your\
uncle Peter used to think so much of?--I mean the one that--\'94\
\
\'93Why, you must mean the Apthorps, ain\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93Of course; bother them kind of names, a body can\'92t ever seem to\
remember them, half the time, somehow. \'a0Yes, she said, say she has run\
over for to ask the Apthorps to be sure and come to the auction and buy\
this house, because she allowed her uncle Peter would ruther they had\
it than anybody else; and she\'92s going to stick to them till they say\
they\'92ll come, and then, if she ain\'92t too tired, she\'92s coming home; and\
if she is, she\'92ll be home in the morning anyway. \'a0She said, don\'92t say\
nothing about the Proctors, but only about the Apthorps--which \'91ll be\
perfectly true, because she is going there to speak about their buying\
the house; I know it, because she told me so herself.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 they said, and cleared out to lay for their uncles, and\
give them the love and the kisses, and tell them the message.\
\
Everything was all right now. \'a0The girls wouldn\'92t say nothing because\
they wanted to go to England; and the king and the duke would ruther\
Mary Jane was off working for the auction than around in reach of\
Doctor Robinson. \'a0I felt very good; I judged I had done it pretty neat--I\
reckoned Tom Sawyer couldn\'92t a done it no neater himself. \'a0Of course he\
would a throwed more style into it, but I can\'92t do that very handy, not\
being brung up to it.\
\
Well, they held the auction in the public square, along towards the end\
of the afternoon, and it strung along, and strung along, and the old man\
he was on hand and looking his level pisonest, up there longside of the\
auctioneer, and chipping in a little Scripture now and then, or a little\
goody-goody saying of some kind, and the duke he was around goo-gooing\
for sympathy all he knowed how, and just spreading himself generly.\
\
But by and by the thing dragged through, and everything was\
sold--everything but a little old trifling lot in the graveyard. \'a0So\
they\'92d got to work that off--I never see such a girafft as the king was\
for wanting to swallow _everything_. \'a0Well, whilst they was at it a\
steamboat landed, and in about two minutes up comes a crowd a-whooping\
and yelling and laughing and carrying on, and singing out:\
\
\'93_Here\'92s_ your opposition line! here\'92s your two sets o\'92 heirs to old\
Peter Wilks--and you pays your money and you takes your choice!\'94\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXIX.\
\
THEY was fetching a very nice-looking old gentleman along, and a\
nice-looking younger one, with his right arm in a sling. \'a0And, my souls,\
how the people yelled and laughed, and kept it up. \'a0But I didn\'92t see no\
joke about it, and I judged it would strain the duke and the king some\
to see any. \'a0I reckoned they\'92d turn pale. \'a0But no, nary a pale did\
_they_ turn. The duke he never let on he suspicioned what was up, but\
just went a goo-gooing around, happy and satisfied, like a jug that\'92s\
googling out buttermilk; and as for the king, he just gazed and gazed\
down sorrowful on them new-comers like it give him the stomach-ache in\
his very heart to think there could be such frauds and rascals in the\
world. \'a0Oh, he done it admirable. \'a0Lots of the principal people\
gethered around the king, to let him see they was on his side. \'a0That old\
gentleman that had just come looked all puzzled to death. \'a0Pretty\
soon he begun to speak, and I see straight off he pronounced _like_ an\
Englishman--not the king\'92s way, though the king\'92s _was_ pretty good for\
an imitation. \'a0I can\'92t give the old gent\'92s words, nor I can\'92t imitate\
him; but he turned around to the crowd, and says, about like this:\
\
\'93This is a surprise to me which I wasn\'92t looking for; and I\'92ll\
acknowledge, candid and frank, I ain\'92t very well fixed to meet it and\
answer it; for my brother and me has had misfortunes; he\'92s broke his\
arm, and our baggage got put off at a town above here last night in the\
night by a mistake. \'a0I am Peter Wilks\'92 brother Harvey, and this is his\
brother William, which can\'92t hear nor speak--and can\'92t even make signs to\
amount to much, now\'92t he\'92s only got one hand to work them with. \'a0We are\
who we say we are; and in a day or two, when I get the baggage, I can\
prove it. But up till then I won\'92t say nothing more, but go to the hotel\
and wait.\'94\
\
So him and the new dummy started off; and the king he laughs, and\
blethers out:\
\
\'93Broke his arm--_very_ likely, _ain\'92t_ it?--and very convenient, too,\
for a fraud that\'92s got to make signs, and ain\'92t learnt how. \'a0Lost\
their baggage! That\'92s _mighty_ good!--and mighty ingenious--under the\
_circumstances_!\'94\
\
So he laughed again; and so did everybody else, except three or four,\
or maybe half a dozen. \'a0One of these was that doctor; another one was\
a sharp-looking gentleman, with a carpet-bag of the old-fashioned kind\
made out of carpet-stuff, that had just come off of the steamboat and\
was talking to him in a low voice, and glancing towards the king now and\
then and nodding their heads--it was Levi Bell, the lawyer that was gone\
up to Louisville; and another one was a big rough husky that come along\
and listened to all the old gentleman said, and was listening to the\
king now. And when the king got done this husky up and says:\
\
\'93Say, looky here; if you are Harvey Wilks, when\'92d you come to this\
town?\'94\
\
\'93The day before the funeral, friend,\'94 says the king.\
\
\'93But what time o\'92 day?\'94\
\
\'93In the evenin\'92--\'91bout an hour er two before sundown.\'94\
\
\'93_How\'92d_ you come?\'94\
\
\'93I come down on the Susan Powell from Cincinnati.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, how\'92d you come to be up at the Pint in the _mornin_\'92--in a\
canoe?\'94\
\
\'93I warn\'92t up at the Pint in the mornin\'92.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie.\'94\
\
Several of them jumped for him and begged him not to talk that way to an\
old man and a preacher.\
\
\'93Preacher be hanged, he\'92s a fraud and a liar. \'a0He was up at the Pint\
that mornin\'92. \'a0I live up there, don\'92t I? \'a0Well, I was up there, and\
he was up there. \'a0I see him there. \'a0He come in a canoe, along with Tim\
Collins and a boy.\'94\
\
The doctor he up and says:\
\
\'93Would you know the boy again if you was to see him, Hines?\'94\
\
\'93I reckon I would, but I don\'92t know. \'a0Why, yonder he is, now. \'a0I know\
him perfectly easy.\'94\
\
It was me he pointed at. \'a0The doctor says:\
\
\'93Neighbors, I don\'92t know whether the new couple is frauds or not; but if\
_these_ two ain\'92t frauds, I am an idiot, that\'92s all. \'a0I think it\'92s our\
duty to see that they don\'92t get away from here till we\'92ve looked into\
this thing. Come along, Hines; come along, the rest of you. \'a0We\'92ll take\
these fellows to the tavern and affront them with t\'92other couple, and I\
reckon we\'92ll find out _something_ before we get through.\'94\
\
It was nuts for the crowd, though maybe not for the king\'92s friends; so\
we all started. \'a0It was about sundown. \'a0The doctor he led me along by\
the hand, and was plenty kind enough, but he never let go my hand.\
\
We all got in a big room in the hotel, and lit up some candles, and\
fetched in the new couple. \'a0First, the doctor says:\
\
\'93I don\'92t wish to be too hard on these two men, but I think they\'92re\
frauds, and they may have complices that we don\'92t know nothing about.\
\'a0If they have, won\'92t the complices get away with that bag of gold Peter\
Wilks left? \'a0It ain\'92t unlikely. \'a0If these men ain\'92t frauds, they won\'92t\
object to sending for that money and letting us keep it till they prove\
they\'92re all right--ain\'92t that so?\'94\
\
Everybody agreed to that. \'a0So I judged they had our gang in a pretty\
tight place right at the outstart. \'a0But the king he only looked\
sorrowful, and says:\
\
\'93Gentlemen, I wish the money was there, for I ain\'92t got no disposition\
to throw anything in the way of a fair, open, out-and-out investigation\
o\'92 this misable business; but, alas, the money ain\'92t there; you k\'92n send\
and see, if you want to.\'94\
\
\'93Where is it, then?\'94\
\
\'93Well, when my niece give it to me to keep for her I took and hid it\
inside o\'92 the straw tick o\'92 my bed, not wishin\'92 to bank it for the few\
days we\'92d be here, and considerin\'92 the bed a safe place, we not bein\'92\
used to niggers, and suppos\'92n\'92 \'91em honest, like servants in England.\
\'a0The niggers stole it the very next mornin\'92 after I had went down\
stairs; and when I sold \'91em I hadn\'92t missed the money yit, so they got\
clean away with it. \'a0My servant here k\'92n tell you \'91bout it, gentlemen.\'94\
\
The doctor and several said \'93Shucks!\'94 and I see nobody didn\'92t altogether\
believe him. \'a0One man asked me if I see the niggers steal it. \'a0I said\
no, but I see them sneaking out of the room and hustling away, and I\
never thought nothing, only I reckoned they was afraid they had waked up\
my master and was trying to get away before he made trouble with them.\
\'a0That was all they asked me. \'a0Then the doctor whirls on me and says:\
\
\'93Are _you_ English, too?\'94\
\
I says yes; and him and some others laughed, and said, \'93Stuff!\'94\
\
Well, then they sailed in on the general investigation, and there we had\
it, up and down, hour in, hour out, and nobody never said a word about\
supper, nor ever seemed to think about it--and so they kept it up, and\
kept it up; and it _was_ the worst mixed-up thing you ever see. \'a0They\
made the king tell his yarn, and they made the old gentleman tell his\'92n;\
and anybody but a lot of prejudiced chuckleheads would a _seen_ that the\
old gentleman was spinning truth and t\'92other one lies. \'a0And by and by\
they had me up to tell what I knowed. \'a0The king he give me a left-handed\
look out of the corner of his eye, and so I knowed enough to talk on the\
right side. \'a0I begun to tell about Sheffield, and how we lived there,\
and all about the English Wilkses, and so on; but I didn\'92t get pretty\
fur till the doctor begun to laugh; and Levi Bell, the lawyer, says:\
\
\'93Set down, my boy; I wouldn\'92t strain myself if I was you. \'a0I reckon\
you ain\'92t used to lying, it don\'92t seem to come handy; what you want is\
practice. \'a0You do it pretty awkward.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t care nothing for the compliment, but I was glad to be let off,\
anyway.\
\
The doctor he started to say something, and turns and says:\
\
\'93If you\'92d been in town at first, Levi Bell--\'94 The king broke in and\
reached out his hand, and says:\
\
\'93Why, is this my poor dead brother\'92s old friend that he\'92s wrote so often\
about?\'94\
\
The lawyer and him shook hands, and the lawyer smiled and looked\
pleased, and they talked right along awhile, and then got to one side\
and talked low; and at last the lawyer speaks up and says:\
\
\'93That \'91ll fix it. \'a0I\'92ll take the order and send it, along with your\
brother\'92s, and then they\'92ll know it\'92s all right.\'94\
\
So they got some paper and a pen, and the king he set down and twisted\
his head to one side, and chawed his tongue, and scrawled off something;\
and then they give the pen to the duke--and then for the first time the\
duke looked sick. \'a0But he took the pen and wrote. \'a0So then the lawyer\
turns to the new old gentleman and says:\
\
\'93You and your brother please write a line or two and sign your names.\'94\
\
The old gentleman wrote, but nobody couldn\'92t read it. \'a0The lawyer looked\
powerful astonished, and says:\
\
\'93Well, it beats _me_\'94--and snaked a lot of old letters out of his pocket,\
and examined them, and then examined the old man\'92s writing, and then\
_them_ again; and then says:  \'93These old letters is from Harvey Wilks;\
and here\'92s _these_ two handwritings, and anybody can see they didn\'92t\
write them\'94 (the king and the duke looked sold and foolish, I tell\
you, to see how the lawyer had took them in), \'93and here\'92s _this_ old\
gentleman\'92s hand writing, and anybody can tell, easy enough, _he_ didn\'92t\
write them--fact is, the scratches he makes ain\'92t properly _writing_ at\
all. \'a0Now, here\'92s some letters from--\'94\
\
The new old gentleman says:\
\
\'93If you please, let me explain. \'a0Nobody can read my hand but my brother\
there--so he copies for me. \'a0It\'92s _his_ hand you\'92ve got there, not mine.\'94\
\
\'93_Well_!\'94 says the lawyer, \'93this _is_ a state of things. \'a0I\'92ve got some\
of William\'92s letters, too; so if you\'92ll get him to write a line or so we\
can com--\'94\
\
\'93He _can\'92t_ write with his left hand,\'94 says the old gentleman.  \'93If he\
could use his right hand, you would see that he wrote his own letters\
and mine too. \'a0Look at both, please--they\'92re by the same hand.\'94\
\
The lawyer done it, and says:\
\
\'93I believe it\'92s so--and if it ain\'92t so, there\'92s a heap stronger\
resemblance than I\'92d noticed before, anyway. \'a0Well, well, well! \'a0I\
thought we was right on the track of a solution, but it\'92s gone to grass,\
partly. \'a0But anyway, one thing is proved--_these_ two ain\'92t either of \'91em\
Wilkses\'94--and he wagged his head towards the king and the duke.\
\
Well, what do you think? \'a0That muleheaded old fool wouldn\'92t give in\
_then_! Indeed he wouldn\'92t. \'a0Said it warn\'92t no fair test. \'a0Said his\
brother William was the cussedest joker in the world, and hadn\'92t tried\
to write--_he_ see William was going to play one of his jokes the minute\
he put the pen to paper. \'a0And so he warmed up and went warbling and\
warbling right along till he was actuly beginning to believe what he was\
saying _himself_; but pretty soon the new gentleman broke in, and says:\
\
\'93I\'92ve thought of something. \'a0Is there anybody here that helped to lay\
out my br--helped to lay out the late Peter Wilks for burying?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 says somebody, \'93me and Ab Turner done it. \'a0We\'92re both here.\'94\
\
Then the old man turns towards the king, and says:\
\
\'93Perhaps this gentleman can tell me what was tattooed on his breast?\'94\
\
Blamed if the king didn\'92t have to brace up mighty quick, or he\'92d a\
squshed down like a bluff bank that the river has cut under, it took\
him so sudden; and, mind you, it was a thing that was calculated to make\
most _anybody_ sqush to get fetched such a solid one as that without any\
notice, because how was _he_ going to know what was tattooed on the man?\
\'a0He whitened a little; he couldn\'92t help it; and it was mighty still in\
there, and everybody bending a little forwards and gazing at him. \'a0Says\
I to myself, _now_ he\'92ll throw up the sponge--there ain\'92t no more use.\
\'a0Well, did he? \'a0A body can\'92t hardly believe it, but he didn\'92t. \'a0I reckon\
he thought he\'92d keep the thing up till he tired them people out, so\
they\'92d thin out, and him and the duke could break loose and get away.\
\'a0Anyway, he set there, and pretty soon he begun to smile, and says:\
\
\'93Mf! \'a0It\'92s a _very_ tough question, _ain\'92t_ it! \'a0_yes_, sir, I k\'92n\
tell you what\'92s tattooed on his breast. \'a0It\'92s jest a small, thin, blue\
arrow--that\'92s what it is; and if you don\'92t look clost, you can\'92t see it.\
\'a0_now_ what do you say--hey?\'94\
\
Well, I never see anything like that old blister for clean out-and-out\
cheek.\
\
The new old gentleman turns brisk towards Ab Turner and his pard, and\
his eye lights up like he judged he\'92d got the king _this_ time, and\
says:\
\
\'93There--you\'92ve heard what he said! \'a0Was there any such mark on Peter\
Wilks\'92 breast?\'94\
\
Both of them spoke up and says:\
\
\'93We didn\'92t see no such mark.\'94\
\
\'93Good!\'94 says the old gentleman.  \'93Now, what you _did_ see on his breast\
was a small dim P, and a B (which is an initial he dropped when he was\
young), and a W, with dashes between them, so: \'a0P--B--W\'94--and he marked\
them that way on a piece of paper.  \'93Come, ain\'92t that what you saw?\'94\
\
Both of them spoke up again, and says:\
\
\'93No, we _didn\'92t_. \'a0We never seen any marks at all.\'94\
\
Well, everybody _was_ in a state of mind now, and they sings out:\
\
\'93The whole _bilin_\'92 of \'91m \'91s frauds! \'a0Le\'92s duck \'91em! le\'92s drown \'91em!\
le\'92s ride \'91em on a rail!\'94 and everybody was whooping at once, and there\
was a rattling powwow. \'a0But the lawyer he jumps on the table and yells,\
and says:\
\
\'93Gentlemen--gentle_men!_ \'a0Hear me just a word--just a _single_ word--if you\
_please_! \'a0There\'92s one way yet--let\'92s go and dig up the corpse and look.\'94\
\
That took them.\
\
\'93Hooray!\'94 they all shouted, and was starting right off; but the lawyer\
and the doctor sung out:\
\
\'93Hold on, hold on! \'a0Collar all these four men and the boy, and fetch\
_them_ along, too!\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll do it!\'94 they all shouted; \'93and if we don\'92t find them marks we\'92ll\
lynch the whole gang!\'94\
\
I _was_ scared, now, I tell you. \'a0But there warn\'92t no getting away, you\
know. They gripped us all, and marched us right along, straight for the\
graveyard, which was a mile and a half down the river, and the whole\
town at our heels, for we made noise enough, and it was only nine in the\
evening.\
\
As we went by our house I wished I hadn\'92t sent Mary Jane out of town;\
because now if I could tip her the wink she\'92d light out and save me, and\
blow on our dead-beats.\
\
Well, we swarmed along down the river road, just carrying on like\
wildcats; and to make it more scary the sky was darking up, and the\
lightning beginning to wink and flitter, and the wind to shiver amongst\
the leaves. This was the most awful trouble and most dangersome I ever\
was in; and I was kinder stunned; everything was going so different from\
what I had allowed for; stead of being fixed so I could take my own time\
if I wanted to, and see all the fun, and have Mary Jane at my back to\
save me and set me free when the close-fit come, here was nothing in the\
world betwixt me and sudden death but just them tattoo-marks. \'a0If they\
didn\'92t find them--\
\
I couldn\'92t bear to think about it; and yet, somehow, I couldn\'92t think\
about nothing else. \'a0It got darker and darker, and it was a beautiful\
time to give the crowd the slip; but that big husky had me by the\
wrist--Hines--and a body might as well try to give Goliar the slip. \'a0He\
dragged me right along, he was so excited, and I had to run to keep up.\
\
When they got there they swarmed into the graveyard and washed over it\
like an overflow. \'a0And when they got to the grave they found they had\
about a hundred times as many shovels as they wanted, but nobody hadn\'92t\
thought to fetch a lantern. \'a0But they sailed into digging anyway by the\
flicker of the lightning, and sent a man to the nearest house, a half a\
mile off, to borrow one.\
\
So they dug and dug like everything; and it got awful dark, and the rain\
started, and the wind swished and swushed along, and the lightning come\
brisker and brisker, and the thunder boomed; but them people never took\
no notice of it, they was so full of this business; and one minute\
you could see everything and every face in that big crowd, and the\
shovelfuls of dirt sailing up out of the grave, and the next second the\
dark wiped it all out, and you couldn\'92t see nothing at all.\
\
At last they got out the coffin and begun to unscrew the lid, and then\
such another crowding and shouldering and shoving as there was, to\
scrouge in and get a sight, you never see; and in the dark, that way, it\
was awful. \'a0Hines he hurt my wrist dreadful pulling and tugging so,\
and I reckon he clean forgot I was in the world, he was so excited and\
panting.\
\
All of a sudden the lightning let go a perfect sluice of white glare,\
and somebody sings out:\
\
\'93By the living jingo, here\'92s the bag of gold on his breast!\'94\
\
Hines let out a whoop, like everybody else, and dropped my wrist and\
give a big surge to bust his way in and get a look, and the way I lit\
out and shinned for the road in the dark there ain\'92t nobody can tell.\
\
I had the road all to myself, and I fairly flew--leastways, I had it all\
to myself except the solid dark, and the now-and-then glares, and the\
buzzing of the rain, and the thrashing of the wind, and the splitting of\
the thunder; and sure as you are born I did clip it along!\
\
When I struck the town I see there warn\'92t nobody out in the storm, so\
I never hunted for no back streets, but humped it straight through the\
main one; and when I begun to get towards our house I aimed my eye and\
set it. No light there; the house all dark--which made me feel sorry and\
disappointed, I didn\'92t know why. \'a0But at last, just as I was sailing by,\
_flash_ comes the light in Mary Jane\'92s window! and my heart swelled up\
sudden, like to bust; and the same second the house and all was behind\
me in the dark, and wasn\'92t ever going to be before me no more in this\
world. She _was_ the best girl I ever see, and had the most sand.\
\
The minute I was far enough above the town to see I could make the\
towhead, I begun to look sharp for a boat to borrow, and the first\
time the lightning showed me one that wasn\'92t chained I snatched it and\
shoved. It was a canoe, and warn\'92t fastened with nothing but a rope.\
\'a0The towhead was a rattling big distance off, away out there in the\
middle of the river, but I didn\'92t lose no time; and when I struck the\
raft at last I was so fagged I would a just laid down to blow and gasp\
if I could afforded it. \'a0But I didn\'92t. \'a0As I sprung aboard I sung out:\
\
\'93Out with you, Jim, and set her loose! \'a0Glory be to goodness, we\'92re shut\
of them!\'94\
\
Jim lit out, and was a-coming for me with both arms spread, he was so\
full of joy; but when I glimpsed him in the lightning my heart shot up\
in my mouth and I went overboard backwards; for I forgot he was old King\
Lear and a drownded A-rab all in one, and it most scared the livers and\
lights out of me. \'a0But Jim fished me out, and was going to hug me and\
bless me, and so on, he was so glad I was back and we was shut of the\
king and the duke, but I says:\
\
\'93Not now; have it for breakfast, have it for breakfast! \'a0Cut loose and\
let her slide!\'94\
\
So in two seconds away we went a-sliding down the river, and it _did_\
seem so good to be free again and all by ourselves on the big river, and\
nobody to bother us. \'a0I had to skip around a bit, and jump up and crack\
my heels a few times--I couldn\'92t help it; but about the third crack\
I noticed a sound that I knowed mighty well, and held my breath and\
listened and waited; and sure enough, when the next flash busted out\
over the water, here they come!--and just a-laying to their oars and\
making their skiff hum! \'a0It was the king and the duke.\
\
So I wilted right down on to the planks then, and give up; and it was\
all I could do to keep from crying.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXX.\
\
WHEN they got aboard the king went for me, and shook me by the collar,\
and says:\
\
\'93Tryin\'92 to give us the slip, was ye, you pup! \'a0Tired of our company,\
hey?\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93No, your majesty, we warn\'92t--_please_ don\'92t, your majesty!\'94\
\
\'93Quick, then, and tell us what _was_ your idea, or I\'92ll shake the\
insides out o\'92 you!\'94\
\
\'93Honest, I\'92ll tell you everything just as it happened, your majesty.\
\'a0The man that had a-holt of me was very good to me, and kept saying he\
had a boy about as big as me that died last year, and he was sorry\
to see a boy in such a dangerous fix; and when they was all took by\
surprise by finding the gold, and made a rush for the coffin, he lets go\
of me and whispers, \'91Heel it now, or they\'92ll hang ye, sure!\'92 and I lit\
out. \'a0It didn\'92t seem no good for _me_ to stay--I couldn\'92t do nothing,\
and I didn\'92t want to be hung if I could get away. \'a0So I never stopped\
running till I found the canoe; and when I got here I told Jim to hurry,\
or they\'92d catch me and hang me yet, and said I was afeard you and the\
duke wasn\'92t alive now, and I was awful sorry, and so was Jim, and was\
awful glad when we see you coming; you may ask Jim if I didn\'92t.\'94\
\
Jim said it was so; and the king told him to shut up, and said, \'93Oh,\
yes, it\'92s _mighty_ likely!\'94 and shook me up again, and said he reckoned\
he\'92d drownd me. \'a0But the duke says:\
\
\'93Leggo the boy, you old idiot! \'a0Would _you_ a done any different? \'a0Did\
you inquire around for _him_ when you got loose? \'a0I don\'92t remember it.\'94\
\
So the king let go of me, and begun to cuss that town and everybody in\
it. But the duke says:\
\
\'93You better a blame\'92 sight give _yourself_ a good cussing, for you\'92re\
the one that\'92s entitled to it most. \'a0You hain\'92t done a thing from the\
start that had any sense in it, except coming out so cool and cheeky\
with that imaginary blue-arrow mark. \'a0That _was_ bright--it was right\
down bully; and it was the thing that saved us. \'a0For if it hadn\'92t been\
for that they\'92d a jailed us till them Englishmen\'92s baggage come--and\
then--the penitentiary, you bet! But that trick took \'91em to the\
graveyard, and the gold done us a still bigger kindness; for if the\
excited fools hadn\'92t let go all holts and made that rush to get a\
look we\'92d a slept in our cravats to-night--cravats warranted to _wear_,\
too--longer than _we\'92d_ need \'91em.\'94\
\
They was still a minute--thinking; then the king says, kind of\
absent-minded like:\
\
\'93Mf! \'a0And we reckoned the _niggers_ stole it!\'94\
\
That made me squirm!\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 says the duke, kinder slow and deliberate and sarcastic, \'93_we_\
did.\'94\
\
After about a half a minute the king drawls out:\
\
\'93Leastways, I did.\'94\
\
The duke says, the same way:\
\
\'93On the contrary, I did.\'94\
\
The king kind of ruffles up, and says:\
\
\'93Looky here, Bilgewater, what\'92r you referrin\'92 to?\'94\
\
The duke says, pretty brisk:\
\
\'93When it comes to that, maybe you\'92ll let me ask, what was _you_\
referring to?\'94\
\
\'93Shucks!\'94 says the king, very sarcastic; \'93but I don\'92t know--maybe you was\
asleep, and didn\'92t know what you was about.\'94\
\
The duke bristles up now, and says:\
\
\'93Oh, let _up_ on this cussed nonsense; do you take me for a blame\'92 fool?\
Don\'92t you reckon I know who hid that money in that coffin?\'94\
\
\'93_Yes_, sir! \'a0I know you _do_ know, because you done it yourself!\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie!\'94--and the duke went for him. \'a0The king sings out:\
\
\'93Take y\'92r hands off!--leggo my throat!--I take it all back!\'94\
\
The duke says:\
\
\'93Well, you just own up, first, that you _did_ hide that money there,\
intending to give me the slip one of these days, and come back and dig\
it up, and have it all to yourself.\'94\
\
\'93Wait jest a minute, duke--answer me this one question, honest and fair;\
if you didn\'92t put the money there, say it, and I\'92ll b\'92lieve you, and\
take back everything I said.\'94\
\
\'93You old scoundrel, I didn\'92t, and you know I didn\'92t. \'a0There, now!\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, I b\'92lieve you. \'a0But answer me only jest this one more--now\
_don\'92t_ git mad; didn\'92t you have it in your mind to hook the money and\
hide it?\'94\
\
The duke never said nothing for a little bit; then he says:\
\
\'93Well, I don\'92t care if I _did_, I didn\'92t _do_ it, anyway. \'a0But you not\
only had it in mind to do it, but you _done_ it.\'94\
\
\'93I wisht I never die if I done it, duke, and that\'92s honest. \'a0I won\'92t say\
I warn\'92t goin\'92 to do it, because I _was_; but you--I mean somebody--got in\
ahead o\'92 me.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a lie! \'a0You done it, and you got to _say_ you done it, or--\'94\
\
The king began to gurgle, and then he gasps out:\
\
\'93\'91Nough!--I _own up!_\'94\
\
I was very glad to hear him say that; it made me feel much more easier\
than what I was feeling before. \'a0So the duke took his hands off and\
says:\
\
\'93If you ever deny it again I\'92ll drown you. \'a0It\'92s _well_ for you to set\
there and blubber like a baby--it\'92s fitten for you, after the way\
you\'92ve acted. I never see such an old ostrich for wanting to gobble\
everything--and I a-trusting you all the time, like you was my own\
father. \'a0You ought to been ashamed of yourself to stand by and hear it\
saddled on to a lot of poor niggers, and you never say a word for \'91em.\
\'a0It makes me feel ridiculous to think I was soft enough to _believe_\
that rubbage. \'a0Cuss you, I can see now why you was so anxious to make\
up the deffisit--you wanted to get what money I\'92d got out of the Nonesuch\
and one thing or another, and scoop it _all_!\'94\
\
The king says, timid, and still a-snuffling:\
\
\'93Why, duke, it was you that said make up the deffisit; it warn\'92t me.\'94\
\
\'93Dry up! \'a0I don\'92t want to hear no more out of you!\'94 says the duke.  \'93And\
_now_ you see what you GOT by it. \'a0They\'92ve got all their own money back,\
and all of _ourn_ but a shekel or two _besides_. \'a0G\'92long to bed, and\
don\'92t you deffersit _me_ no more deffersits, long \'91s _you_ live!\'94\
\
So the king sneaked into the wigwam and took to his bottle for comfort,\
and before long the duke tackled HIS bottle; and so in about a half an\
hour they was as thick as thieves again, and the tighter they got the\
lovinger they got, and went off a-snoring in each other\'92s arms. \'a0They\
both got powerful mellow, but I noticed the king didn\'92t get mellow\
enough to forget to remember to not deny about hiding the money-bag\
again. \'a0That made me feel easy and satisfied. \'a0Of course when they got\
to snoring we had a long gabble, and I told Jim everything.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXI.\
\
WE dasn\'92t stop again at any town for days and days; kept right along\
down the river. \'a0We was down south in the warm weather now, and a mighty\
long ways from home. \'a0We begun to come to trees with Spanish moss on\
them, hanging down from the limbs like long, gray beards. \'a0It was the\
first I ever see it growing, and it made the woods look solemn and\
dismal. \'a0So now the frauds reckoned they was out of danger, and they\
begun to work the villages again.\
\
First they done a lecture on temperance; but they didn\'92t make enough\
for them both to get drunk on. \'a0Then in another village they started\
a dancing-school; but they didn\'92t know no more how to dance than a\
kangaroo does; so the first prance they made the general public jumped\
in and pranced them out of town. \'a0Another time they tried to go at\
yellocution; but they didn\'92t yellocute long till the audience got up and\
give them a solid good cussing, and made them skip out. \'a0They tackled\
missionarying, and mesmerizing, and doctoring, and telling fortunes, and\
a little of everything; but they couldn\'92t seem to have no luck. \'a0So at\
last they got just about dead broke, and laid around the raft as she\
floated along, thinking and thinking, and never saying nothing, by the\
half a day at a time, and dreadful blue and desperate.\
\
And at last they took a change and begun to lay their heads together in\
the wigwam and talk low and confidential two or three hours at a time.\
Jim and me got uneasy. \'a0We didn\'92t like the look of it. \'a0We judged they\
was studying up some kind of worse deviltry than ever. \'a0We turned it\
over and over, and at last we made up our minds they was going to break\
into somebody\'92s house or store, or was going into the counterfeit-money\
business, or something. So then we was pretty scared, and made up an\
agreement that we wouldn\'92t have nothing in the world to do with such\
actions, and if we ever got the least show we would give them the cold\
shake and clear out and leave them behind. Well, early one morning we\
hid the raft in a good, safe place about two mile below a little bit of\
a shabby village named Pikesville, and the king he went ashore and told\
us all to stay hid whilst he went up to town and smelt around to see\
if anybody had got any wind of the Royal Nonesuch there yet. (\'93House to\
rob, you _mean_,\'94 says I to myself; \'93and when you get through robbing it\
you\'92ll come back here and wonder what has become of me and Jim and the\
raft--and you\'92ll have to take it out in wondering.\'94) And he said if he\
warn\'92t back by midday the duke and me would know it was all right, and\
we was to come along.\
\
So we stayed where we was. \'a0The duke he fretted and sweated around, and\
was in a mighty sour way. \'a0He scolded us for everything, and we couldn\'92t\
seem to do nothing right; he found fault with every little thing.\
Something was a-brewing, sure. \'a0I was good and glad when midday come\
and no king; we could have a change, anyway--and maybe a chance for _the_\
change on top of it. \'a0So me and the duke went up to the village, and\
hunted around there for the king, and by and by we found him in the\
back room of a little low doggery, very tight, and a lot of loafers\
bullyragging him for sport, and he a-cussing and a-threatening with all\
his might, and so tight he couldn\'92t walk, and couldn\'92t do nothing to\
them. \'a0The duke he begun to abuse him for an old fool, and the king\
begun to sass back, and the minute they was fairly at it I lit out and\
shook the reefs out of my hind legs, and spun down the river road like\
a deer, for I see our chance; and I made up my mind that it would be a\
long day before they ever see me and Jim again. \'a0I got down there all\
out of breath but loaded up with joy, and sung out:\
\
\'93Set her loose, Jim! we\'92re all right now!\'94\
\
But there warn\'92t no answer, and nobody come out of the wigwam. \'a0Jim was\
gone! \'a0I set up a shout--and then another--and then another one; and run\
this way and that in the woods, whooping and screeching; but it warn\'92t\
no use--old Jim was gone. \'a0Then I set down and cried; I couldn\'92t help\
it. But I couldn\'92t set still long. \'a0Pretty soon I went out on the road,\
trying to think what I better do, and I run across a boy walking, and\
asked him if he\'92d seen a strange nigger dressed so and so, and he says:\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Whereabouts?\'94 says I.\
\
\'93Down to Silas Phelps\'92 place, two mile below here. \'a0He\'92s a runaway\
nigger, and they\'92ve got him. \'a0Was you looking for him?\'94\
\
\'93You bet I ain\'92t! \'a0I run across him in the woods about an hour or two\
ago, and he said if I hollered he\'92d cut my livers out--and told me to lay\
down and stay where I was; and I done it. \'a0Been there ever since; afeard\
to come out.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93you needn\'92t be afeard no more, becuz they\'92ve got him.\
He run off f\'92m down South, som\'92ers.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a good job they got him.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I _reckon_! \'a0There\'92s two hunderd dollars reward on him. \'a0It\'92s\
like picking up money out\'92n the road.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, it is--and I could a had it if I\'92d been big enough; I see him\
_first_. Who nailed him?\'94\
\
\'93It was an old fellow--a stranger--and he sold out his chance in him for\
forty dollars, becuz he\'92s got to go up the river and can\'92t wait. \'a0Think\
o\'92 that, now! \'a0You bet _I\'92d_ wait, if it was seven year.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s me, every time,\'94 says I.  \'93But maybe his chance ain\'92t worth\
no more than that, if he\'92ll sell it so cheap. \'a0Maybe there\'92s something\
ain\'92t straight about it.\'94\
\
\'93But it _is_, though--straight as a string. \'a0I see the handbill myself.\
\'a0It tells all about him, to a dot--paints him like a picture, and tells\
the plantation he\'92s frum, below Newr_leans_. \'a0No-sirree-_bob_, they\
ain\'92t no trouble \'91bout _that_ speculation, you bet you. \'a0Say, gimme a\
chaw tobacker, won\'92t ye?\'94\
\
I didn\'92t have none, so he left. \'a0I went to the raft, and set down in the\
wigwam to think. \'a0But I couldn\'92t come to nothing. \'a0I thought till I wore\
my head sore, but I couldn\'92t see no way out of the trouble. \'a0After all\
this long journey, and after all we\'92d done for them scoundrels, here it\
was all come to nothing, everything all busted up and ruined, because\
they could have the heart to serve Jim such a trick as that, and make\
him a slave again all his life, and amongst strangers, too, for forty\
dirty dollars.\
\
Once I said to myself it would be a thousand times better for Jim to\
be a slave at home where his family was, as long as he\'92d _got_ to be a\
slave, and so I\'92d better write a letter to Tom Sawyer and tell him to\
tell Miss Watson where he was. \'a0But I soon give up that notion for two\
things: she\'92d be mad and disgusted at his rascality and ungratefulness\
for leaving her, and so she\'92d sell him straight down the river again;\
and if she didn\'92t, everybody naturally despises an ungrateful nigger,\
and they\'92d make Jim feel it all the time, and so he\'92d feel ornery and\
disgraced. And then think of _me_! \'a0It would get all around that Huck\
Finn helped a nigger to get his freedom; and if I was ever to see\
anybody from that town again I\'92d be ready to get down and lick his boots\
for shame. \'a0That\'92s just the way: \'a0a person does a low-down thing, and\
then he don\'92t want to take no consequences of it. Thinks as long as he\
can hide it, it ain\'92t no disgrace. \'a0That was my fix exactly. The more I\
studied about this the more my conscience went to grinding me, and the\
more wicked and low-down and ornery I got to feeling. And at last, when\
it hit me all of a sudden that here was the plain hand of Providence\
slapping me in the face and letting me know my wickedness was being\
watched all the time from up there in heaven, whilst I was stealing a\
poor old woman\'92s nigger that hadn\'92t ever done me no harm, and now was\
showing me there\'92s One that\'92s always on the lookout, and ain\'92t a-going\
to allow no such miserable doings to go only just so fur and no further,\
I most dropped in my tracks I was so scared. \'a0Well, I tried the best I\
could to kinder soften it up somehow for myself by saying I was brung\
up wicked, and so I warn\'92t so much to blame; but something inside of me\
kept saying, \'93There was the Sunday-school, you could a gone to it; and\
if you\'92d a done it they\'92d a learnt you there that people that acts as\
I\'92d been acting about that nigger goes to everlasting fire.\'94\
\
It made me shiver. \'a0And I about made up my mind to pray, and see if I\
couldn\'92t try to quit being the kind of a boy I was and be better. \'a0So\
I kneeled down. \'a0But the words wouldn\'92t come. \'a0Why wouldn\'92t they? \'a0It\
warn\'92t no use to try and hide it from Him. \'a0Nor from _me_, neither. \'a0I\
knowed very well why they wouldn\'92t come. \'a0It was because my heart warn\'92t\
right; it was because I warn\'92t square; it was because I was playing\
double. \'a0I was letting _on_ to give up sin, but away inside of me I was\
holding on to the biggest one of all. \'a0I was trying to make my mouth\
_say_ I would do the right thing and the clean thing, and go and write\
to that nigger\'92s owner and tell where he was; but deep down in me I\
knowed it was a lie, and He knowed it. \'a0You can\'92t pray a lie--I found\
that out.\
\
So I was full of trouble, full as I could be; and didn\'92t know what to\
do. At last I had an idea; and I says, I\'92ll go and write the letter--and\
then see if I can pray. \'a0Why, it was astonishing, the way I felt as\
light as a feather right straight off, and my troubles all gone. \'a0So I\
got a piece of paper and a pencil, all glad and excited, and set down\
and wrote:\
\
Miss Watson, your runaway nigger Jim is down here two mile below\
Pikesville, and Mr. Phelps has got him and he will give him up for the\
reward if you send.\
\
_Huck Finn._\
\
I felt good and all washed clean of sin for the first time I had ever\
felt so in my life, and I knowed I could pray now. \'a0But I didn\'92t do it\
straight off, but laid the paper down and set there thinking--thinking\
how good it was all this happened so, and how near I come to being lost\
and going to hell. \'a0And went on thinking. \'a0And got to thinking over our\
trip down the river; and I see Jim before me all the time: \'a0in the day\
and in the night-time, sometimes moonlight, sometimes storms, and we\
a-floating along, talking and singing and laughing. \'a0But somehow I\
couldn\'92t seem to strike no places to harden me against him, but only the\
other kind. \'a0I\'92d see him standing my watch on top of his\'92n, \'91stead of\
calling me, so I could go on sleeping; and see him how glad he was when\
I come back out of the fog; and when I come to him again in the swamp,\
up there where the feud was; and such-like times; and would always call\
me honey, and pet me and do everything he could think of for me, and how\
good he always was; and at last I struck the time I saved him by telling\
the men we had small-pox aboard, and he was so grateful, and said I was\
the best friend old Jim ever had in the world, and the _only_ one he\'92s\
got now; and then I happened to look around and see that paper.\
\
It was a close place. \'a0I took it up, and held it in my hand. \'a0I was\
a-trembling, because I\'92d got to decide, forever, betwixt two things, and\
I knowed it. \'a0I studied a minute, sort of holding my breath, and then\
says to myself:\
\
\'93All right, then, I\'92ll _go_ to hell\'94--and tore it up.\
\
It was awful thoughts and awful words, but they was said. \'a0And I let\
them stay said; and never thought no more about reforming. \'a0I shoved the\
whole thing out of my head, and said I would take up wickedness again,\
which was in my line, being brung up to it, and the other warn\'92t. \'a0And\
for a starter I would go to work and steal Jim out of slavery again;\
and if I could think up anything worse, I would do that, too; because as\
long as I was in, and in for good, I might as well go the whole hog.\
\
Then I set to thinking over how to get at it, and turned over some\
considerable many ways in my mind; and at last fixed up a plan that\
suited me. \'a0So then I took the bearings of a woody island that was down\
the river a piece, and as soon as it was fairly dark I crept out with my\
raft and went for it, and hid it there, and then turned in. \'a0I slept the\
night through, and got up before it was light, and had my breakfast,\
and put on my store clothes, and tied up some others and one thing or\
another in a bundle, and took the canoe and cleared for shore. \'a0I landed\
below where I judged was Phelps\'92s place, and hid my bundle in the woods,\
and then filled up the canoe with water, and loaded rocks into her and\
sunk her where I could find her again when I wanted her, about a quarter\
of a mile below a little steam sawmill that was on the bank.\
\
Then I struck up the road, and when I passed the mill I see a sign on\
it, \'93Phelps\'92s Sawmill,\'94 and when I come to the farm-houses, two or\
three hundred yards further along, I kept my eyes peeled, but didn\'92t\
see nobody around, though it was good daylight now. \'a0But I didn\'92t mind,\
because I didn\'92t want to see nobody just yet--I only wanted to get the\
lay of the land. According to my plan, I was going to turn up there from\
the village, not from below. \'a0So I just took a look, and shoved along,\
straight for town. Well, the very first man I see when I got there was\
the duke. \'a0He was sticking up a bill for the Royal Nonesuch--three-night\
performance--like that other time. \'a0They had the cheek, them frauds! \'a0I\
was right on him before I could shirk. \'a0He looked astonished, and says:\
\
\'93Hel-_lo_! \'a0Where\'92d _you_ come from?\'94 \'a0Then he says, kind of glad and\
eager, \'93Where\'92s the raft?--got her in a good place?\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93Why, that\'92s just what I was going to ask your grace.\'94\
\
Then he didn\'92t look so joyful, and says:\
\
\'93What was your idea for asking _me_?\'94 he says.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I says, \'93when I see the king in that doggery yesterday I says\
to myself, we can\'92t get him home for hours, till he\'92s soberer; so I went\
a-loafing around town to put in the time and wait. \'a0A man up and offered\
me ten cents to help him pull a skiff over the river and back to fetch\
a sheep, and so I went along; but when we was dragging him to the boat,\
and the man left me a-holt of the rope and went behind him to shove him\
along, he was too strong for me and jerked loose and run, and we after\
him. \'a0We didn\'92t have no dog, and so we had to chase him all over the\
country till we tired him out. \'a0We never got him till dark; then we\
fetched him over, and I started down for the raft. \'a0When I got there and\
see it was gone, I says to myself, \'91They\'92ve got into trouble and had to\
leave; and they\'92ve took my nigger, which is the only nigger I\'92ve got in\
the world, and now I\'92m in a strange country, and ain\'92t got no property\
no more, nor nothing, and no way to make my living;\'92 so I set down and\
cried. \'a0I slept in the woods all night. \'a0But what _did_ become of the\
raft, then?--and Jim--poor Jim!\'94\
\
\'93Blamed if I know--that is, what\'92s become of the raft. \'a0That old fool had\
made a trade and got forty dollars, and when we found him in the doggery\
the loafers had matched half-dollars with him and got every cent but\
what he\'92d spent for whisky; and when I got him home late last night and\
found the raft gone, we said, \'91That little rascal has stole our raft and\
shook us, and run off down the river.\'92\'94\
\
\'93I wouldn\'92t shake my _nigger_, would I?--the only nigger I had in the\
world, and the only property.\'94\
\
\'93We never thought of that. \'a0Fact is, I reckon we\'92d come to consider him\
_our_ nigger; yes, we did consider him so--goodness knows we had trouble\
enough for him. \'a0So when we see the raft was gone and we flat broke,\
there warn\'92t anything for it but to try the Royal Nonesuch another\
shake. And I\'92ve pegged along ever since, dry as a powder-horn. \'a0Where\'92s\
that ten cents? Give it here.\'94\
\
I had considerable money, so I give him ten cents, but begged him to\
spend it for something to eat, and give me some, because it was all the\
money I had, and I hadn\'92t had nothing to eat since yesterday. \'a0He never\
said nothing. \'a0The next minute he whirls on me and says:\
\
\'93Do you reckon that nigger would blow on us? \'a0We\'92d skin him if he done\
that!\'94\
\
\'93How can he blow? \'a0Hain\'92t he run off?\'94\
\
\'93No! \'a0That old fool sold him, and never divided with me, and the money\'92s\
gone.\'94\
\
\'93_Sold_ him?\'94 \'a0I says, and begun to cry; \'93why, he was _my_ nigger, and\
that was my money. \'a0Where is he?--I want my nigger.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you can\'92t _get_ your nigger, that\'92s all--so dry up your\
blubbering. Looky here--do you think _you\'92d_ venture to blow on us?\
\'a0Blamed if I think I\'92d trust you. \'a0Why, if you _was_ to blow on us--\'94\
\
He stopped, but I never see the duke look so ugly out of his eyes\
before. I went on a-whimpering, and says:\
\
\'93I don\'92t want to blow on nobody; and I ain\'92t got no time to blow, nohow.\
I got to turn out and find my nigger.\'94\
\
He looked kinder bothered, and stood there with his bills fluttering on\
his arm, thinking, and wrinkling up his forehead. \'a0At last he says:\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you something. \'a0We got to be here three days. \'a0If you\'92ll\
promise you won\'92t blow, and won\'92t let the nigger blow, I\'92ll tell you\
where to find him.\'94\
\
So I promised, and he says:\
\
\'93A farmer by the name of Silas Ph--\'94 and then he stopped. \'a0You see, he\
started to tell me the truth; but when he stopped that way, and begun to\
study and think again, I reckoned he was changing his mind. \'a0And so he\
was. He wouldn\'92t trust me; he wanted to make sure of having me out of\
the way the whole three days. \'a0So pretty soon he says:\
\
\'93The man that bought him is named Abram Foster--Abram G. Foster--and he\
lives forty mile back here in the country, on the road to Lafayette.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I says, \'93I can walk it in three days. \'a0And I\'92ll start this\
very afternoon.\'94\
\
\'93No you wont, you\'92ll start _now_; and don\'92t you lose any time about it,\
neither, nor do any gabbling by the way. \'a0Just keep a tight tongue in\
your head and move right along, and then you won\'92t get into trouble with\
_us_, d\'92ye hear?\'94\
\
That was the order I wanted, and that was the one I played for. \'a0I\
wanted to be left free to work my plans.\
\
\'93So clear out,\'94 he says; \'93and you can tell Mr. Foster whatever you want\
to. Maybe you can get him to believe that Jim _is_ your nigger--some\
idiots don\'92t require documents--leastways I\'92ve heard there\'92s such down\
South here. \'a0And when you tell him the handbill and the reward\'92s bogus,\
maybe he\'92ll believe you when you explain to him what the idea was for\
getting \'91em out. \'a0Go \'91long now, and tell him anything you want to; but\
mind you don\'92t work your jaw any _between_ here and there.\'94\
\
So I left, and struck for the back country. \'a0I didn\'92t look around, but I\
kinder felt like he was watching me. \'a0But I knowed I could tire him out\
at that. \'a0I went straight out in the country as much as a mile before\
I stopped; then I doubled back through the woods towards Phelps\'92. \'a0I\
reckoned I better start in on my plan straight off without fooling\
around, because I wanted to stop Jim\'92s mouth till these fellows could\
get away. \'a0I didn\'92t want no trouble with their kind. \'a0I\'92d seen all I\
wanted to of them, and wanted to get entirely shut of them.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXII.\
\
WHEN I got there it was all still and Sunday-like, and hot and sunshiny;\
the hands was gone to the fields; and there was them kind of faint\
dronings of bugs and flies in the air that makes it seem so lonesome and\
like everybody\'92s dead and gone; and if a breeze fans along and quivers\
the leaves it makes you feel mournful, because you feel like it\'92s\
spirits whispering--spirits that\'92s been dead ever so many years--and you\
always think they\'92re talking about _you_. \'a0As a general thing it makes a\
body wish _he_ was dead, too, and done with it all.\
\
Phelps\'92 was one of these little one-horse cotton plantations, and they\
all look alike. \'a0A rail fence round a two-acre yard; a stile made out\
of logs sawed off and up-ended in steps, like barrels of a different\
length, to climb over the fence with, and for the women to stand on when\
they are going to jump on to a horse; some sickly grass-patches in the\
big yard, but mostly it was bare and smooth, like an old hat with the\
nap rubbed off; big double log-house for the white folks--hewed logs,\
with the chinks stopped up with mud or mortar, and these mud-stripes\
been whitewashed some time or another; round-log kitchen, with a big\
broad, open but roofed passage joining it to the house; log smoke-house\
back of the kitchen; three little log nigger-cabins in a row t\'92other\
side the smoke-house; one little hut all by itself away down against\
the back fence, and some outbuildings down a piece the other side;\
ash-hopper and big kettle to bile soap in by the little hut; bench by\
the kitchen door, with bucket of water and a gourd; hound asleep there\
in the sun; more hounds asleep round about; about three shade trees away\
off in a corner; some currant bushes and gooseberry bushes in one place\
by the fence; outside of the fence a garden and a watermelon patch; then\
the cotton fields begins, and after the fields the woods.\
\
I went around and clumb over the back stile by the ash-hopper, and\
started for the kitchen. \'a0When I got a little ways I heard the dim hum\
of a spinning-wheel wailing along up and sinking along down again;\
and then I knowed for certain I wished I was dead--for that _is_ the\
lonesomest sound in the whole world.\
\
I went right along, not fixing up any particular plan, but just trusting\
to Providence to put the right words in my mouth when the time come; for\
I\'92d noticed that Providence always did put the right words in my mouth\
if I left it alone.\
\
When I got half-way, first one hound and then another got up and went\
for me, and of course I stopped and faced them, and kept still. \'a0And\
such another powwow as they made! \'a0In a quarter of a minute I was a kind\
of a hub of a wheel, as you may say--spokes made out of dogs--circle of\
fifteen of them packed together around me, with their necks and noses\
stretched up towards me, a-barking and howling; and more a-coming; you\
could see them sailing over fences and around corners from everywheres.\
\
A nigger woman come tearing out of the kitchen with a rolling-pin in her\
hand, singing out, \'93Begone _you_ Tige! you Spot! begone sah!\'94 and she\
fetched first one and then another of them a clip and sent them howling,\
and then the rest followed; and the next second half of them come back,\
wagging their tails around me, and making friends with me. \'a0There ain\'92t\
no harm in a hound, nohow.\
\
And behind the woman comes a little nigger girl and two little nigger\
boys without anything on but tow-linen shirts, and they hung on to their\
mother\'92s gown, and peeped out from behind her at me, bashful, the way\
they always do. \'a0And here comes the white woman running from the house,\
about forty-five or fifty year old, bareheaded, and her spinning-stick\
in her hand; and behind her comes her little white children, acting the\
same way the little niggers was doing. \'a0She was smiling all over so she\
could hardly stand--and says:\
\
\'93It\'92s _you_, at last!--_ain\'92t_ it?\'94\
\
I out with a \'93Yes\'92m\'94 before I thought.\
\
She grabbed me and hugged me tight; and then gripped me by both hands\
and shook and shook; and the tears come in her eyes, and run down over;\
and she couldn\'92t seem to hug and shake enough, and kept saying, \'93You\
don\'92t look as much like your mother as I reckoned you would; but law\
sakes, I don\'92t care for that, I\'92m so glad to see you! \'a0Dear, dear, it\
does seem like I could eat you up! \'a0Children, it\'92s your cousin Tom!--tell\
him howdy.\'94\
\
But they ducked their heads, and put their fingers in their mouths, and\
hid behind her. \'a0So she run on:\
\
\'93Lize, hurry up and get him a hot breakfast right away--or did you get\
your breakfast on the boat?\'94\
\
I said I had got it on the boat. \'a0So then she started for the house,\
leading me by the hand, and the children tagging after. \'a0When we got\
there she set me down in a split-bottomed chair, and set herself down on\
a little low stool in front of me, holding both of my hands, and says:\
\
\'93Now I can have a _good_ look at you; and, laws-a-me, I\'92ve been hungry\
for it a many and a many a time, all these long years, and it\'92s come\
at last! We been expecting you a couple of days and more. \'a0What kep\'92\
you?--boat get aground?\'94\
\
\'93Yes\'92m--she--\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t say yes\'92m--say Aunt Sally. \'a0Where\'92d she get aground?\'94\
\
I didn\'92t rightly know what to say, because I didn\'92t know whether the\
boat would be coming up the river or down. \'a0But I go a good deal on\
instinct; and my instinct said she would be coming up--from down towards\
Orleans. That didn\'92t help me much, though; for I didn\'92t know the names\
of bars down that way. \'a0I see I\'92d got to invent a bar, or forget the\
name of the one we got aground on--or--Now I struck an idea, and fetched\
it out:\
\
\'93It warn\'92t the grounding--that didn\'92t keep us back but a little. \'a0We\
blowed out a cylinder-head.\'94\
\
\'93Good gracious! anybody hurt?\'94\
\
\'93No\'92m. \'a0Killed a nigger.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it\'92s lucky; because sometimes people do get hurt. \'a0Two years ago\
last Christmas your uncle Silas was coming up from Newrleans on the old\
Lally Rook, and she blowed out a cylinder-head and crippled a man. \'a0And\
I think he died afterwards. \'a0He was a Baptist. \'a0Your uncle Silas knowed\
a family in Baton Rouge that knowed his people very well. \'a0Yes, I\
remember now, he _did_ die. \'a0Mortification set in, and they had to\
amputate him. But it didn\'92t save him. \'a0Yes, it was mortification--that\
was it. \'a0He turned blue all over, and died in the hope of a glorious\
resurrection. They say he was a sight to look at. \'a0Your uncle\'92s been up\
to the town every day to fetch you. And he\'92s gone again, not more\'92n an\
hour ago; he\'92ll be back any minute now. You must a met him on the road,\
didn\'92t you?--oldish man, with a--\'94\
\
\'93No, I didn\'92t see nobody, Aunt Sally. \'a0The boat landed just at daylight,\
and I left my baggage on the wharf-boat and went looking around the town\
and out a piece in the country, to put in the time and not get here too\
soon; and so I come down the back way.\'94\
\
\'93Who\'92d you give the baggage to?\'94\
\
\'93Nobody.\'94\
\
\'93Why, child, it \'91ll be stole!\'94\
\
\'93Not where I hid it I reckon it won\'92t,\'94 I says.\
\
\'93How\'92d you get your breakfast so early on the boat?\'94\
\
It was kinder thin ice, but I says:\
\
\'93The captain see me standing around, and told me I better have something\
to eat before I went ashore; so he took me in the texas to the officers\'92\
lunch, and give me all I wanted.\'94\
\
I was getting so uneasy I couldn\'92t listen good. \'a0I had my mind on the\
children all the time; I wanted to get them out to one side and pump\
them a little, and find out who I was. \'a0But I couldn\'92t get no show, Mrs.\
Phelps kept it up and run on so. \'a0Pretty soon she made the cold chills\
streak all down my back, because she says:\
\
\'93But here we\'92re a-running on this way, and you hain\'92t told me a word\
about Sis, nor any of them. \'a0Now I\'92ll rest my works a little, and you\
start up yourn; just tell me _everything_--tell me all about \'91m all every\
one of \'91m; and how they are, and what they\'92re doing, and what they told\
you to tell me; and every last thing you can think of.\'94\
\
Well, I see I was up a stump--and up it good. \'a0Providence had stood by\
me this fur all right, but I was hard and tight aground now. \'a0I see it\
warn\'92t a bit of use to try to go ahead--I\'92d got to throw up my hand. \'a0So\
I says to myself, here\'92s another place where I got to resk the truth.\
\'a0I opened my mouth to begin; but she grabbed me and hustled me in behind\
the bed, and says:\
\
\'93Here he comes! \'a0Stick your head down lower--there, that\'92ll do; you can\'92t\
be seen now. \'a0Don\'92t you let on you\'92re here. \'a0I\'92ll play a joke on him.\
Children, don\'92t you say a word.\'94\
\
I see I was in a fix now. \'a0But it warn\'92t no use to worry; there warn\'92t\
nothing to do but just hold still, and try and be ready to stand from\
under when the lightning struck.\
\
I had just one little glimpse of the old gentleman when he come in; then\
the bed hid him. \'a0Mrs. Phelps she jumps for him, and says:\
\
\'93Has he come?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says her husband.\
\
\'93Good-_ness_ gracious!\'94 she says, \'93what in the warld can have become of\
him?\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t imagine,\'94 says the old gentleman; \'93and I must say it makes me\
dreadful uneasy.\'94\
\
\'93Uneasy!\'94 she says; \'93I\'92m ready to go distracted! \'a0He _must_ a come; and\
you\'92ve missed him along the road. \'a0I _know_ it\'92s so--something tells me\
so.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Sally, I _couldn\'92t_ miss him along the road--_you_ know that.\'94\
\
\'93But oh, dear, dear, what _will_ Sis say! \'a0He must a come! \'a0You must a\
missed him. \'a0He--\'94\
\
\'93Oh, don\'92t distress me any more\'92n I\'92m already distressed. \'a0I don\'92t know\
what in the world to make of it. \'a0I\'92m at my wit\'92s end, and I don\'92t mind\
acknowledging \'91t I\'92m right down scared. \'a0But there\'92s no hope that he\'92s\
come; for he _couldn\'92t_ come and me miss him. \'a0Sally, it\'92s terrible--just\
terrible--something\'92s happened to the boat, sure!\'94\
\
\'93Why, Silas! \'a0Look yonder!--up the road!--ain\'92t that somebody coming?\'94\
\
He sprung to the window at the head of the bed, and that give Mrs.\
Phelps the chance she wanted. \'a0She stooped down quick at the foot of the\
bed and give me a pull, and out I come; and when he turned back from the\
window there she stood, a-beaming and a-smiling like a house afire, and\
I standing pretty meek and sweaty alongside. \'a0The old gentleman stared,\
and says:\
\
\'93Why, who\'92s that?\'94\
\
\'93Who do you reckon \'91t is?\'94\
\
\'93I hain\'92t no idea. \'a0Who _is_ it?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s _Tom Sawyer!_\'94\
\
By jings, I most slumped through the floor! \'a0But there warn\'92t no time to\
swap knives; the old man grabbed me by the hand and shook, and kept on\
shaking; and all the time how the woman did dance around and laugh and\
cry; and then how they both did fire off questions about Sid, and Mary,\
and the rest of the tribe.\
\
But if they was joyful, it warn\'92t nothing to what I was; for it was like\
being born again, I was so glad to find out who I was. \'a0Well, they froze\
to me for two hours; and at last, when my chin was so tired it couldn\'92t\
hardly go any more, I had told them more about my family--I mean the\
Sawyer family--than ever happened to any six Sawyer families. \'a0And I\
explained all about how we blowed out a cylinder-head at the mouth of\
White River, and it took us three days to fix it. \'a0Which was all right,\
and worked first-rate; because _they_ didn\'92t know but what it would take\
three days to fix it. \'a0If I\'92d a called it a bolthead it would a done\
just as well.\
\
Now I was feeling pretty comfortable all down one side, and pretty\
uncomfortable all up the other. \'a0Being Tom Sawyer was easy and\
comfortable, and it stayed easy and comfortable till by and by I hear a\
steamboat coughing along down the river. \'a0Then I says to myself, s\'92pose\
Tom Sawyer comes down on that boat? \'a0And s\'92pose he steps in here any\
minute, and sings out my name before I can throw him a wink to keep\
quiet?\
\
Well, I couldn\'92t _have_ it that way; it wouldn\'92t do at all. \'a0I must go\
up the road and waylay him. \'a0So I told the folks I reckoned I would go\
up to the town and fetch down my baggage. \'a0The old gentleman was for\
going along with me, but I said no, I could drive the horse myself, and\
I druther he wouldn\'92t take no trouble about me.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXIII.\
\
SO I started for town in the wagon, and when I was half-way I see a\
wagon coming, and sure enough it was Tom Sawyer, and I stopped and\
waited till he come along. \'a0I says \'93Hold on!\'94 and it stopped alongside,\
and his mouth opened up like a trunk, and stayed so; and he swallowed\
two or three times like a person that\'92s got a dry throat, and then says:\
\
\'93I hain\'92t ever done you no harm. \'a0You know that. \'a0So, then, what you\
want to come back and ha\'92nt _me_ for?\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93I hain\'92t come back--I hain\'92t been _gone_.\'94\
\
When he heard my voice it righted him up some, but he warn\'92t quite\
satisfied yet. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t you play nothing on me, because I wouldn\'92t on you. \'a0Honest injun\
now, you ain\'92t a ghost?\'94\
\
\'93Honest injun, I ain\'92t,\'94 I says.\
\
\'93Well--I--I--well, that ought to settle it, of course; but I can\'92t somehow\
seem to understand it no way. \'a0Looky here, warn\'92t you ever murdered _at\
all?_\'94\
\
\'93No. \'a0I warn\'92t ever murdered at all--I played it on them. \'a0You come in\
here and feel of me if you don\'92t believe me.\'94\
\
So he done it; and it satisfied him; and he was that glad to see me\
again he didn\'92t know what to do. \'a0And he wanted to know all about it\
right off, because it was a grand adventure, and mysterious, and so it\
hit him where he lived. \'a0But I said, leave it alone till by and by; and\
told his driver to wait, and we drove off a little piece, and I told\
him the kind of a fix I was in, and what did he reckon we better do? \'a0He\
said, let him alone a minute, and don\'92t disturb him. \'a0So he thought and\
thought, and pretty soon he says:\
\
\'93It\'92s all right; I\'92ve got it. \'a0Take my trunk in your wagon, and let on\
it\'92s your\'92n; and you turn back and fool along slow, so as to get to the\
house about the time you ought to; and I\'92ll go towards town a piece, and\
take a fresh start, and get there a quarter or a half an hour after you;\
and you needn\'92t let on to know me at first.\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93All right; but wait a minute. \'a0There\'92s one more thing--a thing that\
_nobody_ don\'92t know but me. \'a0And that is, there\'92s a nigger here that\
I\'92m a-trying to steal out of slavery, and his name is _Jim_--old Miss\
Watson\'92s Jim.\'94\
\
He says:\
\
\'93What! \'a0Why, Jim is--\'94\
\
He stopped and went to studying. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93I know what you\'92ll say. \'a0You\'92ll say it\'92s dirty, low-down business; but\
what if it is? \'a0I\'92m low down; and I\'92m a-going to steal him, and I want\
you keep mum and not let on. \'a0Will you?\'94\
\
His eye lit up, and he says:\
\
\'93I\'92ll _help_ you steal him!\'94\
\
Well, I let go all holts then, like I was shot. \'a0It was the most\
astonishing speech I ever heard--and I\'92m bound to say Tom Sawyer fell\
considerable in my estimation. \'a0Only I couldn\'92t believe it. \'a0Tom Sawyer\
a _nigger-stealer!_\
\
\'93Oh, shucks!\'94 \'a0I says; \'93you\'92re joking.\'94\
\
\'93I ain\'92t joking, either.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then,\'94 I says, \'93joking or no joking, if you hear anything said\
about a runaway nigger, don\'92t forget to remember that _you_ don\'92t know\
nothing about him, and I don\'92t know nothing about him.\'94\
\
Then we took the trunk and put it in my wagon, and he drove off his\
way and I drove mine. \'a0But of course I forgot all about driving slow on\
accounts of being glad and full of thinking; so I got home a heap too\
quick for that length of a trip. \'a0The old gentleman was at the door, and\
he says:\
\
\'93Why, this is wonderful! \'a0Whoever would a thought it was in that mare\
to do it? \'a0I wish we\'92d a timed her. \'a0And she hain\'92t sweated a hair--not\
a hair. It\'92s wonderful. \'a0Why, I wouldn\'92t take a hundred dollars for that\
horse now--I wouldn\'92t, honest; and yet I\'92d a sold her for fifteen before,\
and thought \'91twas all she was worth.\'94\
\
That\'92s all he said. \'a0He was the innocentest, best old soul I ever see.\
But it warn\'92t surprising; because he warn\'92t only just a farmer, he was\
a preacher, too, and had a little one-horse log church down back of the\
plantation, which he built it himself at his own expense, for a church\
and schoolhouse, and never charged nothing for his preaching, and it was\
worth it, too. \'a0There was plenty other farmer-preachers like that, and\
done the same way, down South.\
\
In about half an hour Tom\'92s wagon drove up to the front stile, and Aunt\
Sally she see it through the window, because it was only about fifty\
yards, and says:\
\
\'93Why, there\'92s somebody come! \'a0I wonder who \'91tis? \'a0Why, I do believe it\'92s\
a stranger. \'a0Jimmy\'94 (that\'92s one of the children) \'93run and tell Lize to\
put on another plate for dinner.\'94\
\
Everybody made a rush for the front door, because, of course, a stranger\
don\'92t come _every_ year, and so he lays over the yaller-fever, for\
interest, when he does come. \'a0Tom was over the stile and starting for\
the house; the wagon was spinning up the road for the village, and we\
was all bunched in the front door. \'a0Tom had his store clothes on, and an\
audience--and that was always nuts for Tom Sawyer. \'a0In them circumstances\
it warn\'92t no trouble to him to throw in an amount of style that was\
suitable. \'a0He warn\'92t a boy to meeky along up that yard like a sheep; no,\
he come ca\'92m and important, like the ram. \'a0When he got a-front of us he\
lifts his hat ever so gracious and dainty, like it was the lid of a box\
that had butterflies asleep in it and he didn\'92t want to disturb them,\
and says:\
\
\'93Mr. Archibald Nichols, I presume?\'94\
\
\'93No, my boy,\'94 says the old gentleman, \'93I\'92m sorry to say \'91t your driver\
has deceived you; Nichols\'92s place is down a matter of three mile more.\
Come in, come in.\'94\
\
Tom he took a look back over his shoulder, and says, \'93Too late--he\'92s out\
of sight.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, he\'92s gone, my son, and you must come in and eat your dinner with\
us; and then we\'92ll hitch up and take you down to Nichols\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I _can\'92t_ make you so much trouble; I couldn\'92t think of it. \'a0I\'92ll\
walk--I don\'92t mind the distance.\'94\
\
\'93But we won\'92t _let_ you walk--it wouldn\'92t be Southern hospitality to do\
it. Come right in.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, _do_,\'94 says Aunt Sally; \'93it ain\'92t a bit of trouble to us, not a\
bit in the world. \'a0You must stay. \'a0It\'92s a long, dusty three mile, and\
we can\'92t let you walk. \'a0And, besides, I\'92ve already told \'91em to put on\
another plate when I see you coming; so you mustn\'92t disappoint us. \'a0Come\
right in and make yourself at home.\'94\
\
So Tom he thanked them very hearty and handsome, and let himself be\
persuaded, and come in; and when he was in he said he was a stranger\
from Hicksville, Ohio, and his name was William Thompson--and he made\
another bow.\
\
Well, he run on, and on, and on, making up stuff about Hicksville and\
everybody in it he could invent, and I getting a little nervious, and\
wondering how this was going to help me out of my scrape; and at last,\
still talking along, he reached over and kissed Aunt Sally right on the\
mouth, and then settled back again in his chair comfortable, and was\
going on talking; but she jumped up and wiped it off with the back of\
her hand, and says:\
\
\'93You owdacious puppy!\'94\
\
He looked kind of hurt, and says:\
\
\'93I\'92m surprised at you, m\'92am.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re s\'92rp--Why, what do you reckon I am? \'a0I\'92ve a good notion to take\
and--Say, what do you mean by kissing me?\'94\
\
He looked kind of humble, and says:\
\
\'93I didn\'92t mean nothing, m\'92am. \'a0I didn\'92t mean no harm. \'a0I--I--thought you\'92d\
like it.\'94\
\
\'93Why, you born fool!\'94 \'a0She took up the spinning stick, and it looked\
like it was all she could do to keep from giving him a crack with it.\
 \'93What made you think I\'92d like it?\'94\
\
\'93Well, I don\'92t know. \'a0Only, they--they--told me you would.\'94\
\
\'93_They_ told you I would. \'a0Whoever told you\'92s _another_ lunatic. \'a0I\
never heard the beat of it. \'a0Who\'92s _they_?\'94\
\
\'93Why, everybody. \'a0They all said so, m\'92am.\'94\
\
It was all she could do to hold in; and her eyes snapped, and her\
fingers worked like she wanted to scratch him; and she says:\
\
\'93Who\'92s \'91everybody\'92? \'a0Out with their names, or ther\'92ll be an idiot\
short.\'94\
\
He got up and looked distressed, and fumbled his hat, and says:\
\
\'93I\'92m sorry, and I warn\'92t expecting it. \'a0They told me to. \'a0They all told\
me to. \'a0They all said, kiss her; and said she\'92d like it. \'a0They all said\
it--every one of them. \'a0But I\'92m sorry, m\'92am, and I won\'92t do it no more--I\
won\'92t, honest.\'94\
\
\'93You won\'92t, won\'92t you? \'a0Well, I sh\'92d _reckon_ you won\'92t!\'94\
\
\'93No\'92m, I\'92m honest about it; I won\'92t ever do it again--till you ask me.\'94\
\
\'93Till I _ask_ you! \'a0Well, I never see the beat of it in my born days!\
\'a0I lay you\'92ll be the Methusalem-numskull of creation before ever I ask\
you--or the likes of you.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93it does surprise me so. \'a0I can\'92t make it out, somehow.\
They said you would, and I thought you would. \'a0But--\'94 He stopped and\
looked around slow, like he wished he could run across a friendly eye\
somewheres, and fetched up on the old gentleman\'92s, and says, \'93Didn\'92t\
_you_ think she\'92d like me to kiss her, sir?\'94\
\
\'93Why, no; I--I--well, no, I b\'92lieve I didn\'92t.\'94\
\
Then he looks on around the same way to me, and says:\
\
\'93Tom, didn\'92t _you_ think Aunt Sally \'91d open out her arms and say, \'91Sid\
Sawyer--\'92\'94\
\
\'93My land!\'94 she says, breaking in and jumping for him, \'93you impudent\
young rascal, to fool a body so--\'94 and was going to hug him, but he\
fended her off, and says:\
\
\'93No, not till you\'92ve asked me first.\'94\
\
So she didn\'92t lose no time, but asked him; and hugged him and kissed\
him over and over again, and then turned him over to the old man, and he\
took what was left. \'a0And after they got a little quiet again she says:\
\
\'93Why, dear me, I never see such a surprise. \'a0We warn\'92t looking for _you_\
at all, but only Tom. \'a0Sis never wrote to me about anybody coming but\
him.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s because it warn\'92t _intended_ for any of us to come but Tom,\'94 he\
says; \'93but I begged and begged, and at the last minute she let me\
come, too; so, coming down the river, me and Tom thought it would be a\
first-rate surprise for him to come here to the house first, and for me\
to by and by tag along and drop in, and let on to be a stranger. \'a0But it\
was a mistake, Aunt Sally. \'a0This ain\'92t no healthy place for a stranger\
to come.\'94\
\
\'93No--not impudent whelps, Sid. \'a0You ought to had your jaws boxed; I\
hain\'92t been so put out since I don\'92t know when. \'a0But I don\'92t care, I\
don\'92t mind the terms--I\'92d be willing to stand a thousand such jokes to\
have you here. Well, to think of that performance! \'a0I don\'92t deny it, I\
was most putrified with astonishment when you give me that smack.\'94\
\
We had dinner out in that broad open passage betwixt the house and\
the kitchen; and there was things enough on that table for seven\
families--and all hot, too; none of your flabby, tough meat that\'92s laid\
in a cupboard in a damp cellar all night and tastes like a hunk of\
old cold cannibal in the morning. \'a0Uncle Silas he asked a pretty long\
blessing over it, but it was worth it; and it didn\'92t cool it a bit,\
neither, the way I\'92ve seen them kind of interruptions do lots of times.\
\'a0There was a considerable good deal of talk all the afternoon, and me\
and Tom was on the lookout all the time; but it warn\'92t no use, they\
didn\'92t happen to say nothing about any runaway nigger, and we was afraid\
to try to work up to it. \'a0But at supper, at night, one of the little\
boys says:\
\
\'93Pa, mayn\'92t Tom and Sid and me go to the show?\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 says the old man, \'93I reckon there ain\'92t going to be any; and you\
couldn\'92t go if there was; because the runaway nigger told Burton and\
me all about that scandalous show, and Burton said he would tell the\
people; so I reckon they\'92ve drove the owdacious loafers out of town\
before this time.\'94\
\
So there it was!--but I couldn\'92t help it. \'a0Tom and me was to sleep in the\
same room and bed; so, being tired, we bid good-night and went up to\
bed right after supper, and clumb out of the window and down the\
lightning-rod, and shoved for the town; for I didn\'92t believe anybody was\
going to give the king and the duke a hint, and so if I didn\'92t hurry up\
and give them one they\'92d get into trouble sure.\
\
On the road Tom he told me all about how it was reckoned I was murdered,\
and how pap disappeared pretty soon, and didn\'92t come back no more, and\
what a stir there was when Jim run away; and I told Tom all about our\
Royal Nonesuch rapscallions, and as much of the raft voyage as I had\
time to; and as we struck into the town and up through the the middle of\
it--it was as much as half-after eight, then--here comes a raging rush of\
people with torches, and an awful whooping and yelling, and banging tin\
pans and blowing horns; and we jumped to one side to let them go by;\
and as they went by I see they had the king and the duke astraddle of a\
rail--that is, I knowed it _was_ the king and the duke, though they was\
all over tar and feathers, and didn\'92t look like nothing in the\
world that was human--just looked like a couple of monstrous big\
soldier-plumes. \'a0Well, it made me sick to see it; and I was sorry for\
them poor pitiful rascals, it seemed like I couldn\'92t ever feel any\
hardness against them any more in the world. \'a0It was a dreadful thing to\
see. \'a0Human beings _can_ be awful cruel to one another.\
\
We see we was too late--couldn\'92t do no good. \'a0We asked some stragglers\
about it, and they said everybody went to the show looking very\
innocent; and laid low and kept dark till the poor old king was in the\
middle of his cavortings on the stage; then somebody give a signal, and\
the house rose up and went for them.\
\
So we poked along back home, and I warn\'92t feeling so brash as I was\
before, but kind of ornery, and humble, and to blame, somehow--though\
I hadn\'92t done nothing. \'a0But that\'92s always the way; it don\'92t make no\
difference whether you do right or wrong, a person\'92s conscience ain\'92t\
got no sense, and just goes for him anyway. \'a0If I had a yaller dog that\
didn\'92t know no more than a person\'92s conscience does I would pison him.\
It takes up more room than all the rest of a person\'92s insides, and yet\
ain\'92t no good, nohow. \'a0Tom Sawyer he says the same.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXIV.\
\
WE stopped talking, and got to thinking. \'a0By and by Tom says:\
\
\'93Looky here, Huck, what fools we are to not think of it before! \'a0I bet I\
know where Jim is.\'94\
\
\'93No! \'a0Where?\'94\
\
\'93In that hut down by the ash-hopper. \'a0Why, looky here. \'a0When we was at\
dinner, didn\'92t you see a nigger man go in there with some vittles?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93What did you think the vittles was for?\'94\
\
\'93For a dog.\'94\
\
\'93So \'91d I. Well, it wasn\'92t for a dog.\'94\
\
\'93Why?\'94\
\
\'93Because part of it was watermelon.\'94\
\
\'93So it was--I noticed it. \'a0Well, it does beat all that I never thought\
about a dog not eating watermelon. \'a0It shows how a body can see and\
don\'92t see at the same time.\'94\
\
\'93Well, the nigger unlocked the padlock when he went in, and he locked it\
again when he came out. \'a0He fetched uncle a key about the time we got up\
from table--same key, I bet. \'a0Watermelon shows man, lock shows prisoner;\
and it ain\'92t likely there\'92s two prisoners on such a little plantation,\
and where the people\'92s all so kind and good. \'a0Jim\'92s the prisoner. \'a0All\
right--I\'92m glad we found it out detective fashion; I wouldn\'92t give shucks\
for any other way. \'a0Now you work your mind, and study out a plan to\
steal Jim, and I will study out one, too; and we\'92ll take the one we like\
the best.\'94\
\
What a head for just a boy to have! \'a0If I had Tom Sawyer\'92s head I\
wouldn\'92t trade it off to be a duke, nor mate of a steamboat, nor clown\
in a circus, nor nothing I can think of. \'a0I went to thinking out a plan,\
but only just to be doing something; I knowed very well where the right\
plan was going to come from. \'a0Pretty soon Tom says:\
\
\'93Ready?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I says.\
\
\'93All right--bring it out.\'94\
\
\'93My plan is this,\'94 I says.  \'93We can easy find out if it\'92s Jim in there.\
Then get up my canoe to-morrow night, and fetch my raft over from the\
island. \'a0Then the first dark night that comes steal the key out of the\
old man\'92s britches after he goes to bed, and shove off down the river\
on the raft with Jim, hiding daytimes and running nights, the way me and\
Jim used to do before. \'a0Wouldn\'92t that plan work?\'94\
\
\'93_Work_? \'a0Why, cert\'92nly it would work, like rats a-fighting. \'a0But it\'92s\
too blame\'92 simple; there ain\'92t nothing _to_ it. \'a0What\'92s the good of a\
plan that ain\'92t no more trouble than that? \'a0It\'92s as mild as goose-milk.\
\'a0Why, Huck, it wouldn\'92t make no more talk than breaking into a soap\
factory.\'94\
\
I never said nothing, because I warn\'92t expecting nothing different; but\
I knowed mighty well that whenever he got _his_ plan ready it wouldn\'92t\
have none of them objections to it.\
\
And it didn\'92t. \'a0He told me what it was, and I see in a minute it was\
worth fifteen of mine for style, and would make Jim just as free a man\
as mine would, and maybe get us all killed besides. \'a0So I was satisfied,\
and said we would waltz in on it. \'a0I needn\'92t tell what it was here,\
because I knowed it wouldn\'92t stay the way, it was. \'a0I knowed he would be\
changing it around every which way as we went along, and heaving in new\
bullinesses wherever he got a chance. \'a0And that is what he done.\
\
Well, one thing was dead sure, and that was that Tom Sawyer was in\
earnest, and was actuly going to help steal that nigger out of slavery.\
That was the thing that was too many for me. \'a0Here was a boy that was\
respectable and well brung up; and had a character to lose; and folks at\
home that had characters; and he was bright and not leather-headed; and\
knowing and not ignorant; and not mean, but kind; and yet here he was,\
without any more pride, or rightness, or feeling, than to stoop to\
this business, and make himself a shame, and his family a shame,\
before everybody. \'a0I _couldn\'92t_ understand it no way at all. \'a0It was\
outrageous, and I knowed I ought to just up and tell him so; and so be\
his true friend, and let him quit the thing right where he was and save\
himself. And I _did_ start to tell him; but he shut me up, and says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t you reckon I know what I\'92m about? \'a0Don\'92t I generly know what I\'92m\
about?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t I _say_ I was going to help steal the nigger?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93_Well_, then.\'94\
\
That\'92s all he said, and that\'92s all I said. \'a0It warn\'92t no use to say any\
more; because when he said he\'92d do a thing, he always done it. \'a0But I\
couldn\'92t make out how he was willing to go into this thing; so I just\
let it go, and never bothered no more about it. \'a0If he was bound to have\
it so, I couldn\'92t help it.\
\
When we got home the house was all dark and still; so we went on down to\
the hut by the ash-hopper for to examine it. \'a0We went through the yard\
so as to see what the hounds would do. \'a0They knowed us, and didn\'92t make\
no more noise than country dogs is always doing when anything comes by\
in the night. \'a0When we got to the cabin we took a look at the front and\
the two sides; and on the side I warn\'92t acquainted with--which was the\
north side--we found a square window-hole, up tolerable high, with just\
one stout board nailed across it. \'a0I says:\
\
\'93Here\'92s the ticket. \'a0This hole\'92s big enough for Jim to get through if we\
wrench off the board.\'94\
\
Tom says:\
\
\'93It\'92s as simple as tit-tat-toe, three-in-a-row, and as easy as\
playing hooky. \'a0I should _hope_ we can find a way that\'92s a little more\
complicated than _that_, Huck Finn.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then,\'94 I says, \'93how \'91ll it do to saw him out, the way I done\
before I was murdered that time?\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s more _like_,\'94 he says.  \'93It\'92s real mysterious, and troublesome,\
and good,\'94 he says; \'93but I bet we can find a way that\'92s twice as long.\
\'a0There ain\'92t no hurry; le\'92s keep on looking around.\'94\
\
Betwixt the hut and the fence, on the back side, was a lean-to that\
joined the hut at the eaves, and was made out of plank. \'a0It was as long\
as the hut, but narrow--only about six foot wide. \'a0The door to it was at\
the south end, and was padlocked. \'a0Tom he went to the soap-kettle and\
searched around, and fetched back the iron thing they lift the lid with;\
so he took it and prized out one of the staples. \'a0The chain fell down,\
and we opened the door and went in, and shut it, and struck a match,\
and see the shed was only built against a cabin and hadn\'92t no connection\
with it; and there warn\'92t no floor to the shed, nor nothing in it but\
some old rusty played-out hoes and spades and picks and a crippled plow.\
\'a0The match went out, and so did we, and shoved in the staple again, and\
the door was locked as good as ever. Tom was joyful. \'a0He says;\
\
\'93Now we\'92re all right. \'a0We\'92ll _dig_ him out. \'a0It \'91ll take about a week!\'94\
\
Then we started for the house, and I went in the back door--you only have\
to pull a buckskin latch-string, they don\'92t fasten the doors--but that\
warn\'92t romantical enough for Tom Sawyer; no way would do him but he must\
climb up the lightning-rod. \'a0But after he got up half way about three\
times, and missed fire and fell every time, and the last time most\
busted his brains out, he thought he\'92d got to give it up; but after he\
was rested he allowed he would give her one more turn for luck, and this\
time he made the trip.\
\
In the morning we was up at break of day, and down to the nigger cabins\
to pet the dogs and make friends with the nigger that fed Jim--if it\
_was_ Jim that was being fed. \'a0The niggers was just getting through\
breakfast and starting for the fields; and Jim\'92s nigger was piling up\
a tin pan with bread and meat and things; and whilst the others was\
leaving, the key come from the house.\
\
This nigger had a good-natured, chuckle-headed face, and his wool was\
all tied up in little bunches with thread. \'a0That was to keep witches\
off. \'a0He said the witches was pestering him awful these nights, and\
making him see all kinds of strange things, and hear all kinds of\
strange words and noises, and he didn\'92t believe he was ever witched so\
long before in his life. \'a0He got so worked up, and got to running on so\
about his troubles, he forgot all about what he\'92d been a-going to do.\
\'a0So Tom says:\
\
\'93What\'92s the vittles for? \'a0Going to feed the dogs?\'94\
\
The nigger kind of smiled around gradually over his face, like when you\
heave a brickbat in a mud-puddle, and he says:\
\
\'93Yes, Mars Sid, A dog. \'a0Cur\'92us dog, too. \'a0Does you want to go en look at\
\'91im?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
I hunched Tom, and whispers:\
\
\'93You going, right here in the daybreak? \'a0_that_ warn\'92t the plan.\'94\
\
\'93No, it warn\'92t; but it\'92s the plan _now_.\'94\
\
So, drat him, we went along, but I didn\'92t like it much. \'a0When we got in\
we couldn\'92t hardly see anything, it was so dark; but Jim was there, sure\
enough, and could see us; and he sings out:\
\
\'93Why, _Huck_! \'a0En good _lan_\'92! ain\'92 dat Misto Tom?\'94\
\
I just knowed how it would be; I just expected it. \'a0I didn\'92t know\
nothing to do; and if I had I couldn\'92t a done it, because that nigger\
busted in and says:\
\
\'93Why, de gracious sakes! do he know you genlmen?\'94\
\
We could see pretty well now. \'a0Tom he looked at the nigger, steady and\
kind of wondering, and says:\
\
\'93Does _who_ know us?\'94\
\
\'93Why, dis-yer runaway nigger.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t reckon he does; but what put that into your head?\'94\
\
\'93What _put_ it dar? \'a0Didn\'92 he jis\'92 dis minute sing out like he knowed\
you?\'94\
\
Tom says, in a puzzled-up kind of way:\
\
\'93Well, that\'92s mighty curious. \'a0_Who_ sung out? _when_ did he sing out?\
\'a0_what_ did he sing out?\'94 And turns to me, perfectly ca\'92m, and says,\
\'93Did _you_ hear anybody sing out?\'94\
\
Of course there warn\'92t nothing to be said but the one thing; so I says:\
\
\'93No; I ain\'92t heard nobody say nothing.\'94\
\
Then he turns to Jim, and looks him over like he never see him before,\
and says:\
\
\'93Did you sing out?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah,\'94 says Jim; \'93I hain\'92t said nothing, sah.\'94\
\
\'93Not a word?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah, I hain\'92t said a word.\'94\
\
\'93Did you ever see us before?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah; not as I knows on.\'94\
\
So Tom turns to the nigger, which was looking wild and distressed, and\
says, kind of severe:\
\
\'93What do you reckon\'92s the matter with you, anyway? \'a0What made you think\
somebody sung out?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, it\'92s de dad-blame\'92 witches, sah, en I wisht I was dead, I do.\
\'a0Dey\'92s awluz at it, sah, en dey do mos\'92 kill me, dey sk\'92yers me so.\
\'a0Please to don\'92t tell nobody \'91bout it sah, er ole Mars Silas he\'92ll scole\
me; \'91kase he say dey _ain\'92t_ no witches. \'a0I jis\'92 wish to goodness he was\
heah now--_den_ what would he say! \'a0I jis\'92 bet he couldn\'92 fine no way to\
git aroun\'92 it _dis_ time. \'a0But it\'92s awluz jis\'92 so; people dat\'92s _sot_,\
stays sot; dey won\'92t look into noth\'92n\'92en fine it out f\'92r deyselves, en\
when _you_ fine it out en tell um \'91bout it, dey doan\'92 b\'92lieve you.\'94\
\
Tom give him a dime, and said we wouldn\'92t tell nobody; and told him to\
buy some more thread to tie up his wool with; and then looks at Jim, and\
says:\
\
\'93I wonder if Uncle Silas is going to hang this nigger. \'a0If I was to\
catch a nigger that was ungrateful enough to run away, I wouldn\'92t give\
him up, I\'92d hang him.\'94 \'a0And whilst the nigger stepped to the door to\
look at the dime and bite it to see if it was good, he whispers to Jim\
and says:\
\
\'93Don\'92t ever let on to know us. \'a0And if you hear any digging going on\
nights, it\'92s us; we\'92re going to set you free.\'94\
\
Jim only had time to grab us by the hand and squeeze it; then the nigger\
come back, and we said we\'92d come again some time if the nigger wanted\
us to; and he said he would, more particular if it was dark, because the\
witches went for him mostly in the dark, and it was good to have folks\
around then.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXV.\
\
IT would be most an hour yet till breakfast, so we left and struck down\
into the woods; because Tom said we got to have _some_ light to see how\
to dig by, and a lantern makes too much, and might get us into trouble;\
what we must have was a lot of them rotten chunks that\'92s called\
fox-fire, and just makes a soft kind of a glow when you lay them in a\
dark place. \'a0We fetched an armful and hid it in the weeds, and set down\
to rest, and Tom says, kind of dissatisfied:\
\
\'93Blame it, this whole thing is just as easy and awkward as it can be.\
And so it makes it so rotten difficult to get up a difficult plan.\
\'a0There ain\'92t no watchman to be drugged--now there _ought_ to be a\
watchman. \'a0There ain\'92t even a dog to give a sleeping-mixture to. \'a0And\
there\'92s Jim chained by one leg, with a ten-foot chain, to the leg of his\
bed: \'a0why, all you got to do is to lift up the bedstead and slip off\
the chain. \'a0And Uncle Silas he trusts everybody; sends the key to the\
punkin-headed nigger, and don\'92t send nobody to watch the nigger. \'a0Jim\
could a got out of that window-hole before this, only there wouldn\'92t be\
no use trying to travel with a ten-foot chain on his leg. \'a0Why, drat it,\
Huck, it\'92s the stupidest arrangement I ever see. You got to invent _all_\
the difficulties. \'a0Well, we can\'92t help it; we got to do the best we can\
with the materials we\'92ve got. Anyhow, there\'92s one thing--there\'92s more\
honor in getting him out through a lot of difficulties and dangers,\
where there warn\'92t one of them furnished to you by the people who it was\
their duty to furnish them, and you had to contrive them all out of your\
own head. \'a0Now look at just that one thing of the lantern. \'a0When you\
come down to the cold facts, we simply got to _let on_ that a lantern\'92s\
resky. \'a0Why, we could work with a torchlight procession if we wanted to,\
I believe. \'a0Now, whilst I think of it, we got to hunt up something to\
make a saw out of the first chance we get.\'94\
\
\'93What do we want of a saw?\'94\
\
\'93What do we _want_ of it? \'a0Hain\'92t we got to saw the leg of Jim\'92s bed\
off, so as to get the chain loose?\'94\
\
\'93Why, you just said a body could lift up the bedstead and slip the chain\
off.\'94\
\
\'93Well, if that ain\'92t just like you, Huck Finn. \'a0You _can_ get up the\
infant-schooliest ways of going at a thing. \'a0Why, hain\'92t you ever read\
any books at all?--Baron Trenck, nor Casanova, nor Benvenuto Chelleeny,\
nor Henri IV., nor none of them heroes? \'a0Who ever heard of getting a\
prisoner loose in such an old-maidy way as that? \'a0No; the way all the\
best authorities does is to saw the bed-leg in two, and leave it just\
so, and swallow the sawdust, so it can\'92t be found, and put some dirt and\
grease around the sawed place so the very keenest seneskal can\'92t see\
no sign of it\'92s being sawed, and thinks the bed-leg is perfectly sound.\
Then, the night you\'92re ready, fetch the leg a kick, down she goes; slip\
off your chain, and there you are. \'a0Nothing to do but hitch your\
rope ladder to the battlements, shin down it, break your leg in the\
moat--because a rope ladder is nineteen foot too short, you know--and\
there\'92s your horses and your trusty vassles, and they scoop you up and\
fling you across a saddle, and away you go to your native Langudoc, or\
Navarre, or wherever it is. It\'92s gaudy, Huck. \'a0I wish there was a moat\
to this cabin. If we get time, the night of the escape, we\'92ll dig one.\'94\
\
I says:\
\
\'93What do we want of a moat when we\'92re going to snake him out from under\
the cabin?\'94\
\
But he never heard me. \'a0He had forgot me and everything else. \'a0He had\
his chin in his hand, thinking. \'a0Pretty soon he sighs and shakes his\
head; then sighs again, and says:\
\
\'93No, it wouldn\'92t do--there ain\'92t necessity enough for it.\'94\
\
\'93For what?\'94 \'a0I says.\
\
\'93Why, to saw Jim\'92s leg off,\'94 he says.\
\
\'93Good land!\'94 \'a0I says; \'93why, there ain\'92t _no_ necessity for it. \'a0And what\
would you want to saw his leg off for, anyway?\'94\
\
\'93Well, some of the best authorities has done it. \'a0They couldn\'92t get the\
chain off, so they just cut their hand off and shoved. \'a0And a leg would\
be better still. \'a0But we got to let that go. \'a0There ain\'92t necessity\
enough in this case; and, besides, Jim\'92s a nigger, and wouldn\'92t\
understand the reasons for it, and how it\'92s the custom in Europe; so\
we\'92ll let it go. \'a0But there\'92s one thing--he can have a rope ladder; we\
can tear up our sheets and make him a rope ladder easy enough. \'a0And we\
can send it to him in a pie; it\'92s mostly done that way. \'a0And I\'92ve et\
worse pies.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Tom Sawyer, how you talk,\'94 I says; \'93Jim ain\'92t got no use for a\
rope ladder.\'94\
\
\'93He _has_ got use for it. \'a0How _you_ talk, you better say; you don\'92t\
know nothing about it. \'a0He\'92s _got_ to have a rope ladder; they all do.\'94\
\
\'93What in the nation can he _do_ with it?\'94\
\
\'93_Do_ with it? \'a0He can hide it in his bed, can\'92t he?\'94 \'a0That\'92s what they\
all do; and _he\'92s_ got to, too. \'a0Huck, you don\'92t ever seem to want to do\
anything that\'92s regular; you want to be starting something fresh all the\
time. S\'92pose he _don\'92t_ do nothing with it? ain\'92t it there in his bed,\
for a clew, after he\'92s gone? and don\'92t you reckon they\'92ll want clews?\
\'a0Of course they will. \'a0And you wouldn\'92t leave them any? \'a0That would be a\
_pretty_ howdy-do, _wouldn\'92t_ it! \'a0I never heard of such a thing.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I says, \'93if it\'92s in the regulations, and he\'92s got to have\
it, all right, let him have it; because I don\'92t wish to go back on no\
regulations; but there\'92s one thing, Tom Sawyer--if we go to tearing up\
our sheets to make Jim a rope ladder, we\'92re going to get into trouble\
with Aunt Sally, just as sure as you\'92re born. \'a0Now, the way I look at\
it, a hickry-bark ladder don\'92t cost nothing, and don\'92t waste nothing,\
and is just as good to load up a pie with, and hide in a straw tick,\
as any rag ladder you can start; and as for Jim, he ain\'92t had no\
experience, and so he don\'92t care what kind of a--\'94\
\
\'93Oh, shucks, Huck Finn, if I was as ignorant as you I\'92d keep\
still--that\'92s what I\'92D do. \'a0Who ever heard of a state prisoner escaping\
by a hickry-bark ladder? \'a0Why, it\'92s perfectly ridiculous.\'94\
\
\'93Well, all right, Tom, fix it your own way; but if you\'92ll take my\
advice, you\'92ll let me borrow a sheet off of the clothesline.\'94\
\
He said that would do. \'a0And that gave him another idea, and he says:\
\
\'93Borrow a shirt, too.\'94\
\
\'93What do we want of a shirt, Tom?\'94\
\
\'93Want it for Jim to keep a journal on.\'94\
\
\'93Journal your granny--_Jim_ can\'92t write.\'94\
\
\'93S\'92pose he _can\'92t_ write--he can make marks on the shirt, can\'92t he, if\
we make him a pen out of an old pewter spoon or a piece of an old iron\
barrel-hoop?\'94\
\
\'93Why, Tom, we can pull a feather out of a goose and make him a better\
one; and quicker, too.\'94\
\
\'93_Prisoners_ don\'92t have geese running around the donjon-keep to pull\
pens out of, you muggins. \'a0They _always_ make their pens out of the\
hardest, toughest, troublesomest piece of old brass candlestick or\
something like that they can get their hands on; and it takes them weeks\
and weeks and months and months to file it out, too, because they\'92ve got\
to do it by rubbing it on the wall. \'a0_They_ wouldn\'92t use a goose-quill\
if they had it. It ain\'92t regular.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what\'92ll we make him the ink out of?\'94\
\
\'93Many makes it out of iron-rust and tears; but that\'92s the common sort\
and women; the best authorities uses their own blood. \'a0Jim can do that;\
and when he wants to send any little common ordinary mysterious message\
to let the world know where he\'92s captivated, he can write it on the\
bottom of a tin plate with a fork and throw it out of the window. \'a0The\
Iron Mask always done that, and it\'92s a blame\'92 good way, too.\'94\
\
\'93Jim ain\'92t got no tin plates. \'a0They feed him in a pan.\'94\
\
\'93That ain\'92t nothing; we can get him some.\'94\
\
\'93Can\'92t nobody _read_ his plates.\'94\
\
\'93That ain\'92t got anything to _do_ with it, Huck Finn. \'a0All _he\'92s_ got to\
do is to write on the plate and throw it out. \'a0You don\'92t _have_ to be\
able to read it. Why, half the time you can\'92t read anything a prisoner\
writes on a tin plate, or anywhere else.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what\'92s the sense in wasting the plates?\'94\
\
\'93Why, blame it all, it ain\'92t the _prisoner\'92s_ plates.\'94\
\
\'93But it\'92s _somebody\'92s_ plates, ain\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93Well, spos\'92n it is? \'a0What does the _prisoner_ care whose--\'94\
\
He broke off there, because we heard the breakfast-horn blowing. \'a0So we\
cleared out for the house.\
\
Along during the morning I borrowed a sheet and a white shirt off of the\
clothes-line; and I found an old sack and put them in it, and we went\
down and got the fox-fire, and put that in too. \'a0I called it borrowing,\
because that was what pap always called it; but Tom said it warn\'92t\
borrowing, it was stealing. \'a0He said we was representing prisoners; and\
prisoners don\'92t care how they get a thing so they get it, and nobody\
don\'92t blame them for it, either. \'a0It ain\'92t no crime in a prisoner to\
steal the thing he needs to get away with, Tom said; it\'92s his right; and\
so, as long as we was representing a prisoner, we had a perfect right to\
steal anything on this place we had the least use for to get ourselves\
out of prison with. \'a0He said if we warn\'92t prisoners it would be a very\
different thing, and nobody but a mean, ornery person would steal when\
he warn\'92t a prisoner. \'a0So we allowed we would steal everything there was\
that come handy. \'a0And yet he made a mighty fuss, one day, after that,\
when I stole a watermelon out of the nigger-patch and eat it; and he\
made me go and give the niggers a dime without telling them what it\
was for. Tom said that what he meant was, we could steal anything we\
_needed_. Well, I says, I needed the watermelon. \'a0But he said I didn\'92t\
need it to get out of prison with; there\'92s where the difference was.\
\'a0He said if I\'92d a wanted it to hide a knife in, and smuggle it to Jim\
to kill the seneskal with, it would a been all right. \'a0So I let it go at\
that, though I couldn\'92t see no advantage in my representing a prisoner\
if I got to set down and chaw over a lot of gold-leaf distinctions like\
that every time I see a chance to hog a watermelon.\
\
Well, as I was saying, we waited that morning till everybody was settled\
down to business, and nobody in sight around the yard; then Tom he\
carried the sack into the lean-to whilst I stood off a piece to keep\
watch. \'a0By and by he come out, and we went and set down on the woodpile\
to talk. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93Everything\'92s all right now except tools; and that\'92s easy fixed.\'94\
\
\'93Tools?\'94 \'a0I says.\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Tools for what?\'94\
\
\'93Why, to dig with. \'a0We ain\'92t a-going to _gnaw_ him out, are we?\'94\
\
\'93Ain\'92t them old crippled picks and things in there good enough to dig a\
nigger out with?\'94 \'a0I says.\
\
He turns on me, looking pitying enough to make a body cry, and says:\
\
\'93Huck Finn, did you _ever_ hear of a prisoner having picks and shovels,\
and all the modern conveniences in his wardrobe to dig himself out with?\
\'a0Now I want to ask you--if you got any reasonableness in you at all--what\
kind of a show would _that_ give him to be a hero? \'a0Why, they might as\
well lend him the key and done with it. \'a0Picks and shovels--why, they\
wouldn\'92t furnish \'91em to a king.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then,\'94 I says, \'93if we don\'92t want the picks and shovels, what do\
we want?\'94\
\
\'93A couple of case-knives.\'94\
\
\'93To dig the foundations out from under that cabin with?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Confound it, it\'92s foolish, Tom.\'94\
\
\'93It don\'92t make no difference how foolish it is, it\'92s the _right_ way--and\
it\'92s the regular way. \'a0And there ain\'92t no _other_ way, that ever I heard\
of, and I\'92ve read all the books that gives any information about these\
things. They always dig out with a case-knife--and not through dirt, mind\
you; generly it\'92s through solid rock. \'a0And it takes them weeks and weeks\
and weeks, and for ever and ever. \'a0Why, look at one of them prisoners in\
the bottom dungeon of the Castle Deef, in the harbor of Marseilles, that\
dug himself out that way; how long was _he_ at it, you reckon?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\
\
\'93Well, guess.\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. \'a0A month and a half.\'94\
\
\'93_Thirty-seven year_--and he come out in China. \'a0_That\'92s_ the kind. \'a0I\
wish the bottom of _this_ fortress was solid rock.\'94\
\
\'93_Jim_ don\'92t know nobody in China.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s _that_ got to do with it? \'a0Neither did that other fellow. \'a0But\
you\'92re always a-wandering off on a side issue. \'a0Why can\'92t you stick to\
the main point?\'94\
\
\'93All right--I don\'92t care where he comes out, so he _comes_ out; and Jim\
don\'92t, either, I reckon. \'a0But there\'92s one thing, anyway--Jim\'92s too old to\
be dug out with a case-knife. \'a0He won\'92t last.\'94\
\
\'93Yes he will _last_, too. \'a0You don\'92t reckon it\'92s going to take\
thirty-seven years to dig out through a _dirt_ foundation, do you?\'94\
\
\'93How long will it take, Tom?\'94\
\
\'93Well, we can\'92t resk being as long as we ought to, because it mayn\'92t\
take very long for Uncle Silas to hear from down there by New Orleans.\
\'a0He\'92ll hear Jim ain\'92t from there. \'a0Then his next move will be to\
advertise Jim, or something like that. \'a0So we can\'92t resk being as long\
digging him out as we ought to. \'a0By rights I reckon we ought to be\
a couple of years; but we can\'92t. \'a0Things being so uncertain, what I\
recommend is this: \'a0that we really dig right in, as quick as we can;\
and after that, we can _let on_, to ourselves, that we was at it\
thirty-seven years. \'a0Then we can snatch him out and rush him away the\
first time there\'92s an alarm. \'a0Yes, I reckon that \'91ll be the best way.\'94\
\
\'93Now, there\'92s _sense_ in that,\'94 I says.  \'93Letting on don\'92t cost nothing;\
letting on ain\'92t no trouble; and if it\'92s any object, I don\'92t mind\
letting on we was at it a hundred and fifty year. \'a0It wouldn\'92t strain\
me none, after I got my hand in. \'a0So I\'92ll mosey along now, and smouch a\
couple of case-knives.\'94\
\
\'93Smouch three,\'94 he says; \'93we want one to make a saw out of.\'94\
\
\'93Tom, if it ain\'92t unregular and irreligious to sejest it,\'94 I says,\
\'93there\'92s an old rusty saw-blade around yonder sticking under the\
weather-boarding behind the smoke-house.\'94\
\
He looked kind of weary and discouraged-like, and says:\
\
\'93It ain\'92t no use to try to learn you nothing, Huck. \'a0Run along and\
smouch the knives--three of them.\'94 \'a0So I done it.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXVI.\
\
AS soon as we reckoned everybody was asleep that night we went down the\
lightning-rod, and shut ourselves up in the lean-to, and got out our\
pile of fox-fire, and went to work. \'a0We cleared everything out of the\
way, about four or five foot along the middle of the bottom log. \'a0Tom\
said he was right behind Jim\'92s bed now, and we\'92d dig in under it, and\
when we got through there couldn\'92t nobody in the cabin ever know there\
was any hole there, because Jim\'92s counter-pin hung down most to the\
ground, and you\'92d have to raise it up and look under to see the hole.\
\'a0So we dug and dug with the case-knives till most midnight; and then\
we was dog-tired, and our hands was blistered, and yet you couldn\'92t see\
we\'92d done anything hardly. \'a0At last I says:\
\
\'93This ain\'92t no thirty-seven year job; this is a thirty-eight year job,\
Tom Sawyer.\'94\
\
He never said nothing. \'a0But he sighed, and pretty soon he stopped\
digging, and then for a good little while I knowed that he was thinking.\
Then he says:\
\
\'93It ain\'92t no use, Huck, it ain\'92t a-going to work. \'a0If we was prisoners\
it would, because then we\'92d have as many years as we wanted, and no\
hurry; and we wouldn\'92t get but a few minutes to dig, every day, while\
they was changing watches, and so our hands wouldn\'92t get blistered, and\
we could keep it up right along, year in and year out, and do it right,\
and the way it ought to be done. \'a0But _we_ can\'92t fool along; we got to\
rush; we ain\'92t got no time to spare. \'a0If we was to put in another\
night this way we\'92d have to knock off for a week to let our hands get\
well--couldn\'92t touch a case-knife with them sooner.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, what we going to do, Tom?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell you. \'a0It ain\'92t right, and it ain\'92t moral, and I wouldn\'92t like\
it to get out; but there ain\'92t only just the one way: \'a0we got to dig him\
out with the picks, and _let on_ it\'92s case-knives.\'94\
\
\'93_Now_ you\'92re _talking_!\'94 \'a0I says; \'93your head gets leveler and leveler\
all the time, Tom Sawyer,\'94 I says.  \'93Picks is the thing, moral or no\
moral; and as for me, I don\'92t care shucks for the morality of it, nohow.\
\'a0When I start in to steal a nigger, or a watermelon, or a Sunday-school\
book, I ain\'92t no ways particular how it\'92s done so it\'92s done. \'a0What I\
want is my nigger; or what I want is my watermelon; or what I want is my\
Sunday-school book; and if a pick\'92s the handiest thing, that\'92s the thing\
I\'92m a-going to dig that nigger or that watermelon or that Sunday-school\
book out with; and I don\'92t give a dead rat what the authorities thinks\
about it nuther.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 he says, \'93there\'92s excuse for picks and letting-on in a case like\
this; if it warn\'92t so, I wouldn\'92t approve of it, nor I wouldn\'92t stand by\
and see the rules broke--because right is right, and wrong is wrong,\
and a body ain\'92t got no business doing wrong when he ain\'92t ignorant and\
knows better. \'a0It might answer for _you_ to dig Jim out with a pick,\
_without_ any letting on, because you don\'92t know no better; but it\
wouldn\'92t for me, because I do know better. \'a0Gimme a case-knife.\'94\
\
He had his own by him, but I handed him mine. \'a0He flung it down, and\
says:\
\
\'93Gimme a _case-knife_.\'94\
\
I didn\'92t know just what to do--but then I thought. \'a0I scratched around\
amongst the old tools, and got a pickaxe and give it to him, and he took\
it and went to work, and never said a word.\
\
He was always just that particular. \'a0Full of principle.\
\
So then I got a shovel, and then we picked and shoveled, turn about,\
and made the fur fly. \'a0We stuck to it about a half an hour, which was as\
long as we could stand up; but we had a good deal of a hole to show for\
it. When I got up stairs I looked out at the window and see Tom doing\
his level best with the lightning-rod, but he couldn\'92t come it, his\
hands was so sore. \'a0At last he says:\
\
\'93It ain\'92t no use, it can\'92t be done. \'a0What you reckon I better do? \'a0Can\'92t\
you think of no way?\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I says, \'93but I reckon it ain\'92t regular. \'a0Come up the stairs, and\
let on it\'92s a lightning-rod.\'94\
\
So he done it.\
\
Next day Tom stole a pewter spoon and a brass candlestick in the house,\
for to make some pens for Jim out of, and six tallow candles; and I\
hung around the nigger cabins and laid for a chance, and stole three tin\
plates. \'a0Tom says it wasn\'92t enough; but I said nobody wouldn\'92t ever see\
the plates that Jim throwed out, because they\'92d fall in the dog-fennel\
and jimpson weeds under the window-hole--then we could tote them back and\
he could use them over again. \'a0So Tom was satisfied. \'a0Then he says:\
\
\'93Now, the thing to study out is, how to get the things to Jim.\'94\
\
\'93Take them in through the hole,\'94 I says, \'93when we get it done.\'94\
\
He only just looked scornful, and said something about nobody ever heard\
of such an idiotic idea, and then he went to studying. \'a0By and by he\
said he had ciphered out two or three ways, but there warn\'92t no need to\
decide on any of them yet. \'a0Said we\'92d got to post Jim first.\
\
That night we went down the lightning-rod a little after ten, and took\
one of the candles along, and listened under the window-hole, and heard\
Jim snoring; so we pitched it in, and it didn\'92t wake him. \'a0Then we\
whirled in with the pick and shovel, and in about two hours and a half\
the job was done. \'a0We crept in under Jim\'92s bed and into the cabin, and\
pawed around and found the candle and lit it, and stood over Jim awhile,\
and found him looking hearty and healthy, and then we woke him up gentle\
and gradual. \'a0He was so glad to see us he most cried; and called us\
honey, and all the pet names he could think of; and was for having us\
hunt up a cold-chisel to cut the chain off of his leg with right away,\
and clearing out without losing any time. \'a0But Tom he showed him how\
unregular it would be, and set down and told him all about our plans,\
and how we could alter them in a minute any time there was an alarm; and\
not to be the least afraid, because we would see he got away, _sure_.\
\'a0So Jim he said it was all right, and we set there and talked over old\
times awhile, and then Tom asked a lot of questions, and when Jim told\
him Uncle Silas come in every day or two to pray with him, and Aunt\
Sally come in to see if he was comfortable and had plenty to eat, and\
both of them was kind as they could be, Tom says:\
\
\'93_Now_ I know how to fix it. \'a0We\'92ll send you some things by them.\'94\
\
I said, \'93Don\'92t do nothing of the kind; it\'92s one of the most jackass\
ideas I ever struck;\'94 but he never paid no attention to me; went right\
on. \'a0It was his way when he\'92d got his plans set.\
\
So he told Jim how we\'92d have to smuggle in the rope-ladder pie and other\
large things by Nat, the nigger that fed him, and he must be on the\
lookout, and not be surprised, and not let Nat see him open them; and\
we would put small things in uncle\'92s coat-pockets and he must steal them\
out; and we would tie things to aunt\'92s apron-strings or put them in her\
apron-pocket, if we got a chance; and told him what they would be and\
what they was for. \'a0And told him how to keep a journal on the shirt with\
his blood, and all that. He told him everything. \'a0Jim he couldn\'92t see\
no sense in the most of it, but he allowed we was white folks and knowed\
better than him; so he was satisfied, and said he would do it all just\
as Tom said.\
\
Jim had plenty corn-cob pipes and tobacco; so we had a right down good\
sociable time; then we crawled out through the hole, and so home to\
bed, with hands that looked like they\'92d been chawed. \'a0Tom was in high\
spirits. He said it was the best fun he ever had in his life, and the\
most intellectural; and said if he only could see his way to it we would\
keep it up all the rest of our lives and leave Jim to our children to\
get out; for he believed Jim would come to like it better and better the\
more he got used to it. \'a0He said that in that way it could be strung out\
to as much as eighty year, and would be the best time on record. \'a0And he\
said it would make us all celebrated that had a hand in it.\
\
In the morning we went out to the woodpile and chopped up the brass\
candlestick into handy sizes, and Tom put them and the pewter spoon in\
his pocket. \'a0Then we went to the nigger cabins, and while I got Nat\'92s\
notice off, Tom shoved a piece of candlestick into the middle of a\
corn-pone that was in Jim\'92s pan, and we went along with Nat to see how\
it would work, and it just worked noble; when Jim bit into it it most\
mashed all his teeth out; and there warn\'92t ever anything could a worked\
better. Tom said so himself. Jim he never let on but what it was only\
just a piece of rock or something like that that\'92s always getting into\
bread, you know; but after that he never bit into nothing but what he\
jabbed his fork into it in three or four places first.\
\
And whilst we was a-standing there in the dimmish light, here comes a\
couple of the hounds bulging in from under Jim\'92s bed; and they kept on\
piling in till there was eleven of them, and there warn\'92t hardly room\
in there to get your breath. \'a0By jings, we forgot to fasten that lean-to\
door! \'a0The nigger Nat he only just hollered \'93Witches\'94 once, and keeled\
over on to the floor amongst the dogs, and begun to groan like he was\
dying. \'a0Tom jerked the door open and flung out a slab of Jim\'92s meat,\
and the dogs went for it, and in two seconds he was out himself and back\
again and shut the door, and I knowed he\'92d fixed the other door too.\
Then he went to work on the nigger, coaxing him and petting him, and\
asking him if he\'92d been imagining he saw something again. \'a0He raised up,\
and blinked his eyes around, and says:\
\
\'93Mars Sid, you\'92ll say I\'92s a fool, but if I didn\'92t b\'92lieve I see most a\
million dogs, er devils, er some\'92n, I wisht I may die right heah in dese\
tracks. \'a0I did, mos\'92 sholy. \'a0Mars Sid, I _felt_ um--I _felt_ um, sah; dey\
was all over me. \'a0Dad fetch it, I jis\'92 wisht I could git my han\'92s on one\
er dem witches jis\'92 wunst--on\'92y jis\'92 wunst--it\'92s all I\'92d ast. \'a0But mos\'92ly\
I wisht dey\'92d lemme \'91lone, I does.\'94\
\
Tom says:\
\
\'93Well, I tell you what I think. \'a0What makes them come here just at this\
runaway nigger\'92s breakfast-time? \'a0It\'92s because they\'92re hungry; that\'92s\
the reason. \'a0You make them a witch pie; that\'92s the thing for _you_ to\
do.\'94\
\
\'93But my lan\'92, Mars Sid, how\'92s I gwyne to make \'91m a witch pie? \'a0I doan\'92\
know how to make it. \'a0I hain\'92t ever hearn er sich a thing b\'92fo\'92.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, I\'92ll have to make it myself.\'94\
\
\'93Will you do it, honey?--will you? \'a0I\'92ll wusshup de groun\'92 und\'92 yo\'92 foot,\
I will!\'94\
\
\'93All right, I\'92ll do it, seeing it\'92s you, and you\'92ve been good to us and\
showed us the runaway nigger. \'a0But you got to be mighty careful. \'a0When\
we come around, you turn your back; and then whatever we\'92ve put in the\
pan, don\'92t you let on you see it at all. \'a0And don\'92t you look when Jim\
unloads the pan--something might happen, I don\'92t know what. \'a0And above\
all, don\'92t you _handle_ the witch-things.\'94\
\
\'93_Hannel \'91M_, Mars Sid? \'a0What _is_ you a-talkin\'92 \'91bout? \'a0I wouldn\'92\
lay de weight er my finger on um, not f\'92r ten hund\'92d thous\'92n billion\
dollars, I wouldn\'92t.\'94\
\
\
