\
CHAPTER XXXVII.\
\
THAT was all fixed. \'a0So then we went away and went to the rubbage-pile\
in the back yard, where they keep the old boots, and rags, and pieces\
of bottles, and wore-out tin things, and all such truck, and scratched\
around and found an old tin washpan, and stopped up the holes as well as\
we could, to bake the pie in, and took it down cellar and stole it full\
of flour and started for breakfast, and found a couple of shingle-nails\
that Tom said would be handy for a prisoner to scrabble his name and\
sorrows on the dungeon walls with, and dropped one of them in Aunt\
Sally\'92s apron-pocket which was hanging on a chair, and t\'92other we stuck\
in the band of Uncle Silas\'92s hat, which was on the bureau, because we\
heard the children say their pa and ma was going to the runaway nigger\'92s\
house this morning, and then went to breakfast, and Tom dropped the\
pewter spoon in Uncle Silas\'92s coat-pocket, and Aunt Sally wasn\'92t come\
yet, so we had to wait a little while.\
\
And when she come she was hot and red and cross, and couldn\'92t hardly\
wait for the blessing; and then she went to sluicing out coffee with one\
hand and cracking the handiest child\'92s head with her thimble with the\
other, and says:\
\
\'93I\'92ve hunted high and I\'92ve hunted low, and it does beat all what _has_\
become of your other shirt.\'94\
\
My heart fell down amongst my lungs and livers and things, and a hard\
piece of corn-crust started down my throat after it and got met on the\
road with a cough, and was shot across the table, and took one of the\
children in the eye and curled him up like a fishing-worm, and let a cry\
out of him the size of a warwhoop, and Tom he turned kinder blue around\
the gills, and it all amounted to a considerable state of things for\
about a quarter of a minute or as much as that, and I would a sold out\
for half price if there was a bidder. \'a0But after that we was all right\
again--it was the sudden surprise of it that knocked us so kind of cold.\
Uncle Silas he says:\
\
\'93It\'92s most uncommon curious, I can\'92t understand it. \'a0I know perfectly\
well I took it _off_, because--\'94\
\
\'93Because you hain\'92t got but one _on_. \'a0Just _listen_ at the man! \'a0I know\
you took it off, and know it by a better way than your wool-gethering\
memory, too, because it was on the clo\'92s-line yesterday--I see it there\
myself. But it\'92s gone, that\'92s the long and the short of it, and you\'92ll\
just have to change to a red flann\'92l one till I can get time to make a\
new one. And it \'91ll be the third I\'92ve made in two years. \'a0It just keeps\
a body on the jump to keep you in shirts; and whatever you do manage to\
_do_ with \'91m all is more\'92n I can make out. \'a0A body \'91d think you _would_\
learn to take some sort of care of \'91em at your time of life.\'94\
\
\'93I know it, Sally, and I do try all I can. \'a0But it oughtn\'92t to be\
altogether my fault, because, you know, I don\'92t see them nor have\
nothing to do with them except when they\'92re on me; and I don\'92t believe\
I\'92ve ever lost one of them _off_ of me.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it ain\'92t _your_ fault if you haven\'92t, Silas; you\'92d a done it\
if you could, I reckon. \'a0And the shirt ain\'92t all that\'92s gone, nuther.\
\'a0Ther\'92s a spoon gone; and _that_ ain\'92t all. \'a0There was ten, and now\
ther\'92s only nine. The calf got the shirt, I reckon, but the calf never\
took the spoon, _that\'92s_ certain.\'94\
\
\'93Why, what else is gone, Sally?\'94\
\
\'93Ther\'92s six _candles_ gone--that\'92s what. \'a0The rats could a got the\
candles, and I reckon they did; I wonder they don\'92t walk off with the\
whole place, the way you\'92re always going to stop their holes and don\'92t\
do it; and if they warn\'92t fools they\'92d sleep in your hair, Silas--_you\'92d_\
never find it out; but you can\'92t lay the _spoon_ on the rats, and that I\
know.\'94\
\
\'93Well, Sally, I\'92m in fault, and I acknowledge it; I\'92ve been remiss; but\
I won\'92t let to-morrow go by without stopping up them holes.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I wouldn\'92t hurry; next year \'91ll do. \'a0Matilda Angelina Araminta\
_Phelps!_\'94\
\
Whack comes the thimble, and the child snatches her claws out of the\
sugar-bowl without fooling around any. \'a0Just then the nigger woman steps\
on to the passage, and says:\
\
\'93Missus, dey\'92s a sheet gone.\'94\
\
\'93A _sheet_ gone! \'a0Well, for the land\'92s sake!\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll stop up them holes to-day,\'94 says Uncle Silas, looking sorrowful.\
\
\'93Oh, _do_ shet up!--s\'92pose the rats took the _sheet_? \'a0_where\'92s_ it gone,\
Lize?\'94\
\
\'93Clah to goodness I hain\'92t no notion, Miss\'92 Sally. \'a0She wuz on de\
clo\'92sline yistiddy, but she done gone: \'a0she ain\'92 dah no mo\'92 now.\'94\
\
\'93I reckon the world _is_ coming to an end. \'a0I _never_ see the beat of it\
in all my born days. \'a0A shirt, and a sheet, and a spoon, and six can--\'94\
\
\'93Missus,\'94 comes a young yaller wench, \'93dey\'92s a brass cannelstick\
miss\'92n.\'94\
\
\'93Cler out from here, you hussy, er I\'92ll take a skillet to ye!\'94\
\
Well, she was just a-biling. \'a0I begun to lay for a chance; I reckoned\
I would sneak out and go for the woods till the weather moderated. \'a0She\
kept a-raging right along, running her insurrection all by herself, and\
everybody else mighty meek and quiet; and at last Uncle Silas, looking\
kind of foolish, fishes up that spoon out of his pocket. \'a0She stopped,\
with her mouth open and her hands up; and as for me, I wished I was in\
Jeruslem or somewheres. But not long, because she says:\
\
\'93It\'92s _just_ as I expected. \'a0So you had it in your pocket all the time;\
and like as not you\'92ve got the other things there, too. \'a0How\'92d it get\
there?\'94\
\
\'93I reely don\'92t know, Sally,\'94 he says, kind of apologizing, \'93or you know\
I would tell. \'a0I was a-studying over my text in Acts Seventeen before\
breakfast, and I reckon I put it in there, not noticing, meaning to put\
my Testament in, and it must be so, because my Testament ain\'92t in; but\
I\'92ll go and see; and if the Testament is where I had it, I\'92ll know I\
didn\'92t put it in, and that will show that I laid the Testament down and\
took up the spoon, and--\'94\
\
\'93Oh, for the land\'92s sake! \'a0Give a body a rest! \'a0Go \'91long now, the whole\
kit and biling of ye; and don\'92t come nigh me again till I\'92ve got back my\
peace of mind.\'94\
\
I\'92D a heard her if she\'92d a said it to herself, let alone speaking it\
out; and I\'92d a got up and obeyed her if I\'92d a been dead. \'a0As we was\
passing through the setting-room the old man he took up his hat, and the\
shingle-nail fell out on the floor, and he just merely picked it up and\
laid it on the mantel-shelf, and never said nothing, and went out. \'a0Tom\
see him do it, and remembered about the spoon, and says:\
\
\'93Well, it ain\'92t no use to send things by _him_ no more, he ain\'92t\
reliable.\'94 Then he says:  \'93But he done us a good turn with the spoon,\
anyway, without knowing it, and so we\'92ll go and do him one without _him_\
knowing it--stop up his rat-holes.\'94\
\
There was a noble good lot of them down cellar, and it took us a whole\
hour, but we done the job tight and good and shipshape. \'a0Then we heard\
steps on the stairs, and blowed out our light and hid; and here comes\
the old man, with a candle in one hand and a bundle of stuff in t\'92other,\
looking as absent-minded as year before last. \'a0He went a mooning around,\
first to one rat-hole and then another, till he\'92d been to them all.\
\'a0Then he stood about five minutes, picking tallow-drip off of his candle\
and thinking. \'a0Then he turns off slow and dreamy towards the stairs,\
saying:\
\
\'93Well, for the life of me I can\'92t remember when I done it. \'a0I could\
show her now that I warn\'92t to blame on account of the rats. \'a0But never\
mind--let it go. \'a0I reckon it wouldn\'92t do no good.\'94\
\
And so he went on a-mumbling up stairs, and then we left. \'a0He was a\
mighty nice old man. \'a0And always is.\
\
Tom was a good deal bothered about what to do for a spoon, but he said\
we\'92d got to have it; so he took a think. \'a0When he had ciphered it out\
he told me how we was to do; then we went and waited around the\
spoon-basket till we see Aunt Sally coming, and then Tom went to\
counting the spoons and laying them out to one side, and I slid one of\
them up my sleeve, and Tom says:\
\
\'93Why, Aunt Sally, there ain\'92t but nine spoons _yet_.\'94\
\
She says:\
\
\'93Go \'91long to your play, and don\'92t bother me. \'a0I know better, I counted\
\'91m myself.\'94\
\
\'93Well, I\'92ve counted them twice, Aunty, and I can\'92t make but nine.\'94\
\
She looked out of all patience, but of course she come to count--anybody\
would.\
\
\'93I declare to gracious ther\'92 _ain\'92t_ but nine!\'94 she says.  \'93Why, what in\
the world--plague _take_ the things, I\'92ll count \'91m again.\'94\
\
So I slipped back the one I had, and when she got done counting, she\
says:\
\
\'93Hang the troublesome rubbage, ther\'92s _ten_ now!\'94 and she looked huffy\
and bothered both. \'a0But Tom says:\
\
\'93Why, Aunty, I don\'92t think there\'92s ten.\'94\
\
\'93You numskull, didn\'92t you see me _count \'91m?_\'94\
\
\'93I know, but--\'94\
\
\'93Well, I\'92ll count \'91m _again_.\'94\
\
So I smouched one, and they come out nine, same as the other time.\
\'a0Well, she _was_ in a tearing way--just a-trembling all over, she was so\
mad. \'a0But she counted and counted till she got that addled she\'92d start\
to count in the basket for a spoon sometimes; and so, three times they\
come out right, and three times they come out wrong. \'a0Then she grabbed\
up the basket and slammed it across the house and knocked the cat\
galley-west; and she said cle\'92r out and let her have some peace, and if\
we come bothering around her again betwixt that and dinner she\'92d skin\
us. \'a0So we had the odd spoon, and dropped it in her apron-pocket whilst\
she was a-giving us our sailing orders, and Jim got it all right, along\
with her shingle nail, before noon. \'a0We was very well satisfied with\
this business, and Tom allowed it was worth twice the trouble it took,\
because he said _now_ she couldn\'92t ever count them spoons twice alike\
again to save her life; and wouldn\'92t believe she\'92d counted them right if\
she _did_; and said that after she\'92d about counted her head off for the\
next three days he judged she\'92d give it up and offer to kill anybody\
that wanted her to ever count them any more.\
\
So we put the sheet back on the line that night, and stole one out of\
her closet; and kept on putting it back and stealing it again for a\
couple of days till she didn\'92t know how many sheets she had any more,\
and she didn\'92t _care_, and warn\'92t a-going to bullyrag the rest of her\
soul out about it, and wouldn\'92t count them again not to save her life;\
she druther die first.\
\
So we was all right now, as to the shirt and the sheet and the spoon\
and the candles, by the help of the calf and the rats and the mixed-up\
counting; and as to the candlestick, it warn\'92t no consequence, it would\
blow over by and by.\
\
But that pie was a job; we had no end of trouble with that pie. \'a0We\
fixed it up away down in the woods, and cooked it there; and we got it\
done at last, and very satisfactory, too; but not all in one day; and we\
had to use up three wash-pans full of flour before we got through, and\
we got burnt pretty much all over, in places, and eyes put out with\
the smoke; because, you see, we didn\'92t want nothing but a crust, and we\
couldn\'92t prop it up right, and she would always cave in. \'a0But of course\
we thought of the right way at last--which was to cook the ladder, too,\
in the pie. \'a0So then we laid in with Jim the second night, and tore\
up the sheet all in little strings and twisted them together, and long\
before daylight we had a lovely rope that you could a hung a person\
with. \'a0We let on it took nine months to make it.\
\
And in the forenoon we took it down to the woods, but it wouldn\'92t go\
into the pie. \'a0Being made of a whole sheet, that way, there was rope\
enough for forty pies if we\'92d a wanted them, and plenty left over\
for soup, or sausage, or anything you choose. \'a0We could a had a whole\
dinner.\
\
But we didn\'92t need it. \'a0All we needed was just enough for the pie, and\
so we throwed the rest away. \'a0We didn\'92t cook none of the pies in the\
wash-pan--afraid the solder would melt; but Uncle Silas he had a noble\
brass warming-pan which he thought considerable of, because it belonged\
to one of his ancesters with a long wooden handle that come over from\
England with William the Conqueror in the Mayflower or one of them early\
ships and was hid away up garret with a lot of other old pots and things\
that was valuable, not on account of being any account, because they\
warn\'92t, but on account of them being relicts, you know, and we snaked\
her out, private, and took her down there, but she failed on the first\
pies, because we didn\'92t know how, but she come up smiling on the last\
one. \'a0We took and lined her with dough, and set her in the coals, and\
loaded her up with rag rope, and put on a dough roof, and shut down the\
lid, and put hot embers on top, and stood off five foot, with the long\
handle, cool and comfortable, and in fifteen minutes she turned out a\
pie that was a satisfaction to look at. But the person that et it would\
want to fetch a couple of kags of toothpicks along, for if that rope\
ladder wouldn\'92t cramp him down to business I don\'92t know nothing what I\'92m\
talking about, and lay him in enough stomach-ache to last him till next\
time, too.\
\
Nat didn\'92t look when we put the witch pie in Jim\'92s pan; and we put the\
three tin plates in the bottom of the pan under the vittles; and so Jim\
got everything all right, and as soon as he was by himself he busted\
into the pie and hid the rope ladder inside of his straw tick,\
and scratched some marks on a tin plate and throwed it out of the\
window-hole.\
\
\
\
\
CHAPTER XXXVIII.\
\
MAKING them pens was a distressid tough job, and so was the saw; and Jim\
allowed the inscription was going to be the toughest of all. \'a0That\'92s the\
one which the prisoner has to scrabble on the wall. \'a0But he had to have\
it; Tom said he\'92d _got_ to; there warn\'92t no case of a state prisoner not\
scrabbling his inscription to leave behind, and his coat of arms.\
\
\'93Look at Lady Jane Grey,\'94 he says; \'93look at Gilford Dudley; look at old\
Northumberland! \'a0Why, Huck, s\'92pose it _is_ considerble trouble?--what\
you going to do?--how you going to get around it? \'a0Jim\'92s _got_ to do his\
inscription and coat of arms. \'a0They all do.\'94\
\
Jim says:\
\
\'93Why, Mars Tom, I hain\'92t got no coat o\'92 arm; I hain\'92t got nuffn but dish\
yer ole shirt, en you knows I got to keep de journal on dat.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, you don\'92t understand, Jim; a coat of arms is very different.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I says, \'93Jim\'92s right, anyway, when he says he ain\'92t got no coat\
of arms, because he hain\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93I reckon I knowed that,\'94 Tom says, \'93but you bet he\'92ll have one before\
he goes out of this--because he\'92s going out _right_, and there ain\'92t\
going to be no flaws in his record.\'94\
\
So whilst me and Jim filed away at the pens on a brickbat apiece, Jim\
a-making his\'92n out of the brass and I making mine out of the spoon,\
Tom set to work to think out the coat of arms. \'a0By and by he said he\'92d\
struck so many good ones he didn\'92t hardly know which to take, but there\
was one which he reckoned he\'92d decide on. \'a0He says:\
\
\'93On the scutcheon we\'92ll have a bend _or_ in the dexter base, a saltire\
_murrey_ in the fess, with a dog, couchant, for common charge, and under\
his foot a chain embattled, for slavery, with a chevron _vert_ in a\
chief engrailed, and three invected lines on a field _azure_, with the\
nombril points rampant on a dancette indented; crest, a runaway nigger,\
_sable_, with his bundle over his shoulder on a bar sinister; and a\
couple of gules for supporters, which is you and me; motto, _Maggiore\
Fretta, Minore Otto._ \'a0Got it out of a book--means the more haste the\
less speed.\'94\
\
\'93Geewhillikins,\'94 I says, \'93but what does the rest of it mean?\'94\
\
\'93We ain\'92t got no time to bother over that,\'94 he says; \'93we got to dig in\
like all git-out.\'94\
\
\'93Well, anyway,\'94 I says, \'93what\'92s _some_ of it? \'a0What\'92s a fess?\'94\
\
\'93A fess--a fess is--_you_ don\'92t need to know what a fess is. \'a0I\'92ll show\
him how to make it when he gets to it.\'94\
\
\'93Shucks, Tom,\'94 I says, \'93I think you might tell a person. \'a0What\'92s a bar\
sinister?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, I don\'92t know. \'a0But he\'92s got to have it. \'a0All the nobility does.\'94\
\
That was just his way. \'a0If it didn\'92t suit him to explain a thing to you,\
he wouldn\'92t do it. \'a0You might pump at him a week, it wouldn\'92t make no\
difference.\
\
He\'92d got all that coat of arms business fixed, so now he started in to\
finish up the rest of that part of the work, which was to plan out a\
mournful inscription--said Jim got to have one, like they all done. \'a0He\
made up a lot, and wrote them out on a paper, and read them off, so:\
\
1. \'a0Here a captive heart busted. 2. \'a0Here a poor prisoner, forsook by\
the world and friends, fretted his sorrowful life. 3. \'a0Here a lonely\
heart broke, and a worn spirit went to its rest, after thirty-seven\
years of solitary captivity. 4. \'a0Here, homeless and friendless, after\
thirty-seven years of bitter captivity, perished a noble stranger,\
natural son of Louis XIV.\
\
Tom\'92s voice trembled whilst he was reading them, and he most broke down.\
When he got done he couldn\'92t no way make up his mind which one for Jim\
to scrabble on to the wall, they was all so good; but at last he allowed\
he would let him scrabble them all on. \'a0Jim said it would take him a\
year to scrabble such a lot of truck on to the logs with a nail, and he\
didn\'92t know how to make letters, besides; but Tom said he would block\
them out for him, and then he wouldn\'92t have nothing to do but just\
follow the lines. \'a0Then pretty soon he says:\
\
\'93Come to think, the logs ain\'92t a-going to do; they don\'92t have log walls\
in a dungeon: \'a0we got to dig the inscriptions into a rock. \'a0We\'92ll fetch\
a rock.\'94\
\
Jim said the rock was worse than the logs; he said it would take him\
such a pison long time to dig them into a rock he wouldn\'92t ever get out.\
\'a0But Tom said he would let me help him do it. \'a0Then he took a look to\
see how me and Jim was getting along with the pens. \'a0It was most pesky\
tedious hard work and slow, and didn\'92t give my hands no show to get\
well of the sores, and we didn\'92t seem to make no headway, hardly; so Tom\
says:\
\
\'93I know how to fix it. \'a0We got to have a rock for the coat of arms and\
mournful inscriptions, and we can kill two birds with that same rock.\
There\'92s a gaudy big grindstone down at the mill, and we\'92ll smouch it,\
and carve the things on it, and file out the pens and the saw on it,\
too.\'94\
\
It warn\'92t no slouch of an idea; and it warn\'92t no slouch of a grindstone\
nuther; but we allowed we\'92d tackle it. \'a0It warn\'92t quite midnight yet,\
so we cleared out for the mill, leaving Jim at work. \'a0We smouched the\
grindstone, and set out to roll her home, but it was a most nation tough\
job. Sometimes, do what we could, we couldn\'92t keep her from falling\
over, and she come mighty near mashing us every time. \'a0Tom said she was\
going to get one of us, sure, before we got through. \'a0We got her half\
way; and then we was plumb played out, and most drownded with sweat. \'a0We\
see it warn\'92t no use; we got to go and fetch Jim. So he raised up his\
bed and slid the chain off of the bed-leg, and wrapt it round and round\
his neck, and we crawled out through our hole and down there, and Jim\
and me laid into that grindstone and walked her along like nothing; and\
Tom superintended. \'a0He could out-superintend any boy I ever see. \'a0He\
knowed how to do everything.\
\
Our hole was pretty big, but it warn\'92t big enough to get the grindstone\
through; but Jim he took the pick and soon made it big enough. \'a0Then Tom\
marked out them things on it with the nail, and set Jim to work on them,\
with the nail for a chisel and an iron bolt from the rubbage in the\
lean-to for a hammer, and told him to work till the rest of his candle\
quit on him, and then he could go to bed, and hide the grindstone under\
his straw tick and sleep on it. \'a0Then we helped him fix his chain back\
on the bed-leg, and was ready for bed ourselves. \'a0But Tom thought of\
something, and says:\
\
\'93You got any spiders in here, Jim?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah, thanks to goodness I hain\'92t, Mars Tom.\'94\
\
\'93All right, we\'92ll get you some.\'94\
\
\'93But bless you, honey, I doan\'92 _want_ none. \'a0I\'92s afeard un um. \'a0I jis\'92\
\'91s soon have rattlesnakes aroun\'92.\'94\
\
Tom thought a minute or two, and says:\
\
\'93It\'92s a good idea. \'a0And I reckon it\'92s been done. \'a0It _must_ a been done;\
it stands to reason. \'a0Yes, it\'92s a prime good idea. \'a0Where could you keep\
it?\'94\
\
\'93Keep what, Mars Tom?\'94\
\
\'93Why, a rattlesnake.\'94\
\
\'93De goodness gracious alive, Mars Tom! \'a0Why, if dey was a rattlesnake to\
come in heah I\'92d take en bust right out thoo dat log wall, I would, wid\
my head.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Jim, you wouldn\'92t be afraid of it after a little. \'a0You could tame\
it.\'94\
\
\'93_Tame_ it!\'94\
\
\'93Yes--easy enough. \'a0Every animal is grateful for kindness and petting,\
and they wouldn\'92t _think_ of hurting a person that pets them. \'a0Any book\
will tell you that. \'a0You try--that\'92s all I ask; just try for two or three\
days. Why, you can get him so, in a little while, that he\'92ll love you;\
and sleep with you; and won\'92t stay away from you a minute; and will let\
you wrap him round your neck and put his head in your mouth.\'94\
\
\'93_Please_, Mars Tom--_doan_\'92 talk so! \'a0I can\'92t _stan_\'92 it! \'a0He\'92d _let_\
me shove his head in my mouf--fer a favor, hain\'92t it? \'a0I lay he\'92d wait a\
pow\'92ful long time \'91fo\'92 I _ast_ him. \'a0En mo\'92 en dat, I doan\'92 _want_ him\
to sleep wid me.\'94\
\
\'93Jim, don\'92t act so foolish. \'a0A prisoner\'92s _got_ to have some kind of a\
dumb pet, and if a rattlesnake hain\'92t ever been tried, why, there\'92s more\
glory to be gained in your being the first to ever try it than any other\
way you could ever think of to save your life.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Mars Tom, I doan\'92 _want_ no sich glory. \'a0Snake take \'91n bite\
Jim\'92s chin off, den _whah_ is de glory? \'a0No, sah, I doan\'92 want no sich\
doin\'92s.\'94\
\
\'93Blame it, can\'92t you _try_? \'a0I only _want_ you to try--you needn\'92t keep\
it up if it don\'92t work.\'94\
\
\'93But de trouble all _done_ ef de snake bite me while I\'92s a tryin\'92 him.\
Mars Tom, I\'92s willin\'92 to tackle mos\'92 anything \'91at ain\'92t onreasonable,\
but ef you en Huck fetches a rattlesnake in heah for me to tame, I\'92s\
gwyne to _leave_, dat\'92s _shore_.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, let it go, let it go, if you\'92re so bull-headed about it.\
\'a0We can get you some garter-snakes, and you can tie some buttons on\
their tails, and let on they\'92re rattlesnakes, and I reckon that \'91ll have\
to do.\'94\
\
\'93I k\'92n stan\'92 _dem_, Mars Tom, but blame\'92 \'91f I couldn\'92 get along widout\
um, I tell you dat. \'a0I never knowed b\'92fo\'92 \'91t was so much bother and\
trouble to be a prisoner.\'94\
\
\'93Well, it _always_ is when it\'92s done right. \'a0You got any rats around\
here?\'94\
\
\'93No, sah, I hain\'92t seed none.\'94\
\
\'93Well, we\'92ll get you some rats.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Mars Tom, I doan\'92 _want_ no rats. \'a0Dey\'92s de dadblamedest creturs\
to \'91sturb a body, en rustle roun\'92 over \'91im, en bite his feet, when he\'92s\
tryin\'92 to sleep, I ever see. \'a0No, sah, gimme g\'92yarter-snakes, \'91f I\'92s\
got to have \'91m, but doan\'92 gimme no rats; I hain\'92 got no use f\'92r um,\
skasely.\'94\
\
\'93But, Jim, you _got_ to have \'91em--they all do. \'a0So don\'92t make no more\
fuss about it. \'a0Prisoners ain\'92t ever without rats. \'a0There ain\'92t no\
instance of it. \'a0And they train them, and pet them, and learn them\
tricks, and they get to be as sociable as flies. \'a0But you got to play\
music to them. \'a0You got anything to play music on?\'94\
\
\'93I ain\'92 got nuffn but a coase comb en a piece o\'92 paper, en a juice-harp;\
but I reck\'92n dey wouldn\'92 take no stock in a juice-harp.\'94\
\
\'93Yes they would\'a0_they_ don\'92t care what kind of music \'91tis. \'a0A\
jews-harp\'92s plenty good enough for a rat. \'a0All animals like music--in a\
prison they dote on it. \'a0Specially, painful music; and you can\'92t get no\
other kind out of a jews-harp. \'a0It always interests them; they come out\
to see what\'92s the matter with you. \'a0Yes, you\'92re all right; you\'92re fixed\
very well. \'a0You want to set on your bed nights before you go to sleep,\
and early in the mornings, and play your jews-harp; play \'91The Last Link\
is Broken\'92--that\'92s the thing that \'91ll scoop a rat quicker \'91n anything\
else; and when you\'92ve played about two minutes you\'92ll see all the rats,\
and the snakes, and spiders, and things begin to feel worried about you,\
and come. \'a0And they\'92ll just fairly swarm over you, and have a noble good\
time.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, _dey_ will, I reck\'92n, Mars Tom, but what kine er time is _Jim_\
havin\'92? Blest if I kin see de pint. \'a0But I\'92ll do it ef I got to. \'a0I\
reck\'92n I better keep de animals satisfied, en not have no trouble in de\
house.\'94\
\
Tom waited to think it over, and see if there wasn\'92t nothing else; and\
pretty soon he says:\
\
\'93Oh, there\'92s one thing I forgot. \'a0Could you raise a flower here, do you\
reckon?\'94\
\
\'93I doan know but maybe I could, Mars Tom; but it\'92s tolable dark in heah,\
en I ain\'92 got no use f\'92r no flower, nohow, en she\'92d be a pow\'92ful sight\
o\'92 trouble.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you try it, anyway. \'a0Some other prisoners has done it.\'94\
\
\'93One er dem big cat-tail-lookin\'92 mullen-stalks would grow in heah, Mars\
Tom, I reck\'92n, but she wouldn\'92t be wuth half de trouble she\'92d coss.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you believe it. \'a0We\'92ll fetch you a little one and you plant it in\
the corner over there, and raise it. \'a0And don\'92t call it mullen, call it\
Pitchiola--that\'92s its right name when it\'92s in a prison. \'a0And you want to\
water it with your tears.\'94\
\
\'93Why, I got plenty spring water, Mars Tom.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t _want_ spring water; you want to water it with your tears.\
\'a0It\'92s the way they always do.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Mars Tom, I lay I kin raise one er dem mullen-stalks twyste wid\
spring water whiles another man\'92s a _start\'92n_ one wid tears.\'94\
\
\'93That ain\'92t the idea. \'a0You _got_ to do it with tears.\'94\
\
\'93She\'92ll die on my han\'92s, Mars Tom, she sholy will; kase I doan\'92 skasely\
ever cry.\'94\
\
So Tom was stumped. \'a0But he studied it over, and then said Jim would\
have to worry along the best he could with an onion. \'a0He promised\
he would go to the nigger cabins and drop one, private, in Jim\'92s\
coffee-pot, in the morning. Jim said he would \'93jis\'92 \'91s soon have\
tobacker in his coffee;\'94 and found so much fault with it, and with the\
work and bother of raising the mullen, and jews-harping the rats, and\
petting and flattering up the snakes and spiders and things, on top of\
all the other work he had to do on pens, and inscriptions, and journals,\
and things, which made it more trouble and worry and responsibility to\
be a prisoner than anything he ever undertook, that Tom most lost all\
patience with him; and said he was just loadened down with more gaudier\
chances than a prisoner ever had in the world to make a name for\
himself, and yet he didn\'92t know enough to appreciate them, and they was\
just about wasted on him. \'a0So Jim he was sorry, and said he wouldn\'92t\
behave so no more, and then me and Tom shoved for bed.\
