CHAPTER XXXIX.\
\
IN the morning we went up to the village and bought a wire rat-trap and\
fetched it down, and unstopped the best rat-hole, and in about an hour\
we had fifteen of the bulliest kind of ones; and then we took it and put\
it in a safe place under Aunt Sally\'92s bed. \'a0But while we was gone for\
spiders little Thomas Franklin Benjamin Jefferson Elexander Phelps found\
it there, and opened the door of it to see if the rats would come out,\
and they did; and Aunt Sally she come in, and when we got back she was\
a-standing on top of the bed raising Cain, and the rats was doing what\
they could to keep off the dull times for her. \'a0So she took and dusted\
us both with the hickry, and we was as much as two hours catching\
another fifteen or sixteen, drat that meddlesome cub, and they warn\'92t\
the likeliest, nuther, because the first haul was the pick of the flock.\
\'a0I never see a likelier lot of rats than what that first haul was.\
\
We got a splendid stock of sorted spiders, and bugs, and frogs, and\
caterpillars, and one thing or another; and we like to got a hornet\'92s\
nest, but we didn\'92t. \'a0The family was at home. \'a0We didn\'92t give it right\
up, but stayed with them as long as we could; because we allowed we\'92d\
tire them out or they\'92d got to tire us out, and they done it. \'a0Then we\
got allycumpain and rubbed on the places, and was pretty near all right\
again, but couldn\'92t set down convenient. \'a0And so we went for the snakes,\
and grabbed a couple of dozen garters and house-snakes, and put them in\
a bag, and put it in our room, and by that time it was supper-time, and\
a rattling good honest day\'92s work: \'a0and hungry?--oh, no, I reckon not!\
\'a0And there warn\'92t a blessed snake up there when we went back--we didn\'92t\
half tie the sack, and they worked out somehow, and left. \'a0But it didn\'92t\
matter much, because they was still on the premises somewheres. \'a0So\
we judged we could get some of them again. \'a0No, there warn\'92t no real\
scarcity of snakes about the house for a considerable spell. \'a0You\'92d see\
them dripping from the rafters and places every now and then; and they\
generly landed in your plate, or down the back of your neck, and most\
of the time where you didn\'92t want them. \'a0Well, they was handsome and\
striped, and there warn\'92t no harm in a million of them; but that never\
made no difference to Aunt Sally; she despised snakes, be the breed what\
they might, and she couldn\'92t stand them no way you could fix it; and\
every time one of them flopped down on her, it didn\'92t make no difference\
what she was doing, she would just lay that work down and light out. \'a0I\
never see such a woman. \'a0And you could hear her whoop to Jericho. \'a0You\
couldn\'92t get her to take a-holt of one of them with the tongs. \'a0And if\
she turned over and found one in bed she would scramble out and lift a\
howl that you would think the house was afire. \'a0She disturbed the old\
man so that he said he could most wish there hadn\'92t ever been no snakes\
created. \'a0Why, after every last snake had been gone clear out of the\
house for as much as a week Aunt Sally warn\'92t over it yet; she warn\'92t\
near over it; when she was setting thinking about something you could\
touch her on the back of her neck with a feather and she would jump\
right out of her stockings. \'a0It was very curious. \'a0But Tom said all\
women was just so. \'a0He said they was made that way for some reason or\
other.\
\
We got a licking every time one of our snakes come in her way, and she\
allowed these lickings warn\'92t nothing to what she would do if we ever\
loaded up the place again with them. \'a0I didn\'92t mind the lickings,\
because they didn\'92t amount to nothing; but I minded the trouble we\
had to lay in another lot. \'a0But we got them laid in, and all the other\
things; and you never see a cabin as blithesome as Jim\'92s was when they\'92d\
all swarm out for music and go for him. \'a0Jim didn\'92t like the spiders,\
and the spiders didn\'92t like Jim; and so they\'92d lay for him, and make it\
mighty warm for him. \'a0And he said that between the rats and the snakes\
and the grindstone there warn\'92t no room in bed for him, skasely; and\
when there was, a body couldn\'92t sleep, it was so lively, and it was\
always lively, he said, because _they_ never all slept at one time, but\
took turn about, so when the snakes was asleep the rats was on deck, and\
when the rats turned in the snakes come on watch, so he always had one\
gang under him, in his way, and t\'92other gang having a circus over him,\
and if he got up to hunt a new place the spiders would take a chance at\
him as he crossed over. He said if he ever got out this time he wouldn\'92t\
ever be a prisoner again, not for a salary.\
\
Well, by the end of three weeks everything was in pretty good shape.\
\'a0The shirt was sent in early, in a pie, and every time a rat bit Jim he\
would get up and write a little in his journal whilst the ink was fresh;\
the pens was made, the inscriptions and so on was all carved on the\
grindstone; the bed-leg was sawed in two, and we had et up the sawdust,\
and it give us a most amazing stomach-ache. \'a0We reckoned we was all\
going to die, but didn\'92t. \'a0It was the most undigestible sawdust I ever\
see; and Tom said the same.\
\
But as I was saying, we\'92d got all the work done now, at last; and we was\
all pretty much fagged out, too, but mainly Jim. \'a0The old man had wrote\
a couple of times to the plantation below Orleans to come and get their\
runaway nigger, but hadn\'92t got no answer, because there warn\'92t no such\
plantation; so he allowed he would advertise Jim in the St. Louis and\
New Orleans papers; and when he mentioned the St. Louis ones it give me\
the cold shivers, and I see we hadn\'92t no time to lose. So Tom said, now\
for the nonnamous letters.\
\
\'93What\'92s them?\'94 \'a0I says.\
\
\'93Warnings to the people that something is up. \'a0Sometimes it\'92s done one\
way, sometimes another. \'a0But there\'92s always somebody spying around that\
gives notice to the governor of the castle. \'a0When Louis XVI. was going\
to light out of the Tooleries, a servant-girl done it. \'a0It\'92s a very good\
way, and so is the nonnamous letters. \'a0We\'92ll use them both. \'a0And it\'92s\
usual for the prisoner\'92s mother to change clothes with him, and she\
stays in, and he slides out in her clothes. \'a0We\'92ll do that, too.\'94\
\
\'93But looky here, Tom, what do we want to _warn_ anybody for that\
something\'92s up? \'a0Let them find it out for themselves--it\'92s their\
lookout.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I know; but you can\'92t depend on them. \'a0It\'92s the way they\'92ve acted\
from the very start--left us to do _everything_. \'a0They\'92re so confiding\
and mullet-headed they don\'92t take notice of nothing at all. \'a0So if we\
don\'92t _give_ them notice there won\'92t be nobody nor nothing to interfere\
with us, and so after all our hard work and trouble this escape \'91ll go\
off perfectly flat; won\'92t amount to nothing--won\'92t be nothing _to_ it.\'94\
\
\'93Well, as for me, Tom, that\'92s the way I\'92d like.\'94\
\
\'93Shucks!\'94 he says, and looked disgusted. \'a0So I says:\
\
\'93But I ain\'92t going to make no complaint. \'a0Any way that suits you suits\
me. What you going to do about the servant-girl?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll be her. \'a0You slide in, in the middle of the night, and hook that\
yaller girl\'92s frock.\'94\
\
\'93Why, Tom, that \'91ll make trouble next morning; because, of course, she\
prob\'92bly hain\'92t got any but that one.\'94\
\
\'93I know; but you don\'92t want it but fifteen minutes, to carry the\
nonnamous letter and shove it under the front door.\'94\
\
\'93All right, then, I\'92ll do it; but I could carry it just as handy in my\
own togs.\'94\
\
\'93You wouldn\'92t look like a servant-girl _then_, would you?\'94\
\
\'93No, but there won\'92t be nobody to see what I look like, _anyway_.\'94\
\
\'93That ain\'92t got nothing to do with it. \'a0The thing for us to do is just\
to do our _duty_, and not worry about whether anybody _sees_ us do it or\
not. Hain\'92t you got no principle at all?\'94\
\
\'93All right, I ain\'92t saying nothing; I\'92m the servant-girl. \'a0Who\'92s Jim\'92s\
mother?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m his mother. \'a0I\'92ll hook a gown from Aunt Sally.\'94\
\
\'93Well, then, you\'92ll have to stay in the cabin when me and Jim leaves.\'94\
\
\'93Not much. \'a0I\'92ll stuff Jim\'92s clothes full of straw and lay it on his bed\
to represent his mother in disguise, and Jim \'91ll take the nigger woman\'92s\
gown off of me and wear it, and we\'92ll all evade together. \'a0When a\
prisoner of style escapes it\'92s called an evasion. \'a0It\'92s always called\
so when a king escapes, f\'92rinstance. \'a0And the same with a king\'92s son;\
it don\'92t make no difference whether he\'92s a natural one or an unnatural\
one.\'94\
\
So Tom he wrote the nonnamous letter, and I smouched the yaller wench\'92s\
frock that night, and put it on, and shoved it under the front door, the\
way Tom told me to. \'a0It said:\
\
Beware. \'a0Trouble is brewing. \'a0Keep a sharp lookout. _Unknown_ _Friend_.\
\
Next night we stuck a picture, which Tom drawed in blood, of a skull and\
crossbones on the front door; and next night another one of a coffin on\
the back door. \'a0I never see a family in such a sweat. \'a0They couldn\'92t a\
been worse scared if the place had a been full of ghosts laying for them\
behind everything and under the beds and shivering through the air. \'a0If\
a door banged, Aunt Sally she jumped and said \'93ouch!\'94 if anything fell,\
she jumped and said \'93ouch!\'94 if you happened to touch her, when she\
warn\'92t noticing, she done the same; she couldn\'92t face noway and be\
satisfied, because she allowed there was something behind her every\
time--so she was always a-whirling around sudden, and saying \'93ouch,\'94 and\
before she\'92d got two-thirds around she\'92d whirl back again, and say it\
again; and she was afraid to go to bed, but she dasn\'92t set up. \'a0So the\
thing was working very well, Tom said; he said he never see a thing work\
more satisfactory. He said it showed it was done right.\
\
So he said, now for the grand bulge! \'a0So the very next morning at the\
streak of dawn we got another letter ready, and was wondering what we\
better do with it, because we heard them say at supper they was going\
to have a nigger on watch at both doors all night. \'a0Tom he went down the\
lightning-rod to spy around; and the nigger at the back door was asleep,\
and he stuck it in the back of his neck and come back. \'a0This letter\
said:\
\
Don\'92t betray me, I wish to be your friend. \'a0There is a desprate gang of\
cutthroats from over in the Indian Territory going to steal your runaway\
nigger to-night, and they have been trying to scare you so as you will\
stay in the house and not bother them. \'a0I am one of the gang, but have\
got religgion and wish to quit it and lead an honest life again, and\
will betray the helish design. They will sneak down from northards,\
along the fence, at midnight exact, with a false key, and go in the\
nigger\'92s cabin to get him. I am to be off a piece and blow a tin horn\
if I see any danger; but stead of that I will _baa_ like a sheep soon as\
they get in and not blow at all; then whilst they are getting his\
chains loose, you slip there and lock them in, and can kill them at your\
leasure. \'a0Don\'92t do anything but just the way I am telling you, if you do\
they will suspicion something and raise whoop-jamboreehoo. I do not wish\
any reward but to know I have done the right thing. _Unknown Friend._\
